<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Waldheim 1stLd-Writethru a0684 02-25 0607</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Waldheim, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0684,0617</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Waldheim Cancels Speech at Anniversary Ceremony</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 7 grafs to UPDATE with Waldheim acknowledging that
he considered resigning. Pickup 4th pvs: `Austria is ...' DELETES
grafs 9-10 pvs: `He again ...' to CONFORM</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN COSTELLOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Kurt Waldheim acknowledged
Thursday that he had considered resigning, and canceled his
scheduled speech at the main ceremony on the 50th anniversary of
the day Adolf Hitler annexed Austria.
   He said he would address the nation on television instead.
Leading politicians have said a speech by Waldheim, who concealed
his Germany army service and has been accused of war crimes, was
not the way to lead national reflection on atrocities of the Nazi
past.
   The speech on March 11, the day of the Nazi ``anschluss'' in
1938, was decided upon last month as a means of avoiding a
political showdown over whether to invite the 69-year-old president
to address a joint session of Parliament on that day.
   During an interview late Thursday on Austrian state television,
Waldheim was asked if he had considered quitting before his term
ends in 1992.
   ``Naturally I thought of it,'' he said. ``Otherwise I wouldn`t
be a human being. I'd have to be a piece of wood.''
   He again rejected the notion of resigning, which has been
suggested or demanded from all political quarters.
   ``That would only make things worse,'' Waldheim said, adding
that he has a ``clear conscience'' about his past. He was elected
in June 1986 to a six-year term.
   Austria is governed by a coalition of the Socialists, led by
Chancellor Franz Vranitzky, and the conservative People's Party,
which backed Waldheim for president in the 1986 election. People's
Party leader Alois Mock, who is deputy chancellor and foreign
minister, is among his fervent supporters.
   Accusations arose during the presidential campaign about
Waldheim's service as a German army lieutenant in the Balkans, and
the United States put the former U.N. secretary-general on a
``watch list'' of undesirable aliens last year.
   In September, at Waldheim's request, Vranitzky's government
appointed an international panel of historians to investigate his
wartime activities. It concluded in a report this month that he
knew atrocities were being committed in ``close proximity'' to him
and did nothing to stop them, and left the question of personal
guilt open.
   In an interview broadcast Thursday evening on state radio,
Waldheim said he felt the president should promote reconciliation,
and ``it was a result of this feeling of my duty as federal
president that I took this personal initiative'' not to speak.
   Asked whether it was ``painful'' for him to cancel the speech,
Waldheim responded: ``It wasn't very painful, since I will be
present at the ceremony.''
   Waldheim's office said in a statement earlier Thursday: ``In the
interest of efforts aimed at a harmonious remembrance ceremony, the
president will not speak at this event.'' The statement did not
specify a day for the televised address, but Mock said later that
Waldheim would deliver it on March 10, the day before the ceremony.
   His office said Waldheim would attend the unveiling of a plaque
honoring members of Austria's prewar parliament who were victims of
the Nazis. The statement added that he hopes to promote the
``peaceful development of our nation.''
   Leaders of the anti-Waldheim movement had said thousands of
protesters would mass outside the Hofburg Palace, former seat of
the Hapsburg emperors, if Waldheim spoke at the anniversary
ceremony. It is to be held in the palace, which houses the
presidential offices.
   Organizers of the program, including Vranitzky, met with
Waldheim on Thursday to discuss his participation.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
