<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Obit-Salem 1stLd-Writethru a0639 02-25 0192</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Obit-Salem, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0639,0192</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Prime Minister Dies</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS thruout to UPDATE with comment from Mubarak, CORRECT
date of burial to Sunday and date he died to Thursday. No pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>CAIRO, Egypt (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Prime Minister Mamdouh Salem died
Thursday in London while undergoing treatment from an undisclosed
illness. He was 70.
   The state-run Middle East News Agency said Salem would be given
a military funeral Sunday in Cairo.
   The agency said President Hosni Mubarak praised Salem, saying
Egypt would remember him for his ``nationalism, his good manners,
his self-respect and sacrifices for the majority interest and
good.''
   Salem was prime minister from 1975 to 1978. When then-Foreign
Minister Ibrahim Kamel resigned in 1978 to protest the signing of
the U.S.-sponsored Camp David accords between Egypt and Israel,
late President Anwar Sadat appointed a new government. The peace
treaty was signed a year later.
   Salem was a personal aide to Sadat and to Mubarak, who succeeded
Sadat in 1981.
   Born in 1918 in the Mediterranean port of Alexandria, Salem was
governor of Asiut, Gharbiya and Alexandria from 1967 to 1971, when
he was appointed interior minister.
</TEXT>
