<1ST_LINE>u a AM-DrugTestRuling     02-25 0392</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Drug Test Ruling,0404</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NCAA Drug Testing Not a Constitutional Violation, Judge Rules</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY McDONALD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge Thursday upheld the National
Collegiate Athletic Association's drug-testing program, ruling
against a student athlete who contended the taking of urine samples
violated her privacy.
   U.S. District Judge Walter McGovern said any violation of
privacy is outweighed by the NCAA's interest in protecting
students' health, reducing drug use and ensuring fair competition.
   The American Civil Liberties Union, which filed the suit on
behalf of University of Washington runner Betsy O'Halloran and
another athlete who later joined the case, will probably appeal,
said the ACLU's Kathleen Taylor.
   Under NCAA rules, students must sign a consent form before the
regular season begins allowing random testing.
   The testing does not actually occur until post-season playoff
time, but students like Ms. O'Halloran who refuse to sign are
prohibited from regular-season competition.
   Ms. O'Halloran, a cross-country and track athlete, had sued the
university over its mandatory testing program, but last month UW
revised its program so that screening was voluntary and required
only of athletes suspected of drug use.
   The claim against the university was then dismissed, with the
claim against the NCAA program and the university's participation
in it remaining.
   However, UW athletes are still required to sign an NCAA consent
form.
   Ms. O'Halloran had asked McGovern to grant her a preliminary
injunction allowing her to compete for the UW women's track team
this spring.
   But McGovern denied the request, saying any harm done to her by
being barred from competition was outweighed by the potentially
greater harm to the NCAA.
   ``Competent athletes might use banned drugs in violation of NCAA
rules, and the public interest in fair competition without the use
of drugs would not be served,'' McGovern said.
   Ms. O'Halloran has not been able to compete during the fall
cross-country season and will not participate in track this spring
because she will not sign the consent form, Ms. Taylor said.
   Ms. Taylor said the ACLU was surprised by the decision,
especially in light of a Feb. 11 federal appeals court decision
prohibiting drug testing of railway workers without specific
suspicion against a particular individual.
   ``The NCAA's laudable goal of reducing drug use among student
athletes must be carried out in a less degrading and intrusive
manner,'' Ms. Taylor said.
</TEXT>
