<FILEID>AP-NR-02-25-88 0610EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-QuakeExpected     02-25 0658</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Quake Expected,0676</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Earthquake Like October's Los Angeles Tremor Expected East of
Rockies</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MALCOLM RITTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A quake stronger than the Oct. 1 temblor that
caused severe damage in Los Angeles is likely to occur east of the
Rockies in the next two decades, so buildings in the area should be
fortified, experts said.
   The prediction is based on the history and geology of the
region, said Robert Ketter, director of the National Center for
Earthquake Engineering Research at the State University of New York
at Buffalo.
   The California quake, which killed eight people and measured 5.9
on the Richter scale, left an estimated $358 million in destruction
in the Los Angeles area, damaging more than 10,400 buildings and
leaving about 2,200 people homeless.
   ``I feel comfortable there will be a magnitude of 6 or higher
within the next 20 years'' somewhere in the United States east of
the Rocky Mountain foothills, said Ketter.
   Ketter, who called the California quake relatively modest, spoke
Wednesday during a break in a conference on earthquake hazards and
construction design in the United States east of the Rockies.
   Despite the low probability of a serious quake in any one place
east of the Rockies, the region's relatively dense population and
older buildings make for a ``very serious problem'' in risk from
earthquakes, he said.
   Robert Whitman, a civil engineering professor at the
Massachusetts Institute of Technology, called Ketter's prediction
reasonable.
   The last major quake east of the Rockies struck Charleston,
S.C., in 1886, reaching an estimated Richter reading of 7 and
making itself felt as far away as Chicago, conference organizers
say. Other damaging quakes hit New York City in 1884, Anna, Ohio,
in 1937, western Tennessee in 1843 and Giles County, Va., in 1897.
   The most severe earthquakes in the nation's history struck New
Madrid, Mo., in 1811 and 1812, Ketter said. Having an estimated
magnitude of 8.3 to 8.5 on the Richter scale, the quakes were
strong enough to ring church bells in Washington, D.C., Ketter said.
   The Richter scale is a measure of ground motion as recorded on
seismographs.
   An earthquake of magnitude 3.5 can cause slight damage in the
local area, 4 moderate damage, 5 considerable damage, 6 severe
damage. A 7 reading is a ``major'' earthquake, capable of
widespread heavy damage; 8 is a ``great'' quake, capable of
tremendous damage.
   The San Francisco earthquake of 1906, which occurred before the
Richter scale was devised, has been estimated at 8.3 on the Richter
scale.
   Earthquakes east of the Rockies result from pressure exerted by
the floor of the Atlantic Ocean acting on geological areas of
weakness, speakers at the conference said. Because of geology,
Ketter said, an earthquake of a given strength can shake an area
100 times larger in this region than on the West Coast.
   ``We cannot rule out the possibility of a very large earthquake
occuring practically anywhere'' in the region, said Whitman, who
called on architects and engineers to encourage
earthquake-resistant construction.
   Cities and states should adopt the earthquake provisions of
model building codes, he said. Studies suggest that quake-resistant
designs add only about 1 percent to the cost of most new buildings,
he said.
   The more important challenge is what should be done to make
existing buildings more quake-resistant, he said. While it would be
politically difficult to require upgrading to meet the standards of
new construction, he said, steps short of that would be acceptable.
   Substantial upgradings of masonry buildings have been done for
$5 to $6 per square foot in Los Angeles and $5 to $10 per square
foot elsewhere, he said. For buildings with other types of
construction, upgrading can cost $10 to $20 per square foot, he
said.
   The conference is sponsored by Ketter's institute and the New
York Academy of Sciences, and co-sponsored by the National Science
Foundation and the Earthquake Engineering Research Institute, a
professional society for earthquake engineering.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
