<FILEID>AP-NR-02-25-88 0442EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-TheChase     02-25 0664</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-The Chase,620</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>The Night the Entire Republican Party Vanished</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WX9</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE GOULD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Robert Packwood, U.S. senator and fugitive
from a quorum call, thought he was safe, hiding behind a locked
door in his Senate office.
   But Henry Giugni, Senate sergeant-at-arms and former vice and
motorcycle cop, knew he would get his man.
   ``I had to take him in,'' he explained.
   ``I thoughtI was safe,'' Packwood recalled. ``But it's the
little things that trip you up.''
   It was as unlikely a scene _ and a night _ as could be recalled
by Senate historians, parliamentarians and press corps observers.
   It was the night, as Sen. John Kerry, D-Mass., put it, where
``the entire Republican Party in the United States Senate ...
vanished into the night.''
   It was the night Senate Majority Leader Robert Byrd, D-W.Va.,
wanted to keep the Senate in session through dawn's early light to
draw attention to a Republican filibuster that previously had been
quietly played out during daytime hours off and on over many months.
   If the Republicans didn't want a vote on a campaign finance
bill, they would have to keep talking. Republicans didn't want to
keep talking, so they attempted to keep a quorum off the Senate
floor, forcing the Senate to quit for the night.
   They huddled in the cloakroom outside the chamber.
   Then Byrd got tough. He asked for a vote directing the
sergeant-at-arms to ``reques attendance of absent senators.''
   The Republicans were so requested.
   But they stayed behind the cloakroom door.
   Byrd upped the ante.
   He asked that the Senate approve a motion to instruct the
sergeant-at-arms to ``arrest the absent senators and bring them to
the chamber.''
   With 45 Democratic votes, the motion carried.
   And the chase was on.
   Kerry said the sergeant-at-arms' orders resulted in ``a lot of
senators running off into the corridors at night,'' chased by
Giugni and a team of five plainclothes detectives.
   Giugni spotted Idaho Republicans Steve Symms and James McClure
down in a basement corridor where Symms has a ``hideaway'' office.
   At about the same moment, Symms and McClure spotted the
sergeant-at-arms.
   ``We took off. Henry was alone,'' Symms said. He fled down the
corridor.
   ``I didn't want to be the first one caught,'' he said.
   McClure's press secretary, H.D. Palmer, said his boss ``blew out
of there. He was a fugitive from Bobby Byrd's chain gang.''
   Giugni's position was a tough one. He works for the senators in
a capitol where senators' wishes are law. ``I had to do my job ...
I had a list. I went into the hideaways, then the Russell
Building'' where some senators have their offices.
   Giugni got lucky.
   Packwood had just holed up in his office. ``I thought I was
safe, I had been forewarned by my staff that Henry was going around
looking,'' Packwood recalled. After all, he was locked behind a
bolted door, and senators locked behind bolted doors in their
well-guarded office buildings are usually very, very safe.
   Packwood forgot the cleaning lady had seen him enter his office.
   And Giugni, five years on the Honolulu police force under his
ample belt, remembered to ask.
   Moments later, Giugni and his gang of five, armed with a
passkey, threw themselves at another door as the Oregon senator was
trying to slam and bolt it shut.
   ``There were three of them on one side. Their mass beat my
mass,'' Packwood said.
   Giugni was diplomatic. ``It was a misunderstanding. I thought we
were helping him open the door,'' he later joked, Packwood at his
side.
   The senator was hauled out of his office, across the Capitol,
put in an elevator, and, finally, physically picked up and
deposited feet first into the Senate chamber.
   Once there, Giugni had his man and the Senate had its reluctant
quorum of 51 senators.
   The arrest warrant carried with it indignities, but no penalties.
   But Packwood wasn't taking any chances.
   ``I'm asking Gerald Ford for a pardon.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
