<FILEID>AP-NR-02-25-88 0326EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-AIDSCommission     02-25 0547</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-AIDS Commission,530</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Report Calls For Emphasis On Fighting AIDS Among Drug Users</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY ESTILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chairman of President Reagan's AIDS
commission is drawing praise from one of the administration's more
vocal congressional critics for his first round of recommendations
on combating the deadly disease.
   The praise came after retired Navy Adm. James D. Watkins,
promoted to the helm of the struggling commission last September,
said Wednesday the federal government should spend an additional $1
billion a year to fight AIDS among intravenous drug abusers alone.
   Approval of such an ambitious undertaking would virtually double
the $1.3 billion Reagan has requested for all Public Health Service
spending on AIDS in fiscal 1989 _ including research and prevention
measures aimed at the entire population.
   ``Admiral Watkins has compiled a first-rate set of
recommendations that begin to deal with the AIDS epidemic
responsibly and in detail,'' said Rep. Henry A. Waxman, D-Calif.,
who has been frequent critic of the administration during his
health subcommittee's 19 hearings on AIDS.
   ``I hope that President Reagan will attend to these
recommendations of his commission and will amend his budget and
come to the Congress to support them and the spending they
require,''' said Waxman.
   Watkins, who said he was making his recommendations to the full
commission public at the same time he sent them to the White House,
acknowledged that his call for sharply higher federal spending
might be less than well received at the Office of Management and
Budget.
   But he said there is no doubt AIDS is spreading most rapidly
among the nation's estimated 1.3 million intravenous drug abusers,
and their sexual partners, and that efforts to stem the disease
must concentrate on them.
   He expessed confidence the commission will adopt his
recommendations _ which also call on state and local governments to
increase their drug program spending by about $1 billion a year _
and formally pass them to the White House in early March.
   ``It is not in our charter to worry about the political
impact,'' said Watkins.
   A final report is due at the White House June 24 and Watkins
promised it will get into such controversial areas as AIDS testing.
The panel would be ``at loggerheads with ourselves'' if it tried to
deal with them without further testimony and deliberation, he said.
   Watkins also made a number of recommendations in the health care
area, including more training for doctors and federal backing for
home care for dying AIDS patients who may not require full-time
hospitalization.
   ``Many physicians are severely lacking in knowledge about AIDS
and there are signs that medical schools have not yet built up a
curriculum to educate doctors about AIDS treatment,'' Watkins said.
   He also cited a growing nursing shortage, saying an additional
500,000 nurses will be needed throughout the health care system by
1991.
   The report called for more financial support for the Food and
Drug Administration as well.
   Asked his reaction to the possibility of presidential
candidates, particularly Democrats, using his recommendations to
``zing the White House'' for not doing more earlier, Watkins
replied:
   ``How do you avoid politicizing something in an election year?
If they all adopt this and say `Let's get on with it,' that's the
kind of politicization I like.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
