<FILEID>AP-NR-02-25-88 0404EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Robertson-Libel     02-25 0667</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Robertson-Libel,650</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Robertson Pushes Ahead With Libel Suit Although Trial Set Super
Tuesday</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican presidential candidate Pat
Robertson appears ready to push his politically risky libel suit
against a former congressman who questioned his war record even
though the trial is set for Super Tuesday.
   Robertson, who once expressed reget he ever brought the case,
says former Rep. Paul N. McCloskey, R-Calif., is a ``patent liar''
for saying he invoked the political influence of his late father,
Sen. A. Willis Robertson, D-Va., to avoid combat in the Korean War.
   At a press conference in Atlanta on Wednesday, Robertson
conceded that going to trial March 8 _ a day he hopes to do well in
a dozen Southern primaries _ leaves him in ``an untenable
position.''
   ``I have a choice of fulfilling my constitutional right to run
for president ... or every American's right to have his day in
court,'' Robertson told reporters.
   ``The trial is going ahead. I'm looking for some alternative, we
haven't made up our mind,'' Robertson said, hinting he might seek a
way out of his political and legal dilemma.
   But Robertson insisted that paying McCloskey's legal fees of
nearly $400,000 ``is not an option'' even though the former
congressman says he would settle on that basis.
   ``I wouldn't pay a nickel to somebody who is a patent liar,''
Robertson said.
   McCloskey said Robertson's position means a trial of the case is
likely to begin on Super Tuesday before U.S. District Judge Joyce
Hens Green, who refused Robertson's earlier request to postpone the
proceeding until after the primaries are over.
   ``At this stage he has already put us close to $400,000 in legal
fees, we might as well go to trial,'' McCloskey said in a telephone
interview. ``I think that the jury is the best possible place to
determine if he is telling the truth or I am.''
   Roberston filed the lawsuit after two syndicated columns
published the contents of a letter McCloskey wrote to Rep. Andrew
Jacobs Jr., D-Ind., charging that the former television evangelist
cabled his father from Japan to get out of combat duty.
   McCloskey, a decorated Marine who was aboard the troop ship from
which Robertson was removed, also said the former television
evangelist was a ``booze officer'' to a rear-echelon unit.
   Professional political analysts have questioned Robertson's
judgment in filing the case. Robertson himself was quoted by Time
magazine last September as saying: ``In all candor, I think it was
a bad idea.''
   Because of the possibility of intense media coverage during the
three-week trial, political professionals have questioned the
wisdom of proceeding with the suit.
   ``The thing is so dangerous for him, I would just get out of the
thing any way I could get out,'' said Democratic political
consultant Robert Beckel, adding: ``I see nothing coming out of it
good politically for him.''
   ``Most people are not aware of the allegation, the average voter
hasn't focused on Robertson's war record. Nobody is going to attack
him on it. Why raise it yourself?'' Beckel said.
   Charles Black, who is working for rival GOP candidate Jack Kemp,
said, ``I've always thought it was a big negative for him.''
   ``I'm not in a position to judge who's right and who's wrong
about the charges,'' he said. But ``having a libel trial right in
the middle of the primary season will obviously dramatize the
charges against him.''
   By proceeding to trial, Robertson risks extensive news coverage
of potentially embarrassing testimony by several former Marines who
support McCloskey's story and add tales of their own.
   One former Marine said in a deposition that Robertson ``messed
around with the prostitutes'' and was ``scared to death'' of
contracting gonorrhea. Robertson's lawyers are trying to suppress
that comment from the trial as irrelevent to the issues in the case.
   Despite Robertson's expressed misgivings over going forward,
lawyers for both sides say they are preparing to try the case and
are not talking about a settlement.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880225-0031 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-25-88 0405EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-FTC-Subpoena     02-25 0499</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-FTC-Subpoena,500</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>FTC Member Turns Over Documents Demanded By House Panel</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN SKORNECK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Federal Trade Commission member says he's
told his aides not to put anything in writing anymore since a
congressional panel forced him to disclose documents under threat
of finding him in contempt of Congress.
   Commissioner Terry Calvani escaped the contempt citation
Wednesday by appearing under subpoena before the House Committee on
Energy and Commerce's subcommittee on oversight and investigations
and turning over the requested documents, ending a battle that
began last October.
   ``I tell the men and women that serve in my office that I want
their wholly candid assessment and unvarnished recommendation about
matters before me,'' he told the panel, headed by Rep. John D.
Dingell, D-Mich. ``This morning I have instructed my staff that
from henceforth they should not commit their work to paper.''
   The internal documents demanded by the panel concerned the FTC's
views on whether unfair and deceptive advertising practices were
occurring in the airline industry.
   The FTC had written a letter to the National Association of
Attorneys General which reflected that the agency had not studied
the matter. A press release on the question, however, indicated
that the agency believed the airline industry had no such problems.
   The reading of a reference to the press release comment on the
House floor last October helped defeat an amendment by Dingell that
would have transferred responsibility for airline industry consumer
protection from the Department of Transportation to the FTC, said
subcommittee counsel Patrick McLain.
   Rep. Michael Bilirakis, R-Fla., said the statement indicated to
the House members that the FTC believed airline industry consumer
protection was fine as it was and there was no need for the FTC to
take over.
   ``The amendment intended to help the consumers of the country
was greatly thwarted,'' he said.
   Several days after the vote, the subcommittee began asking the
FTC for internal documents on the matter.
   Two commissioners said they had no such documents, two others
allowed subcommittee staff to read pertinent materials in their
offices, but Calvani refused to provide access to such documents.
   After the subcommittee and Calvani exchanged several letters,
the panel on Feb. 4 subpoenaed Calvani to appear and bring the
documents.
   Calvani said that until Friday, the panel had not provided the
legal justification for him to provide the requested materials.
   After testifying, Calvani said he believed he had become caught
in a ``turf fight'' between Dingell and Rep. James J. Howard,
D-N.J., chairman of the Committee on Public Works and
Transportation, who wanted the Transportation Department to keep
control of airline industry consumer protection.
   ``They were looking for a scapegoat, and I'm the unfortunate
person chosen for that,'' he said.
   Dingell's office referred all requests for a response to
Calvani's allegation to McLain, who refused to comment.
   However, both Republican and Democratic panel members said
during the hearing that they supported the issuance of the subpoena
and the need for the documents.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880225-0032 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-25-88 0408EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Robertson     02-25 0888</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Robertson,850</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan: If Robertson Had Hostage Information, He Didn't Tell
Administration</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan questioned GOP hopeful Pat
Robertson's contention that he had information about American
hostages being held in Lebanon, saying if the former television
evangelist did have such knowledge, ``he kept it to himself.''
   ``It'd be very strange if he actually did have information as to
the location of those hostages,'' the president said at a
nationally broadcast news conference Wednesday night. ``Isn't it
strange that no one in our administration was ever apprised of
that?''
   Robertson said Wednesday his Christian Broadcasting Network once
knew the whereabouts of American hostages in Lebanon ``and they
could have been freed.'' Robertson spokesmen later said the the
former television evangelist was referring to hostages seized when
a TWA flight was hijacked to Beirut in 1985, who were eventually
freed.
   When he was asked about Robertson's assertion, Reagan said he
didn't want to comment on the campaign. But he said of the
hostages: ``We have tried our best and through every kind of
channel to establish their whereabouts because that's the beginning
of efforts to try and get them free.''
   ``If he thought that he knew'' where hostages were being held,
Reagan said of Robertson, ``he kept it to himself.''
   ``It's very frustrating to try and establish a location,'' said
the president. ``But we've never let up, and we never will, in
trying to obtain the freedom of all the hostages.''
   Nine Americans are in captivity in Lebanon, including Marine Lt.
Col. William R. Higgins, who was captured last week. Terry
Anderson, chief Middle East correspondent of The Associated Press,
is the longest-held captive, having been kidnapped on March 16,
1985.
   Robertson spokesman Scott Hatch said after Reagan spoke: ``I
think what Pat said was accurate.''
   Even before the president's news conference, Robertson's
comments drew quick criticism from two of his GOP presidential
rivals, Rep. Jack Kemp and Vice President George Bush.
   Kemp, in a statement, called Robertson's statements
irresponsible and said he should ``apologize to the families of the
hostages whom he has needlessly hurt in an attempt to gain
publicity.''
   ``I don't think it was irresponsible at all,'' said Hatch. ``The
whole context was how Pat would deal with terrorism, and he used
that as an example.''
   Bush, campaigning in Boston, said: ``My question would be, how
come he didn't get hold of the proper authorities in the United
States government that were working day and night, trying to figure
out how they could get these people out?''
   Robertson's comments came at an Atlanta news conference during
which he complained that U.S. intelligence in the Middle East is
inadequate and declared that action must be quick when Americans
are taken hostage.
   ``We identified in our news department at CBN the location of
those hostages in Lebanon very shortly after they were taken, and
they were in a position where they could have been rescued,'' he
said.
   ``They were in Beirut, and they could have been freed.''
   Robertson did not provide specifics and did not say which
hostages were involved.
   Benton Miller, spokesman for CBN, based in Virginia Beach, Va.,
said the comments pertained to hostages who had been taken from TWA
Flight 847 in 1985. He later issued a synopsis of the news report
to which Robertson referred.
   The synopsis said that in response to a question from Robertson,
a CBN Middle East correspondent, who was not named, said the
hostages, ``are in several locations in and around Lebanon and we
have also learned that maybe at least one of them, and we do not
know which one, but we have been told by intelligence sources in
Lebanon, that at least one may be being held in Tehran.''
   The suspicion concerning the hostage thought to be held in
Tehran was later reported as incorrect in a subsequent news report
on Robertson's ``700 Club'' talk show, Miller said.
   Asked whether he had told the Reagan administration what he
knew, Robertson said, ``I broadcast it on national television; they
monitor our programs virtually every day.''
   Robertson aide Gary Lane said during the TWA hostage situation,
the State Department contacted CBN for information at that time,
but he said he did not know exactly who made the contact.
   A State Department terrorism expert said he was puzzled by
Robertson's statements, saying he was unaware that CBN had ever
broadcast the precise locations of any hostages.
   The official, speaking on condition of anonymity, also said
knowledge of hostages' whereabouts in terms of a particular city or
even a section of a city wouldn't be enough to mount a rescue
mission.
   Robertson's comments on the hostages marked the second time in
two weeks that his statements on international matters have sparked
controversy. During a Republican presidential debate on Feb. 14, he
alleged that the Soviets have nuclear missiles in Cuba, pointing to
the United States. The Reagan administration denied it.
   In yet another controversy, Bush asked Robertson to apologize or
provide proof to back up his suggestion on Tuesday that
anti-Robertson political motivations were behind the timing of
public allegations of sexual misconduct against television
evangelist Jimmy Swaggart.
   ``By sundown in the old South, I'd like to see him stand up like
a Southern gentleman with a little evidence,'' Bush said. ``I'd
like to see an apology or proof.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
