<1ST_LINE>u i PM-ChatteringBritain Bjt   02-25 0547</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Chattering Britain, Bjt,0563</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>A Telephone Chat Link Gets Out of Hand</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCUS ELIASON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It seemed at first like an innovative way of
getting the British to talk about something other than the weather.
But things apparently went too far.
   Talkabout, a telephone company service linking strangers
together for chats in groups of up to 10 at a time, was forced to
hang up permanently this week under a barrage of public criticism.
   For British Telecom, the country's main telephone company,
Talkabout was a gold mine. The company's privatization in 1984
after decades of state ownership has made it far more
profit-conscious and Talkabout earned it up to $17.5 million a year.
   But parents complained Talkabout rang up huge phone bills.
Members of Parliament claimed it had become a dating service and
drug exchange. Lurid tales circulated of girls being seduced by
older men and of young neo-Nazis pouring out racist hatred.
   While the tabloid press highlighted the sensational aspects of
Talkabout, the Office of Telecommunications (OFTEL), the phone
company's watchdog body, warned that British Telecom's monopoly
privileges would be reviewed unless customers could have Talkabout
blocked from their lines.
   British Telecom said the cost would be prohibitive and on Monday
it stopped the service.
   No one claims to have actually heard the service being seriously
abused, and British Telecom hotly denies the seduction stories. If
anything, say critics who called in to hear Talkabout for
themselves, the conversations generally were dull and witless.
   Nonetheless, Terry Lewis, a lawmaker for the opposition Labor
Party who campaigned against Talkabout, insisted ``the service is
obscene, dangerous, addictive and costly.''
   Costly, definitely. At up to 71 cents a minute at peak time,
Talkabout cost eight times more than an ordinary call.
   Addictive, perhaps. Youngsters calling in to a radio talk show
said they sometimes spent up to four hours a day on Talkabout.
   But obscene and dangerous? British Telecom says the service
attracted 40 million calls but only 27 complaints since its
inception in 1983.
   ``We provided a quite innocent and socially useful pastime to
many thousands of customers,'' the company said in a statement
announcing Talkabout's closure.
   British Telecom says it was prepared for trouble from the
outset, and built in safeguards.
   Conversations were limited to 10 minutes and separate services
existed for teen-agers and for adults.
   A tape recording warned callers not to divulge surnames,
addresses or phone numbers during conversation, and about 200
monitors stood by at the 25 Talkabout exchanges around the country,
ready to step in and cut off abusers.
   ``None of that,'' a monitor would interject the moment a
conversation looked like veering into smut or racism. ``You know
the rules. If you won't behave I will cut you off.''
   But conversation was often an unintelligible mish-mash of
competing voices. Even if an interesting conversation got going,
the 10-minute rule soon guillotined it.
   The notion of Talkabout as a battering ram against the fabled
reserve of the British character was ``one of our theories,'' a
British Telecom spokesman said, insisting on anonymity citing
company rules.
   ``People sit opposite each other on the train five days a week
going to work and never talk. Some of them would probably love an
anonymous chat on Talkabout,'' he added.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880225-0034 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-25-88 0413EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Cuba-HumanRights     02-25 0456</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Cuba-Human Rights,450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>US, Cuba Embroiled in Dispute over Ex-Prisoner</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former Cuban political prisoner in the
Reagan administration is being portrayed by Havana as a terrorist,
liar and impostor who has become a key figure in a U.S. effort to
discredit Cuba.
   Cuba escalated its campaign on Wednesday against Armando
Valladares, head of the U.S. delegation to the U.N. Human Rights
Commission in Geneva, accusing the State Department of spreading
``15 lies'' about his past.
   The Reagan administration has described Valladares as a victim
of Cuban repression who spent 22 years in prison merely for
expressing opposition to communism. It has denied Cuban charges
that Valladares worked for the secret police of the rightist
dictatorship that was overthrown by Fidel Castro and his forces in
1959.
   Cuban diplomats in Washington, the United Nations and Geneva
distributed a 37-page pamphlet outlining the purported U.S. lies
and making public a State Department document where the alleged
misrepresentations are said to have been made.
   Cuba released the pamphlet as Valladares was preparing an
attempt to win approval by the U.N. commission of a resolution
seeking to place Cuba's human rights practices on the 1989 agenda
of the panel. A similar effort last year failed by a single vote.
   Valladares is perhaps best known for his book, ``Against All
Hope,'' in which he outlines what he claims was his systematic
mistreatment during his long detention.
   The Cuban document, disputing the State Department, said
Valladares was never ``a prisoner of conscience'' but rather a
subversive who later became a ``dissident manufactured by the
government of the United States ... to serve its anti-Cuban
campaigns.''
   The Cuban document said that Valladares worked for a
counter-revolutionary group found to possess lethal weapons. But
the State Department contended that a thorough search of
Valladares' home after his December 1960 arrest turned up no
weapons or other evidence of subversive activities.
   The 10-page undated State Department memo made public by the
Cuban government appeared to be authentic, according to a U.S.
official who is familiar with Valladares' role in the government.
   The memo was sent as a cable to all U.S. diplomatic and consular
posts for use as a counter to the ``massive defamation campaign''
against Valladares being waged by Cuba.
   The Cuban document, discussing the U.S. ``lies'' about
Valladares, also said it is not true that:
   _Cuba had ever declared that Valladares had engaged in torture
while serving in the pre-revolutionary secret police.
   _Valladares was arrested for speaking out against communism and
for refusing to display a sign of revolutionary propaganda on his
office desk.
   _Cuba manufactured a forged police identity card in an effort to
verify his service in the secret police.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880225-0035 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-25-88 0331EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-KudzuCurse Bjt   02-25 0593</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Kudzu Curse, Bjt,0606</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Asian Carpetbagger Entangles Dixie</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALEX DOMINGUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FLORA, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Travelers know they're in the South when: A)
The Confederate flag is flying over the state capitol; B) There are
more pickups than cars on the highway; C) A transplanted Asiatic
vine entangles practically everything.
   Unfortunately farmers, loggers, utilities and lovers of roadside
scenery know the answer is C.
   People all over the South know and curse kudzu (pronounced
kuhd'-zoo). The transplanted vine once thought to be a savior has
acquired a status akin to a carpetbagger.
   Planted heavily in Mississippi and other Southern states during
the Depression to control erosion, kudzu's welcome soon wore out as
it spread from the gullies it was planted in. It now covers an area
the size of Belgium.
   ``There are mixed opinions about it,'' said James Wolfe, a plant
materials specialist with the U.S. Department of Agriculture's Soil
Conservation Service, an agency responsible for kudzu planting
during the 1930's.
   ``A lot of people seem to fear it quite a bit. I don't think
it's as bad as some people would say,'' Wolfe said last week. ``It
may not be beneficial, but it's got a lot of character about it as
you travel down the highway and see it climbing all over trees.''
   Kudzu has spread as far as 25 miles on each side of the road
where it was planted 40 years ago, covering trees, old houses and
abandoned cars. The lumber industry, in particular, is not fond of
the plant because it can kill trees by blocking out the light.
   Some of the heaviest concentrations in Mississippi can be found
in the rich cotton-farming area in the Delta region. Macabre
formations of the clinging vine can be seen suffocating trees as
travelers pass through towns such as Flora, Yazoo City and Tchula
on Mississippi 49.
   The vine, brought from Japan in 1876 as an ornamental plant, can
grow as much as 100 feet in a summer _ a foot a day. And without
harsh winters to kill it, or natural predators, it picks up each
spring where it left off the previous fall.
   The weight of its vines has been known to pull down utility
lines.
   ``Kudzu is tough to control. If we don't keep it down it will
climb the poles and guidelines and cause electrical outages,''
Mississippi Power & Light spokesman Ed Jussely said. ``Through a
consistant maintenance program we have been successful in stopping
the outages, but it is a difficult problem for us every year.''
   Kudzu now covers over 7 million acres in Mississippi, Georgia,
Alabama and parts of surrounding states. It extends as far north as
southern Missouri and West Virginia, and as far west as Texas.
   Farmers, utilities and the lumber industry are engaged in a
never-ending battle against kudzu _ Alabama even passed a law
against owning kudzu seeds or seedlings.
   The only thing that will stop it is constant cutting. Farmers
often let cattle feed on kudzu because its nutritional value is
about the same as alfalfa and overgrazing will kill it.
   Outside of open pasture, however, kudzu is king. A variety of
chemicals and other methods have been tried to stop it, none with
much success.
   ``Generally, programs involve a paper company or a few farmers,
but there is not a statewide program to get rid of it,'' said Wayne
Houston, a weed specialist at Mississippi State University.
``Generally, whatever you put down to kill kudzu also kills the
trees. It's difficult and expensive to kill it.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880225-0036 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-25-88 0432EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Reagan-Soviets     02-25 0424</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Reagan-Soviets,420</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Signals Change On US Participation In GATT</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Economics Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan says the question of Soviet
participation in an international trade organization is currently
``being reviewed,'' even though his administration has staunchly
opposed such a move in the past.
   During his news conference Wednesday night, Reagan was asked
whether he would discuss trade liberalization in his upcoming
meeting in Moscow with Soviet Leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev, and
whether he supports the Soviet bid to join the General Agreement on
Tariffs and Trade.
   ``I do know that there has been consideration of them involving
themselves in the GATT procedure, and that, of course, is being
reviewed among those of us who are participants now,'' Reagan said.
   In the past, the United States has led the effort to block
Soviet participation in the 95-nation compact which sets and
enforces international trading rules.
   Just last Jan. 20, presidential spokesman Marlin Fitzwater
underscored the administration's opposition to Soviet participation
in either GATT or its sister economic organizations, the World Bank
and the International Monetary Fund.
   The Soviet economic system ``remains at this point fundamentally
incompatible with participation in free-world institutions,''
Fitzwater said at the time. ``In essence, they don't have a
free-world economy.
   ``The Treasury Department and the administration remain opposed
to Soviet membership.''
   A position of continued opposition to Soviet membership in the
international financial organizations also was spelled out in a
January report to Congress from the White House, entitled
``National Security Strategy of the United States.''
   That report did note ``Soviet policy statements regarding
reconstruction and economic reform,'' suggesting to some analysts
that the GATT-membership question was an open one.
   However, the report went on to add, ``The Soviet economic system
remains at this point fundamentally incompatible with participation
in free world institutions.''
   In September 1986, the United States successfully led the
opposition to a Soviet effort to join GATT to participate in a new
round of trade-liberalization talks, now under way in Geneva.
   Reagan declined to go into details of what he would discuss with
Gorbachev during his Moscow visit this spring.
   On the general subject of East-West trade, Reagan said: ``Our
trade with the Soviet union is restricted mainly on the basis of
where we might be giving them technology and information that could
be used one day against us.''
   Currently, most high-tech equipment is banned from export to the
Soviet Union. However, the administration is currently at work
trimming the list of non-strategic items than can be shipped to the
Soviet bloc.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
