<HEAD>Highlights of News Conference</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Reagan Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are highlights of President Reagan's news
conference Wednesday night, his first in four months:
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>CONTRAS</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Reagan asked again for aid to the Contra rebels fighting the
Nicaraguan government. He said the Soviet Union had doubled
military assistance for the leftist regime in the first two months
of this year over 1987 levels but provided no figures or other
substantiation.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>DEMOCRATS</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The president criticized the Democrats for what he called their
gloom and doom statements about the economy. ``At the moment none
of those things are true,'' he said.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>HOSTAGES</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Reagan said ``we've never let up and we never will'' in efforts
to win freedom for American hostages in Lebanon. He said if
Republican presidential contender Pat Robertson knew anything of
their whereabouts, as Robertson insisted he once did, it was ``very
strange'' that ``he kept it to himself.''
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>IRAN-CONTRA AFFAIR</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The president confirmed anew that Vice President George Bush
expressed reservations during the Iran-Contra affair, but he
refused to say precisely what Bush had told him.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>MEESE</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Reagan said he had ``every confidence'' in the personal
integrity of embattled Attorney General Edwin Meese III but could
not comment on reports of the investigation of Meese's role in a
proposed Middle East oil pipeline.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>MIDDLE EAST</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   He refused to criticize Israeli action against Arab protesters
on the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip. He said he hoped Israelis
and Arabs would ``rid themselves of old ideas and stances that
cannot work'' and begin serious peace negotiations.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>PANAMA</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The president said he had not decided whether to tell Congress
that aid should be resumed to Panama. He has to certify that Panama
is helping in anti-drug efforts. Gen. Manuel Noriega, Panama's
military leader, has been indicted on U.S. drug-trafficking charges.
</TEXT>
