<1ST_LINE>r w PM-AIDS-BloodSupply     02-25 0508</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-AIDS-Blood Supply,510</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Blood Banks To Seek Ways To Protect Supply Against AIDS Infection</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL RECER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New screening techniques to further safeguard
blood donations from the AIDS virus are being studied by the
American Association of Blood Banks.
   The AABB announced Wednesday that the new study was prompted by
reports that ``have raised concerns about the safety of blood
transfusions administered to over 4 million people in the United
States annually.''
   A study published Feb. 25 in the New England Journal of Medicine
traced 13 units of blood infected by the AIDS virus back to seven
people who donated blood even though they had been recently exposed
to the virus.
   Blood banks and hospitals routinely test donated blood for the
human immune virus which causes AIDS, or acquired immune deficiency
syndrome. But the HIV tests are able only to detect antibodies
which may not develop until long after the exposure to the virus.
The AABB said Wednesday its study will test for the HIV antigen, a
marker that may appear in the blood of an infected person before
the antibodies.
   ``The results of this study will determine if an antigen test
would be useful in detecting individuals in early stages of
infection who donate blood,'' the statement said. It added that no
tests for the antigen have yet been licensed.
   Dr. Paul J. Schmidt, the AABB president, said current tests are
``nearly'' 99 percent sensitive, but do not detect people recently
exposed to HIV.
   ``We expected that there would be some infection developing in
transfusion recipients,'' he said. ``We are working on solutions to
the problem of detecting persons even earlier in this infectious
state, and on how to discourage them from donating blood.''
   Schmidt added: ``The risk from not getting a needed transfusion
is infinitely greater than the risk of getting one.''
   AIDS is a fatal disease that is spread most often through sexual
contact, needles or syringes shared by drug abusers, infected blood
or blood products, and from infected pregnant women to their
offspring.
   The federal Centers for Disease Control estimates that at least
1,350 Americans have been infected by the AIDS virus from
transfusions of blood or blood products since 1981. About 900
patients have died.
   A rigorous blood-screen program now has reduced the presence of
the virus in blood supplies to an estimated one unit in 50,000.
   As of Feb. 15, AIDS had been diagnosed in 53,814 Americans, of
whom more than half, 30,158, have died, according to the CDC. No
one is known to have recovered from AIDS.
   AIDS kills by destroying the immune system, leaving patients
susceptible to a host of opportunistic infections.
   Blood banks now screen donor candidates for AIDS risk factors,
but the AABB said it would review these procedures to determine if
they should be tightened.
   The AABB is the world's largest organization of blood banks and
transfusion services, with 2,500 members. It accredits blood banks
and transfusion services and sets standards for agencies collecting
nearly half the nation's donated blood.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
