<1ST_LINE>u a PM-StealthSuit     02-25 0372</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Stealth Suit,0382</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Northrop Accused in Suit of Overcharging on Bomber Project</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government has been overcharged more than
$1 billion for development of the Stealth bomber, according to a
lawsuit against Northrop Corp., the company building the secret
plane.
   The lawsuit was filed Wednesday in U.S. District Court here on
behalf of four current and former Northrop employees who could
collect part of any damages awarded to the government if the suit
were successful.
   The lawsuit, which was sealed under procedures followed in such
cases, accuses Northrop of double-billing, false billing and
misrepresented charges, said Robert Kilborne, the attorney
representing the employees.
   Northrop spokesman Tony Cantafio refused comment, citing a
company policy against responding publicly to lawsuits.
   The Air Force Office of Special Investitations has launched its
own investigation into the allegations, a standard step in such
cases, said Maj. Kathleen McCollom, a spokeswoman for the office.
   Kilborne refused to reveal the names of his clients, identifying
them only as an internal auditor, a former controller, a former
avionics engineer and a former test equipment engineer.
   The lawsuit alleges that Northrop destroyed internal audits that
turned up evidence of improper charges on development of the bomber.
   The plane, dubbed Stealth because it is designed to be difficult
to detect on enemy radar, is under development at the company's
plants in Pico Rivera and Palmdale.
   The audit documented $400 million in overcharges and estimated
those charges amounted to $1 billion by 1987, Kilborne said.
   The Los Angeles Times reported in today's editions the
overcharges alleged in the lawsuit amount to more than $2 billion.
   The lawsuit was brought under the federal False Claims Act,
which allows citizens to sue on behalf of the government and share
in any damage award. The Justice Department must join in the suit
for it to go forward, and the suit remains sealed up to 60 days
while that decision is made.
   It was filed by Kilborne, who with his law partner, Herbert
Hafif of Claremont has brought three other such suits against
Northrop in connection with its work on the MX missile program. In
October, the Justice Department moved to dismiss one of those suits
after failing to substantiate the allegations.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
