<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Simon-StayingIn     02-25 0806</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Simon-Staying In,830</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Simon's Illinois Backers Unfazed By Decision To Skip Super Tuesday
Contests</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BERNARD SCHOENBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   To home-state backers, Sen. Paul Simon's decision
to forgo a big Super Tuesday push has an important virtue _ it
beats seeing him drop out.
   Simon advocates in Illinois contacted Wednesday lauded Simon's
decision to stay in the race following disappointing showings in
the latest contests.
   The Illinois senator announced his new strategy in Washington,
saying that because of a lack of campaign money, there was little
he could do in the 20 states that vote on Super Tuesday, March 8.
   He is on the ballot in all the Super Tuesday primaries, but he
said he will do little or no campaigning in those states _ except
for the nationally televised debates that are a major feature of
the next two weeks.
   And, of course, he'll have a big edge in the Illinois primary,
which is a week after Super Tuesday.
   Simon, meeting here with about 150 supporters, many of them
delegate candidates and elected officials, offered assurances that
he's in the race to stay.
   ``So, there is no misunderstanding, I am on the ballot in every
state. We are in every district, and we are going to contest and
fight for every delegate and every vote,'' Simon said to cheers and
whistles.
   Some of Simon's Democratic rivals suggested that a candidate
who's not campaigning in the Super Tuesday contests poses little
threat.
   ``I have always believed that to win the nomination and to
ultimately win the presidency you can't have a regional strategy
and you can't run in just one part of the country and not others,''
said Rep. Richard Gephardt.
   And Tennessee Sen. Albert Gore, who is concentrating on the
Southern states, was asked whether any contender could afford to
sit out Super Tuesday.
   ``No,'' he said.
   Simon's backers were undaunted, though.
   ``We urged him to take a Midwestern industrial strategy,'' said
state Sen. Vince Demuzio, D-Carlinville, state Democratic chairman.
   Some supporters held out hope that Simon still has a chance to
win the Democratic nomination for president despite the lack of a
first-place finish in any of the early primaries and caucuses.
   Others said Simon has leverage to fashion the party ticket in
case there is no clear winner by the beginning of the Democratic
National Convention in Atlanta _ leverage that would be lost if
Simon were to drop out now.
   Simon himself cited ``growing evidence that for the first time
in recent history there will be no first-ballot winner at the
Democratic convention.''
   One delegate candidate, state Sen. Patrick Welch, D-Peru, also
said some politicians in Illinois, seeking to be Simon delegates
but facing their own races for offices from the county to state
legislative levels, don't want to be embarrassed with losses in the
delegate races.
   ``His (Simon's) campaign recruited a lot of elected individuals
to use their political operations to get Simon elected,'' Welch
said. ``This works both ways.''
   Simon also acknowledged he has had some pressure from Illinois
delegate candidates to stay in the race so they could get to the
convention.
   ``There are people in Illinois who want to go to the convention
and who are Simon delegates,'' he said at a news conference. But,
he said, ``This is not just an Illinois strategy. It is a strategy
to win.''
   State Sen. Dawn Clark Netsch, D-Chicago, said she is among
candidates for Simon-committed delegates who were dismayed when
Simon announced, after a third-place showing in New Hampshire, that
he would drop out of the race if he did not win in either Minnesota
or South Dakota. He later took back that statement and placed
fourth in both races Tuesday.
   Simon came in second in Iowa's Feb. 8 caucuses and third in New
Hampshire's Feb. 16 primary.
   Mrs. Netsch said she knew of no delegate candidate whose only
concern was getting to the convention.
   ``There may be some individuals who feel that way,'' she said,
but ``I can't imagine someone who is angry or upset only because
their ticket to the convention has gone down the drain.''
   Sen. Alan Dixon, D-Ill., said he had counseled Simon not to
waste resources in the Super Tuesday states.
   ``Whatever he gets (in delegates on) Super Tuesday, fine, but
don't spend any money,'' Dixon said.
   ``I firmly believe that he'll run first in Illinois,'' Dixon
said. ``He'll pick up a large bloc of delegates there, and I think
that will give him a bump _ the kind of a bump that (Rep. Richard)
Gephardt got coming out of Iowa.''
   Rep. Lane Evans, D-Ill., said Simon's support may have waned but
is still deep. Simon's campaign plunged into debt before the New
Hampshire primary, but he has collected close to half a million
dollars in the past two weeks.
</TEXT>
