<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Harding'sDeath     02-25 0326</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Harding's Death,0338</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Says President's Death Still A Mystery</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JACK SCHREIBMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge deliberated on the 65-year-old
puzzle of President Warren G. Harding's untimely death before
concluding, ``It's a mystery to me.''
   The ``ruling'' by Judge George T. Choppelas came after an
uproarious session Wednesday of the mock Court of Historical
Review, which considered suggestions that Harding's wife killed him
in 1923.
   But the ``spirit'' of Harding's widow, testifying in a
standing-room-only City Hall courtroom, said ``Madame X,'' her
fortuneteller, told her that Vice President Calvin Coolidge killed
the 29th president.
   It was the 50th session of the just-for-fun court that since
1975 has taken up such weighty questions as ``Who invented the
fortune cookie?'' and ``Is chicken soup Jewish penicillin?''
   Harding, whose administration was torn apart by such corruption
scandals as Teapot Dome, died at age 57 on Aug. 2, 1923, in San
Francisco's Palace Hotel. No autopsy was performed, and his body
was whisked back to Washington for burial.
   Attorney Frank Winston, arguing that Florence Harding killed her
husband, opened by ordering the courtroom to pay no attention to
his opponent, U.S. Attorney Joseph P. Russoniello.
   ``We'll set the record straight,'' snarled Winston, drawing
snorts of derision from Russoniello.
   ``Hmmm,'' said the judge, raising an eyebrow.
   ``I stand for truth, justice and the American way!'' announced
the government prosecutor.
   ``History can be tedious at times,'' sighed Choppelas, a
municipal court judge.
   Russoniello, arguing that the widow did not kill her husband,
claimed Mrs. Harding hated Coolidge and would hardly have done
anything to speed him into the presidency.
   Coolidge was ``a scoundrel,'' testified the ``widow,'' played by
attorney Diane Elan Wick, president of the Lawyers Club of San
Francisco.
   Police Chief Frank Jordan, who was ``sworn in'' and promised to
testify truthfully ``to the limit of my instability,'' affirmed
that local officials did not investigate Harding's death.
   ``It's a mystery to me,'' Choppelas concluded.
</TEXT>
