<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Markets,0255</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nikkei Closes Above 25,000 Mark; Dollar Edges Up Against Yen</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Tokyo Stock Exchange's key Nikkei average
closed above the 25,000-point level for the first time since the
October stock crash today, while the dollar rose marginally against
the Japanese yen.
   The 225-share Nikkei Stock Average rose 132.01 points, or 0.50
percent, in active trading to finish the day at 25,100.66.
   Sato Yamashita of Goldman Sachs in Tokyo said the market was
upbeat, although there was no special driving force behind its
rally.
   ``It's generating its own momentum,'' he said.
   Last October, on the day after a plunge of more than 500 points
in Wall Street's Dow Jones industrial average, the Nikkei index
fell more than 3,800 points, from 25,746.56 to 21,910.08.
   On Tokyo's foreign exchange market today the dollar closed at
128.80 yen, up a slight 0.05 yen from its close on Wednesday. Spot
volume totaled $13.3 billion.
   A dealer at a major commercial bank in Tokyo said Wednesday's
release of fourth-quarter U.S. trade figures showing that the
nation's trade deficit had declined from the previous quarter had
no major effect on the Tokyo market.
   ``Everyone's just ignoring the report,'' he added, speaking on
condition of anonymity.
   The U.S. foreign trade deficit stood at $40.2 billion for the
October-December 1987 quarter, down $200 million from the
July-September period, U.S. commerce officials said Wednesday. The
trade deficit with Japan, however, increased by $1.3 billion
dollars to $15 billion dollars.
</TEXT>
