<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Dole     02-25 0503</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dole,520</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dole Stumps In South Carolina, Stopover On Road To Super Tuesday</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONALD M. ROTHBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FLORENCE, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bob Dole is playing catch-up in South
Carolina and it helps to talk textiles and tobacco and have Strom
Thurmond at his side.
   Hopping from airport to airport on Wednesday, Dole was battling
to become competitive in a state where Vice President George Bush
and former television evangelist Pat Robertson were conceded to
have a large lead.
   In the battle for the 1988 Republican presidential nomination,
South Carolina has a unique role. Its primary is March 5, three
days before Super Tuesday when Republican voters in 17 states will
express their presidential choices in primaries or caucuses.
   ``The threshold to Super Tuesday,'' was how the Kansas senator
referred to South Carolina at Columbia, his first stop.
   Each of Dole's four stops followed the same pattern.
   First, his state campaign chairman introduced Thurmond, the
state's senior senator.
   ``In the beginning, I thought I'd remain neutral,'' said
Thurmond, describing all the Republican candidates as ``friends of
mine.''
   But, he went on, ``people came to me and wanted to know where I
stood.''
   So this week he announced he was supporting Dole.
   Thurmond called Dole ``the head man among the Republicans in the
Senate,'' a man who rose from humble beginnings, the son of
hard-working parents.
   ``In other words,'' he told people crowded into the Florence
airport ``they're not of the so-called elite, they weren't born
with silver spoons in their mouths.'' That's the kind of reference
Dole often uses to contrast his background to that of Bush.
   Thurmond found other, more practical aspects of Dole's
background to recommend the Kansan to South Carolina voters.
   ``Bob Dole supported the textile bill,'' said Thurmond, pointing
out that 300,000 textile industry jobs across the country had been
lost to foreign competition and that 126 textile plants had closed
in South Carolina.
   The South Carolina senator said that 45 percent of the jobs in
his state were in the textile industry.
   The legislation he referred to would limit imports.
   ``We have a textile bill up now,'' he said ``and he (Dole) is
obligated _ not obligated _ he has promised to support that and we
are proud of that.''
   As Republican leader of the Senate, Dole can play a significant
role in determining whether textile import legislation can come to
a vote in Congress, certainly more of a role than Bush or Robertson
could hope to play.
   Florence also is tobacco country and Dole was asked his view on
tobacco subsidies.
   He talked about his role in passage of the current subsidy
program which he described as operating at no cost to the taxpayers.
   ``A lot of people think, why are you subsidizing tobacco,'' he
said.
   ``Those people are farmers, too,'' he went on ``and they've got
a right to, make a living. I've supported the tobacco program in
every vote since I've been in Congress and I'm going to continue to
do so.''
</TEXT>
