<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Shultz-Scene     02-25 0427</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Shultz-Scene,0441</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Holy City Rolls Out Red Carpet For Shultz</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Israel-Shultz, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SERGEI SHARGORODSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   To guarantee the comfort of Secretary of State
George P. Shultz, the holy city saved him the best hotel room in
town, stocked up on exotic fruits and made him chocolates shaped
like the dove of peace.
   A white sculpture of a dove with a 12-foot wing span hangs in
the lobby of Hilton Hotel where the secretary will stay.
   When he arrives today for a five-day Middle East shuttle to
launch a new peace initiative, Shultz will occupy the 20th floor
Royal Suite in the hotel, which dominates the northwestern
outskirts of Jerusalem. His entourage will fill about 160 rooms,
hotel officials said.
   ``When you open the doors leading to the balcony, you see really
a stunning view of Jerusalem, with the whole Old City spread before
you,'' Alon Ben-Gurion, the hotel's deputy manager, told Israel's
army radio.
   Dina Doron, who will be responsible for the reception, said the
rooms have been decorated with orchids and other plants.
   Ben-Gurion said a cook ``was flown from Germany especially for
the occasion to make some sweets, chocolates in the form of doves.''
   ``Shultz ... likes very much seafood, and he usually tries local
dishes, so we brought a selection of Mediterranean fish. He also
likes beer, and usually drinks local beer. During his last visit he
drank (Israeli) Maccabee beer,'' he said.
   ``And, of course, the local fruits, all the exotic fruits that
we have today in Israel, like strawberries, kiwi, and oranges,''
Ben-Gurion added.
   The army radio reported that the hotel's pool has been heated to
the temperature of 79 degrees preferred by Shultz and that several
couples have been invited to play tennis with the secretary of
state.
   But other sights Shultz is likely to encounter in Jerusalem are
bound to be less peaceful.
   Airport police said special riot units were called in and will
stay on duty through Tuesday as Shultz conducts his mission.
   Jerusalem's police force was doubled to 3,000 to forestall
Palestinian protests during the Shultz visit, said city spokeswoman
Sivana Meryn.
   An army spokesman said Israeli police approached the army with a
request for extra manpower in Jerusalem and the military agreed. In
the mixed Arab-Jewish Abu Tor neighborhood, troops were seen
checking the identities of Arab teen-agers.
   It was apparently the first time troops were used in the holy
city since Israel united it after capturing the Arab east Jerusalem
from Jordan in the 1967 Middle East war.
</TEXT>
