<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ShuttleTest     02-25 0605</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Shuttle Test,0622</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Test Of Booster's Nozzle-To-Case Joint Called Success</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURIE SULLIVAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRIGHAM CITY, Utah (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The space shuttle program took another
step toward America's return to space with the apparently
successful fourth test of a joint on the redesigned booster rocket,
a NASA official says.
   Flaws deliberately built into the nozzle-to-case joint for
Wednesday's test allowed hot gases to reach the joint's primary
O-ring seal. But the O-ring stopped the gases from reaching the
secondary or final seal, said Royce Mitchell, NASA solid rocket
motor manager.
   ``It will prove that we can give up two of our seals, or two of
our lines of defense against this hot gas, and still have a good,
safe motor,'' Mitchell said following the six-second test at Morton
Thiokol Inc.'s Wasatch Operations plant 25 miles west of here.
   ``All indications are it's a good test, but we've got another
couple of these to go and, of course, our next motor test will be
in April,'' Mitchell said, adding that a complete analysis of the
joint's performance was not expected for several weeks.
   The solid-fuel rocket booster has undergone extensive redesign
since the Jan. 28, 1986, explosion of the shuttle Challenger that
killed the seven-member crew. The disaster was blamed on a faulty
seal in a booster joint that allowed hot gases to escape and ignite
the fuel tank.
   Wednesday's test, delayed two hours by replacement of a computer
board, was the fourth of six Nozzle Joint Environment Simulator
experiments and one of hundreds of booster component tests.
   The initially favorable results showed the shuttle program is
moving slowly but surely toward resumption of flights, Mitchell
said.
   ``We are maintaining our schedule for the August launch of
Discovery,'' he said. ``It's a very conservative approach.''
   The test was designed to evaluate the main seal's ability to
contain any gases that might leak through bonded adhesive
insulation and a rubber-like ``wiper'' O-ring during launch, said
Thiokol spokesman Rocky Raab.
   Engineers made a quarter-inch-by-five-hundredths-inch hole
through the insulation and disabled the wiper ring, creating two
flaws that assured a gas path to the primary seal.
   The double defects simulated coincidental manufacturing defects
in the insulation and wiper O-ring, a ``worst possible case'' that
likely could never occur, Raab said. It also subjected the joint to
more severe conditions than previous tests.
   The next test will increase the pressure because the primary
O-ring will be purposely flawed to permit gases to reach the
secondary O-ring, Mitchell said. The final test will simulate
complete failure.
   Engineers concluded after the third nozzle-joint test Oct. 8
that the O-ring system withstood gas pressure after a single flaw
was built into the joint, which connects the nozzle to the body of
the segmented booster rocket.
   However, during a full-scale test Dec. 23, a ``blow hole'' was
detected in the joint's adhesive sealant, a defect NASA had not
built into the test.
   Blow holes can occur during assembly of the 126-foot-long
rocket, ``so it happens here at the factory, if it happens,'' Raab
said.
   While the blow hole was not considered a major problem, the
failure of a nozzle boot ring during the December test prompted
NASA officials to delay the scheduled June 2 resumption of shuttle
flights.
   Raab said the test Wednesday simulated ``the most difficult
portion of the environment for the O-rings, that is the first one
second'' of launch.
   In addition to the final two nozzle-to-case tests scheduled
before shuttle flights resume, NASA and Thiokol will conduct
several more Joint Environment Simulator Tests of the booster
rocket and three more full-scale horizontal tests, in April, June
and July.
</TEXT>
