<1ST_LINE>r w PM-CervicalCap     02-25 0320</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Cervical Cap,320</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Advisory Panel Urges Approval Of Women's Birth Control Device</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The birth control device known as the cervical
cap appears headed for regulatory approval after seven years of
testing.
   The device, already used by women in Great Britain and several
other countries, received the green light Wednesday by the Food and
Drug Administration's Obstetrics-Gynecology Devices Advisory Panel.
   The unanimous recommendation was non-binding, but the FDA
usually follows the advice of such panels of outside experts it
maintains to help assess clinical studies.
   The cervical cap is medically similar to the diaphragms already
used by an estimated 3 million U.S. women, but it was not widely
used in the United States in 1977 when Congress ordered FDA to
strengthen its regulation of birth control and other medical
devices.
   Diaphragms and condoms were given ``grandfather'' FDA approval
at that time without the stringent testing subsequently required of
new medical devices.
   In the testing financed by the National Institutes of Health,
the cap has been available to about 50,000 women in 29 states and
the District of Columbia.
   Rather than covering the entire roof of the vagina as a
diaphragm does, the cap fits over the tip of the cervix and thus
allows for more sensitivity during intercourse.
   Another advantage is that it can remain in place longer than the
diaphragm without additional application of spermicide, which is
recommended for use with the cap as it is with the diaphragm.
   Although many women typically wore the cap for three days at a
time in the clinical trials, the panel decided to recommend that it
remain in place no longer than two days at a time. Similar
recommendations for the diaphragm say it should not stay in place
more than 24 hours.
   The cap was found to be 94.6 percent effective in preventing
pregnancy when worn for every instance of intercourse compared to
96.4 percent for the diaphragm.
</TEXT>
