<1ST_LINE>r a PM-EuthanasiaSurvey     02-25 0346</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Euthanasia Survey,0353</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hemlock Society Burns Survey in Which Doctors Admit Euthanasia</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Survey forms on which doctors admitted
helping with mercy killings of terminally ill patients have been
burned to protect the doctors from possible criminal prosecution, a
``right-to-die'' group said.
   The survey responses, including 20 signed forms from doctors who
said they had helped patients, were destroyed because of a ``witch
hunt'' for a doctor who described a mercy killing in a medical
journal, said Derek Humphry, executive director of the Hemlock
Society.
   ``Some people have noticed evidence buried in the survey of what
I would call compassionate crimes,'' Humphry said Tuesday. ``We
decided to destroy the evidence before there is any official
inquiry, and therefore not break any law. We would not want to get
these kindly doctors into trouble.''
   The society, which promotes euthanasia, or mercy killing, last
week released results of the survey showing 51 percent of
California doctors responding would practice euthanasia where they
considered it appropriate.
   Asked if they had ever helped a patient die, 79 of 588 doctors
responded positively, and 20 of those put their names on their
responses, Humphrey said. Of those doctors who had taken the life
of a patient, 15 said they had done it once, 35 said they had done
it two or three times and 29 said they had done it more than three
times, he said.
   The society's news release didn't describe how the doctors
surveyed were selected or how representative they are.
   Humphry said concern over possible prosecution was prompted by
calls for criminal charges against a doctor who wrote anonymously
in the Jan. 8 issue of the Journal of the American Medical
Association of a mercy killing.
   The letter to the editor, titled ``It's Over, Debbie,'' prompted
calls for prosecution from New York Mayor Edward Koch among others.
The district attorney in Cook County, Ill., where the journal is
published, is seeking the name of the letter writer, but the
journal has resisted.
   The Hemlock Society, which claims 23,000 members, is based in
Los Angeles.
</TEXT>
