<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Israel-Intellectuals     02-25 0717</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel-Intellectuals,0740</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Palestinian Disturbances Shake Up Israeli Intellectual Community</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Israel-Violence, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN IZENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Violent Palestinian riots have spilled onto
canvas and into lyrics as many Israeli artists and intellectuals
rebel against government policy in the occupied territories.
   The intellectual rebellion has galvanized the dovish camp but so
far has had no noticeable effect on the middle-of-the road voter
whose support will determine what path Israel follows in the peace
process in elections this November.
   One hundred writers, actors, singers and other well-known
figures in the arts published an advertisement in Israeli
newspapers last week calling for an end to army brutality against
the Palestinians.
   On Saturday, more than 100 artists and photographers are
scheduled to take part in a protest exhibition, many of them
displaying works made since the unrest broke out.
   ``It is not as much the occupation that worries me as what has
happened to us,'' said Nira Yitzhaki, an art gallery owner who is
organizing the exhibition. ``We have lost our humanity.''
   Six art galleries will host the show under the banner: ``We
Favor Immediate Talks With the Palestinians and an End to the
Occupation.''
   Representatives of more than 10 groups of writers, playwrights,
students and university academics are co-ordinating a protest
campaign.
   Playwrights are mounting a vigil outside Prime Minister Yitzhak
Shamir's home, calling for negotiations with Palestinian leaders.
   A growing number of Israelis in the arts, many of them leaders
in their fields, have started to protest the 20-year-long
occupation and the harsh army crackdown on Palestinian
demonstrators.
   According to U.N. figures, more than 60 Palestinians have been
killed since violence began Dec. 8 in the occupied West Bank and
Gaza Strip, which Israel captured from Jordan and Egypt during the
1967 Middle East war.
   Some of the more popular entertainers could be putting their
careers on the line by taking sides in Israel's highly polarized
and emotional debate.
   Among them is Cee Heiman, an up-and-coming rock 'n' roll singer
who recently cut her first record.
   During an appearance last Saturday at an avant-garde theatre run
by the left-wing Mapam Party, Heiman sang the first Israeli protest
song of the current Palestinian uprising.
   The song, ``Shooting and Crying,'' has some tough lyrics.
   ``The window in my home is broken and Tel Aviv rushes in,'' sang
Heiman. ``Even its smell has changed. Boys play with lead and girls
with dolls of steel. Life looks different in the shadow of the
filth.''
   ``We shoot and cry, laugh and burn. Whenever did we learn how to
bury people alive. We shoot and cry, laugh and burn. When did we
forget there was a time our children were also killed.''
   But Aharon Appelfeld, a Holocaust survivor and one of Israel's
internationally known writers, said the intellectuals are
contributing to the discord which is ripping Israeli society apart.
   ``Instead of being a moderating influence, the intellectuals are
adding to the extremism,'' he said in an interview. ``I'm very
afraid of the polarization and they keep fanning the flames.''
   Appelfeld, author of such books as ``Badenheim, 1939'' and ``The
Age of Wonders'' said he agreed Israel should not rule over the
Palestinians but disliked the way the intellectuals were presenting
their arguments.
   ``They are saying that in the present situation the Arabs are
the good guys and the Jews the bad ones,'' he said. ``The Arabs
want to negotiate with us and we don't want to. But this is not
true.
   ``Most Israelis feel that the Arabs still do not accept us in
this region,'' Appelfeld said. ``We want to hear voices from the
other side telling us we are welcome, telling us they won't throw
us into the sea.''
   He warned that the arguments used by Israeli intellectuals were
alienating the silent majority of Israelis who strive for peace but
have genuine and legitimate concerns.
   ``The mainly Ashkenazi (European-origin) intellectuals have not
found a way to reach the religious community or the Sephardis (who
come from Arabic-speaking countries),'' Appelfeld said. ``They are
not rabble. They are people with genuine fears and they must be
understood.''
   ``I am very afraid that two large camps may be formed which
could reach the point of civil war,'' said Appelfeld. ``It's our
job not to light that fire. That's a heavy responsibility.''
</TEXT>
