<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Lites     02-25 0360</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lites,0375</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>On The Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GULF SHORES, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   David Walter says customers will have
to wade for a table at the restaurant he hopes to moor off this
Gulf Coast resort.
   Walter has applied to the U.S. Army Corps of Engineers for a
permit allowing him to moor a 50-foot-long oil field jack-up boat
converted into a restaurant and bar.
   The restaurant would sit in the surf within 50 feet of the beach
in about 3 feet of water, he said recently.
   The eatery would be jacked up on four legs and would face the
beach. Customers would wade through the water and walk up a ramp to
enter the restaurant.
   ``You have to wear something you can get wet,'' Walter said.
Shoes aren't required.
   Walter said he expects his customers to be ``the bathing suit
people'' who lie on the beach, and hopes to do business from May 15
to Sept. 15.
   He said the restaurant initially won't be open at night for
safety reasons. He also has yet to work out a menu, but said the
food will be ``nothing elaborate.''
   If the establishment is not successful, Walter said, he can just
``push two levers and move the boat off and drive away.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BOONVILLE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   No Posie Tweets from the Bright Lights
allowed.
   In ``Boontling'' dialect, that means no flower children from a
big city will be accepted in the four- to eight-week course in
Boontling that will be offered this summer to children in Boonville.
   Jack June, a 65-year resident of Boonville, is one of about a
dozen ``true literates'' of the unusual dialect spoken only in the
little village about 180 miles north of San Francisco.
   ``I'd like to see it (the course), but not if it's half-eesled.
If it's half-eesled, just shy it. Does more harm than good,'' June
said.
   ``Half eesled,'' loosely translated, means ``half-baked.''
   The Mendocino County Convention and Visitors' Bureau has
approved a $1,000 grant to be used as seed money for the pilot
program.
   Officials said the Boontling program may blossom into a
prototype for eventual use in addition to English in Boonville
schools.
</TEXT>
