<1ST_LINE>u i PM-SovietMissiles     02-25 0297</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet Missiles,0306</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviets Start Loading Missiles on Train in Preparation for Removal</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALISON SMALE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet soldiers have started
loading shorter-range SS-12 nuclear missiles onto railroad cars in
preparation for the rockets' removal from Czechoslovakia, the
official news agency said today.
   The loading was taking place in the Moravian town of Hranice,
the news agency CTK added.
   According to the report, the missiles were transported during
the night from a nearby military zone to the railway station where
the loading operation began.
   Czechoslovakia announced Wednesday that the Soviet rockets would
be removed before the U.S. Congress votes on ratification of the
superpowers' missile treaty signed last December in Washington.
   CTK added that the first of the missiles would leave Hranice for
the Soviet Union this evening.
   Foreign Ministry spokesman Dusan Rovensky said Wednesday evening
that under an agreement between Czechoslovakia and the Soviet
Union, ``the withdrawal of Soviet army rocket units armed with
operational-tactical missiles from Czechoslovak territory will
start on Feb. 25.''
   CTK said the removal of the Soviet missiles was being watched by
60 reporters, but it was not known if any Western journalists were
invited.
   A farewell meeting between Hranice citizens and Soviet soldiers
was scheduled for the afternoon, CTK noted.
   Hranice, with a population of 12,500, has been singled out by
Czechoslovak officials as the only place in the country where
Soviet missiles had been stationed.
   ``The step of the Soviet government, the removal of
operational-tactical shorter-range missiles before ratification of
the Soviet-American agreement, is further proof of the sincerity,
concreteness and constructive approach of the Soviet peace policy
to nuclear disarmament and the creation of a more secure world,''
CTK said.
   The withdrawal coincides with the 40th anniversary of Communist
rule in Czechoslovakia.
</TEXT>
