<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Prague-Anniversary     02-25 0483</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Prague-Anniversary,0499</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Czechoslovak Leader Keeps Tight Rein On Economy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALISON SMALE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Communist Party leader Milos Jakes
condemned the social reforms that were crushed by Soviet-led troops
20 years ago, and said the nation will maintain central planning of
the economy.
   Speaking at a celebration Wednesday marking the 40th anniversary
of the communist takeover in Czechoslovakia, Jakes gave little
indication he is about to favor economic and political reforms
similar to those being tried in the Soviet Union, Poland, Hungary
and Bulgaria.
   The 65-year-old Jakes also ruled out all non-communist
opposition.
   Jakes took over party leadership last December from Gustav
Husak, now 75, who was chairman of the solemn meeting on Wednesday.
   Jakes' hourlong speech to 500 party members in Prague's Hradcany
Castle did not essentially differ from the cautious conservatism
Husak displayed during his 18-year tenure.
   The speech preceded celebrations that will include a mass rally
today in Prague's Old Town Square, scene of a triumphant speech by
then-Communist Party leader Klement Gottwald on Feb. 21, 1948.
   Jakes asserted that an economic restructuring process was under
way concerning ``a new framework of the sphere of action for
central bodies.''
   But he hastened to add, ``These measures are in no way meant as
steps toward weakening the role of the centrally managed economy.''
   He revealed that part of the ministerial bureaucracy will be
reassigned to productive work, and, in an apparent allusion to
reform-minded neighboring Hungary, said: ``There is no threat of
unemployment in Czechoslovakia.''
   Jakes attacked the communists who, under the leadership of
Alexander Dubcek, tried in 1968 to introduce some reforms
resembling those recently instituted or proposed by Mikhail S.
Gorbachev in the Soviet Union.
   As head of the party's chief disciplinary body from 1968 to
1977, Jakes was responsible for purging 500,000 people from the
Communist Party after the invasion. Jakes denied there is a need to
reassess the official view of 1968.
   He also rejected any comparison between Dubcek's reforms and
Gorbachev's innovations. The party chief lauded the ``assistance''
Czechoslovakia received from the Soviet Union and its allies to
obliterate Dubcek's reform efforts.
   The communists received nearly 40 percent of the vote in
elections in 1946, but assumed sole power only after a series of
political maneuvers from Feb. 20-25, 1948. Czechoslovakia was the
last country in Eastern Europe to turn communist, setting the seal
on Kremlin domination of the region.
   ``It was no communist coup, as it's always described by hostile
propaganda,'' Jakes said of the 1948 takeover. ``It was the will of
the people.''
   He also issued a warning to the Charter 77 human rights movement
and other non-conformists who are banned from public life in
Czechoslovakia.
   ``The broadening of democratization in no case means the
creation of space for the legalization of political opposition
which, as all experiences to date show, cannot be other than
anti-Socialist,'' said Jakes.
</TEXT>
