<FILEID>AP-NR-02-25-88 0628EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Cyprus-Prospects     02-25 0543</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Cyprus-Prospects,0562</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New President Raises Settlement Hopes, But Problems Remain</HEAD>
<BYLINE>AP News Analysis</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>By ALEX EFTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The election of a dynamic tycoon as
president and a thaw in Greek-Turkish relations has raised hopes
for a settlement of ethnic disputes on this Mediterranean island.
   The Cyprus question has long soured relations between Greece and
Turkey, two NATO allies, posing a potentially serious weakness in
the Atlantic alliance's vulnerable southern flank.
   George Vassiliou, 56, a self-made millionaire, was elected
Cyprus' president for a five-year term Feb. 21. He ran as an
independent with the powerful Communist Party his main backer on a
platform of ``time for change.''
   He vowed to be flexible and work for ``quick results'' to
reunite Cyprus, partitioned since Turkey invaded in 1974 and
occupied the northern third of the island.
   As leader of the 500,000-strong Greek Cypriot majority,
Vassiliou has said he is prepared to meet with Rauf Denktash,
president of the breakaway Turkish Cypriot republic proclaimed in
the north in 1983 and recognized only by Turkey.
   But Vassiliou must overcome deep distrust and military buildups
on both sides which U.N. Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar
has warned could trigger a new confrontation.
   Vassiliou, a political newcomer, is widely viewed as more
flexible than his predecessor, Spyros Kyprianou. But Vassiliou
remains committed to the withdrawal of some 30,000 Turkish troops
and 50,000 Turkish settlers from the north and the return of
200,000 Greek Cypriot refugees.
   Turkey and Denktash insist the troops are needed to protect the
120,000 Turkish Cypriots.
   Hints by the Turkish government that it might be prepared to
pull out some troops in advance of any agreement fueled hopes of
progress.
   It is not clear what concessions Vassiliou is prepared to make.
   Negotiations under U.N. auspices have been deadlocked for three
years because of Kyprianou's hard line.
   Kyprianou had the rug pulled from under him two weeks before the
election, when Greek Prime Minister Andreas Papandreou, who for
years refused to negotiate with Turkey, changed his mind.
   Papandreou conferred with Turkish Prime Minister Turgut Ozal in
the Swiss resort of Davos in late January. The meeting ended with a
``no war'' agreement and an announced determination to settle all
outstanding differences peacefully.
   Apart from the Cyprus problem, what has brought brought Greece
and Turkey to the brink of war repeatedly in recent years is the
issue of territorial waters and underwater oilfields in the Aegean
Sea.
   Greece and Turkey sought to patch together a settlement of the
Cyprus problem in 1958 in what Greek Cypriots refer to as ``the
ignominious, imposed Zurich agreement.''
   This laid the groundwork for independence from Britain two years
later. Under that agreement, the island's constitution gave the
Turkish Cypriot minority, 17 percent of the population, equal
political status with the Greek Cypriots.
   The agreement also made Britain, Greece and Turkey guarantor
powers with the right to intervene.
   That is widely seen by Greek Cypriots as sowing the seeds for
Turkey's subsequent invasion on the pretext of protecting Turkish
Cypriots after a short-lived coup by supporters of union with
Greece plotted with the colonels' junta then in power in Athens.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Alex Efty has been Cyprus correspondent for The
Associated Press for 30 years.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880225-0069 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-25-88 0630EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Britain-Ireland     02-25 0743</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Britain-Ireland,0765</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Relations Getting Worse Almost Day by Day Over Northern Ireland</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCUS ELIASON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After a prolonged warm spell, relations between
Britain and Ireland appear to be going into a dangerous free fall
over a spate of incidents involving the conduct of British security
forces in Northern Ireland.
   So severe is the strain that fears are being voiced for the
survival of the 1985 Anglo-Irish Agreement, the accord that gave
Dublin a say in the running of Northern Ireland and was responsible
for the relative amity that existed between Britain and Ireland
until the beginning of the year.
   The harmony was jolted on Jan. 25. The British government
announced that, having investigated the shooting of six unarmed
Roman Catholics by Northern Ireland police in 1982, authorities
uncovered evidence of a conspiracy to pervert the course of justice
_ yet no policemen would be prosecuted.
   Matters grew worse the same week when a British court rejected
the appeal of six Irishmen who claim they were wrongly convicted of
a 1974 bombing attack in mainland Britain that killed 21 people.
   The Irish government said that despite the ruling, it continued
to believe a miscarriage of justice may have occurred.
   That dispute was quickly followed by a new one as Ireland
accused London of failing to abide by the conditions Dublin has set
for extraditing Irish Republican Army suspects to Britain.
   Next, the British government announced it was making its tough
anti-terrorism law, which requires annual parliamentary renewal,
permanent. Many Irish believe the law tars them with the brush of
the IRA. Only after outcry in Ireland did Britain restore
Parliament's right to review the law annually.
   Tempers grew worse on Sunday when Aidan McAnespie, a 23-year-old
Catholic and supporter of the outlawed IRA's legal political wing,
Sinn Fein, was shot dead from an army observation tower as he was
walking through a security checkpoint on the Ireland-Northern
Ireland border.
   The army expressed regret and the soldier who fired the shot was
charged Wednesday with unlawful killing.
   The Royal Ulster Constabulary said it was investigating the
shooting, but Irish Prime Minister Charles Haughey ordered his own
force to investigate, too.
   This outraged the British, who saw it as a gesture of disdain
for the Royal Ulster Constabulary's efforts. Prime Minister
Margaret Thatcher pointedly warned the Irish to keep their
investigation to their own side of the border.
   She also voiced annoyance at Dublin's behavior on the
extradition issue.
   But then, on Tuesday, the army dropped a new bombshell. It
announced that Pvt. Ian Thain, the only British soldier ever jailed
for life for killing a civilian in Northern Ireland, was free on
parole and back in his regiment, having served only three years of
his term.
   Even the conservative Daily Telegraph, which usually takes
Britain's side in disputes with Britain, called it an act of
``stunning insensitivity.''
   Among Northern Ireland's Catholic minority, angry reactions came
not just from Sinn Fein militants, but from moderates like Cardinal
Tomas O Fiaich, head of Ireland's Roman Catholic church. He called
McAnespie's death ``murder,'' and said Thain's release ``add insult
to injury.''
   A British official who spoke on condition of anonymity said the
incidents were ``a spasm'' in Anglo-Irish relations, not a pattern.
He said Britain's critics were failing to take into account that
the security forces in Northern Ireland were up against a terrorist
organization in a civil war that has claimed more than 2,500 lives
since 1969.
   But Merlyn Rees, a former Northern Ireland secretary, warned
that the Anglo-Irish Agreement was ``tottering.''
   In Dublin, the Irish Press commented: ``There is an alarming but
unmistakable pattern emerging from the behavior of the British
government toward our government. It is almost as if it is trying
to provoke Mr. Haughey into a rash decision.''
   So far the Irish prime minister has kept cool and refrained from
anti-British rhetoric. Most important, perhaps, is his clear
determination to carry on fighting the IRA.
   Police have uncovered several large IRA arms caches north and
south of the border, including one on Wednesday night near Dublin
that contained explosives, grenades and two dozen assault rifles.
   The Irish Press editorialized that it was Britain's system of
justice that had alienated Northern Ireland's Catholics and pushed
some of them into the IRA's embrace.
   It was that alienation that was supposed to be tackled by the
Anglo-Irish Agreement, the paper said, adding: ``That hope is
fading by the week.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
