<1ST_LINE>u i PM-BritishStocks     02-25 0157</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-British Stocks,0160</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Share Prices Higher In Early London Trading</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices rose in early London trading today
with insurance companies showing the strongest gains.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100 index was up 8.5 points
at 1,768.6 at 9:45 a.m. When the market opened at 9 a.m., the index
was up 4.2 at 1,764.3.
   Insurance companies led the gains after Royal Insurance
announced 1987 earnings that were generally better than market
expectations. Royal's pre-tax profit fell 10 percent to 274.0
million pounds in calendar 1987 from 304.8 million pounds the
previous year.
   Royal shares were up 7 pence at 408 pence. Among the other
insurers, General Accident rose 16 to 877 and Commercial Union
gained 10 to 330.
   The early trend followed a small gain in New York Wednesday,
where the Dow Jones industrial average rose 0.83 to 2,039.95, and a
rise in Tokyo overnight, where the Nikkei index climbed 132.01 to
25,100.66.
</TEXT>
