<1ST_LINE>r p PM-PoliticalBriefs     02-25 1087</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Political Briefs,1100</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Poll Shows Bush, Dukakis Favorites For Super Tuesday</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrat Mike Dukakis and Vice President George
Bush appear to be the favorites in the March 8 Super Tuesday
primary elections and caucuses, according to The Denver Post-Gallup
Poll.
   The poll showed Dukakis as the runaway favorite in his home
state of Massachusetts, with 61 percent of the voters saying they
favor their governor. Thirteen percent said they supported Richard
Gephardt; 7 percent Sen. Paul Simon; 6 percent for Jesse Jackson; 3
percent for Sen. Albert Gore, and 2 percent for Gary Hart,
according to the poll.
   Democrats in the 13 Southern states holding primaries or
caucuses on March 8 give Dukakis 26 percent; Gore 18 percent;
Jackson 16 percent; Gephardt 12 percent; Hart 11 percent and Simon
6 percent, the poll results show.
   The poll showed that while Bush still is the solid GOP favorite
in the South and in Massachusetts, Sen. Bob Dole has made
significant gains during the past month of campaigning.
   Bush is favored by 54 percent of the Republicans most likely to
vote in the Southern states March 8, while Dole has the backing of
33 percent the poll shows.
   The poll was conducted by the Gallup Organization of Princeton,
N.J., on Feb. 19-21 through telephone interviews with 1729
registered Republicans and Democrats in the Southern states,
Massachusetts an Oklahoma.
   In the GOP races, the poll's margin of error was plus or minus 6
percent, and in the Democratic contests, the margin was 5 percent.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Hart Camp Struggles To Make New York Primary</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The coordinator of Gary Hart's New York
campaign effort says he is in a race against the clock to get the
former Colorado senator on New York's April 19 presidential primary
ballot.
   ``It's pretty close,'' said John Kaiman. ``The system itself
stinks and when you have a controversial candidate ... it's almost
impossible.''
   Hart was forced out of the presidential race for a time after it
came out that he had spent a weekend in the company of Miami model
Donna Rice.
   To get on the New York ballot, Democratic candidates have until
midnight tonight to get postmarks on petitions containing the
signatures of at least 10,000 registered New York Democrats. At
least 100 signatures must come from each of 17 of the state's 34
congressional districts.
   With New York sending the second largest delegations, after
California, to the national conventions, the state's April 19 could
be crucial to both Democratic and Republican candidates.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Hazeltine: Complaints About Exit Polling Received</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SIOUX FALLS, S.D. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Problems with exit polling were
reported to local and state election officials during Tuesday's
presidential primary, said South Dakota Secretary of State Joyce
Hazeltine.
   ``There were definitely statewide problems. Some exit pollsters
thought that they had been mistreated,'' Hazeltine said in a
telephone interview.
   Hazeltine said she was pleased with the number of people who
voted.
   ``I thought it was great,'' she said of the 43 percent overall
turnout.
   Just over 45 percent of the state's 206,585 registered
Republicans and almost 40 percent of the 179,641 registered
Democrats voted Tuesday.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Simon Still A Contender In Washington</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OLYMPIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Illinois Sen. Paul Simon may have bowed out of
Super Tuesday contention in the South, but he hasn't written off
Washington and will make a campaign swing here, according to state
campaign organizers.
   But Jeff Smith, executive director of the Washington State
Democratic Party, said the senator's campaign moratorium could
greatly dampen his chances of doing well here.
   Simon had been seen as No. 2 presidential hopeful in Washington,
behind Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis. But with Simon
downplaying Super Tuesday, the race is ``increasingly defined'' as
a strong Dukakis victory, with Simon slipping, Smith said.
   Simon has scheduled campaign appearances in four Washington
cities early next week, and still hopes to come in no worse than a
strong second in the state's March 8 caucuses, insisted state
organizer Beth Doglio.
   Simon announced in Washington, D.C., on Wednesday he is
bypassing the 20-state Super Tuesday, mostly in the South and
border states, because he was low on funds and did not see the
day's caucuses as being decisive or critical.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Robertson Campaign Asks For Vote Recount, Secretary Of State Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SIOUX FALLS, S.D. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pat Robertson, who fell just short of
the threshold needed to win Republican South Dakota delegates, has
asked for a recount of presidential primary votes, according to the
secretary of state.
   Robertson received 18,279 votes or 19.6 percent of the
Republican votes cast in Tuesday's election. A candidate needed at
least 20 percent of Republican votes in order to receive any of
South Dakota's 18 delegates to the Republican National Convention.
   Kansas Sen. Bob Dole garnered 55 percent of the vote, the only
Republican to receive more than 20 percent.
   Secretary of State Joyce Hazeltine said Robertson would need 382
more votes to reach the 20 percent mark.
   Her staff and Attorney General Roger Tellinghuisen are reviewing
South Dakota statutes to see whether a recount is allowed after a
primary election.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Robertson Campaign Will Register New Voters</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A spokesman for presidential hopeful Pat
Robertson says the former television evangelist will try to mold an
Ohio version of his ``invisible army'' through the registration of
new voters during March.
   Ray Jeske, executive director of the Republican's campaign, said
Wednesday the effort will include a mailings, along with direct
appeals to members of about 3,000 Ohio churches. ``March is going
to be voter registration month,'' he said.
   He said there also will be training seminars and other events at
which Democrats will be advised how to cross over and obtain GOP
ballots in order to support Robertson in the May 3 primary.
   However Ohio law will require a strategy adjustment because it
requires voters to register 30 days before the primary. While
registrants do not declare their party affiliations up front, they
later join one of the major parties by requesting its ballot at the
polling place.
   Democrats or Republicans already registered on May 3, as a
result of past voting, can cross over by signing a statement that
they now support the principles of the other party, Jeske pointed
out.
   Robertson claims strong support among Democrats, who apparently
have backed his campaign in other states. In Iowa, for example,
crossover voting, which does not require advance registration, and
what Robertson calls his ``invisible army'' showed up at
neighborhood caucuses to help him finish second.
</TEXT>
