<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Iran-Iraq     02-25 0258</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Iran-Iraq,0266</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iran Reports Fighting In Northeast Iraq; Iraq Denies It</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran said its Revolutionary Guards
destroyed 14 Iraqi military bases near the northestern Iraqi oil
city of Kirkuk, then crushed an Iraqi counterattack. Iraq denied
there had been any fighting.
   Iran said the guards were assisted in the military operations
Wednesday and today by guerrillas fighting the Iraqi government and
by Kurdish rebels.
   The official Islamic Republic News Agency said the raiders
killed or wounded 500 Iraqi troops in the area 50 miles southeast
of Kirkuk, a major oil center located 110 miles northeast of the
Iraqi capital of Baghdad.
   Iraq denied fighting occurred in the area. The official Iraqi
News Agency quoted a military spokesman as saying the claim that
hundreds of Iraqis were killed or wounded was ``a new lie which
will be added to many other lies.''
   The Iranian agency said the Iraqi counteroffensive failed and
the Iraqi troops were forced to retreat. It said the guards, the
Iranian-backed Iraqi Moslem guerrillas and the Kurdish rebels
destroyed 14 Iraqi military bases and seized several strategic
heights near Kirkuk.
   The location of the attack, and its apparently modest scale,
indicated it was not the major offensive Western military analysts
had expected Iran to launch this winter. Iran and Iraq have been at
war for more than eight years.
   The analysts say Iran is facing difficulties recruiting enough
volunteers for the front. They say only 150,000 Iranian warriors
were massed on the southern border, at least 100,000 less than
earlier estimates.
</TEXT>
