<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Dollar-Gold     02-25 0336</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dollar-Gold,0356</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Slightly Higher In Thin Trading</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar edged higher in thin European
trading today as the market waited for the release of revised U.S.
economic growth figures for the fourth quarter of 1987.
   Gold prices were slightly lower following heavy falls on
Wednesday.
   Dealers said they hoped the gross national product figures,
scheduled for release later today, would give some new direction to
the market and lift it out of the doldrums.
   ``A good GNP figure would reduce worries about the U.S. economy,
but it wouldn't change the fundamental (negative) picture,'' one
dealer at a U.S. bank in Frankfurt said.
   Other dealers said they don't expect more than a short burst of
activity from the GNP figures.
   ``Indicators have been mostly ignored recently,'' a Frankfurt
dealer said. ``Beside the trade figures, nothing is really
important.''
   In Tokyo, where the business day ends before Europe's business
day begins, the dollar rose 0.05 yen to a closing 128.80 yen.
Later, in London, it climbed to 129.02 yen.
   Other dollar rates at mid-morning, compared with late
Wednesday's rates:
   _1.6968 West German marks, up from 1.6925
   _1.3965 Swiss francs, up from 1.3908
   _5.74145 French francs, up from 5.7240
   _1.90375 Dutch guilders, up from 1.8990
   _1,249.50 Italian lire, up from 1,246.25
   _1.2658 Canadian dollars, up from 1.2651
   In London, the dollar rose against the British pound. It cost
$1.76135 to buy one pound, cheaper than $1.7640 late Wednesday.
   Bullion dealers said gold remained weak after falling through
several technical resistance points on Wednesday.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $433.20 a troy ounce and
at mid-morning, the city's five major bullion dealers fixed a
recommended price of $433.95. Both were down from Wednesday's late
bid of $434.70.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $433.40, down from $434.70 late
Wednesday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell $7.85 to close at a bid $436.35.
   Silver was quoted in London today a bid price of $6.20 a troy
ounce, down from Wednesday's $6.26.
</TEXT>
