<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Pakistan-Armacost     02-25 0350</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Pakistan-Armacost,0360</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Official Meets Rebels, Pakistanis On Afghan Accord</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Najib is correct as one name</NOTE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Undersecretary of State Michael
Armacost today discussed with Pakistan's president recent moves
toward a Soviet troop withdrawal from Afghanistan, officials said.
   Armacost also met for nearly two hours with Afghan Moslem
guerrilla leaders in Pakistan in what a U.S. Embassy official said
was a ``frank and open'' exchange Wednesday.
   He was scheduled to travel next to India for similar talks
before flying back to Washington.
   Armacost's swing through the region follows Secretary of State
George P. Shultz' trip to Moscow this week, where Shultz discussed
the Soviets' pledge to begin leaving Afghanistan by May 15,
depending on the outcome of the next round of U.N.-sponsored peace
talks in Geneva.
   Pakistan, a participant in the Geneva talks, has added a
condition that a military settlement to the fighting in Afghanistan
be coupled with a political settlement to ensure Afghan stability
during a Soviet troop pullout.
   Washington has said only that a political solution would be
``desirable'' and indicated it is willing to settle for an
agreement on a timetable for a Soviet pullout in exchange for a
halt in U.S. military aid to the guerrillas.
   The rebel alliance, under Chairman Yunis Khalis, reportedly
reiterated its vow to Armacost that the guerrillas will continue
fighting until they install themselves as an all-Moslem government
in Kabul.
   One of the more extremist resistance leaders, Gulbaddin
Hekmatyar of the Hezb-i-Islami party, on Wednesday accused
Washington of betraying the guerrilla cause by striking a secret
deal with Moscow on ending the war.
   Pakistani President Mohammad Zia ul-Haq has said Pakistan will
not sign any accord with the present Kabul government, headed by
communist leader Najib.
   Pakistan, in addition to serving as headquarters for the
guerrillas, also shelters about 3.5 million refugees from the
9-year-old Afghan civil war.
   The past weeks have seen hectic diplomatic activity in all
countries involved in the Afghan conflict to prepare for the next,
and possibly final, round of Geneva talks between Pakistan and
Afghanistan, scheduled to begin March 2.
</TEXT>
