<HEAD>Woman Fined for Smuggling Rat into Britain</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TEIGNBRIDGE, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Magistrates fined an unemployed
hairdresser $525 for smuggling an Australian rat nicknamed Napoleon
into England.
   Linda Squire, 21, hid the 5-week-old black and white rodent in
her sweater during the 32-hour flight from Perth, Australia, to
London.
   She did not declare the rat to customs officers at London's
Gatwick Airport, and police later arrested her at her home in
Dawlish in southwest England, said prosecutor David Bick.
   Miss Squires bought the rat in a Perth pet shop for $2.60 at the
end of an 11-month trip to Australia.
   Because she could not afford to put it in quarantine for the
mandatory six months, the rat was cremated by a local vet.
