<1ST_LINE>r a PM-WestiesTrial     02-25 0592</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Westies Trial,0609</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>7 of 8 Convicted in Westies Racket Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The racketeering conviction of seven members of
the Westies has put the murderous Manhattan gang out of business, a
federal prosecutor says.
   A federal jury convicted the seven Wednesday of taking part in
the Westies' violent dealings, including seven murders, three
attempted murders and four kidnappings.
   An eighth defendant was acquitted of all charges, but still
faces a state murder charge in an unrelated case.
   In addition to racketeering, several of the seven, including
Westies boss James ``Jimmy'' Coonan, also were found guilty of
various crimes ranging from attempted murder and loansharking to
drug dealing and tax evasion.
   But the key verdict was the jury's decision that the Westies did
exist, that it constituted a racketeering enterprise and that the
convicted defendants had participated in activities to further the
gang's criminal goals.
   ``The group has been incapacitated and put out of business,''
said Assistant U.S. Attorney Mary Lee Warren.
   During the nearly five-month trial, defense lawyers contended
there was no such organization as the Westies. Even former gang
members testifying for the prosecution conceded the name
``Westies'' was created by the police and the news media to
describe Irish-American hoodlums on Manhattan's West Side.
   Ms. Warren and the other prosecutor, David Brodsky, claimed the
six men and two women on trial were the violent core of the
Westies, which seized control of a neighborhood once known as
Hell's Kitchen on the edge of Manhattan's theater district near
Times Square.
   For 20 years, they claimed, the gang maintained its rule ``with
horrible and ghoulish acts of murder.''
   Witnesses testified that in at least three murders, the victim's
body was cut up and disposed of in what Ms. Warren called ``the
nightmarish signature crime of the Westies.''
   Most of those murders and murder plots were not separate charges
in the indictment, but listed as acts in furtherance of the
racketeering enterprise. To be convicted of racketeering, each
defendant had to have committed at least two of the 28 racketeering
acts charged.
   The 14-count indictment also listed 10 alleged co-racketeers who
were not named as defendants because they had been slain.
   Several witnesss also testified that the Westies forged an
alliance with the Gambino organized crime family, said to be the
largest, most powerful Mafia group in the country.
   The verdict was reached on the eighth day of deliberations.
   Coonan was convicted of attempted murder, murder conspiracy,
loansharking, extortion and income tax evasion, among other crimes.
His wife was convicted of loansharking and tax charges.
   The jury also found that Coonan participated in most of the
racketeering acts charged against him, including seven murders.
   ``A trial on any single act in this indictment would have
resulted in an acquittal,'' said his lawyer, Gerald Shargel. ``It's
just a matter of the government, piling it all together. That's the
nightmare of RICO (the Racketeer Influenced Corrupt Organizations
Act).''
   In addition to Coonan and his 44-year-old wife, Edna, both of
Hazlet, N.J., the others convicted of racketeering and racketeering
conspiracy were: William ``Indian'' Bokun, 30; James ``Jimmy Mack''
McElroy, 42; Richard ``Muggsy'' Ritter, 50; Thomas Collins, 53, and
his wife Florence, 52, all of Manhattan.
   Only John Halo, 36, of New York was acquitted on all charges. He
still faces trial for the June 1985 fatal shooting of his
21-year-old nephew.
   U.S. District Judge Whitman Knapp scheduled sentencing for April
18. All seven face up to 20 years apiece on both racketeering and
racketeering conspiracy.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
