<1ST_LINE>r a PM-StrayShot     02-25 0270</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Stray Shot,0278</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Woman Dies From Stray Bullet</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAKESIDE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An 84-year-old woman was killed when a
stray bullet from youths target-shooting nearby shattered her
kitchen window and struck her in the chest, authorities said.
   Neighbors expressed anger that the youths were allowed to go
free after the shooting.
   Rose Cudigan died at AMI Valley Medical Center in El Cajon less
than two hours after being shot Wednesday morning. Her husband,
Raymond, who was standing near her in the kitchen when she was
struck, was not injured and summoned help.
   Three youths admitted they had been target shooting with a .22
caliber rifle about 100 yards away from the Cudigans' home in the
Lakeview neighborhood of Lakeside, said San Diego County sheriff's
Sgt. Danny Goodrich.
   No charges were filed pending further investigation, and the
teen-agers later were released to the custody of their parents.
   ``I'm mad and I'm bitter,'' neighbor Sharon Dudley said. ``We've
lost a wonderful neighbor and the suspects are free.''
   Neighbors said youths had fired guns in the area before.
   ``The (deputies) told me they had no evidence, that I'd have to
get a restraining order against those boys to stop them from firing
their guns. What good is a piece of paper?'' Dudley said.
   Lt. Bill Baxter said the entire case may ``simply be handed to
the district attorney for a review and final determination on any
charges.''
   Under the state penal code, discharging a firearm at an
inhabited dwelling is a felony, punishable by three, five or seven
years in state prison, or by six months to a year in county jail.
</TEXT>
