<2ND_LINE>PM-EGermany-Soviet Missiles, 1st Ld-Writethru a0547,0700</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviets Begin Removal Of Nuclear Missiles From East Germany</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with detail on withdrawal in East
Germany and to COMBINE with Czechoslovakian removal. EDITS to
tighten, no pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KENNETH JAUTZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BISCHOFSWERDA, East Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet troops today began the
early removal of nuclear missiles from East Germany and
Czechosolovakia under terms of a new superpower arms agreement yet
to be ratified.
   Western reporters this morning saw a train loaded with 32
containers leave Bischofwerda, about 20 miles east of Dresden.
   Officials at the scene said the containers were packed with
parts of dismantled SS-12 rockets and that the train's destination
was the Soviet Union, where the missiles are to be destroyed.
   In addition to the missile parts, 150 of 400 Soviet soldiers
stationed at Bischofswerda also left on the train. Officials at the
site said the remaining soldiers will leave by the end of the month.
   A large banner displayed at Bischofswerda's railroad station
read: ``Removal of Shorter-Range Rockets, a Contribution to
Security and Peace.''
   A local kindergarten class sang: ``We greet you soldiers, you
protect the happiness of children.''
   The top Communist Party functionary of Bischofswerda, Hannelore
Strugalla, said ``the first practical step in nuclear disarmament
is being accomplished in our hometown.''
   The SS-12s are included in the superpower treaty on removal of
medium- and shorter-range nuclear missiles from central Europe. The
accord was signed by President Reagan and Soviet leader Mikhail S.
Gorbachev in December.
   Dmitri T. Yazov, the Soviet defense minister, said Monday while
Secretary of State George P. Shultz was in Moscow that withdrawal
of the SS-12s would begin this month as a ``display of goodwill.''
   The treaty is before Congress and the nominal Soviet parliament
for approval.
   There were five rocket launchers, eight missiles and four
practice missiles stationed at Bischofswerda, according to
officials.
   Removal of the warheads from the missiles was completed one week
ago, officials said, and additional rocket parts are to be removed
from the site within the next two days.
   Soviet troops were also removing SS-12s today from Waren, East
Germany, where there are 22 missiles, nine launchers and seven
training rockets, according to figures released after the
superpower treaty was signed.
   Waren is about 90 miles northwest of Berlin.
   The East German government arranged to transport 100 Western
journalists to the two sites to witness the removal of the rockets.
   The SS-12s _ which have a range of about 560 miles _ fall under
the ``shorter-range'' classification in the superpower arms treaty,
which covers rockets with a range from 300 to 3,100 miles.
   In Czechoslovakia the loading was taking place in the Moravian
town of Hranice, the country's official news agency CTK said.
   According to the report, the missiles were transported during
the night from a nearby military zone to the railway station where
the loading operation began.
   CTK added that the first of the missiles would leave Hranice for
the Soviet Union this evening.
   CTK quoted Soviet Lt. Col. Vyacheslav Granovsky as saying Soviet
officers, mechanics and drivers who had serviced the missiles being
dismantled would leave with the first transport today.
   Granovsky did not say how many rockets and Soviet personnel will
leave Czechoslovakia. He also did not say when withdrawal of all
the missiles would be completed, and gave their destination only as
''a predetermined place in the Soviet Union.''
   CTK said the removal of the Soviet missiles was being watched by
60 reporters, but it was not known if any Western journalists were
invited.
   Hranice, with a population of 12,500, has been singled out by
Czechoslovak officials as the only place in the country where
Soviet missiles had been stationed.
   ``The step of the Soviet government, the removal of
operational-tactical shorter-range missiles before ratification of
the Soviet-American agreement, is further proof of the sincerity,
concreteness and constructive approach of the Soviet peace policy
to nuclear disarmament and the creation of a more secure world,''
CTK said.
   The withdrawal occurs during the 40th anniversary of Communist
rule in Czechoslovakia.
</TEXT>
