<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Census-Maps     02-25 0158</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Census-Maps,160</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Census Asks Municipal Mapping Cooperation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Census Bureau called today for local
govrnment help updating the accuracy of maps to be used in the 1990
national head count.
   Each of the approximately 39,000 municipal and county
governments across the nation will be sent a computer-drawn map
next month, showing the most current boundaries on file at the
bureau.
   Census officials are asking that local government leaders review
these maps and make any changes necessary.
   Even if local boundaries have not changed, local leaders were
urged to carefully inspect the maps, which are the first prepared
by the bureau's new computerized mapping system, said Robert W.
Marx of the Census geography office. He said the agency wants to
promptly catch any errors that may have occurred in preparing the
maps.
   The bureau estimates that one municipality in five has had some
boundary change since the 1980 census through annexations,
detachments, incorporation or disincorporation.
</TEXT>
