<2ND_LINE>PM-Cleveland Teachers, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0516,0541</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Negotiations Continue As Strike Looms</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 14 grafs to UPDATE with school called off because
of snow, negotiators adjourning after marathon session, new
comments from federal mediator, transition. Pickup 11th graf,
`Union negotiators...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GEOFFREY BARNARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CLEVELAND (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A strike by public school teachers set for
today was put on hold this morning as union negotiators considered
the district's latest contract offer and school officials canceled
classes because of snow.
   Talks recessed at 6:30 a.m. today when negotiators for the
Cleveland Teachers Union agreed to take the school board's latest
proposal to the union's executive board later in the day.
   Superintendent Alfred Tutela called off classes for the
district's 72,639 students, citing the weather, although no other
area school districts were closed. Cleveland received up to 3
inches of snow overnight.
   The district is Ohio's largest public school system.
   Union negotiators had set a bargaining deadline of 3 p.m.
Wednesday and a strike deadline of midnight, but talks continued
into early this morning at a downtown hotel under the supervision
of federal mediator Jack Buettner.
   Union President Eugene Kolach said teachers would not set up
picket lines outside schools because classes had been canceled. He
declined further comment.
   The union's executive board agreed to meet at 3 p.m. today to
consider the board's proposal, Buettner said. He declined to say
whether he believed the proposal could lead to a tentative contract.
   ``Both sides were probably shooting for higher goals than they
were able to obtain,'' Buettner said. ``There are several stumbling
blocks, and I can't really get into a lot of detail.''
   The union, which has 5,093 members, has been without a contract
since Sept. 1.
   The school system had planned to close schools if a strike
materialized, but continue classes for the district's 3,600 high
school seniors.
   Bargainers would not comment on details of the negotiations, but
both sides have differed on the issues of teacher salaries and a
career ladder system.
   The latest bargaining session began at 10 a.m. Tuesday and
continued almost non-stop until 6:30 a.m. today, except for a
three-hour break Wednesday night. Buettner shuttled offers back and
forth between the bargaining committees, which were in separate
rooms at downtown hotel.
   Tutela last month urged teachers to accept a mandatory career
ladder system that would hinge pay raises to performance
evaluations.
   Union negotiators have said they want participation in the
career ladder to be an option.
   The union had been seeking a 5.8 percent wage increase this
year, while the district was offering a 2 percent one-time bonus
payment. Union negotiators said the amount of the increases could
vary depending on the length of the proposed contract.
   Annual salaries for teachers range from $17,687 for beginners to
$37,457 for teachers with a master's degree and 35 years
experience. The average teacher pay is $29,000.
   The union represents classroom teachers, guidance counselors,
teacher aides, librarians and reading specialists.
   About 40 parents and others staged a demonstration Wednesday
outside the hotel where talks were being held to encourage
continued negotiations. The rally was organized by the Interchurch
Council of Greater Cleveland.
</TEXT>
