<2ND_LINE>PM-Iran-Saudi,0253</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iran Charges Saudis Impeding Pilgrimage Preparations</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran said today that Saudi Arabia has
forbidden a representative of Iranian revolutionary patriarch
Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini from visiting the country to prepare
for the Moslem pilgrimage.
   The official Islamic Republic News Agency quoted Prime Minister
Hussein Musavi as saying this was evidence of the insolence of the
Saudi government. The agency did not provide a direct quote.
   It said the Saudis refused to let Emam Jamarani, Khomeini's
representative and head of the pilgrimage and religious endowments
organization, travel to Saudi Arabia in preparation of the July
gathering.
   Last summer, riots in the holy city of Mecca during the
pilgrimage left 402 people dead, more than half of them Iranians.
Tehran said police sprayed pilgrims with machine-gun fire. Riyadh
said the violence was planned by Iran and many of the victims died
in stampedes.
   There was no immediate Saudi response to Musavi's comments.
   Saudi Arabian Interior Minister Prince Nayef has affirmed that
the kingdom will not tolerate a recurrence of last year's
``sacrilegious acts.''
   ``Any acts against the safety and security of the pilgrims and
the holy sites will be sternly dealt with,'' he said.
   Iran has said it plans to send 150,000 pilgrims this year and
will organize ``antipathy towards pagans'' rallies again, similar
to the event last year that ended in death.
   Moslems are required to undertake the pilgrimage at least once
in their life if they can afford it.
</TEXT>
