<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Bork     02-25 0303</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bork,290</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bork Says His Defeat Stifled Lawyers Who Want To Be Judges</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Robert Bork said today the defeat of his
Supreme Court nomination has discouraged lawyers from publishing
controversial legal articles and advised future nominees to
consider waging a national campaign to get on the court.
   ``I think this has been very bad for the intellectual life of
the law,'' said Bork, who resigned as a federal appeals court judge
three weeks ago.
   His experience has led several lawyers to withdraw articles from
legal publications, Bork said in an interview on ABC's ``Good
Morning America.'' He described the new lawyers' credo as:
``Express only noble sentiments and arrive at only noncontroversial
results.''
   Bork said judges who have written less than he has could simply
refuse to answer questions about their judicial philosophy at
confirmation hearings, but he felt it necessary to discuss issues
about which he had written.
   ``It certainly will inhibit the development of their thought,
and it will certainly inhibit the development of the law's evolving
intellectual structure,'' he said.
   Bork said that as a judge he did not think it proper for him to
wage a media campaign for his appointment, but said of future
nominees: ``I would advise them to think about it because I think
the alternative is defeat if this kind of campaign is waged against
them.''
   Bork said he wished the White House had done more to counter the
media and mail campaign against his nomination, which was rejected
by the Senate.
   ``The White House was caught flat-foooted by an unexpectedly
virilent campaign and just didn't get around to responding in time.
I understand that,'' said Bork, who is joining the Institute for
Public Policy Research, an educational and research organization
that says it takes no positions on public policy issues.
</TEXT>
