<1ST_LINE>u i PM-NIreland-Bomb     02-25 0400</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-NIreland-Bomb,0414</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Seal Off Downtown Following IRA Bombing That Killed Two
Soldiers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police today sealed off a busy
street in Belfast's main shopping area after a bomb planted by the
Irish Republican Army killed two British soldiers and injured two
others and a civilian.
   While police investigated the explosion, a soldier charged in
the shooting death of a Roman Catholic civilian was freed on bail
and then turned over to military custody.
   The IRA, which is fighting to end British rule in Northern
Ireland, claimed responsibility for the Wednesday night bombing in
a telephoned statement to Belfast news organizations.
   Police said Pvt. James Cummings and Pvt. Frederick Starrett,
both 22, were killed by the remote-controlled explosive as they
locked the steel anti-terrorist gates on Royal Avenue in downtown
Belfast. Two soldiers and a 57-year-old civilian bystander were
slightly injured.
   Belfast police said the bomb probably contained about 150 pounds
of explosives. The blast shattered the windows of shops and offices
several hundred yards away.
   Northern Ireland Secretary Tom King called the attack ``a
carefully planned and very vicious one indeed.''
   The anti-terrorist gates are guarded by Ulster Defense Regiment
soldiers, who search the bags and other items of shoppers and
others passing in and out during the day.
   Police said the bomb went off at 11 p.m. when few civilians were
about and that there was no warning from the bombers.
   The two deaths brought Northern Ireland's death toll since
sectarian and political violence flared in 1969 to at least 2,628.
   On Wednesday, police charged an 18-year-old British soldier,
Pvt. David Jonathan Holden, with unlawfully killing an unarmed
Catholic civilian last Sunday. A Northern Ireland court today
turned Holden over to military custody on $1,925 bail.
   The defense said Holden will plead innocent to the charge of
unlawfully killing Aidan McAnespie, 23, from an army observation
post at a checkpoint near Auchnacloy, half a mile from the Irish
Republic's border. Holden's court appearance is set for March 9.
   McAnespie was an election worker for Sinn Fein, the legal
political arm of the IRA. The British army said McAnespie was
killed by a ricocheting bullet after a machine gun was fired
accidentally.
   But Cardinal Tomas O Fiaich, Roman Catholic primate of all
Ireland, has said he believes McAnespie was murdered. Catholic
leaders in the province said McAnespie had been regularly harassed
by the army.
</TEXT>
