<2ND_LINE>PM-Police Shooting,0359</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dallas Officer Shoots Man to Death During Robbery Attempt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An off-duty police officer shot a man to death
early today during an armed robbery attempt in a restaurant after
the man reached for a weapon and challenged the officer to shoot
him, police say.
   The shooting was the fifth involving Dallas police in less than
two months. Six people have died, including two officers.
   ``Shoot me,'' Dallas Police Lt. Ron Waldrop quoted the man as
telling the off-duty officer as he reached for the weapon in his
waistband. The officer was not in uniform.
   The man was shot twice and was pronounced dead at the scene,
Waldrop said.
   Police withheld the names of the officer and the victim.
   ``We are still doing the interviews,'' Detective Rick Silva
said. ``More details will be available later.''
   The off-duty officer entered a Denny's Restaurant in southwest
Dallas to purchase food when he saw that a man had confronted a
waitress near a cash register, Waldrop said.
   The officer said he heard the man demand money and saw what
appeared to be a pistol in the man's waistband, Waldrop said.
Investigators later discovered that the weapon was actually a knife
with a handle similar to a pistol's, Waldrop said.
   The officer displayed his badge and gun and identified himself,
Waldrop said. It was then that the man went for the weapon and
challenged the officer to shoot him.
   Dallas police have come under fire by minority leaders and City
Hall in the past two years for being trigger-happy when confronting
suspects, especially blacks and Hispanics.
   However, tension flared last month after Police Chief Billy
Prince accused council members of fostering anti-police sentiment
that led to the death of Officer John Chase in a highly publicized
shooting Jan. 23.
   Witnesses told police that Chase was shot by a transient who had
wrestled his gun from him and was egged on by some spectators. The
transient was later shot to death after firing at police.
   Since then, many rallies have been staged in support of the
department.
</TEXT>
