02-25 0486</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Reagan-Iran-Contra, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0474,400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Statements Differ On What Shultz, Weinberger Knew</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Inserts grafs 9-10, Shultz asked, with Shultz quote.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan's assertion that Secretary of
State George P. Shultz and former Defense Secretary Caspar W.
Weinberger did not object to the idea of an arms-for-hostages deal
with Iran goes against earlier statements by himself and the two
Cabinet officers.
   The president, responding to a question about whether Vice
President George Bush objected to the failed policy, said at his
news conference Wednesday night that he did not ``want to be
surrounded by yes men. And yes, there were reservations.''
   The president, as in the past, declined to elaborate on Bush's
role. He then pointed to Shultz and Weinberger as others who voiced
objections _ but he said they were not opposed to the basic policy.
   ``They did not object to the idea that we were trading arms for
hostages,'' the president said.
   He said that Shultz and Weinberger ``knew what we were trying to
do'' and implied their main concern was public image.
   ``Their objection was that, if and when this became known, as it
would be, it would appear that we were trading hostages for, or
arms for hostages,'' he said.
   A year ago, after the two Cabinet secretaries complained about
the Tower Commission report statement that they didn't fight the
policy hard enough, Reagan backed their position.
   ``Both Secretary Shultz and Secretary Weinberger advised me
strongly not to pursue the initiative,'' he said. ``I weighed their
advice and decided in the end that the initiative was worth the
risk and went forward.''
   Shultz, asked about the comments today during a flight to
Israel, said he had testified ``endlessly'' and that it was based
largely on his own records.
   ``I am not going to go over it anymore,'' he said. ``I've
testified and I really don't have anything to add or subtract
because my testimony is based to a very healthy extent on records
and notes and so on.''
   Shultz and Weinberger, testifying last summer before
congressional investigators, said they were kept in the dark by the
White House aides arranging the deals.
   Shultz said he was ``sick to my stomach'' when he first learned
some of the details of the policy. He said he fought a ``battle
royal'' to make sure Reagan was aware of what was going on.
   Both Shultz and Weinberger said they objected to the plans in
1985 and at a Dec. 7 meeting that year ``I made a very strong
objection to the whole idea, as did the secretary of state,''
Weinberger said.
   Weinberger said he objected because the United States was asking
other countries not to sell arms to Iran, that there was no one
reliable to deal with there, and that if it were an
arms-for-hostages deal the government was laying itself open to
blackmail.
</TEXT>
