<HEAD>Armored Car Crash Dumps $400,000 in Coins on Highway, Injures
Three</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES thruout with $400,000 in coins spilled, police saying
weight of coins broke through roof of armored truck, other details.
No pickup. CORRECTS style of Brink's, sted Brinks, in 7th graf,
bgng `The guard...'; ADDS byline.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BARBARA METZLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>INDUSTRY, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An armored truck hauling $400,000 in
coins overturned on a freeway, spilling a torrent of change that
broke through the truck's roof and scattered across the lanes,
authorities said today.
   Three people were treated for minor injuries.
   ``The weight of the coins actually blew the top of the vehicle
right out,'' said California Highway Patrol Officer Lyle Whitten,
describing the accident late Wednesday on the eastbound Pomona
Freeway.
   A guard riding in the back of the truck was ejected by the
force, but he escaped serious injury.
   ``He wasn't buried (in coins), and that's what saved him,''
Whitten said.
   The guard and two other people in the truck were treated and
released at Queen of the Valley Hospital for minor injuries, said
nursing supervisor Terri Coleman. Their names were not released.
   ``I understand they're all OK,'' said Bill Beamon of Brink's
Inc. in San Bernardino.
   The three-ton armored truck was hauling $400,000 in coins from
Los Angeles to San Bernardino-area banks when both right rear dual
tires blew out, Whitten said.
   The truck careened out of control and rolled onto its side as
boxes of coins knocked the roof off and scattered onto the freeway
lanes.
   Brink's and highway patrol officials said they couldn't estimate
the weight of the coins, but Nelson Italiano at the Union Plaza
Casino in Las Vegas said an average weight of the various coins
could equal 38 tons.
   ``It's approximately a half-million dollars in the No. 4 (lane),
the on ramp and the right shoulder,'' said Officer Richard Perez of
the highway patrol.
   Most of the money was boxed, Whitten said, but about $300 in
loose half dollars, quarters, dimes, nickels and pennies rolled
across some 35 feet of roadway.
   Sgt. John Williams, an off-duty highway patrol motorcycle
officer, on his way home from work, saw the accident and stopped to
secure the area, Whitten said.
   ``People had already started to stop, even before he got off his
motorcycle ... and he shooed them away.''
   Another Brink's truck carrying paper money stopped to help the
victims, Whitten said.
   The highway patrol shut down several freeway lanes as Brink's
employees gathered the boxed and loose change and loaded it into
another armored vehicle, dispatcher Sabrina Elswick said. Most of
the money was recovered, officials said.
   ``Police are everywhere guarding it; you couldn't get near it,''
said Los Angeles County fire Capt. Art Montgomery.
   Industry is about 15 miles southeast of downtown Los Angeles.
</TEXT>
