<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Endometriosis     02-25 0368</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Endometriosis,0378</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New Drug Effective Alternative For Endometriosis</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A new drug for treating endometriosis may provide
an alternative for women unable to tolerate the side effects of the
only medicine now available for this common condition, doctors say.
   A report published today concludes that the drug, called
nafarelin, works as well as danazol, the standard medical treatment.
   About 5 percent of all women during their reproductive years
have endometriosis. The disorder occurs when tissue from the lining
of the uterus grows in other places in the female reproductive
system. Symptoms can include back and abdominal pain during or
after menstrual periods. Severe cases may require drug treatment or
surgery.
   Although danazol is highly effective, some women cannot take it
because of its side effects. Nafarelin also causes some unwanted
symptoms, but experts say these may be less offensive to some
patients.
   A report on a comparison of the two drugs in 213 women was
published in the New England Journal of Medicine. The test was
directed by Dr. Milan R. Henzi of Syntex Research, a pharmaceutical
firm in Palo Alto, Calif.
   ``In my opinion, this is the best-designed and best-executed
trial of drug therapy for endometriosis ever reported,'' Dr. Robert
L. Barbieri of Harvard Medical School wrote in an accompanying
editorial.
   Danazol is derived from the male sex hormone testosterone. Some
women who take it complain of weight gain, swelling, acne, hair
growth and deepening of the voice, among other side effects.
Danazol also causes unfavorable changes in blood cholesterol levels.
   Nafarelin, which is given as a nasal spray, does not affect
cholesterol levels, but it has other side effects, mainly hot
flashes, descreased sex drive and vaginal dryness.
   In the study, both drugs reduced the extent of the disease in
more than 80 percent of patients.
   Barbieri said that for women who cannot tolerate danazol,
nafarelin ``represents an important therapeutic alternative.''
   The new drug is one of a class of synthetic hormones that
temporarily shut off the body's production of sex hormones.
Nafarelin is also being tested as a treatment for prostate
enlargement in men. Currently, the drug is approved by the U.S.
Food and Drug Administration only for treatment of prostate cancer.
</TEXT>
