<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Iraq-Britain     02-25 0319</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Iraq-Britain,0331</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iraqi President Pardons British Businessman Convicted of Bribery</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Saddam Hussein pardoned a British
businessman sentenced to life in prison for bribing Iraqi officials
after a plea from British Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher,
officials said today.
   A British Embassy official, who spoke on condition of anonymity,
said the Iraqi president pardoned John Smith on Wednesday as David
Mellor, a British Foreign Office minister, held talks with Iraqi
officials.
   In London, the Foreign Office said Mellor delivered a letter to
the Iraqi president from Mrs. Thatcher asking for his help in
obtaining Smith's release.
   It said 46-year-old Smith of Hazelmere in Lancashire had not
been released yet. ``We don't expect it to be too long. There are
bureaucratic procedures to complete,'' said a spokesman.
   The Foreign Office said Smith's release ``is the happy
culmination of a number of efforts over a number of years.'' It
added that ``no deals have been struck.''
   The Iraqi officials accused of being involved with Smith were
tried and executed.
   Smith, managing director of the specialist vehicle manufacturer
Hestair Dennis, was arrested in 1979 while talking with an Iraqi
official in a park.
   He was convicted in 1980 of bribing officials and sentenced to
life imprisonment, which in Iraq means 20 years.
   At the time he was also accused of ``economic espionage'' but it
was not clear whether he was ever formally charged or convicted on
such a charge.
   The Iraqis convicted in the case were executed according to an
Iraqi law that prohibits receiving bribes from foreign salesman or
providing them with information related to the state.
   Another British businessman, Ian Rechter, is imprisoned in Iraq
after being tried in 1987 and convicted of bribing the mayor of
Baghdad, who was found guilty of taking bribes from Rechter and
later executed.
   Mellor also pressed for Rechter's release but no decision has
yet been taken by Iraqi authorities.
</TEXT>
