<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Philippines-Bomb 2ndLd-Writethru   02-25 0409</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Philippines-Bomb, 2nd Ld-Writethru,a0607,0420</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bomb Explodes During Anniversary Celebration of Marcos' Ouster</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 10 grafs to UPDATE injury toll to 14, ADD witness
quote. Pick up 9th graf pvs: `One unidentified...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MIGUEL C. SUAREZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bomb exploded near a crowded
grandstand tonight as thousands of Filipinos marked the second
anniversary of the overthrow of President Ferdinand Marcos, police
said.
   Elisa Florido, a nurse at the Medical City Hospital, said 14
people were injured, mostly by flying glass and debris. None was
seriously hurt, she said, and there were no reports of fatalities.
   The blast occurred at about 10 p.m. near the main grandstand set
up on Epifanio De Los Santos Avenue, or EDSA, a broad boulevard
between two military camps.
   It was at EDSA two years ago that hundreds of thousands of
Filipinos came to protect mutinous troops from soldiers loyal to
Marcos. The four-day standoff culminated in his flight to exile in
Hawaii on Feb. 25, 1986.
   The blast occurred about five hours after President Corazon
Aquino, Manila Archbishop Cardinal Jaime L. Sin and other
dignitaries attended a mass at the grandstand and prayed for peace
in this troubled island nation.
   None of the dignitaries were believed to be at the scene during
the blast.
   No one immediately claimed responsibility for the bombing.
   The military had been on full alert in case Communist rebels or
right-wing dissidents tried to disrupt the celebrations.
   One witness, Monica Soliman, told radio station DZXL that she
and her family were returning to their car when they saw two men
behind the stage tying what appeared to be three sticks.
   ``When we reached the car, we turned on the radio and suddenly
we heard an explosion,'' she said.
   One unidentified man, interviewed by radio station DZXL, said
the blast occurred during a fireworks display.
   ``We were watching the fireworks when suddenly something
exploded behind us,'' he said. ``My brother was injured in the
back.'' The man said he was about 70 feet from the explosion.
   The blast took place near the end of a daylong celebration that
began shortly after dawn with a flag-raising ceremony and a Mass,
and continued with singing and dancing into the night.
   Earlier, Mrs. Aquino, Defense Minister Fidel Ramos and Gen.
Renato de Villa, the military chief of staff, and other senior
officials had joined hands with thousands of people for a ``chain
of peace'' along EDSA.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
