<1ST_LINE>u p PM-Bush 1stLd-Writethru a0501 02-25 0799</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bush, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0501,790</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Precede GREENVILLE, S.C.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Bush, in South, Opposes Textile Bill Rivals Embrace</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates with Bush on textiles, Robertson on apology demand in
top 11 grafs, picking up in 3rd graf pvs, Robertson said</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PENDLETON, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President George Bush, answering
presidential rivals in South Carolina, today rejected ``pure,
all-out protectionism'' and said existing trade laws are sufficient
to help the state's textile industry against foreign imports.
   Bush raised the subject of textiles a day after Republican
candidate Bob Dole campaigned in the state and called for passage
of legislation restricting foreign textile imports.
   Republican Pat Robertson has also backed the textile bill and
has declared South Carolina _ a state where textiles are an
important industry _ a major battleground for his campaign.
   ``Don't go for this pure, all-out protectionism that may save
one job and then throw three neighbors in this burgeoning state out
of work,'' Bush said. ``That isn't the answer.''
   He spoke to several hundred students, teachers and others at an
assembly at Tri-County Technical College. He also spoke briefly
with students in an industrial electronics class, accompanied by
South Carolina Gov. Carroll A. Campbell Jr., his state campaign
chairman.
   The textile import legislation has support in South Carolina and
other textile and apparel-producing states of the South. President
Reagan vetoed similar legislation after it passed Congress two
years ago.
   ``What I propose is that we enforce the law,'' Bush said.
   Campaigning Wednesday in Vermont, Bush demanded an apology from
Robertson for indicating Bush's campaign was somehow responsible
for the timing of allegations of sexual misconduct against Jimmy
Swaggart, a television evangelist.
   Robertson, however, suggested in Louisville, Ky., today that if
Bush had heard exactly what he said there would be no apology
demand.
   ``I was, frankly, misquoted in the press,'' he said.
   Robertson _ a former television evangelist himself _ said
earlier this week he thought it odd that the Swaggart controversy
erupted just to weeks before Super Tuesday, when 20 states will
choose delegates to the national party conventions, suggesting that
the controversy was timed to embarrass him.
   Robertson said he had no proof of political involvement in the
Swaggart revelations. But in the same interview, Robertson accused
Bush's campaign of ``dirty politics'' and ``trickery.''
   ``By sundown in the old South, I'd like to see him stand up like
a Southern gentleman with a little evidence,'' Bush said Wednesday
in Burlington, Vt. ``I'd like to see an apology or proof.''
   Bush was campaigning today in South Carolina, which holds its
primary on March 5, three days before the Super Tuesday contests in
20 states, mostly in the South.
   Bush also expressed puzzlement over another Robertson contention
_ that his Christian Broadcasting Network at one point had
information about the whereabouts of the American hostages in
Lebanon and that ``they could have been saved.''
   Robertson spokesmen later said Robertson had been referring to
passengers and crew members of a TWA flight, who were held briefly
in Lebanon following a 1985 hijacking.
   ``My question would be, how come he didn't get a hold of the
proper authorities in the United States government that were
working day and night, trying to figure out how they could get
those people out?'' Bush said at a stop in Boston.
   Bush, in appearances Wednesday in New England, sought to set
himself apart from his rivals _ Rep. Jack Kemp, Dole, and Robertson.
   ``You're selecting a president, not a congressman, not a
senator, not a preacher,'' he said.
   On another matter, the vice president said he expected to win in
Vermont's non-binding presidential primary next Tuesday.
   Bush said he did not think his campaign was damaged by a pair of
losses in Minnesota's GOP caucuses and South Dakota's primary, both
Tuesday. Dole won in both states.
   Bush's campaign had pulled resources out of South Dakota and
Minnesota in order to concentrate on the contests of March 8, Super
Tuesday.
   The vice president said he didn't believe the results had any
effect on a subject he ``learned the hard way about in 1980 _
momentum.''
   During that election, Ronald Reagan overcame Bush's early
primary victories to win the Republican nomination.
   Reagan, at a nationally broadcast news conference on Wednesday
night, took the opportunity to defend Bush, who has come under
questioning on the campaign trail about his role in secret arms
sales to Iran. Bush has refused to detail his advice to the
president on the matter, citing confidentiality, but has said he
expressed private reservations.
   Reagan corroborated that, adding: ``I don't want to be
surrounded by yes men.''
   ``There were reservations, but I'm not going to go into (them)
just as he wouldn't go into the private discussions that we may
have had,'' the president said.
</TEXT>
