<FILEID>AP-NY-02-25-88 1228EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w PM-Reagan-Mideast 2ndLd-Writethru a0574 02-25 0619</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Reagan-Mideast, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0574,620</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: New thruout with White House comment on Reagan, Shultz
statements.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TIM AHERN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary of State George Shultz said today
the origins of Palestinian rioting in the Israeli-occupied West
Bank are ``essentially indigenous,'' a statement the White House
said was consistent with President Reagan's assessment that the
riots do not appear to be ``home grown.''
   Shultz, speaking during a flight to Jerusalem, where he hopes to
amerliorate the conflict in the occupied territories, said, ``It's
fundamental origins are essentially indigenous.''
   He also told reporters that ``there is an underlying problem
consisting of a large number of people in occupation who haven't
had the basic rights of governance.''
   Hours earlier, Reagan said at a nationally televised news
conference that ``there is every evidence that these riots are not
just spontaneous and home grown.''
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater, asked about the two
men's statements, said, ``Those are totally consistent.''
   ``The president said the same thing,'' Fitzwater told reporters.
``He just said they (the riots) were partly influenced by outside
sources.''
   ``He is saying that it is indigenous in the nature of the
political problem there but there has been some outside influence
as well,'' the spokesman said. ``He is saying exactly what we have
said all along.''
   Fifty-nine people have died since the rioting began, most of
them shot by Israeli troops.
   Reagan said, ``We have had intimations that there have been
certain people suspected of being terrorists, outsiders coming in,
not only with weapons, but stirring up and encouraging the trouble
in those areas.''
   Asked about saying the riots were not ``home grown,'' Reagan
added:
   ``That isn't something you can go out and say we absolutely
know, but certainly the violence is both ways.''
   Shultz said intelligence showed ``a mixed picture'' with
``interaction with outside force.''
   But he said ``there is an underlying problem consisting of a
large number of people in occupation who haven't had the basic
rights of governance. So we seek among other things consistent with
Israel's security, to look at things that will help Palestinians
gain legitimate rights.''
   Reagan offered no evidence to support his assertion that
outsiders and terrorists are to blame for the violence, saying
security rules prevented him from doing so.
   He declined to criticize Israel's policy of beating large
numbers of Palestinians and occasionally firing on the protestors.
   But he said, ``We don't support that sort of thing and we are
trying to persuade all the participants to try to arrive at a
solution representing justice for all.''
   Reagan added that ``we have spoken to the government there and
we have also spoken to the Palestinian leadership because there is
every evidence that these riots are not just spontaneous and
home-grown.''
   Previously, administration officials had not given any
indication that any outside involvement was suspected in the
rioting.
   The president said ``it's time for us to arrive at a true peace
and recognize the rights of all'' in the Middle East.
   He said peace in the Middle East ``would be one of the greatest
achievements of this administration.''
   Reagan did not go into detail about U.S. proposals, but Israeli
officials have already said they oppose two elements. One part is
an international conference in April to seek an interim solution in
the occupied territories, while the second is a December date for
talks to begin on a final settlement.
   The president said ``it's time for all parties to rid themselves
of old ideas and stances that cannot work and to begin a serious
process of negotiation and reconciliation.''
   ``Any process that is undertaken must meet Israel's security
needs and satisfy the legitimate rights of the Palestinians,'' he
said.
</TEXT>
