<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--India-Missile     02-25 0146</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--India-Missile,0152</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>India Tests First Surface-to-Surface Missile</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   India successfully test-fired its first
surface-to-surface missile Thursday, Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi
announced in Parliament.
   The missile has a range of 155 miles, used a computer-aided
navigation system and could be fitted with different warheads, the
United News of India reported.
   The new missile _ named ``Prithvi,'' the Hindu word for Earth _
was designed by scientists at the government-owned Defense Research
and Development Organization, the news agency said.
   Gandhi did not say where the test took place.
   He said India was the fifth country in the world to successfully
develop this class of missile, the others being the United States,
the Soviet Union, France and China.
   In April, India tested its first domestically produced
surface-to-air missile. India exploded a nuclear device in 1974,
but says its atomic program is for peaceful purposes.
</TEXT>
