<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--Burma-Poppies     02-25 0129</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Burma-Poppies,0133</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Report 41,000 Acres of Illicit Poppies Destroyed Last Year</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RANGOON, Burma (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government destroyed more than 41,000
acres of illicit poppies last year, it was reported Thursday.
   The state-owned Working People's Daily said the government also
seized 3,250 pounds of raw opium, 178 pounds of heroin and 66
pounds of morphine base during 1987.
   The poppies were destroyed both by hand and by aerial spraying
of herbicides, it said.
   In 1986, the government destroyed more than 40,000 acres of
poppies and seized 3,900 pounds of raw opium, 105 pounds of heroin
and 63 pounds of morphine base, the newspaper said.
   The opium is grown mostly by hill tribes in eastern Burma and
refined into heroin by armed trafficking groups operating along the
Thai-Burmese border.
</TEXT>
