<1ST_LINE>r i AM-WrongDay     02-25 0197</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Wrong Day,0203</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Daily Telegraph Apologizes For Getting Day Wrong</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It was one of those days for the Daily Telegraph.
   The masthead of the Wednesday's editions of the newspaper
mistakenly said it was Thursday, and it reportedly caused havoc
throughout the land.
   The Telegraph reported on Thursday's front page that one reader
complained he had traveled to Birmingham a day too soon after being
misled by Wednesday's paper.
   Someone else went to the dentist a day early, and some elderly
readers went to post offices to collect pensions that normally
arrive on Thursday.
   Several hundred people called to point out the mistake, the
paper said.
   ``The majority were puzzled and confused,'' it quoted
switchboard operator Rita Sherman as saying. ``But some were very
annoyed and upset, particularly those who had traveled all over the
place thinking it was Thursday and got there before they found out.
But a nice cross-section saw a funny side to it.''
   The Telegraph said the misprint in 300,000 copies of Wednesday's
final edition.
   ``To all of you _ those who saw the funny side and those who did
not _ we offer our humble apologies,'' the paper said.
</TEXT>
