<1ST_LINE>u p PM-StateSpending 1stLd-Writethru a0432 02-25 0658</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-State Spending, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0432,650</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>FEC Approves Cost-Reporting Split for Candidates' Ads</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates with decision in top 7 grafs, picking up in 4th graf
pvs, The opinion</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Election Commission said today it
is all right for a presidential campaign to write off half the cost
of a TV ad as a fund-raising expense even if the overt money
solicitation is only a tiny part of the commercial.
   In its 4-2 decision, the commission signaled to the presidential
campaigns that it will allow a practice that some critics have said
is a method of evading the state spending limits imposed on the
campaigns.
   Dissenting from the ruling, Commissioner Joan Aikens said the
agency was merely ``sanctioning creative accounting to get around
the limits.''
   ``I think we are absolutely blowing the state limits out of the
water,'' she said.
   But other commission members said the FEC should not be getting
involved with scrutinizing every campaign ad to determine what
portion contained a fund-raising appeal.
   Commissioner Thomas Josefiak said that even if an ad appears to
be mostly issue-related, as long as it has an overt fund-raising
message as well as information on how to contribute _ such as a
telephone number to call _ the ad can be considered to have a dual
purpose. In that case, a 50 percent allocation for fund-raising
would be appropriate, the commission determined.
   Fund-raising allocations are important to presidential campaigns
because they are not counted against the federally mandated limits
on spending in each state.
   The opinion comes in answer to a query from Sen. Albert Gore
Jr., the Democratic contender from Tennessee, whose staff
complained about the approach used in Ioa by rivals Rep. Richard
Gephardt of Missouri and Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis.
   The issue involves how much of the costs of TV ads can be
excluded from the total that a campaign spends against an
expenditure ceiling in each state. Fund-raising costs are not
counted against the cap, which in Iowa this year was $775,000.
   Gore did not mention the other campaigns in his request for an
FEC opinion, but posed his question as a hypothetical involving a
60-second ad for his own campaign, with a fund-raising appeal in
the last three seconds.
   Gore asked if he could count only 50 percent of that ad's cost
against the cap. The legal counsel's opinion was that 5 percent
would be a more reasonable figure.
   Gore's hypothetical paralleled Gephardt's commercial in Iowa in
which the final seconds contained the request for viewers to
``Vote, volunteer, contribute.'' Gephardt excluded half the cost
from the spending his campaign allocated to Iowa.
   Such a practice is valuable in Iowa because all of the campaigns
wanted to spend large sums to get high visibility in the nation's
first Democratic caucus.
   Dukakis also ran ads that contained only a brief fund-raising
appeal at the end, with the rest of the ad focused on issues, and
he counted 40 percent as fund-raising.
   In response to Gore's question, the FEC legal staff said that
writing off part of the ads as a fund-raising expense is
legitimate. But the opinion said the write-off should be generally
proportional to the portion of the ad that contains a fund-raising
message.
   The FEC opinion by counsel Larry Noble said that a 50 percent
writeoff for that would not be reasonable.
   ``Given that the only appeal to contribute occurs in the final
three seconds of the 60-second spot, an allocation of 5 percent (or
less) to the exclusion would be reasonable,'' the opinon said.
   The Gephardt and Dukakis campaigns had cited the precedent of
Sen. John Glenn's presidential campaign in 1984, in which the FEC
allowed a 50 percent fund-raising writeoff for Glenn's half-hour TV
show.
   Noble's opinion noted that the FEC decides such matters on a
case-by-case basis.
   Campaigns use the FEC case-specific rulings, however, as
guidelines for their own activities.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
