<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Reagan 1stLd-Writethru a0424 02-25 1037</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Reagan, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0424,1000</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: New throughout with Fitzwater, Robertson comments.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TERENCE HUNT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP White House Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan broke his silence about the
candidates vying for his job, slapping out at Republican Pat
Robertson, defending Vice President George Bush and ridiculing the
Democrats, saying, ``The kids will play.''
   The president, in fielding questions Wednesday night at his
first news conference in four months, also gave strong backing to
his embattled attorney general, Edwin Meese, saying, ``I have every
confidence in his integrity.''
   However, Reagan refused to comment on the investigation of
Meese's role in a proposed Middle East oil pipeline. Reagan said he
had no recollection of knowing about the pipeline deal until
recently.
   A relaxed Reagan opened with a smile, saying ``on the networks
at last'' _ a gibe at ABC, CBS and NBC for refusing to broadcast
his Feb. 2 speech appealing for Contra aid.
   However, he appeared uncomfortable at times, saying he was not
aware of Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan's complaint in
Senate testimony earlier Wednesday that the administration was
putting too much election-year pressure on the Fed to lower
interest rates.
   In his testimony, Greenspan was highly critical of a letter sent
by Assistant Treasury Secretary Michael Darby to top Fed
policy-makers 10 days before they were to meet to set monetary
growth targets for 1988.
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater, asked today if the
administration agreed with Greenspan, said, ``Yes, we do. We have
the highest regard for Chairman Greenspan and the work he's doing,
(we're) very concerned about any pressure being applied to the Fed
because they are an independent body, doing an outstanding job.''
   At his news conference, Reagan also contradicted his own
previous statements and those of Secretary of State George Shultz
and former Defense Secretary Caspar Weinberger by claiming the two
had not objected to the secret sale of arms to Iran on grounds it
was an arms-for-hostages deal.
   Shultz and Weinberger have said otherwise, and the Iran-Contra
report issued by two congressional committees said the secretaries
``called it a straight arms-for-hostages deal that was contrary to
U.S. public policy.''
   Brushing aside questions on the seemingly differing statements,
Fitzwater said today, ``I don't feel they need any reconciliation.
These are all matters of interpretation.''
   Reagan has tried from the start of the political campaign to
steer clear of the presidential race, but he suddenly switched
course with an open slap at Robertson.
   The former television evangelist had said earlier in the day
that his own Christian Broadcasting Network once knew the
whereabouts of American hostages in Lebanon ``and they could have
been freed'' if the United States had acted promptly.
   In reply, Reagan said that if Robertson knew where the hostages
were being held, ``he kept it to himself.'' The president said it
would be ``very strange'' if it happened the way Robertson
described it.
   As for the plight of the nine Americans now held in Lebanon,
Reagan declared, ``we've never let up, and we never will'' in
trying to obtain their freedom.
   Robertson, campaigning in Louisville, Ky., said today that
reporters for his network did have hostage information in 1985,
that he offered the information to the major television networks
and that he was then contacted by low-level State Department
officials.
   Reacting to Reagan's skepticism, he said, ``I wasn't meaning to
start some major confrontation with a person I admire tremendously,
but obviously the State Department must have dismissed what we had
to say, or else they didn't refer it up the line to the president.''
   In defense of Bush, Reagan corroborated the vice president's
claim that he had expressed private reservations about selling arms
to Iran.
   The president said he put down orders that ``I don't want to be
surrounded by `yes' men. And, yes, there were reservations, but I'm
not going to go into (them) just as he wouldn't go into the private
discussions that we may have had.''
   Asked about Democrats' charges that his administration has been
plagued by corruption, Reagan sidestepped the question and instead
accused Democrats of misrepresenting his administration's record on
the economy.
   ``If anyone listened for more than 15 minutes to their
candidates, he would decide that we're in an economic slump, we're
burdened by inflation, high interest rates and unemployment when,
at the moment, none of those things are true. ...
   ``So, I just think that, you know, the kids will play, and as
long as they want to do that, but I hope it'll easily be
forgotten.''
   Reagan's meeting with reporters coincided with Shultz's
departure for the Middle East to try to get Arab-Israeli peace
talks moving.
   ``It's time for all parties to rid themselves of old ideas and
stances that cannot work and to begin a serious process of
negotiation and reconciliation,'' Reagan said.
   ``Any process that is undertaken must meet Israel's security
needs and satisfy the legitimate rights of the Palestinians.''
   He said there is ``every evidence'' that outside terrorists have
been stirring up trouble in the Israeli-occupied West Bank and Gaza
Strip. He refused to say who he was talking about. Fitzwater today
insisted there was no difference between what Reagan said and
Shultz's claim that the problem was largely indigenous.
   Pointedly, Reagan passed up several opportunities to criticize
Israel's crackdown on Arab protestors in which more than 50
Palestinians have been killed. Reagan's strongest statement on the
subject was ``we don't support that sort of thing.''
   On other topics, Reagan:
   _Said Shultz had given him an ``encouraging'' report on his
just-completed trip to the Soviet Union. During the talks in
Moscow, Shultz and Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard Shevardnadze set
a one-month deadline for arms negotiators to complete drafts on key
elements of a new treaty to curb strategic nuclear weapons.
   _Said that a Democratic proposl limiting aid to the Contras to
``humanitarian'' assistance was ``fine, and then we'll take our
chances'' on another attempt at getting military aid for the rebels.
   _Said he had not decided whether to tell Congress that aid
should be resumed to Panama. To do that, he has to certify that
Panama is helping in anti-drug efforts, but Gen. Manuel Antonio
Noriega, Panama's military leader, has been indicted on U.S.
drug-trafficking charges.
</TEXT>
