<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--WorldCourt     02-25 0139</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--World Court,0143</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>World Court Elects President, Vice-President</HEAD>
<DATELINE>THE HAGUE, Netherlands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The World Court has elected an
Argentine judge as its president and re-elected as vice-president a
judge from Senegal.
   The court's 15 judges on Wednesday chose Judge Jose-Maria Ruda
to hold the body's highest position until 1991, and re-elected Keba
Mbaye as vice president, said the official.
   Ruda, who succeeds Judge Naghendra Singh of India, has been a
member of the court since 1973. Mbaye, elected vice president last
year, has served on the bench since 1982.
   The World Court, formally known as the International Court of
Justice, is the judicial arm of the United Nations. It has has no
power to enforce its rulings.
   Its 15 judges serve nine-year terms and may be re-elected
indefinitely. Presidents and vice presidents are elected for
three-year periods.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
