<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Yugoslavia-Press,0158</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Slovenian Journalists Face Criminal Charges</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LJUBLJANA, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two journalists were charged with
defaming the army and the defense minister after reporting he tried
to sell arms to famine-stricken Ethiopia instead of offering aid,
state television said.
   France Zavrl, chief editor of the Slovenian Mladina youth
weekly, and Andrej Novak, a journalist of the Teleks weekly, were
charged with ``offending and disdaining'' the army and Adm. Branko
Mamula, the defense minister, in published articles, state
television said.
   Mamula has faced tough criticism in a series of articles
published in the liberal republic of Slovenia for his February
visit to Ethiopia.
   The articles said that Mamula traveled to Ethiopia in order to
sell arms instead of offering food and financial aid.
   The charges against the journalists followed a recent sharp
statement issued by Yugoslavia's collective presidency, which
called for action against frequent press attacks on the army and
its leadership.
</TEXT>
