<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Sweden-AIDS     02-25 0168</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sweden-AIDS,0173</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>AIDS-Infected Prostitute Sentenced to Isolation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Swedish court has ordered a
prostitute infected with the AIDS virus to be isolated to keep her
from spreading the disease, it was reported Thursday.
   The unidentified woman, also a heroin addict, said she will
appeal the ruling. She argued that she has abandoned prostitution
and does not pose a health threat.
   She is under 24-hour guard in a hospital ward for AIDS patients,
and will remain there until the government opens a planned
institution for carriers of the disease on an island near
Stockholm, the newspapers said.
   Reports about the institution last year raised protests of
infringement on civil liberties.
   Swedish law allows authorities to restrict the movement of
people with contagious diseases who ignore medical advice on how to
avoid infecting others.
   The government is reviewing the law, which originally was aimed
at venereal diseases and other maladies that could be cured in a
short time, said Agneta Lagerroth of the Social Ministry.
</TEXT>
