<2ND_LINE>PM-Shultz, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0582,0553</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shultz Blames Occupation For Violence in West Bank, Gaza</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Israel-Shultz and Israel-Violence, Bjt</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with five grafs to UPDATE with White House saying
Reagan and Shultz statements consistent. Pick up 4th pvs, `Shultz
flew...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SHANNON, Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Secretary of State George P. Shultz
today blamed longtime Israeli occupation, not outside agitation,
for the violent unrest in the West Bank and Gaza Strip.
   Shultz said, ``Its fundamental origins are essentially
indigenous.''
   President Reagan, at a news conference Wednesday night, blamed
``terrorists'' and ``outsiders'' he did not identify for the
violence in the Israeli-held territories, which Israel seized in
the 1967 Middle East war. He cited intelligence reports but gave no
details.
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said today that the
statements of Reagan and Shultz were ``totally consistent.''
   ``The president said the same thing,'' Fitzwater said. ``He just
said they (the riots) were partly influenced by outside sources.
... He is saying that it is indigenous in the nature of the
political problems there but there has been some outside influence
as well.''
   Shultz flew to Jerusalem today with U.S. proposals for an
overall Mideast settlement.
   He said intelligence showed ``a mixed picture'' with
``interaction with outside force.'' But he added, ``There is an
underlying problem consisting of a large number of people in
occupation who haven't had the basic rights of governance.
   ``So we seek among other things consistent with Israel's
security, to look at things that will help Palestinians gain
legitimate rights.''
   Shultz defended his decision to stop in Syria while in the
Middle East.
   In the past, he accused Syria of terrorism and said the United
States should try to isolate the country. Sanctions were imposed in
1986, including a ban on meetings between high-level U.S. and
Syrian officials.
   ``In the first place, the Syrian involvement in terrorism seems
to have diminished, and we have had some definite moves that have
been made that we found encouraging,'' he said.
   ``I don't mean to say that the problem is resolved,'' Shultz
added, but he said the United States had realized how important a
role Syria plays in the region.
   ``So we will go there and hear what they have to say and tell
them what we have to say, recognizing their significance,'' he said.
   Shultz also seemed to disagree with Reagan over the Iran-Contra
affair.
   The president said Shultz and former Defense Secretary Caspar
Weinberger had objected to the secret sale of U..S arms to Iran,
not because it amounted to a trade for American hostages held in
Lebanon but because it could be perceived that way.
   Shultz, asked about the statement during a refueling stop here
on the way to Israel, did not directly challenge Reagan but said,
``I've testified and I really don't have anything to add or
subtract becasue my testimony is based to a very healthy extent on
records and notes and so on.''
   Shultz testified in private and in public that he had opposed
the U.S. arms sales to Iran because it had amounted to trading
weapons for hostages.
   He said the investigations had not brought out any other
argument by him and Weinberger against the sale.
</TEXT>
