<FILEID>AP-NR-02-25-88 1306EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-ChildHealth     02-25 0372</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Child Health,360</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>More Medicaid Among Steps That Could Improve Child Health,
Congress Told</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JILL LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Child health in the United States could be
improved through a number of steps ranging from an expanded
Medicaid program to child seat-belt requirements, a congressional
report said Thursday.
   The Office of Technology Assessment, which advises Congress on
scientific matters, also recommended better access to medical care
for poor children and pregnant women; newborn screening for several
disorders; and well-child care for those up to age 6.
   OTA said other promising approaches are school-based health
clinics and visiting nurse programs for families in which there is
a high risk of child abuse or the birth of low-birthweight babies.
   Judith Wagner, a senior assosciate at OTA, told the House Energy
and Commerce subcommittee on health and environment that the United
States ranked 17th among industrialized nations in infant
mortality, a position that showed no improvement in the past five
years.
   Wagner also said more than 20 percent of 2-year-olds were not
immunized against measles in 1985. He said poor children bear a
disproportionate share of illness and death, and a substantial
number of children do not have health insurance.
   OTA said it would be both effective and cost-saving to improve
access to early prenatal care for poor women, encourage
immunizations and preventive care for young children, and encourage
the use of child safety restraints in automobiles.
   The office said expanded newborn screening and universal
Medicaid eligibility for poor children would effectively improve
child health, although they would not necessarily save money.
   OTA recommended further study of two other approaches it
characterized as promising: visiting nurses for high-risk families
and comprehensive school clinics that offer family planning
services to adolescents at risk of unwanted pregnancy.
   Wagner said studies of two school-based clinics show they have
achieved some success in reducing pregnancy and birth rates. She
said Congress should seek more information on ``this rapidly
growing approach to delivering health services to high-risk
teen-agers.''
   Congress has been moving in recent years to include more
pregnant women and children in the Medicaid system. Subcommittee
chairman Henry Waxman, D-Calif., said Thursday he would introduce
legislation next week that includes several of OTA's suggestions.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
