<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Soviet-Armenia 3rdLd-Writethru   02-25 0793</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Armenia, 3rd Ld-Writethru,a0632,0819</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Travelers Say Armenians Continue Demonstrations</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 27th graf, `Tass announced...' to CORRECT that former
leader was Armenian. Pick up 28th pvs, `A later...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CAROL J. WILLIAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of people demonstrated today in the
Armenian capital, Yerevan, while the Soviet army sent in troops and
tanks to quell protests over a disputed area in neighboring
Azerbaidzhan, witnesses said.
   Armenians in Nagorno-Karabakh virtually shut down the disputed
area with a strike, travelers from the area said. Some residents
said Armenians had been killed.
   Mofses Gorgiskyan, a resident of Yerevan, said in a telephone
interview that more than 1 million people were demonstrating there
today, but the report could not be verified. He said they demanded
that Armenian authorities act on their demand that Nagorno-Karabakh
be made part of Armenia.
   Soldiers arrived in the morning and took up discreet positions
in downtown Yerevan, particularly around key government buildings,
Gorgiskyan said. They also deployed camouflaged trucks downtown and
stationed tanks in outlying areas, he said.
   Gorgiskyan said some Azeris, members of the main nationality of
Azerbaidzhan, threw stones at a bus in an outlying area of
Nagorno-Karabakh on Tuesday and killed an undetermined number of
Armenians. Azeris also set fire to a school, resulting in other
deaths, he said.
   Gorgiskyan described himself as a 26-year-old member of an
underground group called the Alliance for National Determination.
   In Nagorno-Karabakh, virtually the entire Armenian population,
about 120,000, has been demonstrating in the main city since Feb.
13, said a 17-year-old resident.
   There was no way to verify the reports independently because the
government barred foreign reporters from traveling to the area.
   The resident, a student, also said some Armenians had been
killed by Azeris, but she could offer no details.
   Three-quarters of the residents of Nagorno-Karabakh are
Armenians. The demonstrators are demanding that Armenia's nominal
Parliament support demands that Nagorno-Karabakh be removed from
Azerbaidzhan and turned over to Armenia.
   The resident, a student interviewed in Moscow after flying from
Armenia, spoke on condition she not be identified. She said she saw
a crowd gathered this morning in Lenin Square in Nagorno-Karabakh's
main city, Stepanakert.
   ``Practically the whole population is there. They've come from
all the villages,'' said the student.
   The student confirmed that authorities brought in extra forces
at one point during the 12 days of demonstrations, but she said she
believed they were militiamen, not army troops.
   Another Armenian interviewed at Moscow's Vnukovo Airport
estimated that 1,000 people were demonstrating this morning outside
the Opera House in Yerevan.
   The demonstrations in Nagorno-Karabakh were continuing around
the clock and schools and businesses were closed in a strike, said
the student. ``No one's sleeping. No one is going to work. The only
stores open are groceries,'' she said.
   An official at the Armenian representational offices in Moscow
in charge of internal matters, Rudolf Khatchyanov, told The
Associated Press that a major demonstration by Armenians continued
in Yerevan. But he said he had no details.
   Repeated calls to Yerevan were broken off after only a few
seconds or did not go through at all.
   Paruyr Ayrikyan, an Armenian activist in Yerevan, said Wednesday
that 200,000 people demonstrated in the capital's central square,
demanding that the republic's Parliament convene to resolve the
dispute.
   Armenian officials had proposed annexing the mountainous
territory, but the party's national Central Committee earlier this
month decided Nagorno-Karabakh should remain part of Azerbaidzhan.
   On Wednesday, the Kremlin named an Armenian, Genrikh Pogosyan,
Communist Party chief in the area.
   An Armenian activist in Moscow, Sergei Grigoryants, praised the
appointment, but said it would not likely quell the protests.
   ``This was the first test of the ability of the country's
leaders to work out a compromise to a difficult situation involving
nationalities,'' Grigoryants said.
   But he said Armenian demonstrators are angered over what they
see as unconstitutional interference by the party.
   ``The demonstrators already have deemed this matter outside the
party's control,'' Grigoryants said.
   Demonstrations by Armenians against control by Azeris began late
last week after the party's decision was announced, Ayrikyan said.
   The Soviet army sent in tanks and troops as a show of force, and
rumors spread to Yerevan that some Armenian demonstrators were
killed in the melee that ensued, said Ayrikyan.
   Tass announced Wednesday night that Pogosyan had been named
party leader in the disputed region. Tass said Pogosyan was
Armenian and born in Nagorno-Karabakh. His predecessor, Boris
Kevorkov, also is Armenian.
   A later Tass report said party leaders in Yerevan met and voiced
support for the Central Committee decision to keep Nagorno-Karabakh
in Azerbaidzhan. The party meeting also issued orders to local
officials to take all steps necessary to end the protests.
   Nagorno-Karabakh is 1,760 square miles, smaller than the state
of Delaware.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
