<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SovietMissiles     02-25 0540</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet Missiles,0558</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Officials Say Missile Withdrawal Begins in East Germany,
Czechoslovakia</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KENNETH JAUTZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BISCHOFSWERDA, East Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Communist officials and the
state-run press said Thursday that Soviet troops began withdrawing
SS-12 nuclear missiles from this town, where hundreds of people
waved flags and showered troops with gifts.
   Women pressed flowers on 150 Soviet soldiers and children gave
them books, candy and other gifts in an orchestrated, two-hour
ceremony at the train station. The troops have been here four years.
   As the train loaded with 32 canvas-wrapped containers pulled
away, the soldiers waved at the crowd and pressed the bouquets to
the windows.
   East German officials at the scene and the state-run ADN news
agency said the containers held parts of dismantled SS-12 missiles
and that the train was headed to the Soviet Union, where the
missiles would be destroyed.
   Western diplomats were skeptical.
   ``Until the arms treaty is in place, there is no way of
confirming what we are seeing, and what we are being told is
actually what it all appears to be,'' said one Western diplomat,
who asked not to be identified.
   In neighboring Czechoslovakia, the state-run CTK news agency
said Soviet SS-12 missiles were withdrawn from the town of Hranice,
southeast of Prague. It said a train carrying Soviet troops and 19
missile launchers left Hranice en route to the Soviet Union.
   The commander of Czechoslovak missile units and artillery, Lt.
Gen. Jan Krizan, was quoted by CTK as saying that Hranice was the
only place in Czechoslovakia where SS-12s were deployed.
   The shorter-range missiles, which have a range of 300 to 600
miles, would be the first nuclear weapons to be removed from
Central Europe under terms of a superpower arms treaty signed in
Washington last December.
   Soviet officials proclaimed the early withdrawal an ``act of
trust'' that the U.S. Congress would approve the accord.
   Military bands played and more than 1,000 residents waved small
East German, Soviet and Communist Party flags in Bischofswerda, a
city of about 12,000 near the Czechoslovak and Polish borders.
   Some people carried banners reading, ``An Early Missile
Withdrawal _ Proof of our Will for Peace,'' and ``Long Live the
Soviet-German Friendship.''
   Fifty-four SS-12 missiles have been based in East Germany, at
four separate sites, since 1983. They were deployed after NATO
deployed Pershing 2 and cruise missiles in Western Europe.
   ``This is an act of building trust,'' said Lt. Igor
Vladimirovich Obraszov, Soviet commander of one of the missile
batteries.
   Scores of East German soldiers were also on hand.
   ``Thank God they're leaving,'' said one East German army
lieutenant, referring to the Soviet missiles. ``For the past four
years I have had to accept being a possible target of a Western
attack.''
   The soldiers posed for photographers, shook hands with local
residents and tried to answer questions in halting English or
German.
   ``It is always good to be going home,'' said 1st Lt. Taras
Durayesky, a career army officer from Odessa as he boarded the
train. ``This is a good country, but I have been here four years.''
   More than 150 reporters watched the ceremony.
   CTK said 60 reporters were watching the removal of missiles from
Hranice, but no Western journalists were invited.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
