<DOCNO> AP880225-0128 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-25-88 1334EST</FILEID>
<TEXT>
        ...   with the University of Texas as the guest team.
   It's appropriate that Texas be the opponent because the
Longhorns suffered some deep miseries in the airish, dank building
where you could catch a cold even if you had just been cured of one.
   Perhaps the worst night was when Mike Wacker, center of an
unbeaten Longhorns' team, slipped on a wet spot and so tore up his
knee that it ended any chance of an NBA career.
   Like a curse from some Egyptian tomb, the voodooed Longhorns
sank to a miserable season, giving Abe Lemons' detractors their
chance to fire him.
   The next year when Texas visited, one Baylor coach wanted to
shake the 'Horns by putting a black X where Wacker fell. But more
tasteful and cooler heads prevailed.
   Spooky things always happened at H.O.T. Of course, there was the
first rain delay in college basketball history this year when the
roof leaked, holding up play.
   But that was small trick-or-treat stuff compared to one game I
remember years ago involving the visiting Texas A&M Aggies.
   I believe an Aggie was at the free throw line when a
late-running Baylor tuba player crashed his automobile into the
power pole outside.
   It plunged H.O.T into darker darkness.
   The place had always been so dim that rival coaches threatened
to issue their players coal miners' lamps.
   Of course, A&M Coach Shelby Metcalf was fit to be fried. The
lights never were restored to full power. The Aggies finally agreed
to play the game out under eerie, twilight zone conditions. They
lost.
   ``You had to listen for the swish to know you made one,''
Metcalf quipped.
   Powers failures were always numerous in H.O.T.
   More than one deadline was blown by electrical outages which
sent stories to editorial graveyards. One sports writer slam-dunked
his chair into the stands in one outage outrage.
   More recently, the Baylor mascot knocked a Dallas radio off the
air briefly by stumbling over an electrical cord.
   Just getting into the building could be fun. I recall arriving
at a game early for prime position on gravel within several blocks
of the coliseum on a rainy evening.
   Feeling smug, I advanced to within 25 yards of the building
before almost disappearing in a mud hole large enough to lose a
Shetland pony.
   Baylor always had a big advantage in this ``pit.''
   The Bears at least knew where the dim rims could be found. Crowd
seating on the floor also gave the Bears a huge psychological edge.
   But Baylor was hurt in the recruting wars because of the
decaying coliseum.
   Former Coach Jim Haller always liked to talk about school
academics and such on recruiting visits. He knew he was dead if he
had to take the kid to the barn.
   Baylor's ``dressing room'' to this day is a trailer parked at
one end of the coliseum.
   Once a goal weighing hundreds of pounds fell to the floor only
20 feet from where Pam Davis' Baylor womens' team was exercising.
Another time a retaining wall collapsed just yards away from where
spectators were seated.
   At least the building had a heart: Nobody was ever killed in it.
   The Bears' new coliseum is expected to be ready for Coach Gene
Iba next fall. It's going to be a compact 9,000-seater which will
put the fans within easy shouting distance of the opponents' ear
pans.
   Baylor recruiting should be a lot easier, but opponents will
never have the fear they had amidst the spiders and cobwebs in
H.O.T.
   It was the pit of pits, but on March 5th will become a nostalgic
page in Southwest Conference basketball history.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>END ADV Weekend Editions Feb. 27-28</NOTE>
