<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Trade     02-25 0531</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Trade,520</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Verity Urges Action on Trade Bill; Bentsen Reports Progress</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Commerce Secretary C. William Verity urged
lawmakers Thursday to produce a major trade bill but not resort to
protectionism, while a Senate chairman reported progress in
drafting such a measure.
   ``I think we should have a trade bill and it should be a good
trade bill,'' Verity told the House Foreign Affairs Committee. He
urged the lawmakers to avoid protectionism and praised them for
moving to soften a Senate provision that would ban U.S. sales of
Toshiba products.
   The Senate included its Toshiba provision last year following
reports that a subsidiary of the Japanese electronics producer had
sold sophisticated submarine-silencing technology to the Soviet
Union.
   The administration, however, has been a critic of the provision,
and House negotiators have proposed to leave the decision up to the
president.
   ``We believe that would be the correct approach,'' Verity said.
   Senate Finance Committee Chairman Lloyd Bentsen, D-Texas, said
House-Senate negotiators had dropped ``foreign policy'' provisions
from a compromise version of the two chambers' trade bills.
   He did not specify which provisions that involved, although
House negotiators on Tuesday proposed to delete a feature that
would strip Romania of its guarantee of trade relations with the
United States that are as good as those enjoyed by any other
country. Proponents say the provision would prod Romania to improve
its emigration policies.
   Particular interest has focused on a House offer to drop a
provision of both measures that would allow a handful of sugar
refining companies to collect from the government $400 million in
tariffs paid years ago on sugar imports that since then have been
refined and re-exported.
   Among other matters facing the senators is a House proposal to
drop import curbs on lamb. The feature, contained only in the
Senate bill, was sponsored by one of the conferees, Sen. Max
Baucus, D-Mont., who emerged from the meeting and declared that
``real progress has been made'' but provided no specifics.
   In other trade action, lawmakers from wheat-producing states
sharply questioned Agriculture Secretary Richard Lyng and U.S.
Trade Representative Clayton K. Yeutter at a House Agriculture
Committee hearing.
   The two secretaries were there to discuss the proposed
free-trade agreement between the United States and Canada. One
provision of the agreement would end Canadian transportation
subsidies for wheat shipped to Vancouver but leave untouched a
subsidy for shipments to the big grain port at Thunder Bay,
Ontario. Transporation costs are a key factor in grain prices.
   American wheat growers have been complaining that the Thunder
Bay payments also should have been eliminated under the treaty,
whose major provisions would phase out tariffs between the United
States and Canada.
   Lyng and Yeutter reiterated previous pledges to consider the
Thunder Bay issue in future negotiations and repeated what they
said in earlier clashes, namely that the pact represents an
improvement in U.S.-Canadian trade relations as well as being the
best deal that American negotiators could get.
   But that did not satisfy some lawmakers.
   ``Are you still looking after the interests of U.S. agricultural
producers?'' said Rep. Ron Marlenee, R-Mont.
   ``I would give an emphatic yes,'' Lyng responded.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880225-0131 </DOCNO>
