<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Tibet     02-25 0623</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Tibet,0639</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tibetan Buddhists Begin Festival Despite Fear of Violence</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM ABRAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tibetan Buddhists Thursday began their most
important religious festival, an 11-day celebration that was nearly
canceled because of fears of a repetition of last fall's violent
anti-Chinese demonstrations.
   Foreign sources in Lhasa, the capital of Tibet, said the start
of the Moinlam Qenmo festival passed without incident, although
some monks were reluctant to attend the ceremonies and some people
stayed away to avoid possible trouble.
   An Indian tourist guide in Lhasa, contacted by phone, said some
monks didn't want to participate because they said fellow monks,
who led the pro-independence riots in September and October, were
still detained by Chinese police.
   The guide, who refused to give his name, said there was division
in the Tibetan community over whether to hold the religious rites
as usual this year. He could not confirm reports that some monks
boycotted the festival.
   China's official media earlier said 80 people, including monks,
were detained following the disturbances in which about 14 people
lost their lives. Official reports said almost all had been
released after repenting their actions in the riots.
   A Tibetan-speaking American, who has been in Lhasa four months,
said the city was ``a little tense'' Thursday with uniformed and
plainclothes police on patrol. He said he saw police in riot gear
at the Johkang Temple where the main ceremonies for the holiday are
taking place.
   The American, who also refused to give his name, said foreigners
have been told to return to their hotels by 10 p.m., and that
police have posted signs in English warning foreigners not to
photograph or participate in disturbances.
   The official Xinhua News Agency reported from Lhasa that
ceremonies marking the start of Moinlam Qenmo began when two lamas,
or monks, blew blasts on large trumpets from the Johkang Temple in
the center of the city.
   Xinhua said about 1,000 monks gathered at the temple to mark the
annual ``grand summons'' ceremony, and that about 1,000 people
watched in the square outside the temple.
   The news agency said that with the blowing of the trumpets
dozens of believers threw letters of good wishes tied with silk
scarves to the presiding lama and begged him to pray for their
happiness.
   Inside the temple, one of Tibetan Buddhism's holiest sites,
thousands of lamps glowed while monks prayed to Zong Kaba, founder
of the Yellow Sect of Tibetan Lamaism who started the ceremony in
1409.
   The Panchem Lama, Tibet's second-holiest man after the exiled
Dalai Lama, revealed last month that officials had considered
canceling the festival because of fears that the arrival of
thousands of pilgrims from other parts of Tibet would lead to a new
outbreak of violence.
   The communists, which took control over Tibet in 1950, claims
the remote mountainous region has been an integral part of China
for centuries.
   However, there has long been considerable friction between the
Tibetans and the Hans who are the dominant ethnic group of China,
particularly as a result of the 1966-76 Cultural Revolution when
leftist Red Guards destroyed temples, suppressed local customs and
language, and persecuted religious believers.
   China blames the recent disturbances on the Dalai Lama, who fled
to India following an unsuccessful 1959 uprising and continues to
speak out against what he says are China's oppressive policies in
Tibet.
   The Beijign government has also accused the U.S. Congress, which
has called on China to stop human rights violations in Tibet, of
meddling in its internal affairs
   China has said it made mistakes during the Cultural Revolution
and has tried to make amends by rebuilding temples, guaranteeing
religious freedom and paying for development of the region, one of
the poorest in the country.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880225-0132 </DOCNO>
