<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Army-Officers     02-25 0477</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Army-Officers,470</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Army Announces Steps to Reduce Officer Corps</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Army unveiled plans Thursday for cutting
officer strength in a budget move, including appointment of a board
to select more than 350 colonels and lieutenant colonels for early
retirement.
   The service said it also was beginning a voluntary release
program for all officers regardless of rank who wanted to leave the
military, and would strictly enforce guidelines specifying the
discharge of any first lieutenant who fails for a second time to
win promotion to captain.
   The Army disclosed last week in its fiscal 1989 budget proposal
that it was cutting active-duty strength by 8,600, including about
1,540 officers. The cuts _ down to a total strength of roughly
772,000 _ were prompted by a deficit-reduction agreement reached
with Congress last November.
   Earlier this month, the Army said it would trim its enlisted
ranks through a combination of early discharges for soldiers who
were already preparing to leave the service and reductions in
recruiting goals.
   The service said Thursday it had now begun focusing on the
officer community and hoped the combination of the three new
programs would allow it to reduce those ranks without causing undue
personal hardship.
   Lt. Col. Greg Rixon, an Army spokesman, said the service
expected between 750 and 800 officers to resign or retire as part
of normal attrition. To make up the difference toward the new
target, he said:
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   _The Army will convene a Selective Early Retirement Board in May
to pick 178 colonels and 181 lieutenant colonels for retirement.
These are officers who have already served at least 20 years, and
thus are eligible for a pension, but had not planned to retire yet.
Those selected by the board will have to retire by Nov. 30.
   As of last Sept. 30, the Army had 4,647 colonels and 11,120
lieutenant colonels.
   _The Army will immediately start a voluntary release program for
all commissioned officers. Under this program, an officer who
decides he is ready to leave the military _ but who still ``owes''
time under a special obligation _ will be allowed to resign or
retire anyway.
   The special obligations involve extra commitments of service
stemming from such things as advanced schooling or acceptance of
lengthy overseas tours.
   Younger officers who were ``commissioned through a service
academy, ROTC or Officer Candidate School may have up to 12 months
of their service obligation waived, in exchange for 12 months of
commitment in a National Guard or Army Reserve unit,'' Rixon added.
   _Strict ``involuntary release,'' or dismissal, for certain first
lieutenants no later than Sept. 30. Rixon said a younger officer
who is passed over twice for promotion is normally discharged in
any event. Under the new program, however, there will be no
possibility of a waiver that would allow the officer to remain.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
