<2ND_LINE>PM-Elderly-Shooting, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0672,0278</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Man Opens Fire at Home for Elderly; Five Injured</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with four wounded, fifth suffering heart
attack, details on surrender and conditions; No pickup; ADDS
byline.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SCOTT ROTHSCHILD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ARLINGTON, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who had been evicted from a
retirement home burst into a board meeting at the home with two
rifles today and opened fire, wounding four people, authorities
said. A fifth person suffered a heart attack.
   The gunman fled from the room at the Masonic Home for the Aged
with one rifle tied around his neck with twine, police spokesman
Dee Anderson said. Police captured him after a chase.
   A woman who was one of the four wounded also complained of chest
pain, Anderson said.
   A fifth person, Willie Joe Wright, 67, suffered a heart attack
and was in critical condition at Arlington Memorial Hospital,
hospital spokeswoman Tenya Woods said. The other shooting victims
were in fair condition, she said.
   ``Apparently, they had a board meeting and one former resident,
who was apparently disgruntled, walked into the board room and
started shooting,'' Anderson said.
   Anderson said 16 board members were in the room.
   ``When the officers went to a kitchen in the rear of the
building, the man still had one rifle. He very calmly gave up when
the officers asked him to surrender,'' Anderson said. ``He did not
give any information to police.''
   The gunman, whose name was withheld, had lived at the home for
three years and ``was aware of the time frame of the board meeting.
He had been evicted or asked to leave,'' Anderson said.
</TEXT>
