<FILEID>AP-NR-02-25-88 1442EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Roach-Off     02-25 0352</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Roach-Off,0365</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Annual Roach-Off Launched at School Of Last Year's Winner</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOLLYWOOD, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The annual search for the nation's most
colossal cockroach is off and scurrying.
   The Combat Great American Roach-Off II came to the McNicol
Middle School Wednesday to kick off the contest, which will net the
winner $1,000 and a trip to the Smithsonian Institution's Insect
Zoo in Washington to see their roach enshrined.
   Sponsors picked the McNicol school because last year's winner,
Laine Snyder, who discovered his 2-inch-long entry under a
Hollywood Beach lifeguard stand, attended the school at the time.
   Laine has since moved, but other McNicol students hope to make
their school a winner again, even if it means changing their habits.
   ``I just step on them when I see them,'' said Eric Poirot, 13.
``I guess I better stop stepping on them if I want to win this
contest.''
   Another hopeful is Frank Alvarez, 11, who let contest
coordinator Michael ``Cockroach Dundee'' Bohdan place a hissing
3-inch monster from Madagascar onto his hand.
   ``Hey, no problem,'' he said. ``I handle lizards. This is just a
cockroach.''
   Frank plans to go roach hunting as soon as he can.
   ``I'd like to get the biggest cockroaches. My mother would
scream, though, when I brought it home.''
   He thought a moment. ``She sure wouldn't scream if I brought
home that $1,000.''
   Bohdan, a Dallas exterminator, started the contest last year to
raise awareness about roaches, which he called the most serious
pest problem in the country. The makers of Combat Roach Control
System joined Bohdan in sponsoring the contest.
   The rules: Live cockroaches need not apply. They must be dead,
but not squashed. Those much smaller than last year's winner, which
was more than 2 inches long, won't have a chance.
   Competitions will be held in May in Miami, New York, Washington,
Los Angeles, San Antonio, Texas, and Louisville, Ky. The Roach-Off
finals will be in June in New York.
   Roaches can also be mailed in strong packages _ some got
flattened in transit last year _ to Bohdan at his Pest Shop in
Plano, Texas.
</TEXT>
