<1ST_LINE>u a PM-DeathPenalty     02-25 0379</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Death Penalty,0386</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Upholds Two Death Sentences, Reverses One</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The California Supreme Court today upheld
the death sentences of two men but reversed a third because the
defendant was not given a hearing on his competency to stand trial.
   The two death sentences affirmed _ one for the fatal shooting of
a couple in Los Angeles, the other for the kidnapping and fatal
stabbing of an 8-year-old girl in Hayward _ marked the first time
in recent years the court has upheld more than one death sentence
on a single day.
   The three decisions were written by Chief Justice Malcolm Lucas.
The court was unanimous in two of the cases, but split 5-2 in the
Los Angeles murder. The dissenters said the judge should not have
told jurors to disregard their ``personal choice'' and consider
only the factors listed in the law in deciding on punishment.
   Since last year, when conservatives led by Lucas gained a
majority, the court has upheld six of the 10 death sentences it has
considered.
   In the case that was reversed, Brian Darle Hale was convicted of
fatally shooting two elderly men, robbing one and attempting to rob
the other in Bellflower and Cerritos in October 1980.
   During pretrial proceedings, the court said, Hale said he was
``a president'' and a better judge than the trial judge, said he
had ``little speakers in his ears,'' and called the judge
``Fatso,'' among other rambling statements. Two court-appointed
psychiatrists concluded he was incompetent to stand trial; three
others disagreed.
   Los Angeles Superior Court Judge Cecil Mills ordered a hearing
to decide whether Hale was mentally able to understand the
proceedings or assist in his own defense. But for reasons not
explained on the record, no such hearing was held before the trial
in which Hale was convicted and sentenced to death.
   The court voted 5-2 to uphold the death sentence of Eric B.
Kimble for the August 1978 fatal shootings of Harry and Avonne
Margulies in the Doheny Estates neighborhood of Los Angeles, the
rape of Mrs. Margulies and the burglary of Margulies' stereo
equipment store.
   The court unanimously affirmed the death sentence of Richard
Hovey for the March 1978 kidnapping and fatal stabbing of
8-year-old Tina Salazar in Hayward.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
