<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Czechoslovakia Bjt   02-25 0624</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Czechoslovakia, Bjt,0645</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Czechoslovaks Mark 40 Years of Communism With Low-Key Rally</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALISON SMALE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of people stood in
driving snow Thursday on the site of a triumphant rally that
ushered in Communism in Czechoslovakia 40 years ago.
   Banners and red flags decorated the central Old Town Square,
which in 1948 resounded with the cheers of tens of thousands when
the Communists took power. Thursday's anniversary rally, however,
was short and low-key.
   On Feb. 21, 1948, Klement Gottwald gave a triumphant speech on
the square four days before taking over Czechoslovakia's first
all-Communist government.
   Thursday's crowd was subdued. Huddled under umbrellas, the
number of onlookers appeared to be less than the 80,000 people
estimated by the state news agency CTK. The banners hung limp in
the snow.
   Dozens of people drifted out of the square after party leader
Milos Jakes began a 20-minute speech recalling the ``victorious
February'' of 1948 and Czechoslovakia's sometimes troubled history
since.
   President Gustav Husak, 75, who stepped down as party leader in
December, was the first member of the ruling Politburo to take the
stand where the leadership stood sheltered from the snow.
   When Husak first appeared, nobody cheered or applauded. A few
claps were heard in the crowd once he waved.
   In his speech, Jakes remembered what he called ``dramatic
moments deciding fateful questions of our life'' in 1948.
   Forty years ago, a political crisis arose when most
non-Communist ministers in the government resigned in protest at
growing Communist influence in the security and police forces.
   Five days of well-organized street rallies and fierce political
discussions followed, ending with Gottwald becoming head of a
Communist government.
   The takeover sealed the Kremlin's domination of Eastern Europe,
and installed a Communist regime that swiftly began Stalinist-style
purges of opponents and of party ranks.
   Jakes presented the 1948 takeover as a move that ensured the
triumph of the working class over the ``oppression'' of bourgeois
democrats who ruled in Czechoslovakia before World War II.
   Looking back on the ``Prague Spring'' reforms attempted under
Alexander Dubcek in 1968, Jakes reiterated the hard line voiced in
a long speech Wednesday at a ceremony marking the anniversary.
   He again rejected any comparison between the reforms of Dubcek
20 years ago and the changes said to be under way now in
Czechoslovakia following Mikhail S. Gorbachev's reforms in the
Soviet Union.
   Today's changes aim to strengthen socialism, Jakes said. In
1968, he added, ``the revolutionary achievements of victorious
February and our alliance bonds with the Soviet Union and other
socialist states were threatened.
   ``Such is the historical truth and nothing substantial can be
changed in it.''
   Jakes gave little indication he is about to favor the economic
and political reforms being tried in the Soviet Union, Poland,
Hungary and Bulgaria. He also ruled out all non-communist
opposition.
   His hour-long speech to 500 party members in Prague's Hradcany
Castle did not essentially differ from the cautious conservatism
Husak displayed during his 18-year tenure.
   Jakes' speech Thursday was punctuated by few bursts of applause.
Once he finished, a loudspeaker struck up the Communist anthem,
``The Internationale,'' which was sung by some of the crowd and a
few leaders on the stand.
   Men in the gray-blue uniforms of the People's Militia and
soldiers in khaki dress uniforms marched briskly past the stand.
   In his public appearances recently, Jakes has emulated
Gorbachev's style of chatting to citizens on the streets and in
factories. He closed out the brief ceremony Thursday with thanks to
the citzens for attending and good wishes for their success at work.
   Five minutes later, the square was deserted. Television
schedules had indicated the ceremony would last 75 minutes, but it
was over in half an hour.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
