<1ST_LINE>r a AM-CDC--CruiseShips     02-25 0583</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-CDC--Cruise Ships,0600</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>CDC Says Inspections Have Curtailed Illnesses, Despite Criticism</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: For release 6:30 p.m. EST _ time set by source</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BYRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The federal government's sanitation inspection
program for cruise ships, now 13 years old, has made a marked
difference in preventing illness among travelers, officials said
Thursday.
   The national Centers for Disease Control, which oversees
periodic inspections of cruise ships sailing regularly from U.S.
ports, reported Thursday that the percentage of ships passing
inspection rose dramatically over the program's first decade, while
the number of intestinal illness outbreaks among passengers
declined.
   Despite the positive findings, the CDC has been criticized for
reorganizing its inspection program.
   In 1975, when the program began, cruise ships were reporting 7.7
outbreaks of diarrhea for every 10 million passenger-days sailed,
said Dr. Vernon Houk, director of the agency's Center for
Environmental Health. By 1985, the figure dropped to 2.7 outbreaks
per 10 million passenger-days.
   A passenger-day is one day spent on a ship by one passenger. The
CDC considers an outbreak in progress if 3 percent of the
passengers and crew are ill.
   ``This has been a cooperative effort between us and the cruise
ship industry, and ... (the study) clearly shows it has been
working,'' Houk said. ``Things are going in the right direction.''
   Only 18 percent of the ships inspected in the first year earned
satisfactory ratings, compared with 72 percent in 1985, CDC
researchers said.
   The CDC also presented new findings Thursday indicating ``that
ships that consistently have the highest sanitation scores are less
likely to have an outbreak of diarrheal disease than ships with
lower average scores.''
   On the average, for every 10 million passenger-days, fewer than
two of the ships scoring in the top 20 percent reported diarrhea
outbreaks. That compares with outbreaks aboard more than eight of
the ships scoring in the bottom 20 percent.
   The 1975-85 results aside, critics have charged that the
program's performance has suffered since a reorganization nearly
two years ago. The CDC terminated its inspections in 1986,
substituting a plan by which the cruise lines would conduct their
own inspections. In 1987, a new plan was imposed, using private
inspectors operating under CDC review.
   According to the CDC's latest summary of the 1987 and 1988
inspections, only 55 percent of the ships regularly sailing from
U.S. ports _ 30 of 55 ships _ passed. The CDC has no legal power to
block ships from sailing, but does distribute the results of its
inspections.
   Critics have said the resent inspection results are not good
news for the ``privatization'' plan.
   Thursday, Houk said it is ``too early to draw conclusions'' from
the initial reports from the revamped program. Some ships have not
yet been inspected under the new routine.
   Houk stressed that the inspection program is thorough.
   ``Travelers ought to be aware that these are very tough
inspections,'' he said, ``far tougher than the usual restaurant
inspections done ashore.''
   The CDC inspections act as ``an independent survey'' of how well
the cruise lines' own sanitation programs are working, he added.
   ``The individual traveler should not look at a single inspection
report and make that the determinant whether he'll travel on that
ship or not,'' he said. ``It seems to me the useful question is,
`What is the past history of this ship?'''
   The CDC, in its weekly report, noted that the sanitation
inspections monitor water quality, food storage and preparation,
potential for food contamination, cleanliness and other factors.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
