<1ST_LINE>r a AM-AngelSearch     02-25 0277</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Angel Search,0283</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New Talent Search Under Way for `Charlie's Angels'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Producer Aaron Spelling and Fox Broadcasting
Co. are turning to the time-honored tradition of a nationwide
talent search to find the young women who will be television's new
``Charlie's Angels.''
   Young women across the country will be offered an opportunity to
land one of the four roles in ``Angels '88,'' which will make its
debut this summer on Fox.
   At least five actresses discovered during the search will be
assured of roles in at least one episode of ``Angels '88,'' a Fox
spokesman said.
   Unlike the original series, which ran on ABC from 1976 to 1981,
the new show will have four angels instead of three. Farrah
Fawcett, Kate Jackson and Jaclyn Smith were the original angels,
although there were cast replacements during later seasons.
   The dates and cities for the auditions are as follows: March 3,
Los Angeles; March 4, Chicago, Boston, Dallas; March 11, Miami,
Denver, San Francisco; week of March 14, open calls in 50 cities
with Fox stations; March 18, Atlanta, Detroit, Nashville, Tenn.;
March 21, New York.
   Finalists will take part in auditions in Los Angeles March 31
and the new angels will be announced April 6.
   The talent search is a Hollywood tradition that goes back to the
search for an actress to play Scarlett O'Hara in ``Gone With the
Wind'' 50 years ago. At the last minute British actress Vivian
Leigh was selected to star opposite Clark Gable.
   The Disney Studio is also conducting a nationwide talent hunt
for youngsters who look like the original Mousketeers for a movie
about the ``Mickey Mouse Club.''
</TEXT>
