<2ND_LINE>PM-School Arsonist, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0655,0492</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Arson Suspect Charged in Washington School, Church Fires</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 8 grafs to UPDATE with prosecutor saying man
admitting setting fires, details on charges; Picks up 7th graf,
`Howe's mother ...'</NOTE>
<HEAD>Precede OMAK</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN WILEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OKANOGAN, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former firefighter admitted setting a
series of arson fires that burned a small town's elementary school
and two churches that opened their doors to students, a prosecutor
said today.
   Adrian Julius Howe, 23, of Omak will be charged with six counts
of first-degree arson, prosecutor Jack Burchard said. He was held
in the Okanogan County Jail.
   Howe admitted setting the fires, which caused $6.5 million in
damage, Burchard said. Each arson count carries a possible sentence
of life imprisonment and a $50,000 fine.
   Officials declined to comment on reports that Howe held a grudge
against the burned school, North Omak Elementary School.
   The six fires that began in December and hit the school twice in
eight days led to the creation of a 12-member arson task force and
door-to-door canvassing in search of leads. Two churches and a
church house were also burned; one of the churches was struck twice.
   Howe was arrested Wednesday, said Mimi Curry of the state
Department of Community Development's division of fire protection
services, who has been appointed spokeswoman for the investigation.
   The task force, set up Tuesday and composed of local, state and
U.S. Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms agents, was ``at a
peak of activity,'' with investigators going door-to-door, Ms.
Curry said.
   The string of arsons terrorized Omak, a placid north-central
Washington town of 4,000. Churches and schools stepped up security,
and residents formed night-time patrols.
   Howe's mother, Lena Howe, 67, said she and her 75-year-old
husband, Ben, adopted their son at age 2. He had learning
difficulties and left Omak High School in his junior year, the
mother told The Spokesman-Review in today's editions of the Spokane
newspaper.
   Howe later got a job on the fire patrol in nearby Nespelem, but
was not rehired after he lost his driver's license because of
drinking problems, Mrs. Howe said. He now works at a lumber mill on
the Colville Indian reservation, just east of Omak, Mrs. Howe said.
   Colville Indian Reservation tribal chief Harry Smiskin said Howe
was a firefighter for the U.S. Bureau of Indian Affairs' fire
control department. He said he gave details of Howe's employment to
investigators.
   The Washington state House voted Wednesday night to include in
its $207 million supplemental state budget a $150,000 appropriation
to help Omak and Okanogan County pay for investigation of the
blazes.
   If fully approved, the money would be used for administrative
costs to complete the arson investigation, Ms. Curry said.
   ``The (Okanogan) county budget is being quickly depleted,'' she
said. ``After all, they (county commissioners) didn't plan for this
(the arson fires) to happen.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880225-0143 </DOCNO>
