<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Bush     02-25 0663</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush,660</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Campaigns Against Textile Bill in South Carolina</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GREENWOOD, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   George Bush took on a hot issue in a
state that could be a Republican indicator for the rest of the
South Thursday, rejecting as ``pure, all-out protectionism''
efforts backed by rivals Bob Dole and Pat Robertson to help the
textile industry by limiting foreign imports.
   Bush said he opposed legislation that has been sought by many in
South Carolina and other textile states as a cure for the
industry's troubles. His comments came one day after Dole
campaigned in the same area and called for the bill's passage.
   ``I'm for the textile industry _ not the bill,'' the vice
president said while greeting several hundred people alongside a
Greenwood street. ``There have got to be some changes before I'd be
for it.''
   ``Don't go for this pure, all-out protectionism that may save
one job and then throw three neighbors in this burgeoning state out
of work,'' Bush said earlier at a technical college in Pendleton,
S.C. ``That's not the answer.''
   Bush turned aside most questions about his long-distance
exchange with Pat Robertson over the past two days. But he said the
former TV evangelist hadn't responded to his demand for an apology
or proof ``by sundown in the Old South'' to back up Robertson's
suggestion that the release of sex-scandal allegations against
evangelist Jimmy Swaggart had been timed to hurt Robertson.
   ``Haven't heard a word,'' Bush said. ``I've said all I'm going
to say about that.''
   Robertson, in Louisville, Ky., said he'd been misquoted and
suggested Bush wouldn't be asking for an aplogy if he knew what
Robertson had really said.
   Bush spoke about the textile issue to several hundred teachers,
students and others at an assembly at Tri-County Technical College,
on a day when he toured the northwestern corner of South Carolina
by motorcade and stopped at high schools, colleges and restaurants.
   Dole and Robertson support legislation that would place limits
on the amount of foreign textile products that could be imported.
The legislation is popular in textile-producing areas, but
President Reagan vetoed similar legislation after it was passed by
Congress more than two years ago.
   ``What I propose is that we enforce the law,'' Bush said.
``Sometimes we're fighting the bureaucracy in Washington. We have
the laws on the books _ enforce it, so that the textile industry
will continue to profit.''
   At evey stop Bush underscored the importance he and others
attach to South Carolina in the race for the Republican nomination.
The state holds its GOP primary on Saturday March 5, with 37
delegates at stake. But the state is given broader significance
because it comes three days before the rest of the South votes on
Super Tuesday, a day when one-third of the delegates in both
parties will be up for grabs.
   Robertson has said he must win in South Carolina and has devoted
an intensive effort. Bush has long considered it one of his best
states in the South, since he has broad party support including
that of Gov. Carroll A. Campbell Jr., who accompanied him at his
stops.
   Bush would like a win going into the Super Tuesday states, after
finishing far behind in South Dakota and Minnesota contests last
Tuesday, and he was spending two days campaigning here this week.
   Dole, the Kansas senator, also contesting here, was accompanied
in the state on Wednesday by Republican Sen. Strom Thurmond.
   Bush dropped in on an industrial electronics class where about
30 students interrupted their final examination to hear him speak
briefly and watch as he observed a demonstration of a small,
computer-driven robotics machine.
   He sought to tie himself closely to Reagan at his stops in this
state where the president has been a popular vote-getter. He said,
``I've taken some shots'' for remaining loyal to Reagan, ``but you
and I know loyalty is a strength, not a weakness.''
</TEXT>
