<1ST_LINE>r a AM-People     02-25 0555</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-People,0579</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>People in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY44</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: First item for release 6 p.m. EST.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sidney Poitier says he has worked hard during
his 38-year-career to be considered just an actor, not a black
actor.
   ``Today we have Eddie Murphy, Denzel Washington, Richard Pryor,
Bill Cosby and James Earl Jones,'' said Hollywood's first black
leading man.
   ``We have a lot of black actors who are working. I am now
finally just another actor, and that is a hallowed place to be,''
Poitier says in the Sunday issue of Parade magazine.
   During an interview on the set of ``Shoot to Kill,'' his latest
film, Poitier reminisced about his mother and his poverty-filled
youth growing up in the Bahamas.
   ``When a mother would be giving her son a whipping for one thing
or another, she'd say, `Don't do that to the boy. Leave him alone
and let his mind work. That's the way my young Sidney was _ and
look what happened to him.'
   ``Hearing that was one of the best rewards I ever had,'' said
Poitier.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Singer Willie Nelson will be principal
host of The Nashville Network's Viewers' Choice Awards April 26,
the cable channel has announced.
   The Oak Ridge Boys and TNN's Ralph Emery will also share hosting
duties during the 90-minute live show at the Grand Ole Opry House.
   TNN viewers are now voting for winners in eight country music
categories.
   Nelson is known for such hits as ``On the Road Again'' and
``Always on My Mind'' as well as his longtime commitment to helping
financially plagued farmers.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SAN REMO, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   All eyes were on Patsy Kensit, lead
singer of the British band Eighth Wonder, when she performed at
this year's 38th San Remo music festival.
   At last year's festival, a strap on Ms. Kensit's dress broke
during her number, exposing her breast. This year, her dress stayed
put.
   ``Well, I see your dress didn't fall down this year,'' presenter
Carlo Mazzarini remarked after her performance.
   Foreign talent again dominated the four-day festival, which
wraps up Saturday. Wednesday night's six-hour show featured
Manhattan Transfer, Bryan Ferry, Ben E. King, Debbie Gibson, Def
Leppard and Toto.
   Still to perform were Paul McCartney, Terence Trent D'Arby, Bon
Jovi, Joe Cocker and Art Garfunkel.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ilona Staller, better known as Cicciolina, the porn
star who was elected to Pariliament last year, faced new legal
problems Thursday as prosecutors pressed cases to bring her to
trial on obscenity charges.
   Rome chief's prosecutor, Marco Boschi, announced that he has
asked the Chamber of Deputies to lift Ms. Staller's parliamentary
immunity so she can be tried on charges of conspiring with other
people to produce obscene publications and take part in live shows.
   Only Parliament can decide whether one of its members can be
brought to trial.
   The Rome case is one of three pending against the Hungarian-born
Ms. Staller, who was elected on the Radical Party Ticket.
   Earlier this week, a prosecutor in Venice sent Parliament video
tapes of Ms. Staller riding bare-breasted on horseback through St.
Mark's Square last September. Another case regards photos of her in
a magazine.
   Ms. Staller has often said she would welcome a trial to
demonstrate what she calls the hypocrisy of Italy's laws defining
obscenity.
</TEXT>
