<1ST_LINE>r w AM-SpaceFight     02-25 0603</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Space Fight,590</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Congressman Says Commerce Department Making `Power Grab' In Space</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL RECER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The head of the House space subcommittee said
Thursday the Commerce Department may be trying a ``power grab'' by
granting a Massachusetts company an export license for an
experiment that is to be flown aboard the Soviet Union's Mir space
station.
   ``It's no secret that since space is a sexy subject that the
Department of Commerce wants to get its fingers into the
jurisdiction of space,'' Rep. Bill Nelson, D-Fla., said at a news
conference.
   ``Is this another power grab of trying to get into the space
business?'' an angry Nelson asked.
   Nelson said he was angry that Commerce granted an export license
to Payload Systems Inc. of Wellesley, Mass., for a protein crystal
growth experiment to be carried on the Mir without consulting with
NASA, the Transportation Department or Congress.
   The Florida Democrat said he was very concerned about decisions
being made by U.S. agencies ``who may not understand the full
implications of their decisions upon the civilian and military
space programs of this country.''
   He said there are a number of questions that need to be answered
about the Payload Systems plans and added, ``I want the whole
process put on hold until those questions can be answered.''
   Payload Systems was granted a license to export an experiment to
test techniques for growing protein crystals in weightlessness.
Such experiments have been conducted on American spacecraft in the
past, including the 1986 shuttle flight taken by Nelson. But the
U.S. spacefleet now is grounded and the Soviet spacecraft are the
only manned vehicles now available to experimenters.
   Byron K. Lichtenberg, who flew on the shuttle in 1983 as a
non-astronaut experimenter, founded Payload Systems and has
designed the experiment. The firm contacted the Soviets about
flying it on the Mir in March 1987 and then applied in October to
the Commerce Department for an export license. The license was
approved early this month.
   Nelson said that although the Commerce Department consulted with
some people in the Defense Department, it did not consult with the
National Aeronautics and Space Administration, the Department of
Transportation _ both of which have responsibilites in space _ nor
with Congress.
   The Commerce Department's unilateral decision, he said, has
``ominous implications'' for the future of the U.S. space program.
   Nelson released a letter to Commerce Secretary William Verity in
which he said the process followed for the Payload Systems license
was ``confusing and must be clarified.'' He asked Verity to appear
at a subcommittee hearings on the subject, to provide information
on specific questions about the license.
   The federal government last year refused permission for General
Motors and General Electric to launch American-made communications
satellites on Soviet rockets on the basis that it could result in a
technology transfer to the Soviets.
   Nelson said he fears that Payload Systems' protein crystal
growth experiment could give technology to the Soviets.
   ``I understand enough about the (crystal growth) process that I
know there are questions that ought to be asked before we start
giving away insights into how to do this process,'' he said. Nelson
said the process may have ``important military applications.''
   But Payload Systems research director Anthony P. Arrott said
Sunday that the experiment was to investigate only protein
crystals, bits of organic matter that can be used in medical and
biological research.
   Neither Arrott or Lichtenberg were available Thursday to comment
on Nelson's statements. A secretary at the Wellesley office said
neither man was at the office and that they were not reachable by
telephone.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
