<1ST_LINE>r a AM-NoriegaWitness     02-25 0514</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Noriega Witness,0527</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Key Noriega Witness Sentenced to 14 Years, No Parole</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAT LEISNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TAMPA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A witness instrumental in an indictment of
Panamanian strongman Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega was sentenced
Thursday to 14 years in prison without parole for his part in a
drug-smuggling, money-laundering ring.
   ``Today I would like to apologize to this court and to the
United States for my crimes,'' Steven Michael Kalish told U.S.
District Judge W. Terrell Hodges in an hour-long hearing. He asked
for a ``compassionate sentence,'' promising he ``would not betray
that trust.''
   Kalish, 35, who told congressional investigators last month he
personally handed Noriega a briefcase containing a $300,000 payoff,
previously pleaded guilty to running a continuing criminal
enterprise.
   Prosecutors agreed to a cap of 20 years on what could have been
a life sentence without parole during a plea agreement struck last
March in the 1984 case, said Robert T. Kennedy, chief of the
criminal division of the Tampa U.S. Attorney's office. Kalish
agreed to forfeit $2.8 million in cash and possessions as part of
the bargain.
   ``Without his cooperation, the recent indictment (of Noriega)
would not have been possible at this time,'' the government said in
a sentencing memorandum filed earlier in the week.
   In court, Kennedy acknowledged Kalish's cooperation had been
substantial, but added that didn't diminish the seriousness of his
crimes.
   Hodges said he had ``no difficulty in substantially mitigating
the sentence'' because of Kalish's cooperation and remorse, but
noted a previous conviction in Texas and gave him 14 years without
parole.
   A recommendation of where Kalish would serve his sentence was
suppressed by the court at the request of defense attorneys, who
said their client's life was in danger.
   ``The danger is specifically that he's testified against
Panamanian strongma Manuel Noriega, who is known for having been
violent in the past toward people he deems his enemies,'' Kalish's
attorney, Alan Ellis, said outside the courtroom.
   Kalish has been in federal custody since his arrest in July
1984. He pleaded guilty to being the field supervisor of a
Tampa-based smuggling ring founded by Leigh Bruce Ritch that
smuggled record amounts of Colombian marijuana through Panama.
   Ritch was convicted and is serving a 30-year sentence without
parole.
   Noriega, who is chief of the Panamanian Defense Forces, and
business associate Enrique Pretelt were indicted Feb. 4 by a grand
jury in Tampa for allegedly taking $4 million in payoffs from
Kalish and Ritch to protect their operation.
   Noriega also was charged with laundering more than $100 million
of the ring's profits, partly through a corporation he controlled.
   The same day, a grand jury in Miami indicted Noriega on
racketeering charges accusing him of taking at least $4.6 million
from Colombia's Medellin Cartel to protect 8,800 pounds in cocaine
shipments.
   In January, Kalish told the Senate Permanent Subcommittee on
Investigation that he paid Noriega more than $1 million in bribes
and agreed to pay $3 million more on behalf of the ring, including
leaving a briefcase containing $300,000 in cash the first time he
met the general.
</TEXT>
