<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Animals-Airline     02-25 0259</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Animals-Airline,250</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>United Airlines Pays $11,000 Penalty To Settle Federal Charges</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   United Airlines Inc. has paid an $11,000 civil
penalty to settle 1987 charges that it violated federal
transportation standards involving shipments of live animals, the
Agriculture Department said Thursday.
   The penalty was assessed by the department in an administrative
action stemming from nine shipments of dogs and monkeys in 1985 and
1986. A complaint was filed against United last year by the
department's Animal and Plant Health Inspection Service, which
administers the Animal Welfare Act.
   James W. Glosser, acting administrator of the agency, said the
complaints alleged that United had accepted dogs in shipping
kennels that did not conform to size requirement, and that the
airline ``either failed to observe and care for the dogs properly''
or stowed them in cargo space without sufficient ventiliation.
   Two dogs died during shipment and another was killed by highway
traffic after it escaped shipment, Glosser said. The airline also
was cited for having ``allegedly accepted a shipment of 50 monkeys
in cages that were not structurally sound'' and had no markings to
tell they contained wild animals, he said.
   Other allegations included the company's failure to ``move dogs
expeditiously from an animal holding area to an airplane'' and to
keep shipping containers in an upright position during unloading
operations.
   Glosser said United consented to a cease-and-desist order
against future violations of the act and agreed within a year to
buy a training film approved by USDA and show it to all employees
who handle live animal cargoes.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
