<DOCNO> AP880225-0152 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-25-88 1815EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Minors'Abortions     02-25 0351</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Minors' Abortions,0357</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Refuses To Enforce Consent Law</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB EGELKO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The state Supreme Court refused Thursday to
allow immediate enforcement of a new California law requiring
consent of parents or a judge for an abortion by an unmarried woman
under 18.
   The court's unanimous action apparently means the law, blocked
from taking effect Jan. 1 by a Superior Court judge's order, will
remain unenforced this year while its constitutionality is
challenged.
   Major doctors' organizations and family-planning groups contend
the law violates the right to privacy under the state Constituion
by restricting minors' ability to decide on their own whether to
give birth or get an abortion.
   The law, sponsored by anti-abortion groups, would make it a
crime for a doctor to perform an abortion on an unmarried minor
living at home who did not have written consent from one parent.
   As an alternative to parental consent, the minor could get a
ruling from a judge, after a confidential hearing, that the
abortion was in her best interest or that she was mature enough to
make the decision on her own.
   State officials say about 34,000 women under 18 had abortions in
1985, the latest year for which figures are available. Under the
old law, which remains in effect, a woman of any age can consent to
an abortion as long as her doctor concludes she understands the
procedure and is consenting voluntarily.
   San Francisco Superior Court Judge Morton Colvin issued a
preliminary injunction Dec. 28 prohibiting enforcement of the new
law until a trial could be held on its constitutionality. He said
the law would cause irreparable harm if enforced in the meantime,
and found a reasonable likelihood it would ultimately be ruled
invalid.
   The state's 1st District Court of Appeal let Colvin's order
stand. Attorney General John Van de Kamp, the lead defendant in the
suit as the state's top law enforcement officer, then appealed to
the state Supreme Court, asking the court to take over the case and
to allow enforcement of the law while the suit is pending.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880225-0153 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-25-88 1522EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Bush-Dole Bjt   02-25 0832</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush-Dole, Bjt,850</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>GOP Tax Fight Dramatizes Sensitivity of Pocketbook Issue</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   George Bush scored political points by
depicting Sen. Bob Dole as a supporter of tax hikes, but both
Republican presidential hopefuls have waffled on this volatile
issue in the past.
   Bush acquiesced in the notion of increasing taxes last fall
though he said he didn't like it. He now maintains that he, as
president, would not raise taxes.
   Dole supported the sweeping reduction in tax rates in 1981, but
helped enact a $98.3 billion tax hike a year later. He now bridles
at conservative portrayals of him as willing to support tax
legislation.
   Dole said Bush was ``lying about my record'' in a commercial
that said Dole would readily raise taxes.
   The ad damaged Dole's chances in New Hampshire. Dole admitted
later that he should have responded. He also evidently harmed
himself by brushing aside Pete du Pont's debate challenge to sign a
no-tax pledge.
   The argument revolves about the murky area of the candidates'
intentions with respect to future tax increases, mostly because
neither Bush nor Dole can cite a record of having consistently
opposed such hikes.
   Barry Bosworth, a Brookings Institution fellow who once headed
President Carter's Council of Economic Advisers, said that to the
extent Bush's commercial raised doubts about Dole's tax intentions,
voters ``responded because they vote their pocketbook.''
   The Dole campaign has put forth a truth squad to monitor Bush's
commericals during the balance of the campaign, and the Bush camp
continues to deny that it distorted the senator's position on taxes.
   But the record is full of inconsistencies regarding both general
tax increases and the question of imposing an import fee on foreign
oil.
   During the 1980 campaign, Bush labeled as ``voodoo economics''
Reagan's pledge to restore U.S. military might while cutting taxes
and balancing the budget. But the record shows no evidence of a
Bush dissent from tax increases that Reagan has signed in the
ensuing years.
   In fact, the closest Bush came to a dissent was when he told a
crowd in Iowa last November that while he didn't like the tax hikes
envisioned in the deficit-reduction package, ``I'll support
whatever compromise the president makes.''
   Bush also slipped last October by launching his presidential
campaign with an uncompromising pledge to not raises taxes, only to
subsequently leave the door slightly ajar. In an Oct. 15 interview
on Cable News Network, Bush backtracked from his Oct. 12 Houston
promise.
   ``What I have said is, if I were convinced that all spending
that could possibly be constrained or cut had taken place, then and
only then would I consider a tax increase,'' he said. Later in the
same day, when pressed for an explanation, Bush replied, ``I'm not
going to raise taxes, period.''
   The record shows that Dole supported various deficit-reduction
tax hike proposals, including the $98.3 billion package in 1981, a
$50.6 billion program in 1984 and the $22 billion in hikes
contained in a plan Reagan agreed to last Nov. 20 in the wake of
the Wall Street crash.
   But Dole and his supporters complained bitterly about the Bush
commercials in New Hamsphire _ ads which Sen. Warren Rudman of New
Hampshire called a ``misstatement of (Dole's) record.''
   Both Bush and Dole have made statements which seemed to indicate
at least a willingness to consider an oil import fee, although Dole
says he voted against it five times since 1980, and Bush said ``an
oil import fee is not the way to decrease dependence'' on foreign
oil.
   Bush talks frequently of a need to lessen U.S. reliance on
foreign oil, but discusses only generally the notion of
strengthening the American petroleum industry. An oil import fee
would do that.
   Dole's spokeswoman, Katie Boyle, recently sought to clarify
statements he made indicating he would consider such a fee, saying
that it would have to carry a rebate provision for consumers.
   Bosworth said in times of general economic prosperity,
candidates for political office score big points by suggesting an
opponent would raise taxes.
   ``I think Dole has probably learned from this (loss in New
Hampshire),'' he said. ``It appears Republicans voted for Bush
there because he appeared to be more adamant about not raising
taxes than Dole was.''
   Larry Sabato, a political science professor and presidential
scholar at the University of Virginia, said ``this (Bush) succeeded
only because Dole chose not to respond to it. It was very
uncharacteristic of him.''
   ``Bush has no position. Dole has a record, which includes
revenue increases in concert with the administration,'' said Bob
McIntyre of the private group, Citizens for Tax Justice.
   Martin Anderson, who served as a domestic policy adviser in the
Reagan White House during the first term, said ``my recollection
is'' that Bush was an even more ardent supporter of tax cuts than
was Reagan.
   ``In fact, he is pushing more, including seeking the cut in
capital gains taxes,'' Anderson said of the vice president.
</TEXT>
