<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Korea-Chun     02-25 0439</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Korea-Chun,0452</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chun Creates Precedent By Leaving Office Peacefully</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Korea</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By C.W. LIM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Outgoing President Chun Doo-hwan held
the hand of his 2-year-old granddaughter Thursday as he left the
presidential mansion after seven years in power.
   Looking strained, Chun shook hands with a long line of aides and
officials in the grounds of the Blue House. Occasionally he flashed
a tense smile as he quietly said farewell.
   Less than an hour earlier, Chun had sat in front of the National
Assembly and watched Roh Tae-woo take the oath of office as the
country's new president. The two men then returned to the Blue
House in the center of Seoul for Chun's formal departure.
   It was the first time in South Korea's turbulent 40-year history
that a president had left power peacefully. Officials who arranged
the ceremony said it had been a problem working out what to do
since there was no precedent to follow.
   Chun, who is to serve as an honorary presidential adviser, was
widely disliked for his tough rule and suppression of opposition.
   ``It is still hard to believe he is leaving. It is so quiet,''
said one man watching the departure ceremony that was nationally
televised.
   Roh watched briefly from the doorway as Chun left the mansion
and then went inside. Chun remained outside for a few minutes
shaking hands and then drove off.
   Hundreds of security guards and officials lined sidewalks at the
main gate and applauded as Chun drove away. He waved back as the
car sped past.
   Life at the heavily guarded Blue House quickly returned to
normal after Chun left. Squads of soldiers resumed patrolling the
mansion and its grounds.
   Chun had said repeatedly in recent weeks that he was eager to
leave office after seven taxing years. He said he had no regrets
and had never wanted to be president.
   ``Now is the time for me to leave the stage of history, the time
to be released from the bondage of public life, the time to be free
from the oppressive solitude of the executive office,'' he said in
a farewell address Wednesday night.
   Chun, Roh and other generals took power in 1980 following the
assassination of President Park Chung-hee. Roh was elected to
succeed Chun in December in the first democratic presidential vote
in 16 years.
   Some people cheered the ex-president as he returned to his home
in Seoul. They waved Korean flags and a band of folk dancers
performed a welcoming dance.
   Other spectators complained later to newspapers that they had
been ordered to take part in the ceremony.
</TEXT>
