<2ND_LINE>PM-Chrysler-Acustar, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0694,0308</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>UAW Threatens to Suspend Special Agreements with Chrysler</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Recasts throughout to CORRECT that union only threatening to
suspend agreements, sted of suspended; ADDS details on other
threatened action.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JANET BRAUNSTEIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Auto Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   United Auto Workers union officials today
threatened to block special agreements at six Chrysler Corp. plants
in an effort to discourage the sale of the company's parts-making
division.
   In addition, the union threatened to suspend other programs that
call for cooperation between labor and management at plants
nationwide to persuade the nation's No. 3 automaker to keep Acustar
Inc.
   About 140 local union delegates and members today approved a
resolution calling for the suspension of the team concept operating
agreements, under which a single group of workers is assigned to
put together parts of a car. The traditional American process
involves one worker doing a single task on an assembly line.
   The union is bound by contract to honor the agreements at plants
in Huntsville, Ala.; Indianapolis; Newcastle, Ind.; Newark, Del.;
Trenton, N.J.; and Detroit. So far, the agreements are in effect
only in Huntsville, Indianapolis and Newcastle.
   But the union is looking for ways to block the agreements, UAW
vice president Marc Stepp said. He did not elaborate.
   Chrysler Chairman Lee Iacocca said Feb. 4 that Chrysler was
entertaining offers to sell all or part of the $3-billion division,
saying the company no longer wanted to invest in the research
needed to keep some operations technologically up to date.
   UAW officials have said they feel cheated by talk of the sale
because of concessions they made to help bring Chrysler out of past
financial troubles.
   Acustar employs about 27,000 workers at more than 24 plants
nationwide. It makes car parts and some non-automotive products
such as chemicals and vinyl.
</TEXT>
