<1ST_LINE>r a AM-StudentDemotions     02-25 0478</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Student Demotions,0492</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chicago Parents End School Protest of 250 Student Demotions</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM C. HIDLAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A three-day student walkout at an academically
troubled elementary school ended Thursday after the principal
compromised on her get-tough decision to demote 250 students to
lower grade levels.
   Parents had kept an estimated 400 students out of classes at
Beethoven Elementary School since Monday to protest the demotions
of students whose reading skills were below grade level on
standardized achievement tests.
   But they ended the boycott after Principal Grace Dawson agreed
to return demoted students to their original grade levels if their
parents met individually with her and helped teachers devise
reading-improvement plans.
   Ms. Dawson said Thursday most of the school's 830 students were
back in class and that about 150 of the demoted students had been
returned to their original grade levels.
   But she said 100 students hadn't been reinstated. In some cases,
the parents had agreed to the demotions. In others, she said, the
students wouldn't be reinstated until their parents went to the
school for conferences.
   Cynthia Thomas, whose 10-year-old daughter Tamika had been
demoted from fourth to third grade, said she thought the boycott
had accomplished the parents' goal, but that the children also
would benefit.
   ``They're going to get some extra tutoring and some extra
reading programs for our kids.''
   The principal said she ordered the mass demotions because so
many of Beethoven's students were several years behind in learning
to read. Most of them live in the nearby Robert Taylor Homes, the
nation's largest high-rise public housing project, located in a
South Side neighborhood rife with crime and street gangs.
   ``Sometimes drastic action has to take place to break the ice,''
Ms. Dawson she said Thursday.
   When the demotions took effect Feb. 15, students were not
shifted to other classrooms, but were taught materials and subjects
from the lower grades.
   In some cases, entire classrooms were taught at a lower grade
level, Ms. Dawson said.
   Ms. Dawon said the demoted students scored from two years to
four years behind grade level on the Iowa Basic Skills Test given
last year and on the Metropolitan Achievement Test given in January.
   ``I will not be a party to passing students on to the next grade
who aren't qualified,'' she said. ``As a professional educator, I
will not sit back and say there's nothing we can do. Otherwise, the
children are the losers.''
   The principal said her get-tough policy worked by forcing
parents to become involved in their children's education.
   Since Wednesday, Ms. Dawson said she had met with about 60
parents to discuss the demotions. She said about 25 percent agreed
to leave their children at the lower gade level for the rest of the
year.
   ``I'm happy because we can't do anything to improve education
without parental support,'' she added.
</TEXT>
