<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BurialDispute     02-25 0326</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Burial Dispute,0336</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Woman Accused of Killing Husband Relinquishes Right to Bury Him</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JACKSONVILLE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman accused of murdering her
husband has given up her fight with his family over his burial, but
she will be allowed to arrange a memorial service for him,
attorneys said.
   Denise Monique Horner, 21, is charged with first-degree murder
in the contract shooting of her husband, Vincent Horner, 25, whose
body was found Feb. 2 in his pickup truck in a mall parking lot.
   Mrs. Horner, who is being held without bond at the Duval County
Jail, had arranged for her husband's body to be buried or cremated
by a Jacksonville funeral home.
   But the victim's father, Burt Horner, filed a lawsuit saying
that because Mrs. Horner is accused of killing her husband, she has
lost her right to decide how the body should be disposed. He wanted
to take his son's body to his home state of Louisiana.
   Under Florida law, a dead person's spouse has the right to
dispose of the body unless the spouse caused the death.
   Circuit Judge Charles O. Mitchell ruled that since Mrs. Horner
has not yet been convicted of the crime, Burt Horner would have to
prove during a civil trial that Mrs. Horner caused her husband's
death.
   Wednesday, however, attorneys for both sides reached a
settlement in which Burt Horner would get custody of the body. He
agreed, however, to keep his son's body in Jacksonville for 10 days
so Mrs. Horner and her family could hold a memorial service.
   Alan Chipperfield, Mrs. Horner's attorney, said Wednesday he
hopes to get a judicial order allowing Mrs. Horner to attend the
service in the custody of an officer.
   Prosecutors have said they plan to seek the death penalty
against Mrs. Horner. According to court documents, witnesses told
police Mrs. Horner told them she had arranged to have her husband
killed.
   There have been no other arrests in Horner's death.
 
</TEXT>
