<2ND_LINE>AM-US-South Africa,330</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>House Members Condemn South Africa's Anti-Apartheid Ban</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM DRINKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group of House members on Thursday condemned
South Africa's decision to ban activities of anti-apartheid groups
and scheduled a stepped-up timetable for action on legislation to
impose stricter sanctions on the Pretoria regime.
   Several of the members also had strong criticism for President
Reagan, who in a Wednesday night news conference said South African
unrest results from ``a tribal policy more than it is a racial
policy.''
   Rep. Howard Wolpe, D-Mich., chairman of the House Foreign
Affairs Africa subcommittee, scheduled five days of hearings next
month and said he hoped to bring a strong sanctions bill to the
floor by mid-April or earlier.
   ``Additional sanctions are the only peaceful means for the West
to hammer home to Pretoria that the West will not permit the voices
of opposition to expire,'' Wolpe said at a news conference.
   He called the white minority government's decision to outlaw
even peaceful dissent ``yet one more step towards absolute
totalitarian government control over South Africa's non-white
majority. The South African regime leaves no doubt of its
determination to systematically deny any and all forms of
legitimate protest, to criminalize what we in the United States
know are basic human rights.''
   Wolpe noted that South African Anglican Archbishop Desmond Tutu
had appealed to Western nations to step up anti-apartheid sanctions
in response to the latest crackdown, and said his committee would
begin working on a tough sanctions package sponsored by Rep. Ron
Dellums, D-Calif.
   Rep. Jim Leach, R-Iowa, criticized Reagan's news-conference
comment as ``very insensitive and lacking any sense of history.
This is an issue of democracy. This administration has to stand up
on this issue. It can't just slough it off.''
   Rep. William Gray, D-Pa., said of Reagan: ``His idea of South
Africa is that of a 1930s Tarzan movie.''
   Wolpe noted that the State Department had protested the latest
crackdown on dissent by anti-apartheid groups. But he added, ``the
moment has arrived for the Reagan administration to back its words
with action.''
</TEXT>
