<FILEID>AP-NR-02-25-88 1551EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-StateSpending     02-25 0740</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-State Spending,720</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>FEC Approves Cost-Reporting Split For Candidates' Ads</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Election Commission on Thursday
sanctioned excluding some TV costs from the state spending limits
for presidential campaigns, in what a dissenting member said was
``blowing the state limits out of the water.''
   By 4-2, the FEC told Democratic contender Albert Gore Jr. that
it is all right to count half of a television ad as a fund-raising
expense _ which is exempt from the spending limits _ even if the
overt money solicitation occurs during three seconds of a 60-second
ad.
   Commissioner Joan Aikens objected, saying it is merely
``sanctioning creative accounting to get around the limits.''
   ``I think we are absolutely blowing the state limits out of the
water,'' she said.
   Gore, a senator from Tennessee, sought the opinion after Rep.
Richard Gephardt, D-Mo., and Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis,
who are among Gore's rivals for the Democratic presidential
nomination, ran ads in Iowa and counted up to half the cost as a
fund-raising expense. That allowed them to spend more money against
the Iowa overall limit of $775,000.
   Because of the need to have a good showing in Iowa, scene of the
first Democratic caucuses, candidates try to spend as much as
possible there. Most of the Democratic candidates spent the limit.
   Bob Bauer, Gephardt's campaign attorney, expressed satisfaction
with the FEC decision and discounted as nonsense the allegations
that the practice was merely a way to overspend.
   ``We didn't write the law. We simply read the law ... and
interpreted it as the FEC has interpreted it,'' he said.
   Gore's spokesman Paul Risley said the campaign was glad the FEC
had clarified the issue, but declined to elaborate.
   The commission majority said the agency's auditors should not
have to scrutinize every campaign commercial to decide what portion
should be considered fund raising.
   In arguing the prevailing viewpoint, Chairman Thomas Josefiak
said that even if an ad also has other purposes, as long as it
contains some obvious fund-raising message and information on how
to contribute _ such as a telephone number to call _ the ad can be
seen as having a dual purpose. In that case, a 50 percent
allocation for fund-raising would be reasonable, the commission
determined.
   The decision rejected the recommendation of the FEC legal staff
which had held that the write-off should be generally proportional
to the part of the ad that contains a fund-raising message.
   In the case of the 60-second ad proposed by Gore, with an appeal
for viewers to contribute in the last three seconds, a 5 percent
allocation for fund raising would be reasonable, but 50 percent
would not, FEC counsel Larry Noble contended.
   Commissioner Lee Ann Elliott, who dissented along with Aikens,
suggested a flat 10-percent write-off for fund raising should be
imposed for ads. She criticized the majority decision as a
``mushy'' one that does not give the campaigns a precise guideline.
   The law sets a spending cap for each state and an overall
campaign spending limit of $23 million, plus another $4.6 million
for fund-raising costs. The fund-raising costs can be excluded from
state limits as long as the campaign has not gone over the $4.6
million.
   The FEC for several years has asked Congress to do away with
state-by-state limits as burdensome.
   Gore did not mention the other campaigns in his request, but his
aides said the query was an attempt to get an FEC ruling on the
activity of his opponents.
   Gore's hypothetical case, involving an ad he proposed for
Colorado's April 4 caucuses, paralleled Gephardt's commercial in
Iowa in which the final seconds asked viewers to ``vote, volunteer,
contribute.'' Gephardt excluded half the cost from the spending his
campaign allocated to Iowa.
   The Gephardt and Dukakis campaigns had cited the precedent of
Ohio Democratic Sen. John Glenn's presidential campaign in 1984, in
which the FEC allowed a 50 percent fund-raising write-off for
Glenn's half-hour TV show.
   But commissioners said that example should not be a guideline,
because the FEC decided the matter well after the election during a
routine FEC audit of Glenn's finances to determine if any of his
federal matching funds were improperly spent or if there had been
any irregularities.
   That decision was in the context of negotiation and compromise,
Josefiak noted, after the Glenn campaign had initially tried to
count the entire 30-minute show as a fund-raising expense.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
