<DOCNO> AP880225-0163 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-25-88 1559EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Bennett-ReportCard Bjt   02-25 0852</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bennett-Report Card, Bjt,820</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Educstion Chief Gives Mediocre Grades to States</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Education Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Education Secretary William J. Bennett gave
the states mediocre grades Thursday on an annual report card that
showed dropout rates up slightly, college entrance test scores
level and spending higher than ever.
   ``The news is not what it should be. Test scores are in a dead
stall,'' Bennett said as he unveiled two wall charts crammed with
statistics ranking the states on tests, graduation rates, teacher
pay and other measures.
   ``In saying that I am disappointed, I think I speak for the
American people,'' Bennett told reporters. ``We're paying top
dollar to educate our children, but we're sure not getting top
return.''
   Mary Hatwood Futrell, president of the National Education
Association, the nation's largest teachers union, said in an
interview:
   ``The time has come to halt the wall chart charade and for
people to sit down and really talk about ways we can improve the
quality of education for all young people in this country.''
   ``The chart really doesn't give us a lot of helpful information
... other than to serve as a reminder of what we said a long time
ago: if you don't provide the support and the resources, and you
raise standards, children are going to fall through the cracks,''
Mrs. Futrell said.
   Asked if citizens should use the statistics as ammunition to
vote down school levies, Bennett said that depends on how well the
local schools are performing.
   Referring to Chicago's troubled schools, which he said recently
are in ``an educational meltdown,'' Bennett said:
   ``If I were a citizen of Chicago and they said, `We need more
money to make this school effective,' I'd tell them to take a hike.
... They're spending $6,000 per kid for a 50 percent dropout
(rate).''
   Nationally, Bennett said the graduation rate from public high
schools in 1986 was only 71.5 percent, down from 71.7 percent in
1985.
   The graduation rate is up from 69.5 percent in 1982, but it is
far short of President Reagan's goal of a 90 percent graduation
rate by 1990.
   Only Minnesota, with a 91.4 percent graduation rate, has
bettered that goal. Near it are Connecticut, 89.8 percent; North
Dakota, 89.7 percent; Nebraska, 88.1 percent; and Iowa, 87.5
percent.
   The worst graduation rates are the District of Columbia, 56.8
percent; Florida, 62.0 percent; Georgia and Louisiana, both 62.7
percent; and Arizona, 63.0 percent.
   It was the fifth straight year that an education secretary has
released the controversial all charts. Bennett's predecessor, T.H.
Bell, initiated the practice.
   The Class of 1987's scores on the Scholastic Aptitude Test and
American College Testing program were released last fall. The
national average on the SAT, scored on a scale of 400 to 1,600, was
906. The average on the ACT, which has a scale of 1 to 36, was 18.7.
   Bennett provided his own rankings of the states.
   He singled out South Carolina for praise, although its SAT
average of 832 was again dead last among the 22 states where the
SAT is the dominant test. He said South Carolina has picked up 17
points in the past two years, and he called it a pacesetter in
efforts to hold educators more accountable for student performance.
   Bennett also praised California for a tough new social studies
curriculum; Virginia for efforts to make high school students take
rigorous math courses; and New Jersey for welcoming non-education
majors into the teaching profession.
   The secretary said 43 states now require entering teachers to
pass competency tests, up from 34 last year. They are not required
by the District of Columbia, Alaska, Iowa, North Dakota, Utah,
Vermont, Wisconsin and Wyoming.
   Gordon Ambach, executive director of the Council of Chief State
School Officers, said the graduation rate exceeds 75 percent if
high school equivalency diplomas are counted, but he agreed that is
not good enough. He cautioned against reading too much into
Bennett's scorecard.
   The wall chart listed seven states _ Arkansas, Georgia,
Kentucky, New Jersey, Ohio, South Carolina and Texas _ with laws
allowing state intervention in ``academically bankrupt'' school
districts.
   Bennett said nearly 10 percent of high school graduates now take
advanced college placement exams, up from less than 5 percent in
1982, and a larger proportion of seniors are taking the ACT and
SAT. That ``means we are succeeding in keeping scores level despite
a larger pool of test-takers,'' he said.
   Test results ``show that poor, black and Hispanic children are
performing better,'' said Bennett, although there is still a wide
gap between minority and majority scores.
   Bennett said that since 1976 black students' scores on the SAT
have risen by 42 points to 728, while white students' scores fell
eight points to 936.
   He was asked if it troubled him that SAT scores rose during the
early 1980s, but have stayed flat since he joined the Cabinet.
   ``I don't take that personally.'' he replied. ``I don't think
the children taking these tests are in any particular conspiracy
against me. It's more a comment on what was going on in their
classroom.''
</TEXT>
