<DOCNO> AP880225-0164 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-25-88 2149EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Writer'sTalks     02-25 0774</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Writer's Talks,0798</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Little Rancor, Much Talk During Final Week of Writer's Guild</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD DE ATLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOLLYWOOD (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Movie and television writers are conducting
whisper-quiet negotiations with producers for a new three-year
contract, an uncharacteristic approach for the film capital's most
militant union.
   Three years ago, the 9,000-member Writers Guild of America
shuddered under internal strife. One faction contended union
leaders had misinformed the membership about the producers' offer
and caused an unnecessary two-week strike.
   The union eventually voted to accept virtually the same contract
it had rejected. An organizational shakeup followed.
   Talks for the 1988 contract with the Alliance of Motion Picture
and Television Producers are nearing an end, with writers seeking a
greater share of foreign market income and producers hoping to
restructure residual payments for one-hour syndicated shows.
   The alliance is an umbrella organization representing about 200
studios and producers. The contract with writers expires at
midnight Feb. 29, when the producers say they will make their final
offer.
   The union and producers have been discussing their disagreements
behind closed doors, and carefully handling their public statements
with low-key information campaigns.
   Producers say that despite record box office grosses, the
entertainment industry needs a serious cost-control campaign.
   The union seeks what it calls ``parallel growth,'' meaning more
money from areas in which the producers are doing well.
   Guild West Regional Director Brian Walton said the union is
prepared to strike if necessary, ``but we would first hope to work
out the problems.''
   Herb Steinberg, a spokesman for the alliance, has characterized
chief producer negotiator Nicholas Counter and Walton as ``very
intelligent, bright gentlemen ... there is no sense of rancor or
confrontation.''
   Steinberg said the producers' offer on Feb. 29 will be ``firm
and final.'' Walton said the union has taken precautions to make
sure members are kept informed about negotiations, to avoid the
confusion and rancor of 1985.
   Since its first contract in 1947, the union has hit the bricks
in 1959, 1960, 1973, 1981 and 1985 _ the most strikes by any
Hollywood union.
   Its West Coast members, numbering about 6,500, will vote on the
producers' offer on March 1, while 2,000 of the 2,500 East Coast
members will consider the contract on March. 2. The other 500
members on the East Coast are television newswriters unaffected by
this contract.
   In 1987, union members enjoyed an 11.6 percent increase in
residual payments, to $57 million, with $39.5 million of that from
television. Currently, a writer receives $5,100 for a half-hour
television script, but experienced writers generally negotiate a
substantially higher fee.
   Motion pictures drew a record $4.25 billion in ticket sales for
1987. But producers insist development and production costs are
still overwhelming.
   Steinberg and Walton both refused to characterize any issue as
dominant. But the writers' proposal to increase their residual
share of lucrative foreign market distribution income, and the
producer's desire to cut residual costs for one-hour syndicated
television shows, appear to be the most controversial.
   Writers argue that theatrical and broadcasting product has
become one of the largest U.S. exports, registering at least a $4.9
billion trade surplus in 1986. Producers say looking at individual
growth areas without paying attention to rising production costs is
unrealistic.
   Producers have asked writers to drop the fixed residual rate for
hourlong television shows and accept a sliding scale of residual
payments tied to the show's syndication licensing success.
   Few shows these days turn a first-run profit. The deficit for a
one-hour show in 1986-1987 was $370,274, producers have said.
   While shows for prime-time television have long been
deficit-financed, producers used to make their money back with
lucrative syndication deals for reruns. But new
made-for-syndication shows have hurt that market.
   ``The one-hour show syndication market has dried up,'' alliance
spokesman Steinberg said. ``Some deals are possible, if we could
bring the price down.''
   Walton has said the producers' proposal is not in parity with
the deal movie and television directors got last summer for
accepting the same formula.
   The union said its analysis showed the producers' figures are
derived from the 15 most expensive action-adventure shows. ``Also,
they are still producing and developing these hourlong shows,''
Walton said.
   Producers also want to raise the minimum for defined ``low
budget'' movies and television shows. Writers take a substantial
cut in fees for a defined ``low budget'' work.
   Writers once again are seeking residual increases for
videocassette movies, noting directors received an increase in
their 1987 contract.
   Among the other 107 demands from the guild are increased
affirmative action hiring for women and minority writers; increased
health fund contributions by management; and creative rights for
scriptwriters.
</TEXT>
