<1ST_LINE>r w AM-CollegeLoans     02-25 0314</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-College Loans,310</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Private Group Offers Low-Interest Loans To Colleges, Universities</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A non-profit group on Thursday announced a new
loan service that will allow colleges and universities to borrow up
to $100 million at below prime interest rates.
   The Capital Access Trust will make loans to institutions with
good credit for new buildings, renovations or for operating money.
   It is the latest undertaking of University Support Services
Inc., a non-profit corporation started in 1986 by business and
academic leaders to lend money to students from families that do
not qualify for financial aid.
   The Rev. John P. Whalen, president of University Support
Services and former president of the Catholic University of
America, said more than three-quarters of the nation's campuses
will need to undertake renovations or new construction in the next
five years costing millions of dollars.
   He said the trust is ``a major new source of capital ... in
amounts ranging anywhere from relatively small loans to upwards of
$100 million.''
   He claimed it will be able to make the loan commitments in just
45 days at rates more favorable ``than any source of borrowing we
know, except tax-exempt financing.''
   The trust is funded by the sale of University Support Services
commercial paper notes, backed by a bank line of credit and
underwritten by Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc.
   The interest rate is tied to the commercial paper note rate
quoted in the Wall Street Journal, which Whalen said is
significantly lower than the prime rate.
   Whalen said that if a college borrows $50 million from the trust
for three years instead of borrowing from a bank at the prime rate,
it could save $250,000 to $350,000 in interest.
   University Support Services' student loan program, called
ConSern, lends individuals from $1,500 to $25,000 a year for
private school or college costs. The interest rate varies; it is
currently 10.44 percent.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
