<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SAfrica-Floods     02-25 0332</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-SAfrica-Floods,0340</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Flooding Chases 10,000 From Homes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rising floodwaters forced the
evacuation of more than 10,000 people and have inundated 1,500
houses this week in the central part of the country, officials said
Thursday.
   At least 16 deaths have been reported since Monday in floods
along the Orange River in the Orange Free State and have since
spread to the northern Cape province.
   Rail traffic has been knocked out and the main highway between
Johannesburg and Cape Town is reduced to one lane. Twenty-five
magisterial districts have been declared disaster areas and farmers
are harvesting their crops 24 hours a day to save something from
the encroaching rivers.
   The strongly flowing Orange River, fed by the Vaal and Modder
rivers, has risen more than 6{ feet in two days, the South African
Press Association reported.
   Half of the town of Douglas, 50 miles west of the historic
mining town of Kimberley, was underwater Thursday and hundreds of
residents had been evacuated to a nearby hill, SAPA reported. In
the towns of Prieska and Upington, another 200 miles west along the
Orange River, residents began loading furniture into trucks in
preparation for the wall of water expected to hit them by Saturday.
   Local police said the flood line is already higher than the
level reached in 1974, when the Orange River rose more than 32{
feet, destroying 70 percent of the crops in the central part of the
country and leaving hundreds homeless.
   The Minister of National Health, Willie van Niekerk, estimated
damage to the road and rail network at about $10 million, and
damage to bridges at $3 million. Crop and housing damage could not
be estimated until the waters subside.
   Clean water is still scarce, telephone lines are down, and mail
is being delivered by boat in areas of the Orange Free State.
   Flooded roads, washed-out homes and inundated cropland have also
been reported in Lesotho, Swaziland and Mozambique, but no deaths
have been reported.
</TEXT>
