<1ST_LINE>u a AM-HeroinInflux Bjt   02-25 0682</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Heroin Influx, Bjt,0700</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Drug Agents Predict Street Wars over Growing Traffic in Asian
Heroin</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUE MANNING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two recently slain drug agents may have been
victims of a war pitting old-line dealers and government agents
against Asian gangs who are importing ``Golden Triangle'' heroin
into California, officials said Thursday.
   Emerging Thai, Cambodian and Laotian drug rings will likely
clash with existing Hispanic, black and white gangs, opening the
way for street wars like those in Miami in the 1970s and '80s, said
John Hensley, the top drug enforcement officer for the U.S. Customs
Service on the West Coast.
   ``If the Asians start mixing it up with the Mexican and black
gangs, we may see the gun battles and murders that marked the old
Colombian `cocaine cowboy' wars in Miami a decade ago,'' Hensley
said. ``With the kind of money involved, either side could do the
shooting.''
   Two Drug Enforcement Administration working undercover to crack
an alleged Taiwanese heroin ring were gunned down in Pasadena
earlier this month. Two alleged traffickers also were killed.
   Investigators have said the alleged drug dealers were unaware
they were dealing with federal agents and had set up a drug
purchase with plans all along to rob and kill their ``customers.''
   Such violent confrontations are typical of the turf wars waged
by smugglers and sellers, Hensley said.
   In Miami during the late 1970s and early 1980s, ``I was there
during one turf battle between Colombians and Cubans and we
(federal agents) were the only ones without automatic weapons,'' he
said.
   ``We saw the turf wars there. If we don't get a cap on it now,
it will become a reality here and we don't want it to be a
reality,'' he said.
   The amount of Golden Triangle heroin, named for the fertile
opium-growing area where Thailand, Cambodia and Laos meet, arriving
in California during the last two years has increased dramatically.
Three years ago, only about 15 percent of the heroin smuggled into
the state was of the Asian variety, said DEA spokesman Roger
Guevara.
   ``We now estimate that Southeast Asian heroin represents 50
percent to 80 percent of all the heroin coming into the country.
It's a huge influx for Los Angeles, and it has turned Los Angeles
into a major transshipment center for New York,'' he said.
   ``The Asians, including the Taiwanese, have a ready supply and
the potential growth of Asian gangs in heroin distribution can lead
to more violence,'' Guevara said. ``On the other hand, the blacks,
Mexicans and the whites have always controlled the street heroin
market.''
   It will cost some more lives to stop the war, the men agreed.
Agents dealing with drugs and gangs are always more at risk than
other agents, Hensley said.
   ``They aren't wearing body armor. Undercover you never know when
you're being burned and the backup isn't always that great,'' he
said.
   Heroin is more appealing to dealers than other drugs for several
reasons, Hensley said.
   Because of several national programs, including big anti-drug
pushes by the sports and entertainment industries and anti-drug
messages by stars, use of cocaine and marijuana has stabilized, he
said.
   ``Heroin is different. Users don't look at Michael Jackson as a
role model. The heroin user group is growing slightly, even though
there is a turnover because as new users come in, others overdose
and die out.''
   And heroin brings a distributor a much higher price than a like
amount of cocaine, Hensley added, in part because it ultimately can
be diluted to as low as 3 percent for street sales.
   A pound of heroin sells for about $50,000, and a kilo, 2.2
pounds, for between $90,000 and $200,000, ``depending on the purity
and the dealer,'' he said.
   Agents used to concentrate on couriers who brought in a few
pounds of heroin on ships or international flights, he said.
   But now, heroin has started arriving in the mail, Hensley said.
``About two weeks ago, we seized about 45 pounds at the mail
facility in Oakland.''
   ``We have to look everywhere now,'' he said.
</TEXT>
