<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Pesticides-Groundwater     02-25 0586</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pesticides-Groundwater,570</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>EPA Unveils Policy To Involve States In Deciding On Pesticide Use</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Environmental Protection Agency on
Thursday unveiled a draft policy that could let states decide when,
where and how to use pesticides which could contaminate groundwater.
   States would get such powers by adopting pesticide management
programs approved by EPA. Otherwise, EPA would forbid use of the
pesticide in states or counties with high potential for groundwater
contamination.
   Without a state plan, ``the risk-benefit determinations
underlying these EPA-determined geographic prohibitions will be
rather crude,'' the agency said.
   With a plan, states could employ more detailed land and water
data than EPA would have available. ``Where found appropriate, EPA
would consider modifying the federal registration to accomodate the
state program,'' the agency said.
   EPA published the policy as a draft, asking for comment from the
public over the next four months.
   A single national approach ``is going to over-protect, or
possibly under-protect'' in specific areas, said John A. Moore,
assistant administrator for pesticides and toxic substances, at a
news conference.
   Soils and groundwater vulnerability vary greatly even within
counties, and at the county level and below ``EPA's ability to do
something ... is not very good,'' Moore said.
   But that does not mean ``EPA would walk away from these
pesticides.'' In deciding whether to license a chemical, or
re-license it, EPA has been considering groundwater in deciding
whether to impose national conditions, he said.
   Also, the contamination standards the states would be obliged to
observe would be set by EPA _ existing drinking water standards for
chemicals that don't cause cancer, and for cancer-causing
chemicals, a concentration that would yield a one in a million
chance of cancer for someone drinking from the aquifer over a
lifetime.
   Pesticide contamination of groundwater is a relatively new
issue. The first examples were found in New York and California in
1979.
   EPA expects to complete a survey in 1990 on the extent of
contamination. Two years ago, the agency said 19 pesticides had
been found in groundwater in 24 states. Now, said Patrick Holden,
team leader of the groundwater project in EPA's pesticides office,
50 to 60 different chemicals have been found in wells in 30 states.
Iowa has found pesticides in half the wells serving cities.
   Pesticides are not the only thing that contaminates groundwater,
source of drinking water for half the population and for 97 percent
of people living in rural areas. Fertilizers, waste disposal wells
and leaking underground tanks all can contribute substantially.
   States may get federal aid for setting up wellhead protection
zones, and soon EPA expects to adopt a groundwater strategy that
would require states to classify aquifers under a three-part scheme
for high priority protection, drinking water sources and water
unlikely ever to be drunk and thus needing little protection.
   This strategy has been opposed by many environmentalists as
writing off what could a substantial fraction of groundwater
supplies.
   Sen. David Durenberger, R-Minn., said Thursday in introducing a
bill calling for minimum federal standards for all aquifers, ``I
cannot agree with it.''
   ``We have no right to come in on this slice of the world or life
in 1988 and say we are just going to abandon these resources,'' the
senator told a news conference about his bill, at least the 10th
dealing with groundwater this session.
   The senator said he would have to study EPA's Thursday proposal
for the states, though his bill would permit states to go beyond
federal standards.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880225-0170 </DOCNO>
