<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Dukakis-Gephardt     02-25 0543</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dukakis-Gephardt,550</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis, Gephardt Exchange Barbs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN SEWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DEERFIELD BEACH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic presidential candidate
Michael Dukakis called rival Richard Gephardt a ``flip-flopper'' as
tensions ran high between the two at a long-term health care forum
on Thursday.
   Dukakis warned Gephardt against turning the campaign negative,
but Gephardt said he thought it was important to highlight
differences on issues and experience.
   Dukakis and Gephardt are struggling for stature as the calendar
winds down toward the Super Tuesday round of primaries and caucuses
in the South. Each has won two contests to date.
   Earlier in the day, Dukakis said he learned a painful lesson
about negative campaigning when he lost a 1978 re-election bid as
Massachusetts governor and ``it's not going to happen again.''
   He went on to say in Boca Raton, ``I don't think this `prince of
darkness' routine is going to sell'' and that he would not stand
for Gephardt attacks.
   In the hour-long health care session here, Dukakis and Gephardt
largely agreed on the need for a national long-term health care
program. But Dukakis bristled when a question suggested he was
flip-flopping on the role of private insurance for long-term care.
   ``This is the flip-flopper over here; I'm not the
flip-flopper,'' Dukakis said, looking at the Missouri congressman,
whose record has been criticized by other candidates as
inconsistent.
   Both strongly supported the proposal by Rep. Claude Pepper, the
87-year-old Miami Democrat, to guarantee home health care for the
elderly and chronically ill. Pepper's bill didn't come to a vote
last year as some congressional Democrats worried about a potential
cost in the tens of billions of dollars.
   Pepper's plan would lift the 45 percent cap on income subject to
Medicare payroll tax, and both candidates agreed that extra revenue
should be able to get the program started.
   ``It's the old-fashioned American way of taxing on the ability
to pay, which is what we ought to do,'' Dukakis said.
   ``We're not doing it right today,'' Gephardt said of
government-provided health care. ``It doesn't have to cost a lot
more money.''
   Dukakis said health care presents a fundamental difference
between the Democratic and Republican parties and he called health
care an American birthright.
   ``If you lose your health, nothing else matters,'' Gephardt said
to loud applause from the audience at a retirement community.
   Dukakis said he dominated Gephardt in working-class areas of New
Hampshire and Minnesota, both contests the Massachusetts governor
won, then warned that a negative campaign would hurt the Democrats
and also that Gephardt's record was vulnerable.
   ``People in glass houses shouldn't throw stones,'' Dukakis said
after the senior forum here. He said Gephardt shouldn't attack the
establishment and then accept corporate political action committee
funds.
   ``Something could be said for consistency,'' Dukakis said.
   Gephardt denied his campaign was negative.
   ``I am trying in this campaign and will continue to try to
outline what I think are the differences,'' Gephardt said. ``Let's
have a discussion of the issues.''
   Dukakis scoffed when told Gephardt said he wasn't being negative.
   ``Everybody knows what he's doing. When you're behind you
attack,'' Dukakis said.
   On Wednesday, Gephardt gave a speech in Waco, Texas, that
harshly criticized Dukakis. ``The candidate with the most money has
the least message,'' Gephardt said.
</TEXT>
