<FILEID>AP-NR-02-25-88 1657EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SpudFlap     02-25 0561</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Spud Flap,0581</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Goodbye, British Chips! Hello, American Spuds</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By COTTEN TIMBERLAKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   McDonald's has decided the British spud is a dud
when it comes to French fries, and its plan to switch to American
potato varieties has created a flap among some patriots.
   The fast-food chain plans to use British-grown potatoes of the
North American variety called the Russet Burbank. For years, it has
used British-grown potatoes of the British Pentland Dell variety.
   A company spokeswoman said Thursday the decision to make the
change in the British McDonald's outlets was made ``basically
because the Russet Burbank has got a better flavor and texture.''
   ``It is a more suitable potato for our requirements,'' she said,
speaking on condition of anonymity in accordance with British
custom.
   She said British farmers have been contracted to grow the
American variety.
   McDonald's is a big customer of the British potato farmer. It
needs 55,000 tons of potatoes a year to keep its 263 British
outlets in the chips, as the French fry is called here.
   The American variety produces French fries that hang
tantalizingly over the edge of their packets without breaking in
the middle, farmers told the Today newspaper.
   But agricultural expert Michael Shaw, who isn't happy about the
switch, told the newspaper, ``McDonald's is so powerful in the
fast-food business that they are killing off the great British
chip.''
   Conservative lawmaker Ann Winterton agreed.
   ``My primary interest is promoting food which is grown in this
country. Potatoes is a crop we grow particularly well. There are
many varieties of excellent qualities.''
   She said it would suprise her if the American variety was better.
   Another Tory member of Parliament, Jerry Wiggin, chairman of the
House of Commons select committee on agriculture, said: ``Judging
from the fantastic support from my own children, McDonald's doesn't
appear to be doing badly using British potatoes.''
   McDonald's conducted tests with the Russet Burbank on farms
throughout the country during the past eight years, according to
the Daily Telegraph.
   This year, production of the Russet Burbank, which was developed
in California 112 years ago, is in full swing on about 4,000 acres,
the Daily Telegraph said.
   Britain's Potato Marketing Board is not opposed to the switch.
   ``The amount of potatoes being taken up on the processing side
is increasing and obviously, if growers want to take advantage of
it, obviously they have to grow what the buyers want,'' said a
board spokeswoman, who didn't want to be identified further.
   ``There is not going to be an en masse switch to Russet Burbank
with everyone growing nothing but that,'' the spokeswoman said.
   McDonald's main rivals say they are sticking with their British
spuds.
   John Shedden, a spokesman for Burger King, said the British
variety meets all of Burger King's requirements. Burger King has 18
outlets in Britain.
   Wimpy, a British fast-food chain, operates 400 restaurants that
fry about 8,580 tons of potatoes a year. It uses the British
Pentland Dell variety, as well as another British variety called
the Maris Piper and a Dutch variety called Bintje.
   A Wimpy spokeswoman said the type of potato used has less to do
with the chips' flavor than the fat or oil used to fry it.
   Wimpy says its uses vegetable oil. McDonald's says it uses a
combination of cottonseed oil and beef tallow. Burger King won't
say.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880225-0172 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-25-88 2213EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Walesa     02-25 0395</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Walesa,0406</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Solidarity Says Authorities Blocking Walesa Trip To Australia</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Polish authorities are blocking Solidarity
leader Lech Walesa and three top aides from traveling to Australia
to attend an international trade union congress, a spokesman for
the banned union said Wednesday.
   ``The authorities are trying to block the procedure at every
possible stage,'' said Solidarity's national spokesman Janusz
Onyszkiewicz, in a telephone interview. ``They are trying to play
formal, bureaucratic tricks ... Without actually refusing to grant
them passports.''
   Walesa and three other Solidarity leaders are trying to obtain
passports to allow them to travel to Australia to attend the March
14-18 World Congress of the International Confederation of Free
Trade Unions in Melbourne.
   They were invited by the Australian Confederation of Trade
Unions.
   ``Lech wants to do everything possible to go there, as this is a
congress of a trade union organization of which Solidarity is a
member,'' said Bogdan Olszewski, a Walesa aide, contacted at the
union leader's Gdansk apartment.
   Walesa has not left Poland since the December 1981 imposition of
martial law that suppressed Solidarity.
   Walesa applied 10 days ago for vacation leave from his job as an
electrician at Gdansk's Lenin Shipyard, but so far he has not
received any response from shipyard authorities, Olszewski said.
   Poles must have the approval of their workplace in order to file
an application for a passport, which then can take two to four
weeks to be processed.
   Walesa expected the shipyard would delay its decision until it
was too late for him to make the trip, Olszewski said. Walesa once
earlier tried to obtain a passport to travel to Italy, but was
refused leave from the shipyard.
   Wladyslaw Frasyniuk, the Wroclaw Solidarity leader, said the
local passport office refused to accept his passport application on
Thursday, claiming his invitation was invalid because it was not
issued by a private individual but an institution.
   Bogdan Lis, the Gdansk Solidarity leader, said he would try to
apply for his passport Friday, while union adviser Bronislaw
Geremek of Warsaw has filed his passport application and is waiting
for a decision.
   Polish government spokesman Jerzy Urban told a news conference
Tuesday that if Walesa is granted a leave from work his request for
a passport ''will be examined in accordance with the existing
regulations, as is the case with every other Polish citizen.
</TEXT>
