<FILEID>AP-NR-02-25-88 1637EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-MoscowEmbassy 1stLd-Writethru a0654 02-25 0964</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Moscow Embassy, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0654,930</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Secret Study Harshly Criticizes Ambassador, Staff And Marines</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: ADDS three grafs at end to include preliminary GAO report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOAN MOWER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A secret presidential study harshly criticizes
State Department officials, the American ambassador and Marines for
neglecting security at the U.S. Embassy in Moscow where a
sex-for-secrets scandal erupted last year.
   ``A fundamental reorientation of the way we do business in the
Soviet Union is critical,'' according to the report by a
blue-ribbon panel that President Reagan appointed last spring.
   The report scores the ambassador for his ``aloof'' management
style, calls working conditions at the embassy a ``national
disgrace,'' and says Marine guards ``tolerated'' and then ``covered
up'' incidents of misconduct, including sexual activities,
drunkenness, brawling and currency manipulation.
   ``Many share responsibility for the security vulnerabilities
that existed and in some cases still exist,'' said the panel,
headed by former Defense Secretary Melvin R. Laird.
   The so-called Laird report was submitted to the State
Department, which has refused to release it. Charles Redman, a
department spokesman, said the report has not been made public
because it is a confidential document for Secretary of State George
P. Shultz.
   Laird urged release of an unclassified version of the document,
but said he could not talk about its substance unless the
department unseals it. There is also a classified version of the
report containing more sensitive information.
   The Associated Press was shown a copy of the report, the result
of the panel's work from May 7 until July 17.
   Since the panel finished work, one Marine has been convicted of
spying. But some of the more sensational allegations _ such as
reports that KGB agents were allowed to prowl the embassy's
top-secret areas _ have been discounted.
   The report said what happened at the embassy ``may never be
known,'' and it added: ``Our investigation has revealed that a
situation existed ... that would have permitted the incidents to
have occurred as alleged...''
   Robert E. Lamb, assistant secretary of state for diplomatic
security, said gaps existed in the embassy's security program in
the past. ``There were some holes and we have moved to fill them,''
he said.
   Efforts have been made to upgrade security and add more
personnel to the counterintelligence staff, he said.
   Some of the findings in the Laird report are new; others repeat
concerns raised previously about the embassy. Here is a sampling:
   _Laird called the embassy a ``pigsty,'' and the report said it
was a fire trap. Last week, fire broke out in a section of the
embassy.
   Corridors were cluttered with papers, books and personal
effects; stairwells and hallways were ``strewn with broken
equipment and machinery parts awaiting repair and disposal,'' the
report said.
   ``Those assigned to Moscow find themselves working in a seedy,
disgraceful facility with inadequate support from Washington,'' the
report said.
   _It is ``possible that some Marines who had discipline problems
elsewhere were assigned to Moscow as punishment,'' and the
situation was ripe for exploitation by the KGB, the Soviet spy
agency.
   _The panel reserved ``special criticism'' for the Marines in the
guard detachment as ``their misconduct and failure to perform their
duties in a prescribed manner led to increased vulnerability in the
mission's security,'' the report said. Some embassy staffers also
violated regulations.
   _Confusion marked policies barring Marines from fraternizing
with Soviets and reporting their contacts. The policies ``obviously
were not taken seriously enough to provide security,'' the report
said.
   _The State Department's counterintelligence staff was so
overworked _ only 11 of the 27 authorized positions were filled _
that ``only the most rudimentary investigation was conducted on the
most pressing cases.''
   ``The gross neglect of the State Department's
counterintelligence may be germane to the alleged security breaches
in Moscow,'' the report said.
   _Some of the Soviet citizens working at the embassy were ``known
to be KGB operatives,'' and were ``accorded far too much access to
Americans.''
   The Americans had ``ambivalent and contradictory'' attitudes
towards the Soviets, who worked in a variety of administrative,
clerical and support jobs such as cooks, drivers and baby-sitters.
The Soviets removed their nationals from the embassy in October
1986.
   _The ambassador ``employed a management style that remained
aloof until a specific event occurred and required his attention.
... This was clearly inadequate.''
   Arthur A. Hartman, the U.S. ambassador in Moscow from 1981 until
1987, did not return telephone calls placed to his house and his
office. He has maintained that earlier reports about the embassy's
security problems were overblown.
   Sgt. Clayton J. Lonetree, an embassy guard in 1985 and 1986, was
convicted of espionage for giving the KGB the identities of CIA
agents and the floor plans to the U.S. embassies in Moscow and
Vienna.
   But government prosecutors dropped charges against Lonetree and
Cpl. Arnold Bracy that they permitted KGB agents to roam the
embassy. Another Marine was convicted of dereliction of duty.
   The Naval Investigative Service says eight other
espionage-related cases involving Marines remain open as a result
of polygraph tests administered after Lonetree's confession.
   Besides Laird, the panel included Richard M. Helms, a former CIA
director; Gen. John W. Vessey Jr., former chairman of the Joint
Chiefs of Staff; and Diego C. Asencio, former ambassador to Brazil.
   Also Thursday, the office of Rep. Dan Mica, D-Fla., made
available copies of a preliminary General Accounting Office inquiry
into reports of espionage by Marines. Mica had disclosed details of
the report last week.
   Among others things, the GAO _ the congressional watchdog agency
_ said ``coordination and cooperation'' between the State
Department, the Marines and the Naval Investigative Service was
``less than adequate.''
   For instance, the GAO said the State Department did not always
turn over to the NIS for further investigation reports of possible
criminal or counterintelligence activity.
</TEXT>
