<1ST_LINE>r w AM-MilitaryMedical     02-25 0438</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Military Medical,430</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Military Surgeons General Report Progress in Facilities</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Military medical officials said Thursday that
improvements are needed in battlefield health care but conditions
have improved greatly since five years ago, when only one out of 10
casualties could expect adequate care.
   ``We have to spend either dollars or blood, and we prefer to
spend dollars,'' Navy Surgeon General James A. Zimble told a House
Armed Services subcommittee hearing.
   Zimble said congressional support will be needed for a plan to
attain wartime medical readiness by 1992.
   Dr. William Mayer, assistant secretary of defense for health
affairs, said that five years ago adequate medical attention would
have been available to only 10 percent of battlefield casualties.
After a year, improvements increased that figure to about 20
percent, Mayer said, describing condition as ``still grossly
unacceptable.''
   He said no comparable figures are available for present
conditions but more facilities are still needed abroad. He said
there is no funding for 41 overseas Army hospitals, in addition to
three for the Navy and two for the Air Force.
   Mayer said the U.S. military can now mobilize about 60 percent
of the medical personnel and facilities needed in the event of
``general war.''
   ``I'm very comfortable that we're most of the way toward being
able to respond adequately today in ways that we couldn't have
dreamed of five years ago,'' he told the subcommittee on medical
personnel and compensation which is examining military medical care
readiness abroad. The panel has scheduled a similar hearing on
domestic military medical facilities for March 8.
   Mayer said there is a danger that if improvements in health care
for the armed forces do not continue, it could become ``a national
scandal.''
   Air Force Surgeon General Murphy A. Chesney said he has
purchased 75 percent of the hospital beds that would be needed
overseas in wartime but there is no money to obtain the other 25
percent.
   He said that with the growth of Soviet offensive capabilities,
U.S. Air Force bases have to be considered ``first-strike
targets.'' He said in 1979 it was concluded that potential casualty
rates at air bases were 17 times those previously predicted.
   Since then, he said, the value of medical facilities has grown
from $17 million in 1978 to an expected $450 million when all
funded work is completed. But that still leaves the Air Force
needing 10 more hospitals with 500 beds each, he said.
   Army Surgeon General Quinn H. Becker said, ``Although we have
achieved admirable progress in correcting our medical readiness
shortfalls, critical equipment and personnel deficiences remain.''
</TEXT>
