<2ND_LINE>AM-Swaggart-Canada,0224</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Minister Confident Jimmy Swaggart Canadian Headquarters To Be
Built</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NIAGARA FALLS, Ontario (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Television evangelist Jimmy
Swaggart's admission of moral failure isn't expected to hinder
development of a $2 million Canadian headquarters, says his
representative in Canada.
   The Rev. Norman MacLaren, who has headed Swaggart's Canadian
operation since 1983, said he was planning a new building for his
200-member congregation in Niagara Falls 10 months ago and decided
to make it large enough to serve also as the Canadian headquarters
for Jimmy Swaggart Ministries.
   A foundation has been laid for the building, which will include
a 1,300-seat sanctuary. The building is expected to be finished by
Nov. 30.
   MacLaren said his church is a member of the Pentecostal
Assemblies of Canada, which is affiliated with the Assemblies of
God denomination of which Swaggart is a member.
   Asked if the TV evangelist's temporary absence from the pulpit
and othe4r disciplinary action by the denomination will affect the
local plans, MacLaren said ``we trust it won't.''
   Between 35,000 and 40,000 Canadians subscribe to Swaggart's
evangelical magazine, he said. This is the group that will be
served by the headquarters in Niagara Falls.
   Being the Swaggart headquarters means handling all Canadian
distribution of the evangelist's music, TV tapes and literature and
processing all incoming mail, MacLaren said.
