<2ND_LINE>AM-Springsteen Tour,0332</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>More Than 13,000 Fans Expected As Springsteen Opens Tour</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WORCESTER, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of Bruce Springsteen fans lined
up Thursday outside the Worcester Centrum arena vainly seeking
tickets for the sold-out opening concert of the Boss' nationwide
``Tunnel of Love'' tour.
   ``We do have have some people outside who are not believing
us,'' said Centrum marketing director Kathleen Heinz. ``They think
they will be more tickets. We're telling them that's not the case.
The tickets are all sold.''
   More than 13,000 fans held tickets for the Thursday night
concert.
   During an appearance Wednesday in Boston, Springsteen promised
``plenty of surprises'' in the three sold-out dates at the arena.
   Worcester police Deputy Chief Edward O'Brien said 30 officers
were stationed at the Centrum for crowd control and to hunt down
ticket scalpers, who reportedly were reaping up to $600 a ticket.
   A 23-year-old Worcester man was arrested after he allegedly sold
two $20 tickets to a plainclothes police officer for $400. Police
seized four tickets to Thursday's show and two for the final
Worcester show on Monday, and the man was fined $525 for reselling
tickets and selling tickets without a license.
   And in case anyone was wondering, Worcester cobbler David
Jennette says Springsteen wears a size 10D boot.
   ``I didn't believe it when we got the call Tuesday night asking
if we'd do some work on Bruce Springsteen's boots. I thought it was
a prank,'' Jennette said. ``We were just closing up so I said `OK,
come right over,' thinking it was some kid calling up.''
   It was no joke. A few minutes later, Springsteen's road manager
appeared with a pair of boots and asked to have the leather soles
replaced with non-skid rubber soles.
   Jennette was invited to Springsteen's rehearsal and took his
sister-in-law along.
   ``Bruce was great. After the rehearsal he came over and talked
to us and let us take pictures with him,'' he said.
