<FILEID>AP-NR-02-25-88 2059EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-FBI-Racism     02-25 0659</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-FBI-Racism,640</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Criminal Probe Possible in FBI Agent's Racism Claims, Justice Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A grand jury may investigate possible criminal
wrongdoing stemming from a black FBI agent's claims that he was the
victim of racial harassment by fellow agents, a government lawyer
said Thursday.
   Justice Department attorney David M. Glass told the judge who is
hearing a civil lawsuit brought by FBI Special Agent Donald Rochon
that the department was conducting a criminal investigation of the
case.
   ``There has been some consideration of criminal proceedings,''
Glass told U.S. District Judge Charles R. Richey.
   Glass made the statement in response to the plaintiff's request
to examine FBI documents and investigative files to prepare for the
case for trial.
   Glass contended that opening the files to Rochon's lawyers could
interfere with the investigation being conducted by the criminal
division of the Justice Department's civil rights division.
   Rochon, 37, charged in the lawsuit filed last fall that fellow
agents in Omaha and later Chicago waged a three-year campaign of
harassment that included a letter threatening death, mutilation and
sexual assault of his white wife.
   An FBI agent was suspended for two weeks for forging Rochon's
name on an application for an insurance policy covering his death
or dismemberment and another for burial benefits, according to the
lawsuit.
   A department source, speaking on condition of anonymity, said
investigators are examining letters containing threats to obtain
corroboration of Rochon's charges.
   The letters are being examined to determine if the mails were
illegally used to harass Rochon, the source said.
   Rochon also claims the FBI retaliated against him for
complaining by transferring him to Chicago and placing a letter of
censure in his personnel file. The lawsuit also charges that FBI
officials deliberately ignored his allegations to suppress them.
   On his first day on the job in Chicago, Rochon says agents
placed chocolate in the earpiece of his telephone so that it would
come off on his ear when he used the instrument.
   During a four-day period in the spring of 1985, Rochon says he
received a letter threatening him with violence, mutilation and
death as well as sexual assault of his wife, Susan. The letter
contained a picture of a mutilated black man, the complaint says.
   Four days later, Rochon received a bill for an insurance policy
for death and dismemberment that had been taken out in his name.
   The lawsuit states that FBI officials in Chicago gave agent Gary
Miller a 14-day suspension after determining that he had forged
Rochon's signature on the insurance application and on another for
death and burial benefits.
   But the FBI did not report Miller's actions to prosecutors
``although he clearly violated federal and state criminal laws,''
the lawsuit said.
   The lawsuit charges that in 1986, the Justice Department's civil
rights division deliberately shut down the Equal Employment
Opportunity Commission's investigation of allegations of harassment
in Chicago, saying it was conducting a criminal investigation.
   Rochon's lawsuit charges that even though the Justice Department
notified the EEOC of the criminal investigation, it did not
interview Rochon or agents suspected of wrongdoing until last
summer.
   Last summer the EEOC ruled that Rochon was unfairly disciplined
in Omaha and transferred to Chicago. The EEOC ordered the FBI to
allow Rochon to be transferred to any office of his choice within
the agency.
   EEOC also ordered the FBI to lift the 1984 letter of censure,
which rebuked Rochon for failing to report that he was the victim
of possible housing discrimination.
   The EEOC examiner determined that Rochon was the only FBI
special agent ever censured for failing to report a legal violation
of which he was the victim.
   The EEOC also ordered FBI training sessions for the agents
involved in the racial harassment to ensure such conduct would not
be repeated.
   During the hearing, the judge urged the Justice Department to
find a way to settle the lawsuit to avoid lengthy court proceedings.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
