<DOCNO> AP880225-0181 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-25-88 2207EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-WomanTerrorized     02-25 0536</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Woman Terrorized,0553</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Live-In Housekeeper, Family Terrorized Elderly Woman, Authorities
Say</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities have seized the home of a 90-year-old
woman and evicted a family they say terrorized and beat her and
stole thousands of dollars from her over the past few years.
   The retired teacher, whom authorities declined to identify, has
cancer and was taken to a nursing home several days before police
moved in. She has not been told about the raid and eviction,
officials said.
   Eight district attorney's investigators, two police lab
technicians and two patrolmen raided the house Tuesday night after
relatives became alarmed and called authorities.
   They evicted the live-in housekeeper and her son and
daughter-in-law.
   ``We have evidence at this point of emotional, verbal and
physical abuse _ things that really make you angry to hear about,''
said Dave Heckenbach, chief deputy district attorney.
   ``Like smacking her when she doesn't move fast enough, pushing
her down when she doesn't drink her fluids fast enough, bruises on
her body, bumps on her head, yelling at her, screaming at her,
threatening her,'' he said.
   No charges had been filed as of Thursday.
   ``We recovered numerous documents that we will have to go
through before charges can be filed,'' said Diane Balkin of the
district attorney's office.
   The woman's troubles began in early 1985 when she advertised for
a live-in housekeeper and hired Lois Hicks, 62, authorities said.
   Ms. Hicks took control of the woman's finances and
``substantially depleted her money,'' said Heckenbach.
   ``We don't know the totals yet,'' Heckenbach said, but financial
documents were seized when the house was raided. He said that just
two bank withdrawal slips that he saw showed withdrawals from the
woman's account of $15,000 and $22,000.
   ``And they seized many more than what I saw,'' he said. ``I can
say easily that we are into the many tens of thousands of dollars
that these people took from this lady.''
   Two years ago, officials said, Ms. Hicks' son, John Hicks, 34,
and his wife, Cheryl Hicks, 35, moved into the house with their
eight cats, a dog and a ferret.
   Heckenbach said both John Hicks and his wife are ex-convicts.
Cheryl Hicks was convicted of voluntary manslaughter and murder in
Georgia, and John Hicks was convicted of aggravated robbery in
Georgia, he said. The two met in a halfway house and had been out
of prison a short time when they moved into the elderly woman's
home, said Heckenbach.
   The family hired their own housekeeper and bought three cars,
said Heckenbach.
   Heckenbach said that last October, Lois Hicks told the teacher's
lawyer that the elderly woman wanted to change her will.
   ``The attorney, to his credit, refused to change the will
because his assessment was that she was not mentally able to make a
voluntary decision at that point,'' he said.
   ``He also told us he saw fear in her eyes and terror in her
eyes,'' Heckenbach said. ``It was his distinct impression she was
being intimidated by Lois Hicks.''
   John Hicks was out of town, but Lois and Cheryl Hicks were at
the house when officials seized it. They were allowed to take some
clothing and toiletries before they were locked out, officials said.
</TEXT>
