<HEAD>Barbara Cook Out of New Broadway Bound Version of `Carrie'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Barbara Cook will not appear in ``Carrie,'' a
musical version of the Stephen King novel, when it arrives on
Broadway in April, a spokesman for the show said Thursday.
   Miss Cook, who was the original Marian the librarian in ``The
Music Man,'' will withdraw from the show after it completes its
pre-Broadway run in Stratford, England, on March 5, said the show's
spokesman Jim Baldassare.
   In the musical, Miss Cook plays Carrie's mother. The title
character, a teen-age girl with telekinetic powers, is played by a
17-year-old English actress named Linzi Hateley.
   Miss Cook's decision to leave the show was based on
consultations between the actress, director Terry Hands and
producer Friedrich Kurz, Baldassare said. Several performers are
under consideration to replace Miss Cook but no offer has been
made, the spokesman said. The show was to have been Miss Cook's
first appearance in a Broadway musical in 17 years. Her one-woman
show had a short run on Broadway last spring.
   ``Carrie,'' which also was turned into a Brian de Palma movie
starring Sissy Spacek, has music by Michael Gore and lyrics by Dean
Pitchford.
   The show is scheduled to begin preview performances at the
Virginia Theater on April 12 and open on May 1.
