<FILEID>AP-NR-02-25-88 2219EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-AIDSAntibiotics     02-25 0648</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-AIDS Antibiotics,0667</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Study: Two Antibiotics Help Battle AIDS-Related Pneumonia</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-AIDS Treatments, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM C. HIDLAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two common antibiotics used against traveler's
diarrhea helped a group of AIDS patients live longer by preventing
the pneumonia that is a leading cause of death from the disease, a
study found.
   The drug therapy gives doctors an important new weapon in the
fight against AIDS, a fatal, incurable immune disorder, one of the
study's authors said Thursday.
   ``If we intercede early with medications that may prevent
life-threatening infections, that will prolong life and improve the
quality of life,'' said Dr. Margaret Fischl, lead researcher on the
study published in Friday's Journal of the American Medical
Association.
   The two antibiotics, trimethoprim and sulfamethoxazole,
prevented 30 patients with early stages of AIDS from developing
pneumocystis carinii pneumonia while they remained on the drugs
   The patients also lived much longer than 30 similar patients who
did not receive the drugs, said Ms. Fischl, an associate medical
professor and director of AIDS research at the University of Miami
School of Medicine.
   The patients each had been newly diagnosed as having Kaposi's
sarcoma, a skin cancer that afflicts AIDS patients. But they hadn't
developed pneumocystis carinii pneumonia or any of the other
opportunistic infections that eventually kill AIDS victims, the
study said.
   ``More than 50 percent of patients with AIDS develop
pneumocystis carinii infection and, despite therapy, more than 20
percent die with overwhelming infection,'' the study noted.
   AIDS, or acquired immune deficiency syndrome, destroys the
body's defenses against disease, leaving its victims prey to
infections and certain cancers.
   The patients were studied between January 1984 and June 1985,
and were re-examined in June 1987.
   Sixteen of the 30 patients who didn't receive the antibiotics
developed the pneumonia, the study results showed.
   None of the 30 patients taking the antibiotics developed the
pneumonia while they received the drugs, the study said.
   But half of those receiving the drugs had side effects such as
nausea and skin rashes, the study said. Five had such severe
reactions they had to stop taking the antibiotics, it said. Four of
the five developed the pneumonia within four or five months after
the treatment was halted.
   During the study, 28 of the 30 patients _ 93 percent _ not
receiving the antibiotics died, compared with 18 patients, or 60
percent, in the group that took the drugs.
   Ms. Fischl estimated that 40 percent of the patients who took
the drugs remain alive today. Only one patient who wasn't given the
drugs is still living, she said by telephone from her Miami office.
   A study published in the New England Journal of Medicine in 1982
found that the same two prescription antibiotics were effective in
quickly relieving the misery of travelers' diarrhea, a disorder
common to visitors of Latin America, the Middle East, the Far East
and the Mediterranean.
   Ms. Fischl recommended Thursday that all patients with AIDS and
AIDS-related illness, a condition called ARC, be considered for
therapy with the two antibotics.
   Similar tests are being conducted on other antibiotics to see if
they also may be effective in preventing AIDS-related infections,
she said.
   Ms. Fischl speculated that the medical technique known as
chemoprophylaxis _ trying to prevent infections with low doses of
antibotics _ may become a major weapon against AIDS and be used in
conjunction with other drugs, such as AZT.
   AZT, or azidothymidine, has been shown to prolong the lives of
AIDS patients by reducing the frequency and severity of
opportunistic infections, like the rare pneumonia.
   ``Perhaps the combination of chemoprophylaxis with AZT will
improve the outcome better than either alone,'' said Ms. Fischl,
who also has directed studies of AZT.
   The virus that causes AIDS is believed to be passed mainly
through sexual intercourse, shared hypodermic needles and from
infected mothers to their infants before or during birth.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880225-0184 </DOCNO>
