<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Consumers-Banks     02-25 0290</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Consumers-Banks,290</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Legislation Would Aid Consumers' Dealing With Banks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Reps. Charles E. Schumer, D-N.Y., and Joseph
P. Kennedy, D-Mass., introduced legislation Thursday designed to
aid consumers in their dealing with banks.
   Schumer and Kennedy, both members of the House Banking Committee
_ joined by a coalition of representatives of consumer groups,
including activist Ralph Nader _ told a news conference they hoped
their measure would be included in major legislation to restructure
banking regulations.
   ``As the bank and securities industries argue about how to
divide up the goodies of the financial system, Congress must make
sure that consumers get a fair shake,'' said Schumer. ``Whether or
not Congress grants banks any new powers, Congress must address the
concerns of consumers and communities.''
   Kennedy said that no matter what Congress does on the
Glass-Steagall law, which restricts the role of banks, ``local
communities and consumers deserve to have their rights under the
law enforced.''
   Schumer and Kennedy said their legislation will offer an
opportunity for every person to have a bank account, establish
community organizations to monitor bank performance and will
provide better information about the credit given to businesses in
poor communities.
   The measure requires that banks make available basic checking
accounts to all consumers for a minimal initial deposit. These
accounts would be free of all fees and charges for a limited number
of checking services.
   It also will require regular disclosure of where banks are
lending their depositors' money, giving consumers a better picture
of whether the banks they patronize are serving the community which
supports them, according to Schumer.
   A third provision would establish a system of state-level
organizations to inform and represent consumers' interests before
regulatory authorities, courts, legislatures and other forums.
</TEXT>
