<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Heroin     02-25 0294</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Heroin,0300</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>DEA: Southeast Asian Heroin Dominates In New York</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Heroin Influx, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Southeast Asian heroin importers have supplanted
the Mafia as the largest supplier of the drug in New York, vastly
increasing their share of the illicit market since 1983,
authorities said Thursday.
   However, investigations of the drug rings have led to major
recent seizures of New York-bound heroin in Thailand and Chicago,
said Robert Strang, spokesman for the federal Drug Enforcement
Administration here.
   Five years ago an estimated 4 percent of the heroin reaching New
York was from Southeast Asia and the remaining 96 percent was from
Iran, Afghanistan and Pakistan, where the Mafia dominated the
distribution network, Strang said.
   Now, an estimated 70 percent of the heroin comes from Southeast
Asia _ principally Thailand, Laos and Burma _ imported by gangs
based in Hong Kong and Bangkok, while the share from Iran,
Afghanistan and Pakistan is down to 30 percent, he said.
   Officials are unsure of the reason for the decreasing role of
organized crime, but they speculate that one factor is retrenchment
and disarray in the Mafia ranks caused by recent successful
prosecutions of Mafia leaders in New York.
   The Southeast Asian heroin has an average street-level purity of
45 percent, compared with 15 percent for heroin from Iran,
Afghanistan and Pakistan, Strang noted. Nonetheless, wholesale
prices have remained level, ranging from $75,000 to $150,000 per
pound, he said.
   The DEA responded to the increasing role of Bangkok and Hong
Kong heroin gangs by forming a special investigative group 1{ years
ago, Strang said. The group led to seizures of 180 pounds of heroin
in New York in December, 165 pounds this week in Chicago and nearly
1{ tons in Thailand earlier this month.
</TEXT>
