<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Philippines     02-25 0673</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Philippines,0694</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bomb Wounds 14 At Celebrations Marking Marcos Ouster</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES W. HATTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bomb exploded near a crowded stage
late Thursday and wounded 14 people at the climax of celebrations
marking the second anniversary of the popular uprising that ousted
President Ferdinand E. Marcos.
   Brig. Gen. Rodolfo Biazon, chief of the National Capital Region
Defense Command, told The Associated Press there was no indication
who planted the homemade device, and no one claimed responsibility.
The military had been on full alert in case communist rebels or
militant rightists tried to disrupt the celebration.
   Biazon said the bomb went off during a fireworks display at the
end of daylong celebrations marking the Feb. 25, 1986 ouster of the
Marcos administration.
   Elisa Florido, a nurse at Medical City Hospital, said no one was
seriously hurt. She said most of the injured suffered cuts from
flying glass and debris.
   The blast occurred at about 10 p.m. near the main stage set up
on Epifanio de los Santos Avenue. Seven stages were erected along
the highway, known as EDSA, for religious services and performances
by Filipino entertainers.
   Two years ago, hundreds of thousands of Filipinos swarmed onto
EDSA to form a human wall shielding troops who mutinied against
Marcos after a fraud-tainted election. The uprising swept Corazon
Aquino into the presidency.
   During a Mass attended by Mrs. Aquino Thursday, Cardinal Jaime
L. Sin, archbishop of Manila, appealed for land reform and warned
that the country cannot survive if it does not narrow the gap
between rich and poor.
   ``We have to bring about a more equitable distribution of wealth
throughout our land,'' Sin said. ``Only then can our nation survive
and go forward.
   ``It (land reform) can no longer wait. Many believe it is
already too late. The insurgency, now so much advanced, is at the
gates.''
   More than half the nation's 58 million people live in poverty
that has fueled the 19-year-old communist rebellion.
   Mrs. Aquino ordered land reform last July but left implementing
details to Congress, where the bill has bogged down because of
resistance by landowners.
   During the Mass, Mrs. Aquino made no speech but offered a prayer:
   ``Lord God, you helped us on EDSA two years ago, and we thank
you for helping us all through these difficult two years. ... We
believe that you led us out of bondage. We believe that it was you
who made us free.''
   About 10,000 leftists marked the day with a march and rally, at
which speakers claimed Mrs. Aquino had abandoned the reformist
goals of the 1986 revolution. Hundreds of Marcos supporters also
rallied to demand his return from exile in Hawaii.
   In Honolulu, Marcos said that after two years in exile, he
considers himself a prisoner in the United States. He vowed to
continue his fight to return home, though he said he expects to be
killed by his enemies.
   U.S. officials will not allow Marcos to return to the
Philippines because the Aquino government believes he and his wife
would disrupt the country's political stability.
   The explosion Thursday night was the only incident that marred
the celebrations in Manila, in which tens of thousands of Filipinos
returned to EDSA for a carnival of religious processions and street
dancing.
   The celebration began with the pealing of church bells across
the nation and a flag-raising ceremony at Camp Aguinaldo military
garrison. Mrs. Aquino joined thousands of people outside the camp
to hold hands in a 1{-mile-long ``chain for peace'' down EDSA.
   It was at Camp Aguinaldo where former Defense Minister Juan
Ponce Enrile and Lt. Gen. Fidel Ramos, then the vice chief of
staff, announced they were breaking with Marcos and backing Mrs.
Aquino.
   The mutiny galvanized opposition to Marcos which swelled after
the 1983 assassination of Mrs. Aquino's husband, former Sen.
Benigno Aquino Jr.
   Mrs. Aquino promised broad social and economic reform, but
critics complain she failed to meet the goals because of strong
opposition from conservative groups within the military and the
elite.
</TEXT>
