<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man taken into custody at a campus dormitory
grabbed an officer's gun and opened fire early Thursday, wounding
three people before fleeing, authorities said.
   The suspect, believed to be a 28-year-old student, apparently is
the same person who was arrested Wednesday after allegedly fighting
with a former roommate at the University of Houston-Downtown dorm.
That man was released from the Harris County Jail later Wednesday,
officials said.
   ``He returned to the dorm and started making threats,''
university spokeswoman Martha Cantu said. ``I think (the threats)
were in general.''
   Campus police were called to the dorm to check on a reported
disturbance. One person was taken into custody and then moved to
the university's main building, where two campus police officers
and a maintenance worker were wounded during a scuffle, university
spokesman Andy Gomez said.
   There were conflicting reports as to what time the student was
first taken into custody. Gomez said it was about 2:30 a.m.
Thursday, but Ms. Cantu said the student may have been taken into
custody late Wednesday.
   Ms. Cantu said that the shootings occurred after campus officer
Jim Durbin tried to handcuff the suspect, who apparently got
Durbin's .357-caliber revolver during a scuffle and fired four
shots.
   Durbin was in good condition with a wound in an armpit, Ms.
Cantu said. The other officer was shot in the head and was in
serious condition and the maintenance worker underwent surgery
Thursday, she said.
   Classes continued Thursday for the estimated 7,200 students
enrolled at the downtown branch of the University of Houston.
