<2ND_LINE>AM-Racial Assault,0579</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Activist Says Rape Victim Will Go to Jail Rather Than Testify</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BAUDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 16-year-old black girl who says she was
kidnapped and raped by six white men would sooner go to jail than
testify before a grand jury empaneled by state Attorney General
Robert Abrams, a minister said Thursday.
   The Rev. Al Sharpton, a minister from New York City who is
advising the family of Tawana Brawley, said Gov. Mario Cuomo is
using ``macho politics'' in trying to compel testimony from the
girl from Wappingers Falls, north of New York City.
   ``I see no fear for her (Tawana), her family, her lawyers and
myself for going to jail,'' said Sharpton, who said he met earlier
Thursday with the Brawley family. ``You're probably safer in jail
than you are in the streets.''
   Miss Brawley was found wrapped in a garbage bag and covered with
feces, with racial insults scrawled on her body, after being
missing for four days last November. She said she was assaulted by
six white men, one of whom flashed a police badge.
   On Wednesday Cuomo called on Abrams, who he has appointed as a
special prosecutor in the case, to ask a grand jury when it
convenes Monday in Poughkeepsie to force Miss Brawley and her
family to cooperate with investigators.
   ``Someone is going to give him a macho award for beating up on a
young girl who has already been abused,'' Sharpton said of Cuomo.
   According to Sharpton, the Brawleys and their advisers continue
to seek assurances that Abrams will be personally involved in the
investigation and trial of the case. In addition, he said the
family remains troubled by what he maintains is the ``special
relationship'' between Abrams and Dutchess County Sheriff Frederick
Scoralick, who one newspaper has reported as being implicated in
the case by Miss Brawley.
   The family's advisers are also concerned that Abrams has not
posted a reward for information in the case and that details of
private meetings between the attorney general and Brawley attorneys
C. Vernon Mason and Alton Maddox Jr. earlier this month were
revealed by Abrams' office.
   Timothy Gilles, spokesman for Abrams, did not return a phone
call seeking comment Thursday.
   Maddox and Mason, of New York City, have called for Abrams'
ouster as special prosecutor and asked for the naming of a
permanent state prosecutor to investigate race-related crimes.
   The Brawleys, Sharpton said, have even less trust in the state
since Tuesday's revelation that a former printing employee of
Abrams was arrested and charged with stealing and disclosing a
transcript of testimony taken before a previous Dutchess County
grand jury.
   ``They have made a joke of the grand jury by the robbery,''
Sharpton said. ``Are you going to tell me that if Tawana goes
before the grand jury that a printer isn't going to rob her
testimony?''
   John Poklemba, Cuomo's aide who advised the governor on the
appointment of a special prosecutor, said Wednesday that despite
the objections of Miss Brawley's representatives, he saw no reason
to remove Abrams from the case.
   Sharpton noted that Miss Brawley and her family have defied a
grand jury subpoena already. That court order was issued earlier
this year at the request of Dutchess County District Attorney
William Grady, who later asked to be removed from the case because
of an unspecified conflicts of interest.
</TEXT>
