<1ST_LINE>r w AM-VandalizedArtifacts     02-25 0400</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Vandalized Artifacts,400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Subcommittee Urges Tougher Penalties To Fight Looting Of Indian
Artifacts</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CALLAHAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tougher federal laws are needed to stem the
dramatically increased rate of Indian artifacts looted and
vandalized in the Southwest, a House subcommittee said Thursday.
   A report by the House Interior and Insular Affairs subcommittee
on general oversight and investigations, capping a four-month
probe, said up to 90 percent of the archaeological Indian sites in
Arizona, Colorado, New Mexico and Utah may have been vandalized.
   The subcommittee called it an ``extremely serious problem which
threatens our national heritage.''
   The 73-page report, issued by Rep. Sam Gejdenson, D-Conn.,
chairman of the panel, said vandalism reports have increased by
1,000 percent since 1980 on the Navajo Reservation alone.
   ``If the rate of looting on other Indian lands is as serious ...
the looting problem on Indian land is reaching crisis
proportions,'' the subcommittee concluded.
   Looting in the Southwest is especially severe because of the
value of certain artifacts. For example, an Indian basket and its
contents were sold by a dealer for $180,000.
   The panel recommended revising a law currently in effect that
separates misdemeanors and felonies by a $5,000 threshold on the
artifacts stolen or destroyed. Instead, the report suggested making
digging for artifacts a felony and ``surface collecting'' a
misdeamanor.
   ``The $5,000 threshold causes many problems as it is extremely
difficult to quantify the value of damage to archaeological
sites,'' the report said. ``This is a clear distinction, which
juries and judges can understand without the assistance of an
expert.''
   The subcommittee also said the law should be changed to make it
a crime to attempt to loot or vandalize archaeological sites on
federal lands. Now looters have to be caught in the act.
   The panel wants to have the law apply to artifacts that are at
least 50 years old, instead of the current 100-year-old standard.
   In addition, the lawmakers called for more undercover operations
and patrols, including patrols at archaeological sites that are
important but not protected under the National Historic
Preservation Act.
   The subcommittee said the government should focus on education
and advertising efforts, noting that while many looters are seeking
a profit, some are just archaeology enthusiasts unaware of the need
to protect the artifacts.
   ``The key to protecting archaeological resources is to convince
the general public of their value,'' the report said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
