<2ND_LINE>AM-Dole, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0767,680</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dole Aides Fired in Dispute With Brock</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates in top 15 grafs with details on firing, dispute,
picking up in 7th graf pvs, During his</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BRENT KALLESTAD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JACKSONVILLE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two top strategists for Republican
presidential candidate Bob Dole were fired Thursday in the
culmination of an apparent power struggle that erupted as the
Kansas senator was grearing up for the single biggest day of the
1988 campaign.
   Consultants David Keene and Don Devine left Dole's campaign in
Florida, according to campaign manager Bill Brock.
   ``We're in the process of trying to tighten up on resources,''
Dole said, but he also acknowledged, ``There is tension in any
campaign.''
   Brock said he decided on the firings and notified Dole Wednesday
night.
   ``We don't have any philosophical differences,'' said Brock, a
former senator from Tennessee. ``We're in a different kind of
campaign at this time.''
   Brock said other changes were forthcoming, adding that some Dole
personnel in the national headquarters would be asked to go into
the field for the Kansas senator.
   Keene and Devine flew with Dole on the candidate's chartered
plane when he headed south from Minnesota on Wednesday after his
victories in the South Dakota primary and Minnesota precinct
caucuses.
   Devine, in a telephone interview, said Brock had called them
Tuesday night and ordered them off the plane.
   Both refused, saying they worked for Dole.
   Brock joined the entourage Thursday in Orlando, Fla., after a
day of campaign stops in South Carolina and Florida. And Devine
said that while Dole was delivering a speech, a photographer asked
Brock and Keene to stand together for a picture.
   According to Devine, as the two men stood together, Brock leaned
over and said to Keene, ``We're going to cut the string on you
right now.''
   Then he looked at Devine and said, ``I might as well do both of
you together.''
   Devine said the dispute flared when Brock advised Dole not to go
to South Dakota and Minnesota Tuesday night, despite indications
the senator would carry both states.
   Keene and Devine argued that Dole should go and the senator
agreed.
   During his appearance before the Jacksonville Chamber of
Commerce, Dole said he considered the Republican race a two-man
battle between himself and Vice President George Bush.
   ``I've got a feeling we may be headed all the way to New
Orleans,'' said Dole, referring to the Republican National
Convention in August.
   Aiming his remarks at conservative Republicans in a city that
hosts three huge naval bases, Dole praised President Reagan's
leadership and pitched his remarks toward strong support of the
Strategic Defense Initiative. But he also urged resolving the
federal budget deficit.
   ``The biggest single threat in America ... in my view, is the
deficit,'' said Dole. ``You have a right to insist we deal with the
deficit.''
   Dole said the country needed to control wasteful Pentagon
spending with an inspector general ``meaner than a junkyard dog,''
but said he would not compromise on defense.
   ``If I'm going to make a mistake on defense, I ant to be sure
I've spent enough,'' said the senator.
   Dole also spoke before the Florida Association of Counties
mid-year legislative congress and attended a rally on his behalf
before flyig to Texas.
   Florida and Texas are the two largest of the 20 states that have
contests on March 8, known as Super Tuesday.
   Earlier, at an Orlando campaign stop, Dole told reporters that
Bush had brought a disinformation campaign to Florida.
   Dole complained that TV ads now running in Miami, which were
also used by the Bush campaign in New Hampshire and Vermont,
distort Dole's views on several issues.
   He said the ads say that ``Dole can't wait to raise your taxes,
then there's something about import fees and something about the
INF (nuclear missiles) treaty _ all of which is totally
inaccurate.''
   Later, posing at the Universal Studios construction site with
cartoon and movie characters Woody Woodpecker and Frankenstein's
monster, the Kansas senator quipped that ``we have a broad-based
campaign. ... It's reaching new heights.''
</TEXT>
