<2ND_LINE>AM-Brites,0320</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bright & Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Doug Watson says he's not the greatest salesman
who ever lived, but then how many of his competitors can say
they've sold 117,000 pounds of ice to Fairbanks, Alaska?
   The ice, 390 blocks weighing 300 pounds each, was loaded into
refrigerator trucks Thursday for the first leg of the voyage to the
Fairbanks Ice Festival.
   The price tage was $2,350 with the Fairbanks Convention and
Visitor Bureau also paying for the shipping.
   The shipment from Rainier Ice Co. is due in Fairbanks on March
7, in time for three ice sculptors from Harbin, China, to render
their artwork by the festival's March 18 start.
   ``I thought when they called me about buying the ice that it
gets cold up there and they should have all they want,'' Watson
said.
   ``We don't have the right kind of ice in Alaska,'' said Susan
Stolpe, a spokeswoman for the Fairbanks convention bureau. ``We
need de-oxygenated ice, which is clearer.''
   The ice festival runs through March 20 and celebrates the
approach of spring with dogsled races, art exhibits and a parade of
locally made parkas.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>TULSA, Okla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Employees at a downtown office building have
received a memo suggesting that their visits to restrooms be
wrapped up in 12 minutes _ or they'll be left in the dark.
   Motion sensors that control lights will be installed in the next
few weeks in all restrooms of the building occupied by Cities
Service Oil and Gas Corp.
   The sensors will detect motion when people pass and turn on
lights. If no motion is detected for 12 minutes, the devices will
turn the lights out, according to the memo.
   A spokesman said the devices have been tested in one men's room
in the building and have been found to be effective in reducing
electricity use.
</TEXT>
