<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-Portugal     02-25 0429</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Portugal,420</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Portuguese Leader Sees Pivotal U.S. Role In Angola In Next Months</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALEXANDER G. HIGGINS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States plays a pivotal role in
Portugal's former African colony of Angola and has a chance to end
Cuban and South African involvement there in the next four months,
Portugese Prime Minister Anibal Cavaco Silva said.
   ``This is the right time,'' Cavaco Silva told the National Press
Club. ``If the agreement is not obtained, it is my opinion, in the
next four months, perhaps it will not be achieved in the next two
years.''
   The main factor, he said, is next November's U.S. elections and
the change of administrations.
   ``Perhaps the next administration will take some time, perhaps
two years, to make a new assessment of foreign policy in relation
to that area,'' Cavaco Silva said. ``And it would be a pity because
the suffering of the people will continue, and the opportunities of
economic recovery will be lost.''
   Cavaco Silva said he had discussed Angola with President Reagan
on Wednesday and also with Secretary of State George Shultz and
Chester Crocker, assistant secretary of state for African affairs.
   Crocker has been conducting talks with the Angolan government
for much of the Reagan administration to try to arrange a pullout
of some 40,000 Cuban troops from Angola, which would be coordinated
with South Africa's granting independence to South-West Africa, or
Namibia.
   ``The government of Angola is experiencing big difficulties _
economic difficulties of the decline in oil prices,'' Cacavo Silva
said. It also has suffered a setback in recent fighting with UNITA
rebels, in part because of the intervention of South African
troops, he said. Government troops ``are on retreat now,'' he said.
   ``The United States administration is in a position to achieve a
retreat of the Cuban troops and to explain the arrangement to the
South Africans ... and to force the necessary steps for the
independence of Namibia,'' Cavaco Silva said.
   He said his government has urged Angola to reach an agreement
now and that the Angolan government has accepted the principle of
the total withdrawal of the Cuban troops. ``The difficulty is to
fix the timetable,'' he said.
   ``It is necessary to have in mind that that agreement afterwards
has to be negotiated with South Africa,'' Cavaco Silva said. ``And
South Africa this time has been openly involved. For the first
time, they say that the African troops are there.''
   He said he was less able to see any quick resolution to the
fighting between the Angolan government and UNITA.
</TEXT>
