<1ST_LINE>r a AM-StealthSuit     02-25 0428</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Stealth Suit,0441</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pentagon Probes Alleged Northrop Overcharging on Stealth</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four current and former employees of Northrop
Corp. have filed a lawsuit accusing the aerospace giant of
overcharging the government by more than $1 billion for development
of the radar-dodging Stealth bomber.
   The Pentagon is investigating the allegations in the latest in a
series of inqueries involving alleged mishandling by Northrop of
military programs.
   The Stealth is Northrop's ``crown jewel,'' accounting for about
half of its net income and a third of its workforce.
   Last month, the Air Force confirmed it had awarded a $2 billion
contract to Northrop in the first infusion of regular production
funds for the plane. Only Northrop got a contract, despite
arguments by critics that the Air Force should seek a second source
for the planes because of Northrop's problems.
   In the 1990s, the Pentagon is expected to deploy 132 Stealth
bombers at a cost of $36.6 billion.
   The plane, designed to be difficult to detect on enemy radar, is
under development at Northrop's plants in Pico Rivera and Palmdale.
   The investigation by the Air Force and the Pentagon inspector
general's office was revealed Wednesday after a U.S. District Court
suit was filed by the one current and three former employees under
the federal False Claims Act.
   Under that act, citizens are allowed to sue on behalf of the
government and share in any damage award.
   The government must routinely investigate allegations in such
suit, and the Justice Department must decide within 60 days if
there is sufficient evidence for the government to join the suit or
seek its dismissal.
   Northrop spokesman Tony Cantafio refused comment, citing company
policies against responding publicly to lawsuits and against making
statements regarding the super-secret Stealth bomber.
   The suit, which was sealed under procedures followed in such
cases, accuses Northrop of double-billing, false billing and
misrepresented charges, said Robert Kilborne, the attorney
representing the plaintiffs.
   Kilborne identified his clients only as an internal auditor, a
former controller, a former avionics engineer and a former test
equipment engineer.
   The suit alleges that Northrop destroyed internal audits that
turned up evidence of $400 million in improper charges on
development of the bomber, predicting that such overcharges may
actually total $1 billion.
   Wednesday's suit is the fourth such action brought by Kilborne
or his law partner, Herb Hafif, against Northrop. The other suits
involved Northrop's work on the MX missile program.
   In October, the Justice Department moved to dismiss one of the
earlier suits on grounds that there was insufficient evidence to
substantiate the allegations.
</TEXT>
