<1ST_LINE>r a AM-PoliceShooting     02-25 0552</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Police Shooting,0570</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Off-Duty Officer Shoots Man To Death During Robbery Attempt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAY JORDEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An off-duty police officer shot and killed a man
who challenged him to fire and reached for a knife Thursday, police
said, bringing to six the number of people who have died in Dallas
police shootings in less than two months.
   The shootings have exacerbated racial tensions in Dallas. Two of
the police department's most vocal critics are black members of the
City Council, who contend department's deadly force policy hurts
minorities.
   Both the officer and the slain man in Thursday's shooting were
black.
   According to police, the man ordered to waitresses to empty a
restaurant cash register, and was confronted bu Officer Cloyce
Addison Shannon.
   ``Go ahead and shoot me; shoot me,'' the man told Shannon as he
reached for a weapon tucked in his weapon, police reports said.
   Shannon, 29, shot the man twice in the chest. He was pronounced
dead at the scene, Police Lt. Ron Waldrop said.
   The officer was under the impression that the weapon was a gun,
but it turned out to be a long-bladed knife with a handle similar
to that of a pistol, Waldrop said.
   The Dallas County Medical Examiner's office identified the
victim as Robert Keith Johnson, 30, of Dallas.
   Six people have died in five shootings involving Dallas police
this year, including a black transient slain by off-duty police
after he killed a white officer in a downtown parking lot as some
members of a street-corner crowd cheered him on.
   The department has come under fire for its use of deadly force
and has been criticized as being out of touch with the minority
community.
   Police Capt. Rick Stone, who helped write the department's
deadly force policy, said the use of such force is limited to the
defense of life.
   ``Officers are prevented from firing warning shots and are
prevented from using deadly force to protect property interests
alone,'' he said. ``In essence, the officer must feel that either
he or another individual is in imminent danger of death or serious
bodily injury.''
   Police Chief Billy Prince, who issued no statement on latest
shooting, was criticized by city officials last month for blaming
the death of Officer John Chase on council members. Prince said
some members' criticism of the department created an environment of
potential violence.
   Price was criticized again Wednesday by Mayor Annette Strauss
and City Manager Richard Knight for comments concerning the
department's affirmative action program, implemented following
Chase's death.
   Prince said the new policy forced him to promote a black officer
who had scored one point lower on a civil rights exam than three
white candidates.
   Fueling the racially tense atmosphere were plans by the Ku Klux
Klan to march Saturday.
   ``The KKK is abhorrent to the Dallas Police Department,'' Prince
said in a statement. ``We did not solicit and do not want their
support.
   ``We regret the organization's plans to demonstrate in Dallas
Saturday and strongly urge them to abandon the planned
demonstration.''
   In the other police shootings this year, officer James Joe was
shot while off-duty as he investigating a burglary at the apartment
complex where he lived.
   The other two victims were shot by police last week. One was
black and one was white.
</TEXT>
