<FILEID>AP-NR-02-25-88 1842EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Nicaragua-Economy     02-25 0546</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nicaragua-Economy,0565</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sandinista Economic Measures Cause Confusion</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYNA BRENNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The sudden change of currency to
combat runaway inflation, accomplished largely by lopping zeros off
the old one, has caused confusion, shortages of staples and some
cheating.
   ``We are in a horrible crisis,'' said Julia Duarte, a fruit
vendor at the open-air Eastern Market in Managua. ``We don't have
rice, beans, and people are going hungry.''
   President Daniel Ortega, citing a yearly inflation rate of 1,500
percent, announced Feb. 14 that the cordoba currency was being
revalued at 10 to the dollar. At that time a dollar was worth
20,000 cordobas on the legal rate and 50,000 on the black market.
   His government said the new currency would end the black market,
foil a CIA plan to flood the country with the old money, and
deprive the U.S.-supported Contra rebels of Nicaraguan bills
supplied by the CIA.
   After Ortega announced the change, the opposition Private
Enterprise Council predicted it would drive real prices higher.
   The black market has continued, despite threats that
participants would be arrested, and the Contras claimed they got $1
million worth of the new money by downing a Sandinista helicopter
carrying the cash.
   Store owners said they were bewildered by the change in money
and many closed for several days. Rice and beans, staples for
Nicaraguans, disappeared from store shelves.
   The Intercontinental Hotel, unsure of how the new system worked,
charged $46 for breakfast, and $16 for a chicken sandwich.
   Nicaraguans had three days to trade their old money for new.
Those who were out of the country or otherwise missed the deadline
found the old bills worthless.
   Prices set by the government have increased sharply in objective
terms. On a dollar scale, a dozen eggs went from just under $1 to
$2.50, an average restaurant meal featuring beef went from under
$10 to $25, and gasoline rose from about 60 cents a gallon to $1.50.
   A new scale set monthly wages from $50 to $753. At a store
recently, the cost of a shirt was $33 and jeans were marked at the
equivalent of $66.
   La Prensa, the opposition newspaper La Prensa said in an
editorial that the daily wage in 1979, when the cordoba was last
valued at 10 to the dollar, was $15.20 and now it is $16.66. It
also noted that meat cost $7.22 a pound then and is $35 now.
   The leftist Sandinistas overthrew President Anastasio Somoza in
July 1979, ending a family dynasty that had been in power 42 years.
   A few days after the currency change, police swept through the
Eastern Market, broke some wooden stalls with clubs and confiscated
goods sold by vendors operating without licenses.
   The government said more than 3,000 vendors at the market had
been operating illegally.
   ``The police come, they push out some of the vendors, and they
take and resell the stuff,'' said Mrs. Duarte, 60, sitting in front
of large straw baskets filled with golden mangos and green oranges.
   ``We have to work harder than ever,'' said a nearby vegetable
vendor, Miguel Sanchez Sales. ``This new money isn't worth anything
either. We used to eat on 10 cordobas a day. Now we're lucky if we
can get by on 100.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
