<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Bennett-Bush     02-25 0242</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bennett-Bush,210</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Education Secretary Rejects Request By Columnist To Rate Bush</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A request from columnist Jack Anderson's
associate to Cabinet officers to tell all about Vice President
George Bush got a brusque reply Thursday from Secretary of
Education William J. Bennett.
   Dale Van Atta, co-author of the Anderson column, wrote all 34
present and former Reagan Cabinet members who have served with
Bush, asking them to rate him as presidential timber.
   Calling Bush ``a mystery to the voters,'' the columnist asked
for instances where Bush influenced policy decisions or actions,
and warned that a failure to reply ``may send a negative message
about Mr. Bush.''
   Bennett's wrote back that it was ``nonsense'' to call Bush a
mystery to the voters. He also said he would not violate the
confidentiality of Cabinet discussions, or ``the president's
injunction to all his Cabinet members to stay neutral in the
presidential race.''
   ``Finally, and most incredibly, you threaten that you will
construe a refusal to accede to your demands as sending `a negative
message about Mr. Bush.' I cannot believe anyone will credit such a
perverse interpretation,'' said Bennett.
   ``I am confident that the American people will judge the vice
president's distinguished record of public service on its merits.''
   Bush has said repeatedly on the campaign trail that he wants to
be known as ``the education president.'' Bennett has been mentioned
as a possible running mate for whoever wins the Republican
nomination.
