<FILEID>AP-NR-02-25-88 2346EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Reading     02-25 0471</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Reading,460</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Poor Readers Getting Shortchanged in U.S. Schools, Study Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Education Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American schools are still having trouble
trying to make good readers out of poor ones, according to a
federal released Thursday.
   The report from the government-backed testing program, the
National Assessment of Education Progress, said poor readers are
left at a disadvantage by teachers who help them figure out hard
words but neglect to make them discuss the meaning of the entire
passage.
   ``American schools continue to have difficulty in narrowing the
performance gap between better and poorer readers as they progress
through school,'' said the report, ``Who Reads Best?'' The study
was based on an analysis of reading tests the National Assessment
gave 35,000 students ages 9, 13 and 17 in 1986.
   The National Assessment, run under a federal contract by the
Educational Testing Service, refrained from making any comparisons
between these test results and such assessments of reading in 1984
and earlier.
   ETS officials revealed last month there were sharp, unexplained
declines in reading scores among the 9- and 17-year-olds in 1986.
They suspect something went wrong in the test itself, not the
students' performance.
   There were no sharp declines in other subjects tested in 1986,
they noted.
   The new report said there is still no explanation for the
``precipitous declines'' in reading, which it called ``simply not
believable.''
   The National Assessment switched to a different scale to report
the 1986 test results. But officials expressed complete confidence
in the conclusions reached in ``Who Reads Best?''
   The report suggests teachers use the same ``thought-stretching
activities'' for poor readers that they routinely employ with
better readers.
   Students had ``particular difficulty with tasks that require
them to elaborate upon or defend their evaluations and
interpretations of what they have read,'' it said.
   ``Poor readers report doing less independent reading than good
readers,'' it said. ``Poor readers report that their teachers use a
narrower range of (instructional) approaches than are used with
better readers.''
   They focus more on decoding strategies than comprehension and
critical thinking, it said.
   ``In the elementary grades, teachers of better readers are more
likely to preview reading material and read new parts aloud to the
class _ both activities which emphasize the meaning of the
selection,'' it said.
   ``At the high school level, better readers reported more
previewing of material, while poorer readers indicated their
teachers more frequently pointed out the hard words and read new
parts aloud.''
   Younger students and those in the bottom quarter of reading
scores generally were exposed to fewer instructional strategies,
while older students and those in the top 25 percent reported
engaging ``in more before-and after-reading activities.''
   They were ``more likely to be asked to engage in
thought-stretching activities after they have finished their
reading of the text,'' the report said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
