<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Swaggart-Taxes     02-25 0481</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Swaggart-Taxes,0496</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Trial Dates Set For Tax Cases Involving Swaggart Ministries</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Swaggart-Assemblies, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAY JORDEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   While Jimmy Swaggart contends with the fallout
from his self-confessed moral lapse, his ministry is battling
litigation involving taxes on a church radio station and
allegations he skimmed ministry profits.
   One case concerns the tax status of the station, KJOJ-FM in
Shenandoah. The Louisiana-based ministry sued county authorities
over their denial of a tax exemption for the station, which the
ministry contends is a place of worship.
   In two other cases, city and school authorities are seeking more
than $130,000 in delinquent taxes and other claims involving the
Christian station.
   An attorney for the ministry, James W. Bradford Jr., did not
immediately return telephone calls Thursday.
   Russell R. Graham, an attorney for the Montgomery County
Appraisal District, said the station does not meet the legal
definition of a place of worship. The agency denied the station
tax-exempt status in 1982.
   He said the agency's defense in the ministry lawsuit had been
hampered by the ministry's reluctance to reveal financial
information. But he said the county has received ``considerable
cooperation'' from the ministry since the county agreed to a
judge's order in July sealing further filings in the case until the
April 4 trial.
   In motions filed last year, the ministry revealed it collected
$455.8 million in contributions and sales of religious materials
from 1979 to 1985. Contributions rose about 25 percent annually
since 1979, financial statements show.
   The ministry had claimed the operation did not make a profit,
but a 1982 financial statement showed $11.9 million classified as
``excess revenues'' after expenses.
   Graham, in a letter to the judge obtained last year by The Texas
Lawyer magazine, had complained that the ministry would not provide
detailed accounting of millions of dollars in ``excess profits.''
   Tax officials ``believe that further discovery will reflect that
Jimmy Swaggart retained these funds for his personal use,'' the
letter said.
   ``The Texas statute on exemptions provides that not only does
the use of the property have to fit the narrow definition of what
is exempt, but you have to use income for accepted purposes under
the statute and avoid a situation where anyone receives any private
gain,'' Graham said.
   Ministry lawyers have denied that Swaggart skimmed ministry
profits.
   Hinging on the outcome of the Montgomery County suit are tax
cases against the ministry by the city of Shenandoah, set for a
March 21 trial, and by the Conroe Independent School District, for
which no trial date has been set.
   Shenandoah claims the ministry owes nearly $60,000 on the
station from 1980-87 and on its equipment from 1981-87, city
attorney Michael J. Darlow said.
   The school district claims it is owed more than $70,000 in back
taxes from the radio station, its contents and a broadcast tower,
said school attorney Robert A. Mott.
</TEXT>
