<1ST_LINE>r w AM-CampaignBill     02-25 0305</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Campaign Bill,290</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Senate Snarled in Debate Over Bill To Halt Big Campaign Spending</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The legislation that has snarled the Senate in
a filibuster is a Democratic response to the escalating cost of
getting elected to Congress.
   The bill, being pushed heavily by the self-described citizens
lobby, Common Cause, has 52 co-sponsors, all of whom are Democrats
except Robert Stafford, R-Vt., and John Chafee, R-R.I.
   It would set up a system to encourage Senate candidates in
general elections to voluntarily observe spending limits ranging
from $950,000 to $5.5 million, depending on a state's population.
   In 1986, the average cost of winning a Senate seat was $3
million, a fivefold increase from 1976. In larger states, the cost
in 1986 often exceeded $10 million.
   Under the Democrats' plan, a candidate observing the state
spending limit would be allowed to put no more than $20,000 in
personal funds into the campaign.
   In an effort to curb the growing role of political action
committees as a source of campaign money, a participating candidate
could get no more than 20 percent of his or her money from PACs. In
1986, PACs provided more than half the money spent by more than 200
House and Senate candidates.
   A candidate observing the limit would be eligible for campaign
money from the Treasury if an opponent did not adhere to the limit.
Tax dollars also would be awarded in cases in which a participating
candidate was the target of heavy spending by independent groups.
   A participating candidate also would be eligible for reduced
mailing rates. The bill would require radio and television stations
to charge the candidate the ``lowest unit rates'' for advertising.
   Campaign ads by candidates not observing spending limits would
have to carry the disclaimer, ``This candidate has not agreed to
abide by voluntary spending limits.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
