<1ST_LINE>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     02-25 0386</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0396</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>High Pressure Produces Mostly Sunny Skies Across Nation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Most of the nation enjoyed mostly sunny skies Thursday thanks to
a large high-pressure zone, while snow fell over parts of the
Midwest and New York state.
   The snow, ranging from flurries to major accumulation, fell from
lower Michigan across the eastern Great Lakes to upstate New York,
with heavier snow squalls near Lakes Erie and Ontario.
   Up to 17 inches was dumped on Pulaski, N.Y., overnight Thursday,
and up to 8 inches fell at Oswego, N.Y., between midnight and 7
a.m. EST.
   Three to 5 inches of snow fell Thursday morning in Ohio's Geauga
and Lake counties, while 2 to 3 inches covered downtown Cleveland.
   Light rain fell in northwest Washington state, and a trace of
rain fell in parts of the Texas Rio Grande Valley.
   Temperatures remained low in the Northeast, with midday readings
mostly in the teens and 20s from the upper Mississippi Valley
across the Great Lakes and northern sections of the Ohio Valley to
the northern and central Appalachians. Winds of 10 to 20 mph
produced wind chills in the single digits as far south as
Bluefield, W.V.
   Temperatures warmed into the 60s, 70s and 80s across the desert
Southwest. Readings in the 60s were also common across the southern
Plains, Louisiana and southern and central Florida.
   Temperatures around the nation at 2 p.m. EST ranged from 14 at
Gunnison, Colo., to 87 at Palm Springs, Calif. The early-morning
low for the nation was 18 below zero at Gunnison.
   For Friday, sunny skies again were expected across most of the
country, while snow was forecast across the Great Lakes region and
scattered snowshowers over the central Appalachians and northern
Maine. Light rain was expected along the northern Pacific Coast,
while clouds should increase across southern Texas. Much of the
nation will have highs in the 40s or 50s. Highs will be in the 20s
and 30s from eastern North Dakota across the Great Lakes region and
the upper Ohio Valley to the northern two-thirds of the Atlantic
Coast. Temperatures will reach the 60s and 70s over the southern
tier of states as well as over Arkansas, Oklahoma, Kansas, western
Nebraska and parts of Nevada, with readings in the 80s over
portions of the desert Southwest.
</TEXT>
