<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Balkans     02-25 0466</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Balkans,0480</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Balkan Nations Off To Rocky Beginning of Conference</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By IVAN STEFANOVIC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Albania said Wednesday it was
breaking out of its isolationist shell to build better relations
with its neighbors, but bitter differences between Turkey and
Bulgaria showed the region is still rife with disputes.
   Albania's presence at a three-day conference of six Balkan
states was its first appearance at a regional forum after a decade
of spurning invitations to attend low-level Balkan gatherings.
   ``Development of relations with neighboring countries
constitutes one of the priorities of the foreign policy'' of
Albania, Foreign Minister Reis Malile told his counterparts from
Greece, Turkey, Yugoslavia, Romania and Bulgaria.
   ``Not only do we not hesitate to cooperate with others. On the
contrary, we want this cooperation and consider it a factor which
contributes to our internal development,'' he said.
   But the conference, the first high-level gathering of Balkan
nations since World War II, was marked by Turkey's indirect
denunciation of Bulgaria's treatment of its Turkish minority.
   ``Attempts to alter the cultural and religious identity of
ethnic minorities can neither be reconciled nor coexist with the
new beginning we all seem desirous to make here in Belgrade,'' said
Turkish Foreign Minister Mesut Yilmaz
   Relations among most Balkan countries are still strained by
bilateral quarrels over ethnic minorities that date back to the
late 19th century when much of the region belonged to the Ottoman
Empire.
   Yilmaz did not assail Bulgaria by name nor mention its estimated
one million ethnic Turks specifically, but the minority issue is
the primary point of contention between the two countries.
   A campaign forcing Turkish citizens to change their names was
begun in 1984. It was first reported by Turkish newspapers and
later confirmed by Western diplomats in Sofia and by the human
rights group, Amnesty International.
   Bulgarian authorities, who have so far denied the existence of a
self-contained Turkish minority, said the decision to adopt
Bulgarian names was voluntary and no pressure was exerted.
   The Turkish foreign minister's comments were expected to be
cause tension during the three-day meeting.
   He expressed his satisfaction about the ``common understanding''
he reached with his Bulgrian counterpart Peter Mladenov in signing
an agreement Tuesday that he said would establish a mechanism for
the settlement of the existing problems between the two countries.
   But Yilmaz added that ``anachronistic policies cannot be either
defended or ignored,'' a reference to Bulgaria's policy toward the
ethnic Turks.
   Asked to comment on Yilmaz' speech, Mladenov said he would
comment on it only after reading it.
   A member of Turkish delegation, asked why the Turkish foreign
minister decided to criticize Bulgaria even after the protocol was
signed, said: ``We are seeking a mechanism to solve our problem.
But we have yet to see whether it will work.''
</TEXT>
