<HEAD>Jackson Mines For Votes In Eastern Kentucky Coal Country</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: To update, tops with 9 grafs on Jackson visit to eastern
Kentucky; picks up 5th graf pvs, bgng ``In Louisville''</NOTE>
<HEAD>Precede LOUISVILLE, Ky.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVE ROBRAHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HAZARD, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson mined for votes in eastern
Kentucky coal country Thursday, the first Democratic presidential
candidate since 1968 to campaign in this area where he said the
land is rich but the people are poor.
   Jackson visited a strip mine site near Hazard, then went to a
rally that drew about 3,000 people.
   ``Right down here in Appalachia, the land is wealthy _ the
people are poor,'' Jackson told a crowd in the Hazard Memorial
Gymnasium.
   Jackson, campaigning for support in Kentucky's March 8
Democratic presidential primary, said miners, farmers and factory
workers must forge a coalition to battle abuses of large
corporations which he said pay few taxes and hold down wages.
   Jackson drew the most applause when he discussed coal-related
issues. It is unfair, he said, when big coal companies pay almost
no taxes. He also said: ``What good is land if it is stripped from
beneath your feet?''
   Earlier, in Louisville, Jackson stressed his Southern roots and
his record. ``I return to the South as a son of the South,''
Jackson said.
   ``I have given 25 years of national and international service,''
Jackson said. ``My track record on national service is more
substantial than my opponents. I know foreign policy better than my
competitors.''
   Jackson, a Baptist minister, addressed the 44th annual Black
Baptist Pastors' Conference in Louisville before flying to Eastern
Kentucky.
   No other Democratic presidential candidates have ventured into
eastern Kentucky this year _ or in any year since Robert F. Kennedy
made a campaign trip to the Kentucky mountains in 1968.
   
   In Louisville, Jackson said his Southern credentials and
campaign message will carry him through the Super Tuesday primary
March 8.
   ``I return to the South as a son of the South,'' said Jackson,
who was born in South Carolina. ``I helped make the new South
better 25 years ago, and now I want to make it even better by
focusing on the agenda of today.''
   Jackson said that agenda includes improving day care, attaining
equal rights for women, increasing the minimum wage, increasing aid
to education and stopping a loss of jobs.
   ``We must care about the family and working people,'' he said.
``We can't be a great nation if we abandon those whose shoulders we
stand on.''
   Asked about his chances on Super Tuesday _ when Democrats go to
the primaries and caucuses in 20 states and American Samoa _ and,
in particular, about how he will do in the balloting in Kentucky,
Jackson said:
   ``I'm not projecting a certain number. Those who support me feel
I can win. I know I can win.''
   Jackson, who carried Louisville and Lexington in 1984 Democratic
caucuses, made a plug for campaign contributions in his address to
the ministers.
   He later discounted claims that a lack of money will keep him
from waging an effective campaign.
   ``I cannot buy the nomination. I will outwork my opposition,''
Jackson said. ``I come to the South with a message and a track
record, not money and television commercials.''
</TEXT>
