<1ST_LINE>r a AM-CBS-Sajak     02-25 0409</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-CBS-Sajak,0420</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>CBS Announces Sajak Talk Show</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHRYN BAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   CBS and Pat Sajak insist they won't be gunning
for NBC's ``The Tonight Show starring Johnny Carson'' when their
new talk show premieres next January, despite its time period
opposite the late-night king.
   CBS made a formal announcement of the signing of Sajak,
well-known as the host of ``Wheel of Fortune,'' at a news
conference Wednesday.
   CBS Entertainment President Kim LeMasters said the show would be
90 minutes instead of Carson's hour and would premiere on Jan. 9,
1989.
   ``There is no attempt on our part here to compete with Johnny
Carson,'' LeMasters said. ``Mr. Carson is a tradition, he is
much-beloved and a brilliant performer in what he does, and that's
not our aim. Our aim is that the environment in late night can
stand more than just one talk-show format.''
   ``If you're going to do a late-night show, that's a fact of
life, that Mr. Carson is going to be there. We can't worry about
that. We have to worry about doing the best show we can,'' said
Sajak.
   Carson, who has been host of ``The Tonight Show'' for a
quarter-century, last year signed only a two-year extension of his
contract with NBC, but both Sajak and LeMasters said they did not
plan on Carson retiring.
   ``I have been hearing Johnny Carson is retiring for literally 20
years,'' said Sajak. ``It wouldn't shock me to be having the same
conversation in 10 years, that Johnny Carson is retiring in a
couple of years.''
   There's no name yet for the new show yet, though Sajak joked,
``We're thinking of the Wilton South Show,'' a reference to the
quickly canceled Fox late-night show ``The Wilton North Report.''
He added, ``perhaps the name Pat will be in the title.''
   Sajak will continue as host of the syndicated nighttime version
of ``Wheel of Fortune,'' which is the No. 1 syndicated show. His
contract for the NBC daytime version of the show expires in
December.
   LeMasters said CBS would have launched a talk show years ago
``if we'd had the personality.'' He said the network chose Sajak
because ``we were looking for someone intelligent, which Pat is,
well-read and with the ability to attract guests. And he's cute.''
   LeMasters said CBS might put its current schedule of late-night
original dramas, ``Adderly'' and ``Night Heat,'' in the 1 a.m. time
period instead of canceling them.
</TEXT>
