<1ST_LINE>r w AM-ArmsTreaty     02-25 0524</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Arms Treaty,520</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kissinger Calls For More Effective West European Alliance</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Secretary of State Henry A. Kissinger
called on the European members of the NATO alliance Wednesday to
unify their military defenses against the Soviet Union and to
coordinate British and French nuclear forces as an important first
step.
   Kissinger also suggested that Western Europe and the United
States present Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev with a
comprehensive plan to reduce nuclear and conventional arms
simultaneously.
   ``I am convinced that he has the intelligence and the
imagination to make an intelligent response,'' Kissinger told the
Senate Armed Services Committee. ``And if he refused, we would at
least understand the nature of the challenge better than we do
now.''
   Kissinger said the Western alliance will work better if Europe
sheds much of its military dependence on the United States and
develops ``a capacity for independent action'' based on ``a
rational balance of responsibilities.''
   As it stands now, he said, the 16 European members of NATO often
go along with U.S. military decisions for lack of a better
alternative. The result is not consultation or a mutual
decision-making process but merely a U.S. ``briefing'' on already
decided U.S. actions.
   Under conditions of relative prosperity, Kissinger said,
Europe's military dependence on the United States ``can breed
guilt, self-hatred and a compulsion to display independence of the
senior partner whenever doing so is safe, especially with regard to
Third World issues, the Middle East and some aspects of East-West
relations.''
   For those reasons, he said, the United States has a positive
interest in encouraging the evolution of a more independent
European voice in defense matters.
   Kissinger said that while some fear that military independence
might weaken Europe's military ties to the United States, ``the
opposite is almost certainly the case.''
   ``There is no foreseeable East-West conflict in which Europe
will not be better off with American support,'' Kissinger said.
   ``This is why, if the British and the French can agree on
coordinating their nuclear forces, the United States should
encourage it as an important first step toward a greater European
role in a joint nuclear defense,'' he said.
   ``Above all, the United States should make clear that European
union on defense matters will be viewed as strengthening, not
weakening Atlantic ties,'' he said.
   A European military union, he asserted, would ease West
Germany's fears of isolation and help overcome a ``logistical
nightmare'' caused by the effort of each European nation to
``stretch already inadequate defense efforts across the whole
panoply of weapons.''
   Kissinger said that divisive trends within the alliance have
been magnified by the successful ratification of the new treaty
eliminating medium-range U.S. and Soviet nuclear-armed missiles in
Europe and elsewhere.
   He repeated recent statements that the treaty strains the
alliance by making the nuclear defense of Europe dependent largely
on nuclear weapons located not in Europe but in the United States
or on submarines at sea.
   ``Many Europeans are convinced a gap is being created that in
time will enable the Soviet Union to threaten Europe while sparring
with the United States,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
