<1ST_LINE>r a AM-TestsShredded     02-25 0221</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Tests Shredded,0226</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>School Winces After Ungraded Law Exams Destroyed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 100 ungraded results from an
upper-level law exam were accidentally shredded, leaving Washington
University officials with red faces and some students furious.
   ``It seemed to be just a matter of time before a huge
administrative error occurred,'' Maia Brodie, a third-year law
student and president of the Student Bar Association, said of the
shredding, which was revealed last week. ``Some students want their
money back, they're so furious.''
   School officials said a student working without supervision in
the registrar's office accidentally shredded both the questions and
answers to a three-hour exam that was given in December.
   The exam was to provide the sole basis for the grades of 116
students who were enrolled in the evidence course.
   The shredding occurred two weeks ago. Law School Dean Dorsey D.
Ellis Jr. gave the bad news to the class in a memorandum dated Feb.
16.
   School officials decided to give each student in the evidence
class a ``credit'' that will have no bearing on grade-point
averages.
   One student studied nearly full-time for five weeks in hopes of
raising her grade-point average through the exam, she said.
Moreover, minor differences in grade averages can ``make the
difference between a $26,000 job and a $40,000 job,'' Brodie said.
</TEXT>
