<2ND_LINE>AM-Filibuster, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0671,890</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Weary Senators End 53-Hour Filibuster</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: Top 6 grafs new with end of filibuster; picks up 3rd pvs,
bgng: Give us; editing in 11th pvs, bgng: Senate Majority</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT M. ANDREWS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A weary Senate ended 53 hours of continuous
and sometimes cantankerous debate over campaign finance Thursday,
leaving Democrats no closer to victory than when the filibuster
began Tuesday.
   By agreement between majority Democrats and stubborn
Republicans, the talking stopped about 7 p.m., setting up a Friday
vote on a Democratic cloture motion to force a vote on their
campaign legislation.
   Democrats have the votes to pass the bill, but they had
virtually no hope of mustering the 60 needed to win Friday's
cloture roll call. The expected loss could scuttle the divisive
issue for the 100th Congress.
   As the filibuster wound down, Majority Leader Robert Byrd,
D-W.Va., made a final pitch for voluntary spending limits to
counter the escalating cost of getting elected, with increasing
amounts of money coming from special-interest political action
committees.
   ``The Senate should not be owned by an aristocracy of money,''
Byrd said. ``Campaign reform gives the little guy an equal share.
... This business of the golden handshake _ nobody likes it.
Senators don't want to spend all their time going from fundraiser
to fundraiser with their hand out begging for money.''
   Another advocate of spending limits, Sen. David Boren, D-Okla.,
conceded that ``negotiations have fallen apart'' because of GOP
opposition to proposed voluntary spending limits on Senate
campaigns.
   ``Give us a chance!'' Boren shouted, urging his Republican foes
to join in shutting off debate and allowing a floor vote on the
campaign finance measure, which Democrats have the votes to win.
   Boren promised that if GOP senators switched sides and provided
the winning margin to invoke cloture, the Democratic bill would be
open to all ``legitimate, relevant'' amendments the Republicans
might propose to reach a compromise.
   But GOP senators made clear their fears that the spending limits
proposal disguises an attempt to reinforce the Democrats' election
advantage in large, heavily Democratic states and to perpetuate
their majority control of the Senate.
   Sen. Warren Rudman, R-N.H., called it the ``incumbent protection
act'' and said it would work against election challengers with
little name recognition or financial support.
   ``Everyone in politics knows that with these (spending) limits,
what we absolutely say to most challengers is, `you've had it,'''
Rudman said.
   ``We've heard a lot of accusations on this floor that this bill
is designed to end the Republican Party,'' Rudman said. ``I don't
believe that ... but to many of us on this side of the aisle it
kind of feels that way.''
   The Senate will vote at 10 a.m. Friday on whether to invoke
cloture, or halt further debate on the bill.
   The measure has 52 co-sponsors, more than the majority of 51
senators necessary for passage, but Democratic strategists say they
are still short of the 60 votes required to invoke cloture and
proceed to a floor vote on the bill itself.
   Byrd lost a record seven cloture votes on the bill last year,
and the lack of any significant weakening in GOP determination to
block the measure made it likely that Byrd would lose again Friday
morning.
   He hasn't said what would happen to the bill after the expected
cloture defeat, but Democratic aides said privately that it would
be shelved.
   Byrd, who once threatened to continue round-the-clock
filibustering through next week, relented Wednesday night and
announced agreement with the GOP leadership to end the talkathon
late Thursday afternoon.
   Byrd spokeswoman Linda Peek denied that the agreement
represented a Democratic defeat. ``The defeat is for the
Republicans who are consistently against the campaign spending
limits and are afraid to vote on the bill,'' she said.
   The measure calls for voluntary ceilings on Senate campaign
spending that range from $950,000 to $5.5 million, depending on a
state's population. Participating candidates would be eligible for
Treasury funds if their opponents exceed the limits or if
independent groups spend large amounts against a candidate
observing the restriction.
   The bill also would prohibit a participating candidate from
receiving more than 20 percent of campaign funds from
special-interest political action committees. In 1986, more than
200 House and Senate candidates _ most of them incumbents _
received more than half their campaign money from PACs.
   Republicans argued that spiraling campaign costs, rather than
spending, should be the primary issue.
   Sen. Ted Stevens, R-Alaska, said the only compromise he would
accept would be to allow candidates in individual states to agree
on their own spending limts. Rudman argued for reallocating
contributions under a formula that would allow 50 percent to come
from individuals, 30 percent from the political parties and 20
percent from PACs.
   The debate Thursday was much calmer than the day before, when
Republicans angrily denounced Byrd's successful motion to have the
Senate sergeant-at-arms, Henry K. Giugni, arrest absentee
Republicans and force them to return to the chamber.
   Under Giugni's direction, armed plainclothes Capitol police
broke into the locked offices of Sen. Bob Packwood, R-Ore., and
carried him feet-first onto the Senate floor. Packwood's arrival
provided the 51st senator necessary to constitute a quorum or
majority of senators on the floor.
   Byrd hoped to embarrass the Republicans by focusing attention on
their stalling tactics, and without a quorum to keep the filibuster
alive, the Senate would have been forced to adjourn.
   Before he arrested Packwood, Giugni reportedly approached Sen.
Lowell P. Weicker Jr., R-Conn., in the Russell Senate Office
Building. But Weicker, a large man known for his hot temper,
refused to submit and Giugni left without a protest.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
