<1ST_LINE>r a AM-AIDSDoctor     02-25 0415</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-AIDS Doctor,0428</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Signs Decree Ensuring Hospital Duties For Doctor With AIDS</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED WHITE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A doctor with AIDS once ordered to stay away from
patients at Cook County Hospital was guaranteed full medical duties
under an agreement approved Wednesday by a federal judge.
   The consent decree signed by U.S. District Judge John A.
Nordberg ensures that the neurologist will be able to examine
patients, draw blood, perform spinal taps and handle other
procedures included in his speciality.
   The Cook County Board restored most of those duties last
September after the doctor filed a lawsuit, but Nordberg had
suggested the board could again reverse itself and asked for a
formal agreement between the doctor and hospital.
   A year ago, the board, which governs the hospital, barred any
contact between patients and the doctor.
   In July, the board said the doctor could see patients, but could
not puncture the skin or come in contact with body fluids of
patients.
   The American Civil Liberties Union, acting on behalf of the
doctor, filed a lawsuit a month later seeking the return of full
medical responsibilities for him.
   ``We're all gratified that the Cook County Hospital has agreed
to follow medical evidence that a doctor with AIDS can continue to
practice,'' said ACLU attorney Ben Wolf of the agreement worked out
between the ACLU, the hospital and the board.
   ``He will follow Centers for Disease Control guidelines, which
require gloves when certain procedures are performed,'' Wolf said.
``He has even agreed to wear double gloves in certain instances.''
   Wolf said complications from AIDS have caused the doctor to miss
some days of work.
   ``When his health permits, he's practicing. He's had some tough
times,'' the attorney said.
   A spokeswoman for the hospital, Wanda Robertson, forwarded all
calls to hospital Director Terrence M. Hansen, who did not return
messages requesting comment.
   Under the decree, the doctor is not required to tell patients he
has AIDS, Wolf said.
   The decree said the doctor would not perform muscle biopsies or
cerebral work, but not because he has the fatal disease.
Neurologists have not handled those procedures in years, Wolf said.
   AIDS, or acquired immune deficiency syndrome, destroys the
body's defenses against disease, leaving a person prey to
life-threatening infections and certain cancers.
   The virus that causes the incurable and fatal disease is
believed to be passed mainly through sexual intercourse, shared
hypodermic needles and from infected mothers to their infants
before or during birth.
</TEXT>
