<1ST_LINE>r w AM-NASA-Fletcher     02-25 0306</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-NASA-Fletcher,300</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NASA Chief Says Civil Space Important To Continued U.S. Leadership</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL RECER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   NASA chief James Fletcher said Wednesday that
the civil space program is the key to questions ``about where this
civilization is going'' and should not be allowed to suffer from
the shortsightedness of ``naysayers.''
   ``We need to adopt a rigorous space agenda beyond the 1990s and
stick to it,'' Fletcher said in a speech before the National Space
Club.
   He said American technological leadership will ride on the
consistent and longterm national support for the space policy
recently announced by President Reagan.
   ``The stakes are very high,'' Fletcher said. ``The Soviets have
let it be known that they are in space to stay. .... Leadership (in
space) is not just who is ahead, but is a sustained and consistent
effort toward goals over a long period of time.''
   He said Reagan's space policy affirms the nation's commitment to
the space station and to human exploration beyond Earth orbit, such
as to Mars. The policy is supported in the president's budget
presented last week to Congress.
   ``The program presented to Congress is the right policy at the
right time,'' Fletcher said. ``We now need to rally national
support to it through the various congressional hurdles.''
   ``The civil space program is key to the much larger questions
about where this civilization is going,'' he said. ``We can't let
the program founder through shortsightedness.''
   The NASA administrator cautioned that some oppose the space
program and that public support is needed to overcome these
objections.
   ``It's surprising how many naysayers there are in and out of
Congress,'' he said. ``We have to guard against the naysayers.''
   The National Space Club is an organization of industrial,
military, congressional and governmental supporters of the U.S.
efforts in space and rocketry.
</TEXT>
