<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Soviet-Armenia 1stLd-Writethru a0746 02-25 0793</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Armenia, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0746,0815</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tanks, Troops Brought In As Armenians Demonstrate; Deaths Rumored</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 5th pvs: `The demonstrators ...' to DELETE extraneous
word `disputed,' SUBS 6th graf pvs: `A member ... to INSERT word
`non-voting</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Armenians demanding annexation of part of a
neighboring republic massed by the thousands in two cities
Thursday, and Red Army troops and tanks were sent into one area as
a show of force, witnesses said.
   A senior official was quoted as saying there were ``human
victims'' of the unrest.
   Demonstrations in the Armenian capital of Yerevan appeared to be
the largest unsanctioned gatherings in Soviet history, according to
eyewitness accounts. Some witnesses said more than 1 million people
participated in protests and strikes. There was no official
estimate of the numbers.
   The demonstrators were demanding that the Nagorno-Karabakh
region, now part of the republic of Azerbaidzhan, be annexed to
Armenia.
   In addition to the territorial dispute involving the
1,760-square-mile autonomous region in the Caucusus Mountains, the
people are divided by religion. Armenians are predominantly
Christians, and most Azeris, the dominant ethnic group in
Azerbaidzhan, are Shiite Moslem.
   A non-voting member of the ruling Politburo, Vladimir I.
Dolgikh, said in a television broadcast Wednesday night from
Yerevan that there were ``human victims'' of the unrest, according
to an Armenian telephone operator in Yerevan.
   The operator said Dolgikh did not provide details.
   An Armenian nationalist activist said he heard rumors that
Azeris had stoned a bus in Nagorno-Karabakh, killing an
undetermined number of Armenians. The activist, Mofses Gorgisyan,
said he also heard that Azeris set fire to a school, resulting in
other deaths.
   In Glendale, Calif., Apo Boghigian, editor of the Armenian
newspaper Asbarez, said he spoke by telephone Wednesday to Hovig
Vassilian, a newspaper editor in Yerevan. Boghigian said Vassilian
described the demonstrators in Yerevan as ``very peaceful'' but
said clashes elsewhere had resulted in deaths.
   Four victims were to be buried Thursday in Askeran, an Armenian
village of about 1,000 people, Boghigian said.
   In Nagorno-Karabakh's main city, Sepanakert, about 120,000
people have demonstrated daily since Feb. 13, said one resident.
   The 17-year-old student, interviewed in a Moscow airport after
arriving from Armenia, said some Armenians had been killed by
Azeris in the region, but she had no details.
   The official Tass news agency said a deputy prosecutor from the
central government was sent to Azerbaidzhan, indicating serious
concern over the unrest.
   Tass quoted the prosecutor, Alexander Katusev, as saying: ``All
sorts of rumors and inventions that are being circulated mostly
outside of the Nagorno-Karabakh Autnomous Region and for which
gullible people often fall are groundless.''
   He acknowledged, however, that crimes were committed and
promised to investigate.
   There was no way to verify the reports independently because the
government barred foreign reporters from traveling to the area.
   Gorgisyan, interviewed by telephone, estimated there were more
than 1 million demonstrators in Yerevan. A telephone operator said
that figure seemed accurate.
   Soldiers arrived Thursday morning and took up discreet positions
in downtown Yerevan, particularly around key government buildings,
Gorgisyan said. They deployed camouflaged trucks downtown and
stationed tanks in outlying areas, said Gorgisyan, a 26-year-old
member of an underground group called the Alliance for National
Determination.
   The soldiers did not try to stop the demonstration, and
Gorgisyan said the protesters were trying not to provoke the troops.
   ``We're trying not to break any laws. The demonstration is very
well organized and orderly,'' he said.
   He said businesses and schools were closed in the city and in
many other parts of the Armenian republic, the smallest of the
Soviet Union's 15 republics and home to 3.4 million Soviets.
   In Nagorno-Karabakh, the student said she saw a large crowd of
demonstrators Thursday in Lenin Square in Stepanakert.
   ``Practically the whole population is there. They've come from
all the villages,'' said the student, who spoke on the condition of
anonymity.
   The protests were continuing around the clock. ``No one's
sleeping. No one is going to work. The only stores open are
groceries,'' she said.
   An official at the Armenian representational offices in Moscow
in charge of internal matters, Rudolf Khatchyanov, confirmed a
major demonstration by Armenians was going on. He said to call
authorities in Yerevan for more details, but telephone calls to
police in Yerevan did not go through.
   The Communist Party's national Central Committee this month
decided Nagorno-Karabakh should remain part of Azerbaidzhan. Radio
Moscow said Armenian authorities planned to ask the Central
Committee to reconsider its position.
   The demonstrations in the region began after the party's
decision was announced, Ayrikyan said.
   Tass announced Wednesday night that an Armenian, Genrikh
Pogosyan, had been named party leader in the disputed region. He
replaced Boris Kevorkov, who also is Armenian.
</TEXT>
