<1ST_LINE>u a AM-HeadRemoved     02-25 0309</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Head Removed,0318</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Possible Charges in Cryonics Case A Month Away</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RIVERSIDE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prosecutors said Thursday it may take
up to a month to decide whether to file charges in the death of a
woman whose head was cut off and frozen in hopes of bringing her
back to life someday in a new body.
   The Riverside County Coroner's Office this week ruled the death
of 83-year-old Dora Kent a homicide caused by a lethal dose of
barbiturates. She died in December at the Alcor Life Extension
Foundation cryonics laboratory.
   Assistant District Attorney Jay Thompson Hanks said the decision
to bring charges could take up to a month ``only because there are
other questions to be asked and answered, and other pieces of
evidence we want tested or examined.''
   Thompson said ``a wide range of charges'' is being contemplated.
Those under investigation include ``everyone associated with the
death,'' he said.
   Mrs. Kent's son, Saul Kent, 48, is a supporter of the cryonics
movement, which freezes bodies or heads in the belief that science
will advance to the point where they can be brought back to life.
   On Dec. 9, Mrs. Kent's physician determined she was gravely ill.
Her son then removed her from a Riverside nursing home and brought
her to Alcor.
   Kent says his mother was maintained there briefly on a
respirator before dying Dec. 11. Her head was surgically removed.
   The coroner's office investigated because no doctor was present
when Mrs. Kent died.
   The coroner asked to examine the head, but Kent has refused to
give it location. A judge blocked the coroner from disturbing any
of the frozen remains at Alcor.
   Mrs. Kent's son said barbiturates are used after death to slow
brain damage caused by lack of oxygen. But the coroner's
investigation concluded that Mrs. Kent was alive when drugs were
administered.
</TEXT>
