<FILEID>AP-NR-02-25-88 2013EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Filibuster-Analysis 1stLd-Writethru a0735 02-25 0679</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Filibuster-Analysis, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0735,630</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Byrd Wanted a Show _ and He Got It With GOP Filibuster</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: SUBS 16th graf, bgng: After vowing, to show filibuster ended</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Filibuster Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID GOELLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When Majority Leader Robert Byrd forced the
Senate into its night-and-day campaign spending filibuster on
Tuesday, he said he wanted to expose Republican stalling tactics to
the American public.
   The public got a show, but it was not quite the one the West
Virginia Democrat was looking for.
   Overshadowing the lesson in how a Senate minority can use the
debate rules to thwart the will of the majority was a late-night
cops-and-robbers show produced by the Democrats.
   The climax came early Wednesday when a plainclothes police posse
led by Sergeant-at-Arms Henry Giugni, acting on orders from
Democrats, pushed through the office door of Sen. Bob Packwood,
R-Ore., arrested him and carried him feet first into the Senate
chamber.
   Packwood's commanded performance gave Byrd the quorum he needed
to keep the filibuster going. It also gave angry Republicans a
rallying point to shift the focus away from their refusal to let
the Senate vote on a Democratic bill with 52 co-sponsors from the
100-member chamber.
   ``Illegal, unlawful, null and void,'' snarled Arlen Specter,
R-Pa.
   The former Philadelphia district attorney said Packwood's
apprehension ``really constituted false arrest of a U.S. senator.
... There is a sense that the Senate is falling apart, that the
Senate is disintegrating.''
   Specter complained that his colleague was treated like a
``common criminal,'' subjected to police-state measures appropriate
to ``Nazi Germany and communist Russia.''
   ``Banana republic,'' snapped Orrin Hatch, R-Utah. ``The tyranny
of the majority,'' said acting minority leader Alan Simpson, R-Wyo.
``Demeaning and humiliating,'' was the verdict of Malcolm Wallop,
R-Wyo.
   Democrats responded that Packwood _ and other absent Republicans
who escaped the posse's clutches _ had it coming.
   After all, they said, Democrats were only forcing the GOP to do
something that voters sent them to Washington to do: answer the
bell and vote.
   ``In the span of 45 minutes, the entire Republican Party in the
United States Senate, with the exception of one, the designated
(floor) leader, vanished into the night,'' said Sen. John Kerry,
D-Mass.
   Like most filibusters, this one was a game of chicken. Which
side would cave in? Would the Senate compromise over the central
question of setting spending limits for Senate races?
   Democrats insist that limits are crucial to any legislation to
curb the escalating cost of getting elected.
   But Republican leaders held fast that limits were not negotiable.
   After vowing to keep the Senate in continuous session at least
through the end of next week, Byrd agreed late Wednesday to bring
the filibuster to a close at 5 p.m. Thursday, get a night's sleep
and vote Friday on a Democratic motion to shut off debate and bring
the bill to a vote. It finally ended at 7 p.m., two hours past the
original target.
   Byrd will probably lose that cloture vote, just as he lost a
record seven cloture votes last year, never getting closer than 55
of the 60 votes needed to end the debate that has consumed 30 days
since last June.
   Republicans, outnumbered 54 to 46, have made opposition to
spending limits a party issue. So far, only three GOP senators have
broken ranks and supported cloture: bill co-sponsors Robert
Stafford of Vermont and John Chafee of Rhode Island and non-sponsor
Nancy Landon Kassebaum of Kansas.
   One key to the eventual outcome is a handful of other
Republicans who are known to support some form of spending limits
but who thus far have stayed loyal to their party's line.
   Democrats had hoped to pick up support for cloture before they
had to concede defeat and pull the bill from the floor. The
necessary crossovers never materialized, leaving campaign finance a
very sick, if not dead, issue for the 100th Congress.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   David Goeller has been covering Capitol Hill
campaign finance issues for The Associated Press since 1983.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
