<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Noriega-Drugs     02-25 0534</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Noriega-Drugs,0551</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Prosecutor Says Move To Oust Noriega Gutsy; No Move To Drop
Charges</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILL LESTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   If Panamanian strongman Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega
left Panama because of attempts to oust him from power, ``we would
attempt to extradite him like any other dope dealer,'' a federal
prosecutor said Thursday.
   ``There is no consideration whatsoever to dropping this
indictment,'' said Richard Gregorie, chief assistant U.S. attorney
in Florida's southern district. ``I have not been asked by anybody
to do that.''
   Noriega was indicted in Miami with 15 others Feb. 4 on charges
of taking at least $4.6 million to protect shipments of Colombian
cocaine, launder money, supply drug laboratories and shield drug
kingpins. Also charged were Medellin drug cartel leader Pablo
Escobar Gaviria and a top Noriega aide, Capt. Luis del Cid.
   Gregorie, the lead prosecutor in the Noriega drug case, said
Panamanian President Eric Arturo Delvalle made a ``pretty gutsy
move'' Thursday in ordering Noriega out of his post and named a
replacement.
   ``Assuming he does step down, he's going to be like any other
citizen,'' Gregorie said, ``and I would assume there might be a
great likelihood that he would leave the country and go somewhere
where we'd have a chance of getting him.''
   In Tampa, a grand jury Feb. 5 indicted Noriega and Panamanian
businessman Enrique Pretelt on marijuana conspiracy and importation
charges.
   A 1904 treaty between the United States and Panama does not
oblige either state to extradite its own citizens.
   The indictment alleged that Noriega allied himself with the
Medellin cartel and once enlisted the help of Cuban leader Fidel
Castro to mediate a dispute with the cartel over drug money.
   Castro said in an interview with NBC News aired Thursday that
Jose Blandon, former Panamanian consul general in New York, lied
about Castro's role as a mediator for Noriega. Castro was named in
the indictment, but not charged.
   U.S. Attorney Leon Kellner charged at the time of the indictment
that Noriega used his position of power in Panama to ``sell the
country of Panama to drug traffickers.''
   If Noriega is ever brought to trial and convicted of all
charges, he could face up to 145 years in prison and fines of more
than $1.1 million, prosecutors say.
   A defendant in the Miami indictment, Brian Alden Davidow, 26, of
Miami surrendered to authorities and pleaded innocent a week ago.
   Ambler Moss, former U.S. ambassador to Panama, said Thursday
that Delvalle's move was unlikely to bring Noriega to trial.
   ``It's highly unusual because the military in Panama has
dominated politics there for a very long time,'' said Moss,
ambassasor from 1978 to 1982. ``It's very unusual that he would
even dare try to separate the head of the armed forces from his
powers.
   ``It's a very courageous act, although we don't know whether
some deal was worked out in advance,'' he said. ``I doubt this
would ever result in his standing trial in the United States.''
   Gregorie held a glimmer of hope. ``If Mr. Noriega chooses to
come here tomorrow morning to be arraigned, he will receive
discovery immediately,'' he said, ``and we will be prepared to go
to trial in 60 days.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
