<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Khrushchev     02-25 0530</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Khrushchev,0548</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Writer Praises Former Soviet Leader in Major Reassessment</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In a major reassessment of Nikita Khrushchev, a
prominent writer has said the former Soviet leader deserves praise
for ending Stalin's cult of personality and introducing economic
reforms.
   The article was the most wide-ranging appraisal of Khrushchev in
the official media to date.
   Fedor Burlatsky said Khrushchev should be praised for putting an
end to the cult of personality that surrounded his predecessor,
Josef Stalin, and for improving the economy and bringing modern
technology to the country.
   Burlatsky also believes, however, that Khrushchev did a bad job
of managing the vast Soviet bureaucracy and was not completely
candid about the nation's problems.
   ``Now that we are guided by the experience of glasnost, we can
see clearly how little was done to inform people about the past,
about real problems, about planned decisions,'' Burlatsky wrote in
an article published Wednesday in the Literary Gazette newspaper.
   Khruschev ruled in 1953-1964 and declared that the Soviet Union
would bury the West, but he was later removed from the leadership
in disgrace.
   Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev has encouraged a review of
history in his campaign for ``glasnost,'' or openness in some
matters.
   Numerous articles have appeared about Stalin and his excesses
but Burlatsky is the first to take a detailed look at Khrushchev.
The journalist and playwright, who was an aide to Khrushchev, said
the former leader's name was taboo for nearly 20 years until
Gorbachev mentioned him Nov. 2.
   ``A wind of change swept the country, the people's spirits rose,
they took heart, became bolder and more confident,'' Gorbachev
said, and praised Khrushchev for ridding the country of Stalin's
cult of personality.
   Burlatsky, 61, picked up that theme in his full-page article.
   ``The main significance Khrushchev gave to the ideological side
of matters was ... unmasking the cult of personality, to speak out
the truth about the crimes of the 30s and other periods,'' he wrote.
   He praised Khrushchev for such technological achievements as
putting the first man in space and reviving Soviet agriculture.
   Khrushchev was not candid in revealing his actions under Stalin,
however, because ``many in the party knew about the role that he
played in persecuting'' people, Burlatsky wrote.
   He also faulted Khrushchev for using ``traditional
administrative and even bureaucratic methods'' that ruined what
began as bold reforms in agriculture and the overall economy.
   Khrushchev was ousted from the leadership in October 1964 by a
``strange symbiosis of political forces'' ranging from
conservatives and Stalinists to reform-minded officials, Burlatsky
said.
   After the fall, Khrushchev sank into obscurity. He died in 1971
and the government of Leonid I. Brezhnev ordered that he be buried
in Moscow's Novodevichy Cemetery, second in importance to the
Kremlin wall.
   Rumors have been circulating that his remains might be moved to
the Kremlin, where the nation's other top leaders are buried.
   In a telephone conversation from his newspaper office Thursday
night, Burlatsky said he had not heard any proposals for moving the
body.
   ``Maybe some informal group is talking about it, but it's
certainly not a firm proposal among party members,'' said
Burlatsky, who is a member of the Communist Party.
</TEXT>
