<2ND_LINE>AM-GNP, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0731,800</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Economy Expands At 4.5 Percent Rate In Fourth Quarter</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: SUBS 10th graf pvs bgng, `Prsident Reagan,' to CORRECT day of
news conference to Wednesday; PICKS UP 11th graf pvs bgng, `If
anyone'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN CRUTSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. economy expanded at a 4.5 percent
annual rate from October through December, the fastest pace in
almost two years, the government reported Thursday.
   The growth in the gross national product, the broadest measure
of the economy's health, was revised up from an original estimate
of 4.2 percent made a month ago.
   The Reagan administration said the growth rate showed the
economic recovery, now in its sixth year, a record for peacetime,
was suffering no ill effects from the October stock market
collapse. However, private economists said they were still
concerned about the lopsided nature of the growth.
   The rapid expansion in the fourth quarter occured without a
pickup in inflation. A price index tied to the GNP rose at an
annual rate of 3.7 percent from October through December, little
changed from a 3.4 percent increase in the third quarter.
   Three-fourths of the growth last quarter came from a buildup of
business inventories which was occurring at the same time that
consumer spending was plunging 3.1 percent, the biggest spending
drop in more than seven years.
   The last such sharp drop in consumer spending occurred in 1980
during the brief recession that year which helped doom President
Jimmy Carter's re-election bid.
   Many economists believe that growth will slow substantially in
the first half of this presidential election year, but in what
could be good news for Republican chances to hold onto the White
House, they are not forecasting an outright recession.
   Some analysts said the revisions made in the new GNP report made
them more confident that a recession can be avoided.
   ``As we move into 1988, there has to be a slowdown to work off
excessive retail inventories, but it will be a pause and not a
recession,'' said Allen Sinai, chief economiXq
</TEXT>
<HEAD>_^?4</HEAD>
<HEAD>o^Lhey were</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   released, hinted at his press conference Wednesday night
that the figure would be a good one and he attacked Democratic
presidential candidates for misrepresenting his administration's
economic achievements.
   ``If anyone listened for more than 15 minutes to their
candidates, you would decide that we're burdened by inflation, high
interest rates and unemployment, when at the moment none of those
things are true,'' Reagan said.
   Analysts said they were encouraged by the new GNP report because
it showed that consumer spending, while falling sharply, was not as
weak as previously believed. The report also increased the estimate
of business investment spending, another area of expected strength
in the new year.
   ``The economy is better than most people think. Consumers are
not fizzling out,'' Sinai said.
   On the basis of the revised GNP figures, Sinai said he had
boosted his estimate of growth in the current quarter to between 1
percent and 2 percent, up from an earlier prediction that growth
could be as low as 0.5 percent in the first three months of this
year.
   James Cochran, an economist with Texas Commerce Bancshares of
Houston, said that the new GNP report ``confirms that we will have
positive growth in the first quarter. It won't be fantastic, but it
will be positive.''
   Some economists had been so concerned that the huge buildup in
inventories would force widespread factory layoffs, that they were
predicting possibly one quarter of negative GNP growth. A
traditional recession is defined as two consecutive quarters in
which the GNP declines.
   The 4.5 percent increase in economic growth followed a gain of
4.3 percent in the third quarter and was the fastest advance since
a 5.4 percent rise in the first quarter of 1986.
   The fourth-quarter gain boosted growth for the year to 3.9
percent, when measured from the end of 1986, up slightly from the
3.8 percent estimate made a month ago. Growth when all four
quarters of the year are averaged together showed a 2.9 percent
increase in 1987, the same as 1986.
   The Reagan administration is forecasting that growth this year
will slow to a rate of 2.4 percent. Many private economists believe
even this scaled-down figure is too optimistic given the huge
overhang of inventories that will slow production in the early part
of the year.
   The administration believes the country will get half of its
growth this year from an improving trade deficit as American
manufacturers continue to benefit from the decline in the value of
the dollar.
   That trend was evident in the fourth quarter as the country's
trade deficit, after adjusting for inflation, shrank by $2 billion
as exports shot up by 15.1 percent, outpacing a 9.7 percent rise in
imports.
   The various changes added $42 billion to the total GNP in the
fourth quarter, leaving it at an inflation-adjusted $3.88 trillion.
</TEXT>
