<1ST_LINE>u i BC-Panama-Text     02-25 0777</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Panama-Text,0795</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>President Orders Noriega Out of Office</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is the text of President Eric
Arturo Delvalle's nationally broadcast message ordering Gen. Manuel
Antonio Noriega removed from his post as military chief, as
translated from Spanish by The Associated Press:
   ``Panama currently is experiencing one of the most difficult and
dangerous moments of its history. It really is lamentable that
after having achieved in a few years, with international help and
support, success in the struggle for its sovereignty, and after
having begun a transition toward a promised democracy and even more
recently having started its stalled economy, today the country
finds itself virtually at siege economically by external pressures
and tensions, in its international prestige as a nation.
   What has been able to take us to such a terrible crossroads in
such a short time?
   Certainly a dose of unawareness from many, exaggerated ambitions
from some and a great lack of understanding from others have
contributed decisively to placing us in such a severe as well as
critical situation.
   I should confess with honor that in my unchangeable desire to
achieve my goal I have been able to commit some mistakes, but it is
even worse to be a victim as I have been of so many
misunderstandings without allowing that they might change my way of
acting, as I am doing with deep love for my country.
   I must consider with sadness that many of the successes that
have been obtained have been vanishing in the past eight months.
   This has converted my concerns into fruitless yearnings.
   What is certain is that the mistaken positions, the unconsulted
actions and the mistakes committed, now or in the past, have led to
acts of extreme significance, such as those that represent the
noticeable paralysis, the rhythm of social and economic development
that we have experienced since the midway point of last year.
   The pressures and tensions of which we are an object and the
serious accusations of the grand jury of Florida against Noriega,
accusations which have been gathered and spread by the
international press, have damaged the image and prestige of Panama.
   These actions which U.S. officials have taken on the basis that
the country is not moving toward a true democracy and the
accusations against Noriega, are starting to be reflected in an
unfavorable international attitude toward the Panamanian nation
that is financial as well as diplomatic.
   That situation places the republic before a very serious risk in
which the present and future well being of the Panamanian people is
found at risk.
   Facing this enormous responsibility as a leader, several days
ago I decided that I should suggest, and that's what I did, to Gen.
Noriega that he voluntarily step aside from his high command until
the charges that had been raised against him might be investigated,
and that would reflect highly on his own good and the health and
tranquility of the republic.
   I have not had evidence that the healthy purposes that motivated
my suggestion in the sense expressed have had any impact
whatsoever. I decided that it was prudent to wait some days so that
he might have sufficient time to meditate on the seriousness of the
situation to which he is exposing himself and to which he is
submitting the country.
   For all that might be deduced that the accusations against Gen.
Noriega have a political nature, the internal situation of Panama
cannot be ignored. Each day it becomes more complex and dangerous
and there will not be peace nor liberty nor progress in Panama nor
will be be able to perfect or consolidate our democratic system,
unless we overcome the passions that have been unleashed and we
clarify the deeds beyond all doubt.
   To find solutions to the serious crisis that affects
institutional life and economic stability, it is indispensable that
as soon as possible the country might return to the climate of
peace and tranquility.
   The reasons that might take us to fiscal and economic imbalance
and that might push thousands of Panamanians to unemployment,
misery and despair cannot persist.
   The causes for which the international credit agencies and the
international banking community, which always have collaborated
with us, might turn their backs to us, worsening our already
weakened and precarious situation, cannot persist.
   The attitudes and conduct that might justify friendly nations to
adopt positions that isolate our country and reduce the prestige of
our nation cannot persist.
   We cannot persist in incubating our own disaster, whatever might
be the motive, reason or justification that any entity, group or
person might brandish, because nothing or no one comes above the
nation.''
</TEXT>
