<1ST_LINE>u a AM-MotoristSlain     02-25 0414</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Motorist Slain,0428</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mistrial Declared In Highway Patrol Officer's Murder Trial</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DENNIS GEORGATOS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN DIEGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A mistrial was declared Thursday after a jury
deadlocked in the case of a former California Highway Patrol
officer accused of murdering a motorist he had pulled over at an
isolated freeway exit in 1986.
   ``It does not seem to me that any further deliberation is likely
to produce a verdict,'' Superior Court Judge Richard Huffman after
seven days of deliberation in the case against 37-year-old Craig
Peyer of Poway.
   Peyer was accused of strangling Cara Knott, a 20-year-old San
Diego State University student. The 13-year CHP veteran was the
second officer in the agency's 58-year history to be charged with
killing a motorist while on duty.
   Jury forewoman Walnetta Lenhardt said that after three ballots,
jurors deadlocked 7-5 in favor of conviction.
   ``I have always thought he was innocent. It's in God's hands. It
always will be,'' Peyer's wife, Karen, said outside court.
   Steve Casey, a spokesman for the district attorney's office,
said no decision had been made on whether to retry the case against
Peyer.
   ``We're tough. We'll do it for Cara. We're going to see it
through for Cara,'' said a tearful Joyce Knott, the victim's mother.
   Peyer has been free on $1 million bail throughout the trial.
First-degree murder carries a sentence of 25 years to life in
prison.
   Peyer was fired by the Highway Patrol in May after an internal
investigation.
   The prosecution in the trial that began Jan. 19 alleged that
Peyer, patrolling Interstate 15, stopped Knott because of a
defective tail light and forced her to drive down a dark, isolated
offramp.
   Knott's white Volkswagen was found abandoned in a cul-de-sac
near the bottom of an exit, and her body was found at the bottom of
a nearby 65-foot highway bridge.
   Twenty-two women had testified during the trial that Peyer
pulled them over on I-15 and directed them down the same isolated
ramp. State officials closed the ramp for safety reasons soon after
Knott's killing.
   Prosecutors presented blood and fiber evidence that they said
linked Peyer to the victim, as well as two surprise witnesses who
said they saw a CHP unit pull over a light-colored Volkswagen on
I-15 the night Knott was slain.
   The defense argued the blood and fiber evidence was flimsy and
unreliable and accused the two witnesses of lying, noting both had
waited a year before coming forward with their stories.
</TEXT>
