<1ST_LINE>u a AM-CubsLights 2ndLd-Writethru a0873 02-25 0718</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cubs Lights, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0873,0735</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>City Council Approves Lifting Ban On Night Games At Wrigley Field</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 3 grafs after 6th graf pvs, `They may ...,' to UPDATE
with comment from governor's spokesman on effect of vote and Cubs
statement about installation of lights.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ED WHITE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The City Council voted Thursday to lift a ban on
night games at the only major-league ballpark without lights,
signaling a likely end to a 72-year-tradition of daytime-only
baseball at Wrigley Field.
   The vote was 29-19 in favor of lights.
   The Tribune Co., owner of the Chicago Cubs, has threatened to
move the team out of Chicago if lights aren't allowed at the
venerable, ivy-covered ballpark.
   A state law limiting noise at night effectively banned night
games at Wrigley. The law was suspended last year for post-season
nighttime play, and similar action may be needed to allow
regular-season night games, some officials said Thursday.
   Alderman Bobby Rush, chairman of the committee that held
hearings on the city ordinance, said state legislators have agreed
to follow the city in rolling back the ban.
   ``They may have to make some adjustments, but there won't be any
snags,'' he said. ``The Cubs will probably proceed with lights as
soon as weather permits.''
   Jim Bray, a spokesman for Gov. James R. Thompson, said the
effect of the council vote was uncertain.
   ``There's always been a question whether the original
legislation ever would have been able to prevent night games if the
Cubs wanted to and did install lights,'' Bray said.
   The Cubs said after the vote that the club would install a $5
million lighting system that should be ready in four to six months.
   The proposal approved by the council and endorsed by Mayor
Eugene Sawyer would allow eight night games this season and 18 each
of the following years until 2002 at the ballpark.
   At the team's Mesa, Ariz., training camp, pitcher Rick Sutcliffe
said, ``I think the night games will give us a chance to rest up
during the day after coming off long road trips.
   ``A lot of times we don't get home from road trips till 2 or 3
in the morning, and only get about four hours of sleep before
heading back out to the ballpark,'' he said.
   Wrigley Field, a neighborhood landmark since 1914, is bordered
by small apartment houses where residents can sit on the roof and
watch the action for free. Many residents of ``Wrigleyville'' are
vehemently opposed to night games, anticipating rowdy crowds and
parking problems.
   League owners voted earlier Thursday to play the 1990 All-Star
game at Wrigley Field if the city lifts the ban on night games.
   By playing during the day only, club executives say, the team
misses out on lucrative revenue from TV networks interested in
airing evening baseball.
   If the Cubs made the playoffs while the night-game ban was in
force, the team probably would have to play elsewhere, they say,
because playoff games are scheduled to accommodate network requests
for prime-time exposure.
   The Cubs finished last in the National League East last year.
   Opponents say night games in Wrigleyville would mean boisterous
fans pouring out of bars in the wee hours, limited parking for
residents returning from work, and littered lawns and streets.
   ``I have no objection to people having a good time, but they
just don't respect the neighborhood,'' said Dwight Guyer, who can
hear the roar of the crowd from his home a few blocks away. ``I
don't like people urinating in my yard. I don't like to wake up to
trash.''
   The Chicago Tribune, also owned by the Tribune Co., entered the
fray last week with a lively editorial that said aldermen opposed
to lights at Wrigley Field were ``boneheads'' and ``political
lightweights.''
   State Sen. William Marovitz, a Chicago Democrat, said the state
noise law could prevent regular-season night games at Wrigley.
   ``If the noise from Wrigley Field violates the decibel limit, a
resident might file a lawsuit,'' said Marovitz, who represents
Wrigleyville and is against the lights.
   But Rep. John Cullerton, another Chicago Democrat, said City
Council approval clears the way for regular-season night games
without further legislative action.
   ``If we did nothing, they could play night games,'' said
Cullerton, who also represents Wrigleyville.
</TEXT>
