<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Lebanon-Bomb     02-25 0207</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lebanon-Bomb,0215</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bomb Kills Two, Wounds Four in Beirut</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bomb in a taxicab exploded Wednesday
outside the building housing the Greek Embassy in west Beirut,
killing a street vendor and a passenger in the car, police said.
   The cab driver and three passers-by were wounded when the bomb,
hidden in the trunk of the moving taxi, blew up.
   Police said the bomb exploded at 2:40 p.m. in front of the Sadat
Tower, a building that also houses offices of the embassies of
Finland and Mexico.
   Police said there was nobody at the Greek Embassy at the time of
the blast. No arrests were made.
   The Finnish and Mexican missions have been closed since April
1986, when most foreigners left Moslem west Beirut after a wave of
assassinations and kidnappings involving foreign nationals.
   The bomb turned the white Mercedes taxi into a pile of twisted
metal. No group claimed responsibility for the bombing.
   Syrian troops, who were deployed in west Beirut to restore
security, blocked off the site for half an hour after the explosion.
   More than 100,000 people have been killed since Lebanon's civil
war began in April 1975. Druse, Shiite Moslem and Christian
militias have done most of the fighting.
</TEXT>
