<1ST_LINE>r w AM-BRF--WorldSugar     02-25 0136</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--World Sugar,130</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Work Sugar Forecast Revised Upward</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   World production of sugar in 1987-88 has been
revised upward to an estimated 101.9 million metric tons, a 1
percent increase from the previous forecast of 100.8 million tons
made last October, the Agriculture Department said Wednesday.
   The department's Foreign Agricultural Service said the revision
``reflects changes in several key countries'' since the October
estimate.
   Regionally, the new figures showed increases in raw sugar
production for North America, 10.92 million tons, compared with
10.71 million forecast in October; the European Economic Community,
13.85 million tons, compared with 13.43 million; and the Soviet
Union, 9 million tons, compared with 8.3 million.
   Despite the larger estimate, this season's global sugar
production still is expected to trail the 102.8 million tons
produced in 1986-87, the agency reported.
</TEXT>
