<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Elderly-Shooting     02-25 0468</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Elderly-Shooting,0482</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Man Opens Fire at Home for Elderly; Five Injured</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 9 grafs to UPDATE with gunman's age, description
of weapons, date of his eviction, comment from administrator of his
current home. Picks up 9th graf pvs, `Several women ...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SCOTT ROTHSCHILD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ARLINGTON, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A elderly man with two rifles burst into
a board meeting at a retirement home where he once lived and opened
fire Thursday, wounding four people and sending a fifth into heart
failure, authorities said.
   The 79-year-old gunman fled the meeting room at the Masonic Home
for the Aged with one rifle tied around his neck with twine but
surrendered moments later, said police spokesman Dee Anderson.
   The four people struck by gunfire suffered minor wounds, she
said. However, Willie Joe Wright, 67, who suffered the heart
attack, was in critical condition at Arlington Memorial Hospital,
said spokeswoman Tenya Woods.
   ``Apparently, they had a board meeting and one former resident,
who was apparently disgruntled, walked into the board room and
started shooting'' at the 15 to 16 people there, Anderson said.
   The assailant, whose identity was not released, had lived at the
home for about three years before being evicted in September for
breaking rules, Anderson said. He knew when the monthly board
meeting was to be held, she said.
   When officers confronted the man in a kitchen in the building,
he calmly surrendered and gave them his rifle. Both weapons were
.22-caliber semiautomatic rifles, Anderson said.
   ``He did not give any information to police,'' Anderson said.
   Officials at the man's current residence, the Arlington Villa
retirement home, said they were shocked to hear of the shooting.
``He is a good resident, very congenial and sociable,'' said
administrator Gennie Pace.
   Officials of the Masonic home refused to comment on the 11 a.m.
shooting and put the buildings and grounds of the home off limits
to visitors.
   Several women gathered outside the home after hearing of the
shooting to make sure their relatives, residents of the home, were
safe. One woman, who declined to be identified, said her mother had
lived there for the past 13 years and called it ``a wonderful
place.''
   Of the shooting victims, Eldon Brooks, 54, was in fair condition
with a gunshot wound to the left thigh, Ms. Woods said, while Frank
Smith, 77, was in good condition with a gunshot wound in his back.
   John Thompson, 49, was in fair condition with a gunshot wound to
his right arm and was later transferred to Harris Methodist
Hospital in Fort Worth.
   Dorothy Heath, 67, received a gunshot wound to her thigh and
complained of chest pains. She was in fair condition.
   An employee at the retirement home who would not give her name
identified Ms. Heath as the home's administrator.
</TEXT>
