<HEAD>State Department Suggests Travel to Rio Be Deferred</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Department on Wednesday suggested
that Americans planning trips to Rio de Janeiro consider postponing
their travel because of torrential rains and flooding that have
killed 300 people and left thousands homeless.
   No formal travel advisory was announced, but Ruth van Heuven, a
department spokeswoman, said people who called to check on
conditions in the Brazilian resort city were told they ``may wish
to defer their trip until the local situation improves.''
   The department said rains were expected to continue
indefinitely, city services were strained, some areas were without
electricity and water and several tourist areas were inaccessible.
