<FILEID>AP-NR-02-25-88 0750EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-WestiesTrial     02-25 0661</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Westies Trial,0683</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>7 of 8 Convicted in Westies Rackets Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Seven people were convicted Wednesday on federal
racketeering charges for taking part in the violent activities of a
murderous gang known as the Westies, which terrorized Manhattan's
Hell's Kitchen neighborhood for 20 years.
   An eighth defendant was acquitted of all charges as the
five-month trial ended.
   In addition to the racketeering convictions, some of the
defendants, including reputed Westies boss James ``Jimmy'' Coonan,
were found guilty of crimes ranging from attempted murder and
loansharking to drug dealing and tax evasion.
   But the key verdict was the jury's decision that the Westies did
exist, that it constituted a racketeering enterprise and that the
convicted defendants had participated in its activities to further
the gang's criminal goals.
   Defense lawyers had contended that there was no such
organization as the Westies. Even former gang members testifying
for the prosecution said the name ``Westies'' was created by the
police and the news media to describe Irish-American hoodlums on
Manhattan's West Side.
   Prosecutors Mary Lee Warren and David Brodsky had contended the
six men and two women on trial were the violent core of the
Westies, which they said seized control of the neighborhood once
known as Hell's Kitchen and maintained their rule ``with horrible
and ghoulish acts of murder.''
   Witnesses testified that in at least three murders, the victim's
body was cut up and disposed of in what Ms. Warren called ``the
nightmarish signature crime of the Westies.''
   There was also testimony by several witnesses that the Westies
had forged an alliance with the Gambino organized crime family,
said to be the largest and most powerful Mafia group in the country.
   The key prosecution witness, former No. 2 Westie Francis
``Mickey'' Featherstone, said the gang had even shot a union leader
as a favor to reputed Gambino boss John Gotti.
   But the defense attacked the credibility of Featherstone, an
admitted three-time killer, and other informants who testified for
the government in return for leniency.
   Featherstone, who said he had been Coonan's ``right-hand man,''
admitted that he had lied under oath in other cases, had been in
and out of mental institutions, suffered delusions and was a former
abuser of alcohol and drugs.
   The racketeering charges alleged eight murders, four murder
conspiracies and three attempted murders. To be convicted of
racketeering, each defendant had to be found to have committed at
least two of the 28 racketeering acts cited.
   The verdict came on the eighth day of jury deliberations.
   Coonan, 41, was found guilty of attempted murder, murder
conspiracy, loansharking, extortion and income tax evasion among
other crimes.
   His wife, Edna, 44, was convicted of loansharking and tax
charges.
   In addition, the jury found Coonan participated in most of the
racketeering acts charged against him, including seven murders.
   ``A trial on any single act in this indictment would have
resulted in an acquittal,'' said Coonan's lawyer, Gerald Shargel.
``It's just a matter of the government, piling it all together.
That's the nightmare of RICO (the Racketeer Influenced Corrupt
Organizations Act).''
   As the courtroom deputy, Bernard Wasserman, read out the verdict
against William ``Indian'' Bokun, his father swore audibly.
   ``Don't tell me to shush!'' John Bokun angrily told a marshal.
``That's my son there.''
   The younger Bokun, 30, of Manhattan, who was convicted of drug
dealing as well as racketeering, tried to comfort his weeping,
cursing father.
   ``Don't worry pop, I'm all right,'' Bokun shouted across the
courtroom before being led back to jail.
   Only one defendant, John Halo, was acquitted on all charges.
   In addition to the Coonans, both of Hazlet, N.J. and Bokun, the
others convicted of racketeering and racketeering conspiracy were:
James ``Jimmy Mack'' McElroy, 42; Richard ``Muggsy'' Ritter, 50;
Thomas Collins, 53, and his wife Florence, 52, all of Manhattan.
   Knapp scheduled sentencing for April 18. All defendants face up
to 20 years apiece on both racketeering and racketeering conspiracy.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
