<1ST_LINE>r i AM-China-Hepatitis     02-25 0189</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-China-Hepatitis,0195</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Seven Reported Dead in Shanghai From Hepatitis</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A hepatitis epidemic in Shanghai has killed
seven people, but the number of new cases has dropped considerably,
the pro-Beijing Hong Kong newspaper Ta Kung Pao reported Wednesday.
   It quoted Wang Daomin, director of the Shanghai Public Health
Bureau, as saying health officials verified seven deaths. Previous
reports did not mention deaths.
   The viral disease, commonly spread in food and water, causes
inflammation of the liver, nausea, vomiting and fever.
   Wang also was quoted as saying the number of new cases of
hepatitis A had dropped 80 percent from the height of the epidemic.
   Shanghai officials earlier put the number sickened in the
2-month-old outbreak at 16,000. Western doctors there said the
number could be as high as 40,000. The epidemic was blamed on
contaminated clams harvested from polluted coastal waters.
   China's official English-language newspaper China Daily said
Beijing health authorities launched a city-wide sanitation
inspection.
   In Canton, capital of southern Guangdong province, health
officials warned people to refrain from shaking hands, to wash
their hands when visiting others and to avoid eating river snails.
</TEXT>
