<1ST_LINE>r w AM-CapitalCrimeSpree     02-25 0318</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Capital Crime Spree,300</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>D.C. Police Chief To Arm Civilian Volunteers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD KEIL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   District of Columbia Police Chief Maurice
Turner said Wednesday he intends to arm up to 1,000 civilian
volunteers as part of an effort to fight a crime spree in the
nation's capital.
   Volunteer reserve officers, who currently lecture neighborhood
groups on crime control and help city residents burglar-proof their
homes, will get guns and full police powers, Turner said in a
statement issued by the police department.
   They'll serve in support positions augmenting the city's
3,880-member police force, accompany officers on regular patrols,
and have the power to make arrests, he said.
   Twenty-one members of the 175-member reserve force were selected
for an extensive training program similar to training given
full-time officers. Turner said ultimately he hopes to expand the
reserve corps to 1,000 officers.
   The trained reserve officers will carry a gun while on duty, but
will be required to turn it in the end of their shifts, said
Turner, who originally disclosed his plan in an interview with The
Washington Times.
   The chief's announcement came amid a surge in crime,
particularly drug-related violence. Fifty-two people have been
murdered in Washington so far this year, compared with 33 at this
time last year. Police say nearly three-quarters of the murders are
drug related.
   Turner said earlier this week that about 100 officers working at
desk jobs will return to patrol work after civilians are found to
fill their positions. Last week, Turner said he was replacing
officers' six-shot service revolvers with 9mm semiautomatic pistols
in an effort to counter the increasingly sophisticated weapons
wielded by drug dealers.
   Mayor Marion Barry has said there are enough officers, but
police union officials said 500 more full-time officers are needed.
   Turner did not say when the new program would go into effect, or
where the reserves would be deployed.
</TEXT>
