<2ND_LINE>AM-Racial Assault, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0799,0547</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cuomo: Grand Jury Should Compel Brawley's Cooperation</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 7th graf, `Timothy Gilles ...' with two grafs to UPDATE
with comment from attorney general's office; ADDS one graf with
suspect attempting suicide, in good condition.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BAUDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A grand jury should require Tawana Brawley
and her family to cooperate with authorities investigating the
teen-ager's alleged kidnapping and sexual assault by six white men,
Gov. Mario Cuomo said Wednesday.
   The continued refusal of the girl's lawyers to allow her to
discuss the case with investigators is fostering ``a disrespect for
the process of law,'' the governor said at a news conference.
   Miss Brawley was found wrapped in a plastic garbage bag and
covered with feces, with ``KKK'' and ``nigger'' scrawled on her
body, after being missing for four days last November. She said she
was assaulted by six white men, one of whom flashed a police badge.
   A grand jury will convene Monday in Poughkeepsie to investigate
the case.
   Cuomo said he'll ask state Attorney General Robert Abrams, the
special prosecutor in the case, to ask the grand jury to compel
Miss Brawley and her family to cooperate.
   ``The way the investigation is not proceeding now _ and it's not
proceeding as it should _ is bad for Tawana, is bad for the state,
is bad for the system of justice. And I want to change it,'' Cuomo
said.
   The lawyers for Miss Brawley and her family, C. Vernon Mason and
Alton Maddox Jr., did not return calls to their New York City
offices.
   Nancy Connell, a spokeswoman for Abrams, said that ``we're fully
in agreement with the governor's statement.'' But she would not say
what Abrams will recommend to the grand jury.
   Mason and Maddox have advised Miss Brawley not to cooperate,
have called for Abrams to be removed from the case and for Cuomo to
create a permanent special state prosecutor for racial cases.
   The NAACP lawyer who initially represented Miss Brawley before
being replaced by Mason and Maddox said the two lawyers were using
the girl as a pawn to achieve political aims.
   ``The politicizing of the case in the manner it has been allows
for a lot of speculation and detracts from the genuine sympathy and
outrage this case should have,'' attorney George Hairston told the
Albany Times Union.
   The Rev. Al Sharpton, a Pentecostal minister from Brooklyn who
has also been advising the Brawley family, said that because Abrams
maintains a residence in Dutchess County he has a ``relationship''
with Sheriff Frederick Scoralick. Sharpton said Scoralick was a
``suspect'' in the case.
   On Tuesday, a former worker in the attorney general's print shop
was arrested and charged with stealing and disclosing a transcript
of testimony to a previous grand jury that was investigating the
attack.
   Samuel Evans of Manhattan allegedly took the transcript before
leaving his job Feb. 5. He then gave the transcript to an
unidentified person, who notified authorities.
   On Wednesday, Evans attempted suicide by downing a quart of
rubbing alcohol and other chemicals in his apartment, said New York
City police spokesman Raymond O'Donnell. He was listed in good
condition after having his stomach pumped.
</TEXT>
