<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Nicaragua-Fighting     02-25 0235</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nicaragua-Fighting,0240</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Contras Damage Microwave Tower, Causing Widespread Outages</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Contra rebels damaged a microwave
repeater tower in northern Nicaragua overnight, cutting off
telecommunications with northern Central America and Mexico, the
Defense Ministry said Wednesday.
   The brief defense statement said the tower was at Mesa de las
Lagunas, outside the provincial capital of Esteli, 90 miles north
of the capital of Managua. It did not say how the rebels damaged
the tower or give other details.
   In Guatemala City, Bosco Matamoros, a spokesman for the
U.S.-backed rebels, said the Contras blew up the tower at 1 a.m.
Wednesday.
   ``Nicaragua is isolated,'' he said. The Contras, he said, want
to hinder communications between the country and the rest of
Central America.
   Nicaragua could communicate by microwave with Panama and Costa
Rica but not with Honduras, El Salvador, Guatemala and Mexico.
Satellite communications were not affected.
   The rebels blew up a microwave repeater tower last October at
Laguna de Santa Clara, east of Esteli, and destroyed another one in
November at Las Cuchillas hill in Chontales province, 90 miles east
of Managua. That sabotage also caused widespread outages.
   The rebels have been fighting for more than six years to oust
the leftist Sandinista government in Nicaragua. The Sandinistas
came to power in July 1979 at the end of a revolutionary war that
ended 42 years of rule by the rightist, pro-American Somoza dynasty.
</TEXT>
