<2ND_LINE>AM-Cocaine Traveler,0199</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ticket Agent's Suspicions Lead To Arrest</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LANSING, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An airline ticket agent suspicious about a
man carrying two big suitcases for a three-hour visit to Michigan
tipped off police Wednesday to what turned out to be an $11 million
cocaine bust, authorities said.
   The man, who was arrested after his plane's arrival here, had
bought a round-trip ticket in Los Angeles from the United Airlines
agent, said narcotics Detective Lt. Gene Wriggelsworth.
   ``He paid cash for his tickets,'' Wriggelsworth said. ``He fit
the drug smuggling profile.''
   The detective said 14 kilos, or about 30 pounds of cocaine, were
confiscated, ``the biggest we've ever had.''
   A drug-sniffing dog was ready when the flight landed at Capital
City Airport for the scheduled three-hour visit and singled out two
large suitcases, Wriggelsworth said
   Police then watched as the man claimed the suitcases and met two
people. All three were arrested, and a car and $4,000 in cash were
confiscated with the cocaine.
   The three were being held in the Clinton County jail on
drug-possession charges. Their names were not released.
   The name of the United agent was not immediately available.
