<FILEID>AP-NR-02-25-88 0815EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Canada-Black     02-25 0447</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Canada-Black,0462</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Montreal Policeman Acquitted in Killing of Unarmed Black Teen-Ager</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MONTREAL (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A jury on Wednesday acquitted a police officer
of manslaughter in the shooting death of an unarmed black teen-ager
last year, a case that sparked accusations of racism in the
Montreal police department.
   The Nov. 11 shooting of 19-year-old Anthony Griffin had prompted
three inquiries _ by the Quebec Human Rights Commission, the Quebec
Police Commission and the 4,500-member Montreal police force.
   A black community leader, Ronald Rock, said Wednesday that
blacks will march in the streets following the acquittal of
Constable Allan Gosset, 38, a 16-year veteran of the department.
   Gosset, who said the shooting was accidental, rolled his eyes,
sighed and slumped in his chair when the all-white jury of seven
men and five women handed down the verdict after deliberating 16{
hours. The trial lasted four days.
   Griffin's mother, Gloria Augustus, wept as she left the
courtroom, and exclaimed: ``You want us to trust the justice
system? What kind of a justice system do we have?''
   Rock, executive director of the Black Community Council of
Quebec, said, ``I'm very disappointed. This has set relations with
the Montreal police back 15 years. We're going to have to hit the
streets again.''
   Gosset said he will have to await Police Chief Roland Bourget's
decision on whether he will return to work.
   ``I think I should be reinstated,'' he said.
   Griffin was brought to a police station in a patrol car by
Gosset and his partner last November, according to testimony. He
bolted in the parking lot but obeyed Gosset's shouted order to stop.
   Griffin turned around and Gosset shot him once in the forehead
with his .38-caliber service revolver, testimony showed.
   Gosset said Griffin turned to face him, went into a crouch and
began weaving from side to side. Gosset said he feared Griffin
planned to confront him so he drew his gun to intimidate him and it
went off, although he did not recall cocking it.
   Defense lawyer Serge Menard told the jury it was obvious
Gosset's actions were not motivated by racism, because Griffin was
being detained on the basis of an arrest warrant.
   Crown prosecutor Rene de la Sablonniere said Gosset was
irresponsible and should not have pulled his gun because his life
was not in danger.
   On Wednesday, Griffin's mother told reporters she was ``shocked
and saddened'' by the verdict and promised to pursue the case.
Lawyers for the family said they filed a wrongful-death lawsuit for
$850,000 Tuesday against Gosset, the police department and
Montreal's regional government.
   Most of Canada's estimated 400,000 blacks are West Indian
immigrants. The largest black communities are in Toronto and
Montreal.
</TEXT>
