<HEAD>Takeover Continues At Hamphire College</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: RESTORES dropped AP logo in lead; rewrites throughout to add
further comment from student protest leader, background on Dakin
house, deleting some detail to tighten. No pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN LUMSDEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AMHERST, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leaders of 100 minority students occupying
a Hampshire College building handed the school's president a list
of demands Wednesday and settled in for what they predicted would
be a long siege.
   ``We're a little disappointed. They wouldn't even talk to us,''
said Dean of Students Trey Williams after a morning meeting with
the protesters was cut short.
   ``We felt that they needed to take time to look at the
demands,'' responded Anita Fearman, a student from Los Angeles and
a protest leader. Another meeting was scheduled for Thursday.
   Some 50 black, Hispanic, Asian, Indian and other students, or
nearly half the minority student population at the 1,100-student
private liberal arts college, took over Dakin House on Tuesday to
protest what they described as the administration's indifference to
their longstanding complaints.
   Another 50 minority students from nearby Smith, Amherst, and
Mount Holyoke colleges and the University of Massachusetts joined
the protesters Wednesday, said Ms. Fearman. UMass was the site of a
similar protest that ended last week.
   About 300 sympathizers, most of them white, accompanied the
negotiators to the meeting with administrators Wednesday in a
library building, where the demands were given to President Adele
Simmons.
   The crowd marched through classroom and administration buildings
on the way, chanting, ``Racism has got to go.''
   A protest leader, Penny Predmas, predicted: ``This is going to
take a while.''
   Among the dozen demands of the group, Students of
Underrepresented Cultures, were calls for money for Third World
speakers and publications, the hiring of a racial harassment
officer and the drafting of a racial harassment policy.
   Williams, who is black, said school officials were worried that
students might be seeking attention rather than results by delaying
negotiations.
   ``Usually building takeovers are the last resort,'' he said. ``I
don't know why the students feel they have no other recourse.''
   The takeover followed the six-day occupation of a building at
nearby UMass. That occupation by 125 students ended Feb. 17 with an
agreement to increase minority recruitment at the 25,000-student
campus.
   ``The problems (at Hampshire) are the same, although the sizes
of the minority communities are different,'' said Ms. Fearman.
``There's a general feeling here that we've been more or less
pushed under the rug.''
   Dakin House contains living quarters for two staff members, an
office and meeting space used by minority students. The staff
members are being allowed to use their living quarters during the
occupation.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
