<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Thailand-RiverMan     02-25 0375</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Thailand-River Man,0385</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>American River Man Paddles To Thai Capital</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER ENG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A free-lance writer from Oregon paddled
his teakwood boat into Bangkok Wednesday, the 55th day of his solo
exploration of the effect of rivers on Thailand's history and
culture.
   Two dozen Thais greeted an exhausted and tanned Steve Van Beek,
offering him food and soda as he pulled into a pier near the foot
of the Memorial Bridge.
   Van Beek, 43, of Portland, Ore., said he expected to complete
his nearly 600-mile journey on Saturday, when he is scheduled to
reach the Gulf of Thailand at Samut Prakarn province just southeast
of Bangkok.
   Van Beek paddled his 11{-foot-long boat by day, seeking shelter
with local residents at night and listening to their stories of the
river and its effect on their lives. He sampled what he called a
``whole new experience'' of food, including raw fish with rice,
pig's blood and boiled eel.
   He said the beauty of the countryside and the hospitality of the
Thai people have impressed him.
   ``How many other places could you walk up to someone and say,
`I'm paddling a boat. I need something to eat, a place to stay,
something to eat in the morning,''' he said. ``These people, they
just opened up their entire houses.''
   Water, he said, ``permeates every aspect of life in Thailand. It
is in rites of passage, festivals. Fish and rice are both grown in
water, and they are the principal sources of food here.''
   ``I lived on the edge of the river for 11 years,'' he added. ``I
always wondered where it came from, so I decided to go find out.''
   Van Beek hired a village builder to fashion the flat-bottomed
boat.
   He started his trip in Meaja, about 60 miles north of the
provincial capital of Chiang Mai. He followed the Ping river south
through five provinces, after which it joined the Chao Phraya river.
   Van Beek spent three years in a village in Nepal as a Peace
Corps volunteer before arriving in Thailand in 1969. He worked on
English-language newspapers and magazines before 1977, when he
became a free-lance writer and film maker specializing in
Thailand's art, history and culture.
</TEXT>
