<1ST_LINE>r a AM-SnakebiteHomicide     02-25 0321</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Snakebite Homicide,0334</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Man Found Guilty Of Manslaughter In Snakebite Death of Toddler</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. GEORGE, Utah (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man was convicted of manslaughter
Wednesday in the snakebite-death of a girl around whose shoulder he
had draped a rattlesnake.
   District Judge J. Philip Eves announced the verdict against
Darrell Wessendorf in the non-jury trial.
   Wessendorf, 24, had been charged with second-degree murder in
the death last year of 21-month-old Stevie LuRen Kirkwood of La
Verkin. He had pleaded innocent by reason of insanity.
   The judge said that he found Wessendorf guilty of the lesser
charge because the defendant hadn't been aware of the possible
results of his actions.
   Wessendord, who was renting an upstairs apartment from the
child's mother, Jeri Ann Kirkwood, at the time, testified that he
found the 5-foot rattlesnake on a road and was trying to show the
girl that that it would not hurt her.
   He said he had partially wrapped the snake around the child's
shoulder when Mrs. Kirkwood entered the room and screamed, causing
him to flinch and the snake to bite the child.
   Sentencing was set for April 11. Manslaughter carries a one- to
15-year sentence. Second-degree murder would have brought five
years to life.
   Defense attorney J. MacArthur Wright had claimed that only 0.2
percent of those bitten by rattlesnakes die and called on the judge
to ``make a distinction here on what constitutes a grave risk of
death.''
   ``People bitten by rattlesnakes are often not even treated,'' he
said.
   Prosecutor O. Brent Rowe argued that Wessendorf's actions were
intentional and malicious.
   Earlier Wednesday, a psychologists, George Dunford, said that
Wessendorf suffered from mild schizophrenia and that he did not
believe the defendant understood he was endangering the child.
   An expert on snakes, James Glenn, testified for the defense that
the snake is one of the least aggressive types of rattlers and that
the hospital did not give the girl enough anti-venom.
</TEXT>
