<2ND_LINE>AM-School Evacuation,0173</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fumes Send 149 People To Hospital</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ARLINGTON HEIGHTS, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A mixture of cleaning chemicals
sent fumes through a school Wednesday, sickening at least 149
people, most of them students, authorities said.
   A 12-year-old girl with a history of respiratory ailments was
admitted to Holy Family Hospital in Des Plaines for observation,
said spokesman Frank Buccitelli. The other victims were treated at
hospitals and released.
   Most of those affected by the fumes at Thomas Junior High School
complained of dizziness, nausea and shortness of breath.
   ``Maintenance men were cleaning a drain,'' said police Cmdr. Jay
Plaisted. ``They used a degreaser and a drain opener, and the two
together gave off a noxious odor.
   ``They opened a window to try to air out the fumes, but the
mixture had already moved through the pipes into other rooms in the
school,'' Plaisted said.
   Before noon, state environmental officials declared the school
safe and classes resumed for most of the 700 students, said
Assistant Principal Al Swanson.
</TEXT>
