<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Britain-SAfrica     02-25 0415</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-SAfrica,0428</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Britain Condemns South African Crackdown</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-SAfrica-Ban, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Britain's government and opposition leaders
condemned South Africa's crackdown on major black organizations
Wednesday and feared the move would bring the ``frustration and
despair'' that breed violence.
   Britain, the staunchest opponent of sanctions against South
Africa, faced renewed demands from the opposition Labor Party and
the Anti-Apartheid Movement organization that Prime Minister
Margaret Thatcher approve tough embargoes against South Africa.
   Neil Kinnock, Labor Party leader, said the Thatcher government
``bears a heavy responsibility,'' for the South African government
ban on political activity by 18 major black movements opposed to
apartheid, including the United Democratic Front.
   ``Because it has been so weak against apartheid, we now have
even more vicious jackboot rule,'' Kinnock said.
   Foreign Secretary Sir Geoffrey Howe said he was ``shocked and
saddened'' by the crackdown.
   ``We do not see how the suppression of non-violent political
activity can possibly contribute to a peaceful solution to South
Africa's problems,'' Howe said in a statement, describing the ban
as ``oppressive.''
   ``We are particularly concerned that the black opposition in
South Africa should not lose hope of peaceful fundamental change.
Frustration and despair breed violence,'' Howe added.
   Sir Shridath Ramphal, secretary-general of the Commonwealth,
called on the international community, particularly Western
countries opposed to sanctions, to show South Africa ``in every
possible way ... that this repression is as intolerable as
apartheid.''
   Mrs. Thatcher regularly has been isolated at summits of the
Commonwealth, the 48-nation association of Britain and its former
colonies, for her refusal to impose tough embargoes against South
Africa, a major trading partner.
   The Anti-Apartheid Movement planned demonstrations at the South
African Embassy and said it would join other groups in an
``international demonstration.''
   Anti-Apartheid Movement president, Anglican Archbishop Trevor
Huddleston, said South Africa ``is once again prohibiting
non-violent resistance to apartheid and has slammed the door on any
prospect of genuine negotiation.''
   ``Britain and South Africa's other major trading partners must
act decisively,'' Huddleston added, saying he would appeal again to
Mrs. Thatcher to change her stance on sanctions.
   Mrs. Thatcher argues that harsh sanctions against South Africa
will harden white resistance to change, harm blacks most, and be
evaded by third party countries which are not now big trading
partners.
   By law and custom, apartheid establishes a racially segregated
society in which South Africa's 26 million blacks have no vote in
national affairs. The 5 million whites control the economy and
maintain separate districts, schools and health services.
</TEXT>
