<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Britain-Strike     02-25 0329</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Strike,0341</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Thousands March in Scotland As Health Workers Strike</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EDINBURGH, Scotland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tens of thousands of health workers
marched in Scottish cities Wednesday as part of a one-day walkout
by 60,000 workers at hospitals nationwide, police and union
officials said.
   The Scottish Trade Unions Congress called the strike to protest
a government plan to force state-run hospitals to compete
competitively with private bidders for auxiliary services.
   About 15,000 workers marched in Glasgow and 10,000 in Edinburgh,
police said. They estimated about 60,000 people took part in the
walkout.
   A union spokesman said rallies were also held in Dundee,
Aberdeen, Inverness, Lochgilphead and Dumfries.
   Union officials said all hospitals remained equipped to give
emergency services, but government officials alleged that even
those services were not being provided in some areas.
   Michael Forsyth, the British lawmaker responsible for health
care in Scotland, said in a radio interview with the British
Broadcasting Corp. that he was ``disgusted'' at the lack of care
available.
   He said he would talk with the strikers when ``they stop
organizing attacks on the sick and stop organizing disruption in
our hospitals.''
   The situation caused an angry clash between opposition and
government lawmakers in the House of Commons in London.
   Conservatives shouted ``disgraceful!' in response to remarks by
the opposition party's spokesman for Scotland, Donald Dewar, that
the protest was justified.
   Scottish Secretary Malcolm Rifkind said the strike ``has led to
operations being canceled in their hundreds, and it will
undoubtedly add to waiting lists over the weeks and months to
come.''
   Health workers have staged regional walkouts recently, but
Tuesday's action was the first nationwide protest.
   Forsyth said the government would not changes its plans, saying
the strike pointlessly damaged the National Health Service, which
provides free health care to Britons.
   The Scottish action follows the Feb. 3 walkout by nurses in
London to demand higher pay and more government funding of the
health service. Automakers and teachers also staged separate
strikes this month.
</TEXT>
