<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Mexico-US     02-25 0388</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mexico-US,0400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mexico, U.S. Conclude Trade, Foreign Investment Talks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ANDERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. and Mexican officials pledged to
exchange more tariff and investment information during talks that
reviewed a trade agreement last year, the newspaper El Nacional
announced Wednesday.
   But the two sides reached no new concrete agreements during
talks Monday and Tuesday, officials said.
   ``We held informal discussions, nothing more,'' said a U.S.
official close to the talks, speaking on condition of anonymity.
``They never were intended to be negotiations.''
   El Nacional, citing attending Mexican officials, said the two
sides ``agreed to establish a greater flow of more precise and
opportune information in tariff and foreign investment matters.''
   The two nations trade about $30 billion worth of goods and
services.
   The U.S. delegation, led by deputy trade representative Peter
Murphy, met with its Mexican counterpart, headed by Foreign Trade
Undersecretary Luis Bravo Aguilera, at the resort of Cocoyoc, south
of Mexico City.
   Under the Nov. 6 pact, Mexican and U.S. officials will meet
periodically to review progress made in foreign investment,
services, patents and copyrights, textiles, steel, electronics,
agricultural products and information exchanges.
   The U.S. trade representative and Mexican Commerce Department
reached separate agreements on steel, shoes, beer and textiles late
last year.
   The textile accord, signed by Presidents Reagan and Miguel de la
Madrid at their Feb. 13 summit meeting in Mazatlan, permits Mexico
to increase such exports to the United States by about 6 percent
each year. In turn, Mexico is opening its domestic market to many
finished U.S. textile products for the first time.
   On other issues, the two sides remain far apart. The United
States has pressed for Mexico to liberalize its foreign investment
law, generally restricted to 49 percent of ownership in Mexican
enterprises.
   Mexico has resisted tampering with the law, but it did set up
task force to look at the issue.
   Another point of friction is Mexico's law on patents and
copyrights, which U.S. officials consider too weak to permit
American manufacturers _ particularly in pharmaceuticals _ to
export much to Mexico.
   The United States, Mexico's largest trading partner, takes in a
third of Mexico's exports and provides about the same percentage of
its imports. Mexico ranks fourth as a trading partner with its
northern neighbor, after Canada, Japan and West Germany.
</TEXT>
