<1ST_LINE>r i AM-NuclearWarning     02-25 0216</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nuclear Warning,0221</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Official Test System That Sparked Nuke Fears</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A worldwide nuclear warning system was
tested without a hitch Wednesday after an earlier one sparked
unfounded fears of a second serious nuclear accident in the Soviet
Union.
   During the test, attended by reporters, a nuclear plant in West
Germany transmitted routine meteorological data to the Vienna-based
International Atomic Energy Agency.
   Sixteen countries taking part in the test confirmed within 30
minutes that they received the information. Agency officials hailed
the test as a success of the sophisticated new warning system.
   The system has become extremely important after the Cherbobyl
nuclear accident, said Morris Rosen, nuclear safety director for
the agency.
   A test of the warning system earlier this month was
misinterpreted, prompting momentary fear worldwide of a nuclear
accident in the Soviet Union.
   The warning system, called the Global Telecommunication System,
can be picked up at 160 points throughout the world, mostly
national meteorologcal centers. It receives information from
nuclear reactors worldwide and is expected to become fully
operational this summer.
   The April 26, 1986, accident at the nuclear reactor at
Chernobyl, about 80 miles north of Kiev, was the world's worst
nuclear reactor accident. It killed 31 people, hospitalized
hundreds and sent a cloud of radiation around the world.
</TEXT>
