<NOTE>$adv28</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Feb. 28, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>ATLANTA: not permitted.</HEAD>
<HEAD>GEORGIA</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   In Georgia, one of three Southern states to hold a presidential
primary on the same day four years ago, Bush is the acknowledged
leader for the 48 Republican delegates, but uncertainty over
Robertson's ``invisible army'' clouds most predictions.
   On the Democratic side, it's a three-man race among Dukakis,
Jackson and Gephardt@Gore, depending on who's doing the talking.
The state will send 77 committed delegates to the convention in
Atlanta in July.
   ``You have to say Gephardt is the man to beat,'' said pollster
Claibourne Darden, although he said Gephardt has done a poor job of
building on momentum gained in Iowa, New Hampshire and South Dakota.
   Democratic officials see Dukakis, Gore and Jackson as the
leaders.
   Republican party officials say Bush's identification with
President Reagan, his years of campaigning and healthy treasury put
him far ahead.
   Robertson is the wild card, with party officials unsure whether
organizational strength displayed in precinct meetings earlier this
month will translate into votes.
   GOP officials claim Robertson will draw dissatisified Democrats
to their primary, but Democrats disagree and the assertion is
difficult to analyze as the state does not register voters by party
and there are no restrictions attached to voting in either party's
primary.
   Little polling has been done since mid-January when a newspaper
survey showed Bush far ahead in the Republican race. The poll gave
Jackson a solid lead, followed by Hart.
   An estimated 2.6 million people will be eligible to vote,
although exact figures aren't available yet. Blacks account for an
estimated 20 percent of the registered voters.
   In 1984, just over 31 percent of the state's 2.4 million
registered voters participated in the presidential primary, with
684,541 voting Democratic and only 50,793 participating in the GOP
primary.
   But in 1980, Republicans got 200,171 of the 584,951 primary
votes and Lee Raudonis, a former state party chairman currently
working for Bush, predicts the party will almost double that number
this year.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
<HEAD>HAWAII</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Even Dukakis workers see Jackson as the leader in Hawaii's
Democratic caucuses.
   ``The way it is standing right now, Jackson is in the lead with
40 percent of the people who will show up,'' said state Rep. Mike
Crozier, Dukakis' state co-chairman. ``The way I see it, it'll be
Jackson, Dukakis and uncommitted,''
   Although Hawaii has about 30,000 Democrats, the usual turnout at
precinct caucuses is between 2,500 and 2,800, allowing the more
than 2,000 additional members signed up by Jackson's campaign to
have a major impact on the results.
   Gov. John Waihee, a Democrat, has urged Hawaii's 28-member
delegation to remain uncommitted.
   ``Our view is that Hawaii can provide the same impetus to
Jackson's campaign that West Virginia did for John F. Kennedy who
was running as a Catholic in a non-Catholic state,'' said Jackson
state campaign chairman Richard Port.
   ``Hawaii has very few blacks, but has a lot of people who look
beyond skin color and look at the man. It's hard to overlook a man
who gets support from people who aren't supporting him because he's
black,'' said Port. Of Hawaii's more than 1 million people, 2.4
percent are black.
   Jackson, the only candidate to visit Hawaii, had the backing of
17 percent of the likely Democratic voters surveyed in a recent
media poll. Hart and Dukakis both got 11 percent with Gephardt and
Sen. Paul Simon each at 8 percent, and Gore at 1 percent.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
<HEAD>IDAHO</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Like Hawaii, only Democrats are participating in Idaho on Super
Tuesday as they hold caucuses to select 18 delegates to the Atlanta
convention.
   Few candidates have paid much attention to the state, with Gore
the only visitor.
   Democratic Party officials expect about 10,000 people to
participate in the caucuses.
   Although no polls have been conducted, observers say Dukakis may
have a slim lead, though he may suffer because of attempts by some
party leaders to field an uncommitted delegation.
   Analysts think Dukakis has the inside track because of a
superior organization that includes former Gov. John Evans as
co-chairman.
   ``We regard it as an important statement how he does in these
western states,'' said Dukakis' Idaho campaign director John
Greenfield. ``It will be an indication of his status as a national
candidate.''
   Campaign officials for both Dukakis and Gore say a victory in
Idaho is important in their effort to dispell images as regional
candidates.
   The Republicans will hold a primary May 24 to select 18 of their
national convention delegates. Democrats vote again that day, but
the results don't affect delegate selection.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
<HEAD>KENTUCKY</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Gore has worked Kentucky harder than any candidate and has been
endorsed by Gov. Wallace Wilkinson. Voter turnout is expected to be
very low _ less than 20 percent of the 1.3 million registered
Democrats _ and Wilkinson's organization should give Gore a lift.
   Jackson, who had a surprisingly strong showing in 1984 party
caucuses, has a strong base of support among the Democrats in a
state with 104,640 registered black voters.
   Gephardt has the backing of popular Louisville Mayor Jerry
Abramson, while Dukakis has been endorsed by former Gov. Martha
Layne Collins.
   Among Republicans, Bush, who has made Kentucky Sen. Mitch
McConnell one of his national campaign chairmen, is considered the
clear front-runner.
   A newspaper poll conducted in late January showed Bush with 44
percent and Dole 25 percent among the 550,000 Republicans.
Robertson, who unsuccessfully challenged a state law prohibiting
voters from changing party registration between elections, was
third with 7 percent.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
<HEAD>LOUISIANA</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Louisiana, with 41 GOP and 63 pledged Democratic delegates, has
attracted little attention, but officials expect that to change.
   ``I think it's coming in full force. There are a few bumper
stickers around. But they're all going to pick up with their media.
It's going to be mostly radio and television, depending upon their
campaign,'' said state Democratic chairman James Brady.
   Although no polls had been taken, Brady said Gore, Jackson and
Gephardt are the early favorites. Jackson won Louisiana in 1984.
   State Rep. Quentin Dastugue, state co-chairman for Dole,
predicted that Dole would carry four of the state's eight
congressional districts, with Bush getting three and Robertson one.
   Much of early effort has involved voter registration drives,
with Robertson's state director claiming credit for helping to
swell Republican rolls by 6 percent since October.
   However, Rep. Richard Baker, Bush's state chairman, said the
growth was due to widespread GOP efforts designed to warn voters
they would be locked out of the Republican balloting if they
remained registered Democrats.
   ``I think they had made a choice to support a Republican
presidential candidate,'' Baker said.
   Nevertheless the GOP remains drawfed more than 5-to-1 by the
Democrats: of the 2.2 million registered voters, 1.7 million are
Democrats and 328,618 Republican.
   No crossover voting is allowed, and the 185,191 voters who
registered as ``no party'' cannot participate March 8.

</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
