<NOTE>$Adv28</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Feb. 28, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>ATLANTA: early January.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
<HEAD>NORTH CAROLINA</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   North Carolina is viewed widely as Bush's to lose in the GOP
race. Among Democrats, Jackson's extensive grassroots organization
and solid base of black support may give him a plurality as
Dukakis, Gephardt and Gore fight over the remaining Democratic
votes.
   The state's 82 Democratic delegates and 54 GOP delegates make it
one of the largest pots on Super Tuesday.
   Ted Arrington, University of North Carolina at Charlotte
political scientist and a Republican, says Bush is running first
and Dole second, with Robertson and Kemp fighting it out for third.
   But he said Bush is not a strong first and polls have shown
changing levels of support.
   A newspaper poll in mid-February showed Jackson leading the
Democrats and gaining ground with 21 percent of those polled.
Dukakis was second at 18 percent, Gephardt 13 percent and Gore 11
percent.
   The results were a blow to Gore, who has visited often, been
endorsed by Sen. Terry Sanford and former Gov. Jim Hunt and been
running commercials for weeks.
   Merle Black, political science professor at the University of
North Carolina at Chapel Hill, said Jackson would get at least 90
percent of the black vote, about 19 percent of registered voters,
and 5 percent to 10 percent of the white vote, leaving Gore,
Dukakis and Gephardt to fight for the rest.
   ``Jackson is in a very enviable position,'' said Wallace Hyde, a
Raleigh fund-raiser and Gore strategist. ``His vote I'd say is
motivated. It's sort of a crusade to his people.''
   The latest figures showed 2.1 million registered Democrats,
850,351 Republicans and 132,421 unaffiliated.
   Spot checks show the GOP is picking up some ground, and state
GOP Chairman Jack Hawke says he's convinced Robertson is behind
much of the growth.
   Crossover voting is not allowed in North Carolina but the GOP
permits independents to vote in its primary. The Democrats do not.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
<HEAD>OKLAHOMA</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Gore and Gephardt have been the most visible of Democratic
candidates in Oklahoma, but party officials say the race is wide
open.
   ``Name ID is the name of the game,'' state party chairman Bill
Bullard said. ``I think it could boil down to who is on television
delivering their message the last three days _ Saturday, Sunday and
Monday.''
   Bullard said the winner might have 23 percent or 24 percent of
the vote. It takes 15 percent to pick up any of Oklahoma's 46
delegates at stake.
   Gephardt's call for an oil import fee is playing well in a state
hit hard by the sagging fortunes of the oil industry.
   Bush and Dole are generally considered the leading Republicans,
but some of their supporters are nervous about Robertson and his
draw with many conservative Democrats who have been re-registering
as Republican.
   Tom Cole, state GOP chairman, says he thinks ``any of the three
of them could win.'' Jack Kemp also is well organized, but thus far
political experts see him finishing fourth.
   Dole's strength is partly due to the fact that he is from
Kansas, a neighboring state that is heavily dependent, as is
Oklahoma, on agriculture.
   Matt Seward, Bush campaign coordinator in Oklahoma, says it is
``a neck-and-neck'' race with Dole, downplaying Robertson's
strength despite reports that Robertson supporters got more than 50
percent at February precinct meetings.
   Eighteen of the GOP 36 delegates will be chosen on the basis of
the primary vote in the six congressional districts and Robertson's
best chances are in the heavily Democratic 2nd and 3rd districts of
eastern and southern Oklahoma.
   Oklahoma had 1,356,460 Democrats registered as of Jan. 1,
compared with 616,232 Republicans and 53,933 independents.
   County election officials have reported scores of Democrats have
been switching to GOP to vote for Robertson.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
<HEAD>RHODE ISLAND</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Dukakis and Bush, with the support of party leaders and the most
visible organizations, are expected to win Rhode Island, but each
faces some competition for the 22 Democratic delegates and 21 GOP
delegates.
   The Massachusetts governor is a familiar face here, but Rhode
Island Democrats have a history of rejecting the establishment's
choices, picking Hart in 1984 and Jerry Brown in 1976 despite the
opposition of party regulars.
   Gore, whose organization includes a small group of legislators,
and Simon, who is backed by several influential labor leaders, have
made a serious effort for second place.
   Jackson won 8 percent of the vote in 1984, in a state that is
only 2 percent black, but must win 15 percent to qualify for any
delegates.
   Among Republicans, Dole organized the state first, but Bush has
attracted most of Rhode Island's top Republicans, including Gov.
Edward D. DiPrete.
   About 514,000 voters _ there is no party registration _ are
registered for the primary, virtually the same as in 1984. But
since 1976, when the primary was instituted, turnout has averaged
just 10.1 percent.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
<HEAD>TENNESSEE</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Gore is the undisputed champion in his home state, where his
father was also a senator for almost two decades. Only Jackson has
bothered to campaign for the 70 Democratic delegates available and
he has the support of most of the state's blacks.
   The Republican race for 45 delegates is harder to call. Bush has
most of the leading Republican fund-raisers and most prominent
executive committee members backing him, Dole has former Sen. Bill
Brock working for him but Robertson is a wild card.
   Robertson has a strong organization and Bible belt appeal.
   State Republican Chairman Jim Henry said Robertson is ``going to
get 40,000 or 50,000 votes in Tennessee. That will probably give
him a solid third. They've identified 40,000 Robertson supporters.
I expect about 200,000 votes in the Republican primary, about the
same number who voted in '80.''
   Tommy Harper, Bush's Tennessee campaign director said Robertson
``is going to do pretty well,'' battling Dole for second place.
   There were 2,466,220 registered voters at the end of 1987.
   There is no party registration, but estimates are that the state
is about 30 percent Republican, 50 percent Democrat and the rest
independent.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
