<NOTE>$adv28</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Feb. 28, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>ATLANTA: rest independent.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
<HEAD>TEXAS</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Texas offers the biggest slice of the Super Tuesday pie, with
183 Democratic delegates and 111 Republican delegates at stake.
   One-time oilman Bush has adopted the state as his home, and
newspaper polls show him well ahead, with Robertson in third but
gaining on Dole.
   Robertson may gain further from a low Republican turnout on
primary day.
   Like many Southern states, Texas does not register by party,
leaving voters free to choose either primary. In addition, Texas
remains a one-party state in many respects, and lots of local
primary races are Democrats only. This may reduce the number of
people who vote in the GOP presidential race, leaving the door open
for Robertson.
   Bush has a solid GOP establishment organization, chaired by
former Rep. Tom Loeffler and endorsed by Gov. Bill Clements.
   Dukakis has won raves for his organization and has moved up to
the lead in at least one poll. Gore, meanwhile, has picked up lots
of establishment endorsements. Gore also has lined up Democratic
fund-raiser Jess Hay of Dallas, who put together a $750,000 night
for him in Dallas Feb. 10. Jackson has his 1984 organization in
place and looks strong in inner city Houston and Dallas.
   Texas has more than 7.8 million registered voters, with final
counts still to be made in four of the biggest counties, including
Dallas and Houston. Registration is up 7.2 percent, boosted by a
high-profile registration drive. The state does not record
registration by race; however, Hispanics probably make up the
largest group of minority voters.
   Secretary of State Jack Rains estimates as many as 1 million
people will vote in each of the primaries on March 8.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
<HEAD>VIRGINIA</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Among Virginia's Democrats, Jackson is ``in the driver's seat,''
said Larry Sabato, a University of Virginia political analyst.
   ``He's got three strong, white Democrats running against him
(Gephardt, Gore and Dukakis),'' Sabato said. ``If all three of them
stay in contention ... then Jesse Jackson is bound to do well. I
think he's got a good chance to be the plurality winner, but not
the majority winner.''
   Seventy-five of the Virginia's 85 Democratic delegates will be
selected based on the primary results.
   Republicans in Virginia, Robertson's home state, will select 50
delegates through a complicated series of local caucuses and
district and state conventions that are not connected to the March
8 primary.
   Steve Haner, director of the GOP legislative caucus in Virginia,
said a loss by Robertson to Bush in the primary might look bad,
``but after the mass meetings start, reality will set in,'' he said.
   Three months ago, about 1,200 Robertson supporters packed a
western Virginia arena where the state GOP central committee was
meeting. Don Moseley, a member of the committee, said it was ``an
awesome display. Those are very committed people, and they're not
going to go away.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
<HEAD>WASHINGTON</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Washington has 2.2 million registered voters, but traditionally
no more than 50,000 to 100,000 people attend the precinct caucuses.
Party leaders, who beat back legislation to create a presidential
primary, predict they'll meet or beat the 100,000 mark this year,
particularly with the infusion of Robertson supporters.
   The caucuses are binding on the 65 Democratic delegates but not
for the Republicans. The state has no registration by party. Caucus
attenders attest on a sign-in sheet that they consider themselves
Democrat or Republican.
   Robertson is given a good shot at edging out Dole and Bush,
although more party regulars are predicting Dole, Robertson and
Bush finishing in that order with Kemp trailing. State Party
Chairwoman Jennifer Dunn, who once predicted a Dole victory, now
says the candidates are so bunched up she can't make a prediction.
   Robertson is charging hard, using pastors, fundamentalists and
viewers of his ``700 Club'' show to recruit followers. Party
officials say most of the Robertson supporters seem to be political
neophytes.
   Robertson state Chairman Bruce Hawkins predicts a first- or
second-place finish.
   Both Hawkins and Dole spokesman Brett Bader say it's a
Robertson-Dole race. Dole has targeted Washington more than any
other candidate, going to the state eight times and locating his
western coordinator there.
   On the Democratic side, Dukakis seems to have it sewed up. He's
the favorite of many party regulars and has wooed labor. He made
several visits, more than the others, and appears to be the
favorite of Gov. Booth Gardner.
   Party state Chairwoman Karen Marchioro sees Simon second,
followed by Jackson and Gore. Gephart does poorly in the state,
largely because of his protectionist stance in a staunchly
free-trade state.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, Feb. 28</NOTE>
</DOC>
