<NOTE>$Adv26-28</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions, Feb 26-28 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>THE GRAMMY AWARDS: Playing the '80s</HEAD>
<HEAD>Child Abuse, Love and Politics Make Music</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOLORES BARCLAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Everything's coming up New York at the 30th
Annual Grammy Awards, as the music industry returns to a town with
a rich legacy of contributions to American song.
   ``We had a couple of choices this year,'' said Ken Ehrlich,
producer of the show. ``We opted to downplay that it's the 30th
anniversary. Instead, we took advantage of what was really unique
to New York. A lot of nominations are New York-based musicians and
New York-oriented songs.''
   The three-hour show will be telecast live on CBS-TV at 8 p.m.
EST on Wednesday from Radio City Music Hall. It is the first time
in seven years that the presentation by The National Academy of
Recording Arts & Sciences will originate from New York instead of
Los Angeles.
   Highlighting the awards extravaganza is a production number
celebrating the sounds of the city, featuring Tito Puente and Celia
Cruz with their hot Latin rhythms; Run DMC with its funky rap; and
Billy Joel, whose songs have traveled from downtown to uptown, from
romantic Greenwich Village bistros to Spanish Harlem.
   ``It's a number that has a lot of different layers and
textures,'' said Ehrlich, who is producing the show for the seventh
time. ``The size and the scope of the city is so big.''
   Guitarist-vocalist George Benson will perform ``On Broadway.''
New York based do-wop groups will do what they do best. Do-wop.
   Jazz legend Miles Davis and sax-man David Sanborn will blow
their horns in the art deco entertainment palace.
   Michael Jackson, Suzanne Vega, Whitney Houston, Terence Trent
D'Arby, Randy Travis, K.T. Oslin, Restless Heart and comedian
Jackie Mason will also perform.
   In the past few years, the Grammy show has struggled for an
upbeat image, moving away from the banalties of middle-of-the-road
pop music. Last year the accent was on blues, gospel and country
music. The year before, Grammy tried jazzing things up with a
tribute to bebop and swing.
   This year the nominees range from the sensuous funk of Prince to
the lyrical charms of Suzanne Vega.
   Fun and love still make major notes, but South Africa, child
abuse and national pride have claimed places on the charts as well.
It seems that listeners are tired of the endless party with its
synthetic orchestrations, and long for real emotions and a touch of
reality backed by raw sounds and solid music.
   U2 sold more than 12 million copies of its Grammy nominated LP,
``The Joshua Tree,'' with its tunes about war and the meaning of
life. Vega's Top 10 hit, ``Luka,'' a soliloquy of an abused child,
has been nominated for record of the year and song of the year, and
she's up for best female pop vocalist.
   Paul Simon also is nominated for record of the year for the
title track from his Grammy award-winning ``Graceland'' LP, which
fused the songwriter's poetry with the rhythms of the black
township of Soweto in South Africa. The Graceland collection won
Album of the Year last year.
   Up for Album of the Year is Prince's ``Sign 'O' the Times,''
with its allusions to drug addiction, destitution and AIDS.
   Though the rock-pop mainstream is serving up serious songs for
serious listeners, frothy feelings still sell: Dolly Parton, Linda
Ronstadt and Emmylou Harris have been nominated for album of the
year for ``Trio''; Grammy winner Whitney Houston is up for her
self-titled ``Whitney'' LP.
   Although women have a strong presence in the three major Grammy
contests, the record academy eliminated the ``best rock vocal
performance, female'' category this year.
   ``I wish the nominations had been otherwise,'' Ehrlich said. ``I
think this has been a terrific year for women in pop music in
general. I would have liked to have had more rock presence.''
   The Grammys have separate categories for male and female singers
in pop and rhythm 'n' blues. The rock category combines them this
year. Tina Turner, who was named best female rock vocalist last
year, is nominated along with Richard Marx, Bob Seger, Bruce
Springsteen and Joe Cocker.
   The sultry singer will not be performing in the telecast,
though, because she's touring in Europe.
   Al Schlesinger, president of NARAS, said the academy has a rule
that the 6,000 industry professionals who are members must nominate
10 people in a category for that category to exist. Rock vocalist
nominations must be from solo albums; lead singers of groups, such
as Grace Slick, aren't eligible.
   This year, NARAS couldn't come up with 10 female nominees for
rock vocalist.
   Other nominees range from such pop veterans as Barbra Streisand
(``One Voice'') and Carly Simon (``Coming Around Again'') to jazz
singer Al Jarreau (``Moonlighting''), rhythm and blues great Wilson
Pickett (``In the Midnight Hour''), country rage K.T. Oslin (``80's
Ladies''), avant-garde rocker Frank Zappa (``Jazz From Hell'') and
comedian Robin Williams (``A Night at the Met'').
   Grammy winners in 73 categories will be determined by balloting
among the record academy members of the record academy in seven
chapters nationwide. Members include recording artists,
songwriters, musicians, producers and technicians.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Weekend editions, Feb. 26-28</NOTE>
