<NOTE>$Adv05-06</NOTE>
<HEAD>Advance for Weekend Editions, March 05-06, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Honda Accord Continues to Get Raves</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto, LaserGraphic</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ANN M. JOB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>For The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The raves just roll in for the Honda Accord _
they have been for a number of years now _ and I have to add mine.
   What an utter pleasure to drive such a well-designed, well-built
car. It doesn't matter who does the judging: The Accord always
seems to land on top.
   The car has been named one of the 10 best by Car and Driver
magazine for six years _ including the current 1988 model year.
This is the compact sedan that feels right to both import and
domestic buyers, the magazine wrote in its January edition.
   Popular Science was no less laudatory. The Accord is the best
family sedan sold in the United States, the periodical said last
summer. Car buyers also vote in favor of the Accord, having made it
the third-best seller in the last model year, 1987, with sales of
more than 337,000. Only the Ford Escort and Ford Taurus had more
sales.
   Why is the Accord so successful? The 1988 LXi sedan I drove had
excellent fit and finish, one of the best ergonomically-designed
interiors of any car I've been in, a responsive, fuel-injected,
four-cylinder engine coupled with a smooth five-speed manual
transmission and fine handling _ just to mention a few of the major
items.
   But what really shows is Honda's attention to the little things.
For example, there was a small, blue light that illuminated the
ignition keyhole for several seconds after the driver door was
opened and closed _ just to help the driver find the spot for the
key.
   There was a safety on the cruise control. While the set speed
and resume buttons are on the four-spoke steering wheel, the button
to turn on the whole system was on the dashboard to the left of the
driver, so the cruise should not be activated accidentally.
   Below the cassette player was a large center bin to keep
cassettes organized. To the left of the driver was a small, shallow
drawer _ ideal for coins for the parking meter. The driver-side
window would go all the way down if the driver just pushed the
power window button past the first stop.
   I didn't have to continue to hold the button down as I drove.
There was a lock on the other windows, if you have children, and
there were child-proof locks for the rear doors. I could go on. The
Accord simply has a lot of carefully-planned features. Of course,
they don't come cheap.
   The LXi is the top-of-line model and has a base price of
$15,200. You could get a compact Tempo GL four-door for around
$9,000, in contrast. But the Accord price includes a lot of
amenities that are standard, such as a power moonroof with wind
deflector and manual sunshade.
   Consumer Reports rates the Accord highly, with the car's trouble
index _ trouble experience of owners _ much better than average for
the 1982-86 model years.
   However, I had a problem with my test car. The engine warning
light came on while I was on the highway, and I limped the car
(with 2,029 miles on it) back to the garage as instructed by the
owner's manual, which said something may have malfunctioned in the
fuel injection system. Honda spokesman Dave Jenkins said later it
was likely a loose wire, because after checking under the hood, the
garage could not make the light go back on, even after 150 miles of
driving.
   Another drawback in the Accord was the small rear seat. Sure you
can fit three adults back there, but they will sit real close
together. There have been complaints of sudden acceleration in
Honda Accords _ claims that the vehicles took off on the drivers
and the brakes were not effective.
   Honda has not found any widespread defect in the cars involved,
and two federal government probes into the complaints were closed
with no common malfunction found. The Accord attracts a large
percentage of yuppie buyers _ 46 percent are between 25 and 39
years of age.
   Income-wise, the biggest group (18 percent) are buyers with
household earnings of $30,000 to $40,000 a year. More than 70
percent of Accord buyers are married, and more than 80 percent have
some college education. More than 60 percent of the buyers have
professional-manager type jobs, Honda said.
   Officials at many domestic automakers just drool over that kind
of demographics and have spent years trying to get their vehicles
to the Accord's level of quality and comfort _ not to mention
sales. In the cutthroat auto business, that says a lot. Imitation
is, after all, the sincerest form of flattery.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Ann Job has covered the auto industry for The
Associated Press, the Detroit Free Press and The Detroit News,
where she is now assistant news editor.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Weekend Editions, March 5-6</NOTE>
