<1ST_LINE>s w BC-WeeklyFarm Adv28   02-25 0692</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Weekly Farm, Adv 28,0709</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv28</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Feb. 28, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Soviets May Have a Crush on U.S. Soybean Meal, Says USDA Analyst</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A decision last fall by Moscow to buy
high-protein soybean meal from the United States is seen by an
Agriculture Department analyst as a significant development for
Soviet consumers and American farmers.
   The sales in November, the first in eight years, totaled 1.3
million metric tons and were worth an estimated $300 million, says
Thomas W. Bickerton of the department's Economic Research Service.
   Overall, the Soviets are expected to import a record 3.2 million
tons of soybean meal in 1987-88, including the U.S. shipments.
   Although the Soviet Union has bought U.S. soybeans from time to
time _ more than 813,000 tons have been sold for delivery this year
_ the huge purchase of meal has special significance.
   Underlying the decision to buy U.S. meal is Soviet leader
Mikhail Gorbachev's commitment to reform the agricultural sector,
including greater profitability and more meat for consumers.
   ``The speed at which these two economic goals can be reached
depends to a great extent on how quickly the Soviets can introduce
more protein meal into their livestock sector,'' Bickerton said.
``The most cost-effective way to rapidly increase protein inputs is
to sharply expand imports.''
   Also, he added, by adding the United States to its list of
suppliers the Soviets are able to see more price competition and to
contract for year-round shipments.
   High-protein meal in feed allows livestock and poultry to do
well with less grain than otherwise might be required. Soybeans,
after being crushed into meal and oil, are a prime source.
Cottonseed, sunflowerseed and other oil crops also are important.
   ``More meal in feed rations will allow the Soviets to obtain
greater output of meat and other livestock products at a savings,''
Bickerton said in a report by the agency. ``Soviet per capita meat
consumption is currently only about one-half that of the United
States.''
   Prior to last fall's orders, the Soviet Union last bought U.S.
soybean meal in 1979, just before then-President Carter imposed a
partial embargo on further sales of grain and other commodities in
response to the Soviet invasion of Afghanistan.
   After that, Argentina, Brazil and the European Economic
Community shared the Soviet market, exporting an average of 1.2
million tons of soybean meal annually.
   Bickerton said the U.S. sales ``suggest that the Soviets now
feel confident in their ability to handle U.S. meal in large
quantities'' and have created expectations that the Soviet Union
will be a good customer in the future.
   ``The Soviet agricultural sector lacks the resources to produce
sufficient protein to bridge the existing large gap between
domestic protein supply and demand,'' he said.
   In all, Bickerton said that the Soviet Union's livestock protein
deficit is estimated in the range of 9 million to 13 million tons a
year, in soybean meal equivalent.
   Further, he said, Soviet oilseed crushing capacity ``remains
stagnant'' at levels reached in the early 1970s, a factor which may
have encouraged Moscow to buy more meal instead of whole soybeans.
   Another likely reason cited by Bickerton for the Soviet Union
changing its mind about U.S. soybean meal have been the marketing
work done by private trade groups, including the U.S. Soybean
Processors Association and the American Soybean Association.
   Still another factor was the decline in the value of the U.S.
dollar against major foreign currencies, although Bickerton said
this has been limited in the case of soybean meal because of a rise
in meal prices in the international market.
   Bickerton said the large U.S. sales are expected to cut into the
shares of the Soviet market held by competitors.
   In 1986-87, the EEC, Argentina and Brazil divided the Soviet
soybean meal market among themselves, sharing 29 percent, 34
percent and 37 percent, respectively, he said.
   This year, the Argentine and Brazilian shares may drop to a
range of 20 percent to 25 percent each, and the EEC could wind up
with as little as 9 percent of the Soviet meal business, he said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, Feb 28</NOTE>
