<1ST_LINE>s p BC-SuperTuesday-Jackson Adv28   02-25 0905</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Super Tuesday-Jackson, Adv 28,0924</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv28</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Feb. 28</NOTE>
<HEAD>Bridge From Bloody Sunday To Super Tuesday A Victory March For
Jackson</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KENDAL WEAVER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SELMA, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For Jesse Jackson and his Deep South campaign
army, Super Tuesday may well be a victory march that began on a
bridge on Bloody Sunday.
   Black marchers seeking the right to vote were routed by Alabama
troopers on the bridge at Selma on what became known as Bloody
Sunday, March 7, 1965. As that anniversary approaches, black voters
are now forming ranks across Dixie to make Super Tuesday, March 8,
1988, a landmark march to the ballot box.
   Political and campaign officials say Jackson, the black
candidate for the Democratic presidential nomination, could win six
states _ Alabama, Mississippi, Louisiana, Georgia, Virginia and
North Carolina _ with some whites joining his core of black support.
   They say he possibly could run first in Arkansas, may be in the
top two in Maryland, and likely will run among the leaders
qualifying for rich numbers of delegates in the South's big bookend
states of Texas and Florida.
   ``February is black history month,'' says Rose Sanders, a black
who brought her Harvard Law School degree back to handle civil
rights work in Selma. ``We're telling young people to make super
black history on Super Tuesday.''
   Eleven Southern states with double-digit black voting
percentages are among 20 that hold primaries or caucuses March 8. A
12th, South Carolina, Jackson's home state, holds Democratic
caucuses four days after Super Tuesday. More than 900 Democratic
National Convention delegates are at stake among this Dixie dozen,
with Jackson in position to claim perhaps a third or more.
   That would delight his followers and also disturb his critics
who see him as an unelectable candidate threatening to fracture his
party. It will take 2,081 delegates to win the nomination at the
convention in Atlanta, far more than any campaign operatives or
political observers see Jackson cornering.
   Rivals such as Sen. Albert Gore Jr., who is expected to win
overwhelmingly in his native Tennessee, are angling for their share
of the Southern delegates. Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis and
Missouri Rep. Richard Gephardt _ whose home states are also in the
Super Tuesday lineup _ are counting on scores of delegates from
Super Tuesday states such as Texas as well as those inside and
outside the South.
   But while the final mix may be confusing, Sonia Jarvis,
executive director of the National Coalition on Black Voter
Participation in Washington, said Super Tuesday likely will be a
showcase for Jackson, particularly if he continues to draw white
voters to his cause.
   ``I think he will be very hard to beat in at least half the
primaries,'' she said.
   ``Jackson is in a very enviable position,'' said Wallace Hyde of
Raleigh, a Gore strategist, discussing North Carolina. ``You'd have
to say he is the favorite. His vote, I'd say, is motivated. It's
sort of a crusade to his people.''
   ``He's got three strong, white candidates running against him,''
said Larry Sabato, a University of Virginia political analyst,
reviewing that state's outlook. ``If all three of them stay in
contention for the three weeks of the campaign, then Jesse Jackson
is bound to do well. I think he's got a good chance to be the
plurality winner, but not the majority winner.''
   Jarvis said that in Jackson's first run for the presidency in
1984 his vote generally matched up with the percentage of black
voters. ``It wasn't always true, but that was the pattern,'' she
said.
   Now in such states as Iowa, New Hampshire and Minnesota, states
with small black voter percentages, Jackson has added white votes
in numbers that have elated his campaign.
   ``He is not just the blacks' candidate,'' said Sanders. ``He's
the people's candidate. Finally there are some whites in this
country beginning to recognize this.''
   Martin Moe, a white who graduated last year from Oberlin College
in Ohio, came out of Jackson's national campaign office in Chicago
to work for the candidate in Iowa and more recently help organize
in Alabama, where Jackson has targeted disenchanted whites,
including the poor, laid-off labor and beleaguered farm voters, as
well as blacks.
   ``Jackson is significantly broadening the base of his support,''
said Moe.
   But some blacks felt wounded by 1984, when a number of black
leaders sided with Walter Mondale and party rules rankled the
Jackson campaign.
   ``This time there is more of a wait-and-see approach among black
voters as opposed to the fervor of the first time around,'' said
Jarvis. Black voters, she said, seem to be saying, ``Let's see what
they do with Jackson this time around ... then we'll see how active
we'll be.''
   State Rep. Charles Young of Meridian, vice chairperson of the
black caucus in Mississippi, said he senses no apprehension that
the Democratic Party won't play fair with Jackson. For most blacks,
he said, the feeling is ``let's deal with the situation as it
comes.''
   The question looming now for the Jackson campaign is not whether
he will make history on Super Tuesday but what happens once that
bridge is crossed, especially if he should arrive in Atlanta with
none of his rivals having locked up the nomination.
   ``Whatever the results,'' said Robert James Jr., a north Alabama
Jackson campaign official, ``this country will never be the same
again poliltically.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, Feb. 28</NOTE>
