<1ST_LINE>s w BC-CISPESProfile Adv28-2Takes   02-25 1109</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-CISPES Profile, Adv 28-2 Takes,1133</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv28</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Feb 28, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>The Investigation of CISPES, and Shades of the 1950s</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PHYLLIS MESSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Angela Sanbrano was a student in law school
and working on immigration cases in a legal clinic in 1980. She
kept running into women from El Salvador who said they had been
tortured. ``I wondered how we could try and stop this,'' she says.
   Leslie Schuld was a student at the Univesity of Dayton in Ohio
in 1981 when she saw a film on the violence in El Salvador. She
says she started reading the troubled history of that troubled
country.
   Jon Haines was working as an aide in a nursing home in Seattle.
``In 1981, it looked like the United States would be getting more
invlved in El Salvador, and I was really concerned about that,'' he
says.
   These people were drawn to an organization which was just coming
into being at the time _ CISPES, the Committee in Solidarity with
the People of El Salvador.
   So was the FBI _ twice. In a case which recalls the excesses of
the communist-hunting days of the 1950s that led to restrictions on
FBI investigations into political activity, the bureau has come
under criticism for the way it infiltrated CISPES and employed an
informer for more than three years who, the FBI now says, supplied
``disinformation and misinformation.''
   The first time the FBI investigated CISPES it suspected it was
operating as a foreign front. The second time, it suspected CISPES
was engaging in terrorism and had ``cells'' of members planning to
commit violence and sabotage.
   But the upshot was embarrassment, and a new round of qustions
about the bureau's squeaky clean image under former Director
William Webster, now the head of the CIA.
   The Senate Intelligence Committee already has conducted one
hearing into the FBI's conduct and the House panel that oversees
the FBI plans to hold hearings as well.
   At issue is whether the FBI went too far in conducting domestic
surveillance of CISPES, violating the First Amendment rights of
group members to express their political opinions.
   Or as Sen. Howard Metzenbaum, D-Ohio, a member of the Senate
Intelligence Committee, put it, ``The issues we're talking about go
to the very heart of the confidence the American people have in the
FBI.''
   Why did the FBI conduct two investigations of CISPES over a
five-year period if, in fact, the group was merely one of hundreds
in the United States that work to bring about change in American
foreign policy?
   The Associated Press interviewed members of CISPES and reviewed
the 2,000 pages of FBI documents, many partially or totally blacked
out by government censors. They were provided in response to a
Freedom of Information request to the Center for Constitutional
Rights in New York. The FBI gave its first detailed explanation of
its investigation in a report to the Senate Intelligence Committee
on Tuesday.
   The story begins in October 1980, with the founding of CISPES at
conferences in Los Angeles and Washington.
   The FBI claims that it obtained a document, reportedly seized
from the Communist guerillas in El Salvador, indicating that the
Communist Party in the United States was involved in the
establishment of CISPES.
   Specifically, the FBI says Farid Handal, the brother of the head
of the Salvadoran Communist Party, met with Sandra Pollock, a
member of the central committee of the Communist Party in the
United States, in March 1980 to work out a way of getting financial
and moral support for the Salvadoran guerrillas. CISPES was that
way, the FBI contends.
   Beth Perry, a spokeswoman for CISPES who attended the founding
conference in Los Angeles, acknowledged in a recent interview that
Handal did attend the meeting.
   ``People knew he was a member of the Communist Party,'' Perry
said. ``Handal put out his opinions in discussions. We listened
because we were interested in all Salvadorans' opinions. But
dominating, he wasn't.''
   Perry said Pollock attended the East Coast conference in
Washington, and ``just like Farid's, hers was just one voice. In
terms of this is the (Communist Party) line, absolutely not. In
terms of what we ought to do, absolutely not.''
   At the time, the violence in El Salvador was in the news almost
daily. One news story at the end of 1980 declared that the civil
war in the Central American nation had taken 8,500 lives that year.
   Less than two months after CISPES' founding, three Roman
Catholic nuns and a lay worker were killed and buried in a roadside
grave. The sisters were in El Salvador to aid refugees from rural
areas who were fleeing the violence between leftist and rightist
guerillas.
   ``When I was getting the testimony from these people for filing
their immigration papers, I learned of what these people had gone
through in El Salvador,'' said Sanbrano, the law student who was
working on immigration cases in 1980. ``Some of the women had been
involved in starting unions. They talked about how they had been
tortured, and it really touched me. I wondered how we could try and
stop this.''
   She joined CISPES as a volunteer and worked her way up to
Southwest regional coordinator in 1983 to national coordinator in
1985. She was re-elected to the top spot in 1987, with the new
title, executive director.
   She said the group has two main objectives _ ``to change U.S.
policy in El Salvador from a militaristic policy to a
political-diplomatic policy and to allow Central Americans to
determine their own destiny.''
   ``Being in solidarity with the people of El Salvador means we
support their struggle for peace and justice and work with them to
win that struggle,'' she said. ``Solidarity means to take someone
else's struggle and make it your own.''
   Sanbrano, who is of Mexican origin, said CISPES ``openly
supports'' the Communist guerillas, known as the Frente Farabundo
Marti de Liberacion Nacional, or FMLN. But she said the support is
not financial. ``We believe they are a legitimate political
organization in El Salvador.''
   The FBI, in its report on the CISPES investigation, says the
FMLN is responsible for numerous terrorist activities, including
the May 1983 assassination of Navy Lt. Cmdr. Albert A.
Schaufelberger, who was the U.S. military adviser in El Salvador.
   Perry, the spokeswoman for CISPES, agreed that the FMLN has
killed Americans. ``We don't want to see anyone killed, but there's
a civil war going on there. People get caught in a war.''
   She later added, ``We feel Americans should not be there. If the
United States got out of El Salvador, no Americans would be
killed.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880225-0276 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-25-88 1423EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s w BC-CISPES-Profile Adv28-1stAdd   02-25 0738</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-CISPES-Profile, Adv 28-1st Add,0750</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv28</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Feb 28, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>WASHINGTON: killed.''</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   No one in CISPES interviewed by the AP recalled any violent
actions ever being discussed at meetings. All said there no secret
``cells'' of members planning terrorist actions. And all generally
gave the same report of activities in their area by CISPES, ranging
from petition drives to demonstrations to inviting speakers to
their meetings. Two described their meetings as ``long and boring.''
   Sanbrano said CISPES also does a lot of fund-raising, much of it
going to running the group and producing newsletters and other
literature. She said she gets a salary of $865 a month, as do most
of the full-time workers for CISPES.
   Some of the money the group raises does go for humanitarian aid
and for agricultural projects in El Salvador, she said, ``but we
don't fund the FMLN.''
   Although the CISPES members interviewed had different reasons
for joining the group, all said they joined to bring about a change
in U.S. policy in Central America.
   Leslie Schuld, the University of Dayton student, now Midwest
regional director of CISPES, joined the group in 1981. She said the
film shown by a local chapter of CISPES on the violence in El
Salvador shocked her. She said she read up on the history of El
Salvador and on U.S. involvement in Central America and went to
work as a volunteer for CISPES.
   Jon Haines, the nursing home aide, joined at about the same
time. He said he was growing increasingly concerned about U.S.
involvement in El Salvador. ``In 1981, it looked like the United
States would be getting more involved in El Salvador, and I was
really concerned about that,'' he said.
   In Dallas, Parker Wilson was a legal counsel to Sears. ``I
remember having a general concern about the Central America
situation and our government's actions,'' he said. He joined the
local chapter of CISPES, which he described as ``a little, scraggly
group'' in the early 1980s. It held meetings in a Catholic church.
   Not long after the Dallas chapter was formed, the FBI hired a
former evangelist from El Salvador, Frank Varelli, to inform on the
group. Varelli began work on March 10, 1981, according to his
testimony last year to the House Judiciary subcommittee on civil
and constitutional rights.
   For more than three years, he testified to the House panel, he
told the FBI what it wanted to hear. He told the FBI that CISPES'
activities were being directed by the Salvadoran guerillas and that
members of CISPES were engaged in international terrorism or were
knowingly helping those engaged in terrorism.
   The FBI says it began its first investigation of CISPES on Sept.
3, 1981, at the Justice Department's request. In its report to the
Senate Intelligence Committee, the FBI says it was asked to
determine whether CISPES was supplying money and material to the
Communist guerillas in El Salvador and, therefore, should register
under the Foreign Agents Registration Act.
   Oliver B. Revell, FBI executive assistant director, told the
Intelligence panel, that the probe was ``just a records check,''
and it was closed on Feb. 23, 1982.
   The FBI opened its second investigation of CISPES on March 30,
1983, largely on the basis of Varelli's information, the FBI says
in its report to the Senate Intelligence Committee. This was a
counterterrorism investigation, which gives the FBI far more
sweeping powers than the first probe. It requires only that there
be probable cause to suspect a terrorist threat to justify domestic
surveillance.
   Varelli continued working as an informer for the FBI for more
than three years, telling it in 1984 that members of CISPES were
plotting to assassinate President Reagan and disrupt the Republican
National Convention in Dallas. He stopped working for the FBI in
August 1984 and in March 1986 filed suit to get the rest of the pay
he felt he was owed for his FBI work. The case is still pending.
   The FBI closed its investigation of CISPES on June 18, 1985,
because, Revell said, ``we found insufficient evidence to continue.
... Part of the reason for that was the disinformation and
misinformation supplied by Mr. Varelli.''
   Wilson, of the Dallas chapter, said he considers the FBI
infiltration of the group ``so peculiar. The organization has
always been open to anyone who wanted to come. There was no need
for infiltration.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, Feb 28</NOTE>
</DOC>
