<FILEID>AP-NR-02-25-88 0422EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-BusinessHighlights 1stAdd   02-25 0472</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Highlights, 1st Add,0491</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   United Mine Workers President Richard Trumka says
he considers the union's failed merger with the Oil, Chemical and
Atomic Workers union ``a closed deal'' that won't be reconsidered.
   OCAW's executive board on Tuesday voted 6-2 to reject a merger
that would have created the United Mine, Energy and Chemical
Workers of America from the two powerful unions.
   Trumka said Wednesday the OCAW board had left open the
possibility of reconsidering the merger, but the UMW's board voted
Wednesday to rescind the approval it gave on Sunday.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge has given the Environmental
Protection Agency until April 15 to ban the sale and commercial use
of products containing an anti-termite pesticide believed to cause
cancer.
   U.S. District Judge Louis Oberdorfer ruled Wednesday that the
EPA had acted illegally by allowing 197 holders of federal
pesticide licenses to sell existing stocks of products containing
the pesticides chlordane and heptachlor.
   Oberdorfer said EPA failed to take into account whether
continued sale or use of the products ``would pose any unreasonable
risk to man or the environment.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A new blood test for AIDS antibodies virtually
eliminates the false positive readings that needlessly terrorize
healthy people, the test's creator claims.
   SmithKline Bio-Science Laboratories said Wednesday it would
perform the confirmatory tests at its own lab for $80 apiece, about
the same price as the tests they are intended to replace. It said
the service was available immediately.
   Doctors familiar with the new test said it was a major advance.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A new ``condom for females'' pioneered in Europe
will be tested this spring in the United States, and developers
predicted it would be a major weapon in the fight against AIDS and
other sexually transmitted diseases.
   The new disposable contraceptive, made of polyurethane,
resembles a condom but is worn by women, researchers said Wednesday
as they unveiled the device.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan says the decline in the value
of the dollar has opened opportunities for U.S. exporters but they
could be undermined by protectionist legislation Congress is
considering.
   ``The fact that the dollar's exchange rate is at a far more
realistic level is of great significance'' to the market for U.S.
exports, the president said Wednesday to members of Export Now, a
public-private group organized by the Commmerce Department.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Gold prices tumbled Wednesday as traders appeared to take a more
optimistic view of chances for continued low inflation. The dollar
was mixed in foreign exchange.
   The stock market was little changed. The Dow Jones average of 30
industrials edged up 0.83 to 2,039.95.
   Bond prices edged lower. Grain and soybean futures settled
mostly higher, livestock and meat futures were mixed; energy
futures retreated; and stock-index futures declined.
</TEXT>
