<1ST_LINE>r f PM-AIDSTest Bjt   02-25 0649</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-AIDS Test, Bjt,0668</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New AIDS Antibody Test Is More Exact, Company Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A new test that identifies AIDS virus antibodies
in blood is dramatically reducing the incidence of inconclusive
tests for evidence of the deadly disease, its maker says.
   Inconclusive results of AIDS tests can be terrifying for
patients because they raise the possibility of infection,
SmithKline Bio-Science Laboratories said Wednesday in announcing
immediate availability of the new test.
   Known as Hivagen, the new test also virtually eliminates false
positive readings, which are already uncommon under current testing
procedures for acquired immune deficiency syndrome, the
Philadelphia-based company said.
   ``This test is a quantum leap forward in AIDS testing,'' John
Mills, chief of infectious diseases at San Francisco General
Hospital, said in a statement released by SmithKline.
   Mills performed clinical trials on the value of Hivagen as a
replacement for the Western blot assay, the current standard test
for blood samples that flunk mass screenings.
   SmithKline said it would perform the tests at its own lab for
$80 apiece, about the same price as the Western blot assay.
   False positive readings, even though they represent a small
fraction of tests, have become more common because AIDS antibody
testing itself has become more common.
   About 29 million people will be screened for AIDS antibodies
this year, and about 500,000 will be referred for further tests,
SmithKline officials estimated. The company said false positive
readings might range as high as 5 percent on certain inferior
versions of the Western blot assay, commonly used for further
testing.
   In response, Du Pont Co. said its own widely used version of the
Western blot assay produces virtually no false positives because
the company has an extremely strict standard for what constitutes a
positive reading.
   SmithKline officials conceded the Du Pont test, the only one
licensed by the Food and Drug Administration for blood donor
screening, produces few if any false positives.
   With the Hivagen test, false positive readings simply cannot
occur, company officials asserted. But some scientists were
cautious.
   ``It may well be that this represents a substantial advance, but
you wonder whether it can really be perfect,'' said Dr. Klemens
Meyer, an internist and decision analyst at New England Medical
Center in Boston, who said he had no first-hand knowledge of
Hivagen.
   The presence of AIDS antibodies does not necessarily mean a
person has the disease. The most recent studies have shown that 30
percent to 40 percent of people with AIDS antibodies have later
developed the disease, although many doctors believe that
percentage will rise eventually.
   SmithKline has applied for patents on the synthetic molecules
used in the Hivagen test, said Martin Rosenberg, vice president of
biopharmaceutical research and development.
   In tests of more than 2,500 blood samples at San Francisco
General Hospital, Hivagen was inconclusive in 2.5 percent to 4.2
percent of the patients, vs. 15.6 percent to 18 percent
inconclusive results for the Western blot assay, said Dr. John
Mills, the hospital's chief of infectious diseases.
   In another test of the blood of volunteers, the Hivagen test was
accurate for all 225 people who did not have the AIDS antibody and
was accurate in 135 of the 136 patients without symptoms who did
have the AIDS antibody. In the lone exception, the test was
inconclusive, Mills said.
   Other companies also have introduced or are working on better
tests for AIDS, including Cetus Corp. of Emeryville, Calif., which
is developing a test for AIDS virus genes, and Cambridge BioScience
Corp. of Worcester, Mass., which has applied for regulatory
approval for an antibody test.
   The Hivagen test does not require FDA approval because the
technology is not for sale to others, Groome said. However, FDA
officials are aware of the test and have invited a SmithKline
scientist to speak on the subject at a conference next week in
Washington, he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
