<FILEID>AP-NR-02-25-88 0658EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-UMW-OCAW     02-25 0308</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-UMW-OCAW,0321</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Unions Reject Proposed Merger</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTHA BRYSON HODEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When plans for a national energy union fizzled,
United Mine Workers President Richard Trumka said he started
looking for other ways to expand his union's influence.
   ``We're going to pursue a policy of growth for our
organization,'' Trumka said Wednesday after the Oil Chemical and
Atomic Workers International Union and the UMW rejected a merger
agreement that would have created the United Mine, Energy and
Chemical Workers of America.
   ``I spent four or five hours last night with pencil and paper
trying to work out ways to expand our union,'' Trumka said.
   Trumka said he considers the failed merger ``a closed deal''
that won't be reconsidered, although OCAW spokesman Rod Rogers said
his union doesn't necessarily agree.
   ``It's always possible there could bea resurrection of the
idea,'' he said.
   ``There were compelling reasons why this merger was a good idea,
and those reasons haven't gone away,'' Rogers said. ``This
particular merger proposal is dead, yes, but we could take action
to re-initiate things.''
   Trumka said he was ready to look elsewhere to expand, however.
   ``I'll come back at the next (UMW) board meeting and say, `That
didn't work; let's try something else,''' Trumka said.
   The proposal for a merger between the two energy unions, which
each claim about 100,000 active members, was rejected Tuesday by
OCAW's executive board on a 6-2 vote, largely because it wanted
assurances there would be no dues increase, Trumka said. The UMW
then rescinded the approval it gave Sunday.
   Trumka said both unions would continue to work together,
especially on negotiations with common employers.
   While he plans to look for other ways to expand the UMW's
influence, Trumka said, he said he did not consider it good policy
``to merge just for the sake of merging.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
