<FILEID>AP-NR-02-25-88 0611EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-GMProduction Bjt   02-25 0616</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-GM Production, Bjt,0637</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>GM Restoring Production, Recalling 8,600 Laid-off Workers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JANET BRAUNSTEIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Auto Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Automaking giant General Motors Corp., which a
year ago was wallowing in lotfuls of unsold cars, is showing signs
of resurgence because of higher demand for profitable models and an
aggressive sales-incentive campaign.
   The biggest U.S. automaker announced Wednesday that it will add
about 130,000 cars and 45,000 trucks to previously trimmed 1988
production plans and recall 8,600 employees at four factories.
   The expansion will be made via restoration of second shifts at
three plants, reopening of a closed plant in Framingham, Mass., and
running some plants on overtime.
   ``The strengthening demand for GM vehicles reflects the ongoing
product quality improvements resulting from plant modernization and
employee involvement programs,'' GM President Robert Stempel said
in a statement.
   ``This combined with very competitive retail incentive programs
has increased the value of GM products,'' he said.
   At the three plants where GM had dropped the second shift,
workers from both shifts were sharing jobs by alternating between
two weeks on layoff and two weeks on the job, GM said.
   The Framingham assembly plant, which GM closed abruptly Nov. 30,
will reopen May 9 on one shift with 2,000 of its 3,700 workers. The
plant will build the Oldsmobile Cutlass Cierra, but will not resume
production of the Chevrolet Celebrity, GM spokeswoman Kathy Tanner
said.
   GM will restore the second shift at its
Buick-Oldsmobile-Cadillac Group assembly plant in Lansing, Mich.,
April 11, returning 2,000 people to full-time work. The
4,350-worker plant builds the Oldsmobile Cutlass Calais and Buick
Skylark.
   The second shift at GM's 4,200-worker Van Nuys, Calif., assembly
plant will be restored March 14, bringing 1,900 employees back full
time. The plant, which is GM's only Chevrolet Camaro and Pontiac
Firebird source, dropped the second shift last week.
   GM also will restore the second shift at its Oshawa No. 1 plant
in Oshawa, Ontario, bringing back 2,700 laid-off workers on March
21. The plant builds the Oldsmobile Cierra and Pontiac 6000.
   The company said it would increase production at the Cadillac
plant in the Detroit enclave of Hamtramck by running its single
shift on overtime, adding 4,700 cars between Feb. 20 and June 1.
   Cadillac General Manager John Grettenberger said the increased
production was necessary because dealers need more of the restyled
Eldorado coupe and Seville sedans, enjoying high popularity due to
a new engine model.
   GM's expansion plans contrast sharply to the same time about a
year ago, when it suffered slumping sales, a three-month backlog of
vehicles and loss of market share to its main U.S. rivals, Ford
Motor Co. and Chrysler Corp.
   Uncertainty over GM's prospects was heightened after the October
stock market crash, which raised fears that consumers would buy
fewer cars. All domestic automakers trimmed production plans
afterward, but pessimism has since been eased by healthy sales.
   In January, Ford Motor Co., the nation's No. 2 automaker, added
75,000 cars to its plans for the first half of 1987, including
53,000 cars in the second quarter, said Ford spokesman Raymond
Windecker.
   Chrysler Corp., the No. 3 automaker, announced plans last week
to add 20,000 cars to its second-quarter schedule.
   Chris Cedergren, an industry analyst with the firm J.D. Power
and Associates, said the change in GM's plans reflect ``a little
bit of resurgence'' of sales.
   He noted that the added cars are high-profit models, an
indication that GM's profitability may improve in 1988 after two
years of higher earnings by Ford.
   The changes do not affect GM's Buick-Oldsmobile-Cadillac Group
assembly plant in Kansas City, Mo., still scheduled to shut down
indefinitely on April 15, idling 1,600 workers, GM spokesman Tom
Pyden said.
</TEXT>
