<1ST_LINE>r f PM-FemaleCondom Bjt   02-25 0686</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Female Condom, Bjt,0708</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Independent Researcher Questions Effectiveness of New Female
Condom</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM C. HIDLAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A new ``condom for females,'' pioneered in
Europe, was hailed by developers as revolutionary, but an
independent researcher questioned the device's effectiveness.
   The disposable contraceptive, made of polyurethane, resembles a
condom but is worn by women, researchers said Wednesday as they
publicly unveiled the device.
   The developers said the female condom would be effective at
preventing pregnancy and predicted it would become a major weapon
in the fight against the spread of AIDS and other sexually
transmitted diseases.
   ``It takes the advantages of both the male condom and the female
diaphragm and gets rid of significant disadvantages,'' said Mary
Ann Leeper, head of the research team developing the device for
Wisconsin Pharmacal Co., which will market it in the United States
and Canada.
   But Dr. Gerald Zatuchni, a gynecologist with 25 years experience
in researching and developing new contraceptives, said he saw the
potential for ``real problems'' with the device.
   ``I have not seen the device nor have there been any published
studies that would indicate its acceptability to couples, the
effectiveness of the device in preventing pregnancy or any
side-effects from using the device,'' Zatuchni said.
   The device, known in Europe as a ``fem-shield'' or vaginal
shield, isn't sold anywhere yet, but testing has begun in Europe
and is to start in the United States in March, officials said.
   The developers said they wouldn't have statistics on how
effective the device is in preventing pregnancy or the spread of
diseases like acquired immune deficiency syndrome until additional
studies are completed.
   The contraceptive consists of a soft, loose-fitting polyurethane
sheath and two diaphragm-like, flexible polyurethane rings, Ms.
Leeper said.
   One ring lies inside the sheath and serves as an insertion
mechanism and internal anchor, fitting against the woman's cervix
much like a diaphragm, she said. The other ring forms the outer
edge of the sheath and remains outside the vagina.
   ``It is no more difficult to insert than a tampon,'' said Dr.
Paul Salmon, who helped organize tests of the device at London's
Middlesex Hospital.
   The company, based in Jackson, Wis., said the device would
provide more protection than the male condom, in part because the
material is stronger and covers a larger physical area, reducing
chances of infection or exposure to body fluids.
   It also would be more convenient to use than a diaphragm, Ms.
Leeper said, because it doesn't have to be initially fitted by a
doctor and can be inserted ``six hours before the sex act or six
minutes before.''
   But Zatuchni, a gynecology and obstetrics professor at
Northwestern University Medical School in Chicago, said the idea of
a ``one-size-fits-all'' condom for females ``would be sort of
ridiculous because women's anatomy varies so much.''
   ``It would be hard to envision such a device staying on during
the act of intercourse,'' Zatuchni said.
   Ms. Leeper said proper fitting would take place during
intercourse.
   She said the company had no estimate on how much the device
would cost consumers.
   The ``female condom'' was developed by an international group of
gynecologists and obstetricians, headed by Danish gynecologist Dr.
Erik Gregersen and his wife, Bente.
   The device has been tested on 80 couples in the United Kingdom,
Denmark and Sweden, and additional clinical trials are continuing
in Europe, Ms. Leeper said.
   The World Health Organization also plans to conduct clinical
trials in 15 countries, including Brazil, Thailand, Singapore and
nations battling the spread of AIDS in central Africa.
   AIDS, a deadly disease with no known cure, is believed to be
spread mainly through sexual intercourse, shared hypodermic needles
and from infected mothers to their infants at or before birth.
   In the United States, a first round of 500 clinical tests of the
new contraceptive is to begin in March, followed by a second phase
of 1,000 tests in May, Ms. Leeper said.
   The company hopes to apply to the U.S. Food and Drug
Administration this summer for permission to begin marketing the
device commercially in the United States by the end of the year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
