<DOCNO> AP880225-0286 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-25-88 0701EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-HuntBrothers-Silver     02-25 0469</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Hunt Brothers-Silver,0486</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Civil Lawsuit Against Hunt Brothers Opens in Manhattan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The lawyer for a South American mineral concern
suing the Hunt brothers of Dallas opened his case Wednesday by
spinning a tale of financial intrigue involving Texas oilmen and
Arab sheiks.
   Minpeco S.A., a mineral marketing company owned by the Peruvian
government, is suing the three Hunt brothers, claiming they
conspired to corner the world silver market in 1979 and 1980.
   Named as defendants in the case that opened before U.S. District
Judge Morris E. Lasker were: Nelson Bunker Hunt, William Herbert
Hunt and Lamar Hunt.
   ``We will show that they did this using their incredible
fortunes with utter contempt for the legal and economic system that
was so good to them,'' Mark Cymrot, attorney for Minpeco, told the
jury in his opening statement at federal court in Manhattan.
   None of the Hunts were present in court and they were not
expected to appear until the defense begins its case.
   Other defendants include Mahmoud Fustok, described as the owner
of one of the world's largest thoroughbred stables and
brother-in-law of a Saudi Arabian prince.
   ``We will show that they were greedy, power-hungry and
unscrupulous,'' said Cymrot, adding ``What we intend to show is
that these men rigged the silver market.''
   He claimed that the Hunts and their alleged co-conspirators were
responsible for the sharp rise in silver prices from about $9 an
ounce to more than $50 an ounce between September 1979 and January
1980.
   Minpeco claims the skyrocketing prices caused it to lose more
than $100 million when the world silver market collapsed in March
1980, with prices falling back to about $10 an ounce.
   Six financial institutions accused of participating in the
alleged conspiracy have settled with Minpeco for a total of $64.6
million.
   Minpeco is seeking about $150 million in damages plus treble
damages under both the anti-trust and racketeering laws which it
claims the Hunts and thier co-conspirators violated.
   But in his opening argument to the jury, the Hunts's lawyer
belittled those claims.
   The defense lawyer, Paul Curran, said rising interest rates,
inflation and crude oil prices, coupled with an unstable world
political situation, led to the silver market price rise.
   He ticked off the Iranian revolution, the seizure of American
hostages at the U.S. embassy in Teheran and the Soviet invasion of
Afghanistan.
   ``It was these world and economic events that were the reason
for the sharp rise in silver prices,'' said Curran.
   He conceded silver prices went up, but noted gold, platinum and
diamond prices also rose during the same period because ``the price
of silver has historically fluctuated as a result of events in the
market place and in the world.''
   The trial is expected to last several months.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880225-0287 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-25-88 0736EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-ToxicWarnings     02-25 0679</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Toxic Warnings,0699</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>California Begins Posting Toxic Warnings In Stores, Workplace</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Report for Thursday AMs.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER KERR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Signs warning of potentially harmful
chemicals in everything from foods to workplaces will sprout across
California this weekend under a law approved by voters in 1986.
   ``WARNING: This product contains a chemical known to the State
of California to cause cancer.'' This sign could be seen on store
shelves.
   ``WARNING: Chemicals known to the State of California to cause
cancer, or birth defects or other reproductive harm may be present
in foods or beverages sold or served here.'' This sign could be
printed on restaurant menus.
   ``WARNING: This area contains a chemical known to the State of
California to cause cancer.'' This sign could be posted on a
service station island, along a factory fence or on an assembly
line.
   In addition, there will be labels, newsaper advertisements,
letters and telephone hot lines telling people about chemicals in
the products they buy and the environment in which they work and
live.
   But there probably won't be any warning signs for the more than
15,000 grocery, drug and cosmetic products bought every day.
Temporary state regulations say that such products manufactured
under existing state and federal rules don't have to contain
warnings.
   The signs will be the first visible result of the anti-toxics
initiative approved by voters following a bitter struggle between
environmentalists who wrote the measure, including the Sierra Club
and the Environmental Defense Fund, and business interests.
   Proposition 65 will also mean confusion, with businesses
responding differently to its warning requirements. And dozens of
lawsuits could occupy the courts for years as supporters and
opponents continue to quarrel over its intent and requirements.
   ``The period ahead will be filled with charges and
countercharges, pressures and counterpressures and intense
courtroom litigation,'' says Assemblyman Tom Hayden, one of the
initiative's major backers and the leader of a star-studded
Hollywood group that campaigned hard for the measure.
   ``There are probably still people who wish the proposition had
never happened ... but there are people who have come to grips with
it as an expression of people's concern,'' said Thomas Warriner of
the state Health and Welfare Agency, who wrote the regulations.
   The initiative requires anyone who causes people to be exposed
to any of 29 chemicals known to the state to cause cancer or birth
defects to issue an advance warning.
   Those chemicals include five that business officials say are
present in varying levels throughout society: asbestos, benzene,
lead, chromium and arsenic.
   For example, benzene is in gasoline and most service stations
will probably have to post warning signs on their fuel islands.
Chromium is in stainless steel, magnetic tapes, paint pigments and
cement.
   Also, citizens who feel they've been exposed to a cancer- or
birth defect-causing chemical can take action if authorities won't
and collect 25 percent of any eventual fine.
   Republican Gov. George Deukmejian, who opposed the initiative,
followed issued the list of 29 chemicals ``known to the state to
cause cancer or reproductive toxicity'' and has appointed a
12-member panel to study whether more than 200 other chemicals
should be added to the list.
   Backers of the plan sued Deukmejian, saying the initiative
required about 250 chemicals to be on the first list. A Superior
Court judge agreed, but the Deukmejian's appeal is pending.
   The advisory panel has in the past year added almost all the
200-plus chemicals to the list. But adding them later, rather than
on Feb. 27, means they are subject to the initiative's other
requirements at later dates.
   The initiative requires any business with 10 or more employes to
give a ``clear and reasonable warning'' before exposing anyone to
any of the chemicals on the list, beginning one year after their
making the list.
   Another part of the initiative doesn't take effect until Oct. 27
for the first 27 chemicals. That part prohibits businesses from
discharging any of the listed chemicals into drinking water
sources, beginning 20 months after a chemical's inclusion on the
list.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880225-0288 </DOCNO>
