<1ST_LINE>r f PM-SantaFe-Henley     02-25 0545</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Santa Fe-Henley,0563</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Santa Fe Rejects Henley's Takeover Offer</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Henley Group Inc., rebuffed in its latest attempt
to take control of Santa Fe Southern Pacific Corp., has accepted
the rejection quietly.
   ``We are disappointed but not surprised,'' said Henley spokesman
Norm Ritter.
   Santa Fe Southern on Wednesday turned down Henley's bid to buy
44.6 million new shares for $780 million. The offer, made on
Monday, was conditioned up the company abandoning its ``poison
pill'' takeover defense and restructuring a $4.7 billion special
dividend to stockholders.
   The Chicago railroad, land and natural resources concern also
rebuffed Henley late last year when Henley offered to buy the
entire company for $63 a share, or $8.34 billion.
   Santa Fe's directors discussed the latest proposal with their
investment bankers and legal advisers and concluded the plan would
benefit only Henley, Santa Fe President Robert D. Krebs said in a
letter to Michael Dingman, Henley's chairman.
   ``That ownership percentage would transfer effective control of
the company without the payment of a control premium to our
shareholders,'' Krebs wrote. ``In addition, the offer would dilute
the interests of all our shareholders except for The Henley Group.''
   Henley's proposal would have given it 34.3 percent ownership of
Santa Fe. The La Jolla, Calif., manufacturing, engineering and
financial-services firm currently holds a 15.7 percent stake.
   Santa Fe stock rose 75 cents to $24.25 share Wednesday in New
York Stock Exchange trading.
   Krebs said in his letter to Dingman that Santa Fe's
special-dividend plan represented a better value to shareholders
than the alternative proposed by Henley.
   The rejected Henley proposal asked Santa Fe to stop the planned
March 1 payment of $5 per share in ``junk bonds'' for each of its
157.3 million shares. Santa Fe already has made a $25-per-share
cash payout as part of the special dividend.
   Henley contends the bonds will leave shareholders with a large
tax liability because of the way they are structured.
   Instead, Henley proposed that Santa Fe sell it $780 million
worth of new stock at $17.50 per share. Proceeds from that deal
would have been used to make a one-time $5-a-share cash payout to
all shareholders.
   Henley had also asked Santa Fe to void the poison pill takeover
defense it adopted in December.
   Under the defense, if any stockholder's stake exceeds 20
percent, other Santa Fe shareholders would be permitted to buy new
stock at half price, diluting the hostile buyer's stake and making
a takeover prohibitively expensive.
   Henley has said the takeover defense restricts the
maneuverability of major holders like itself and Toronto-based real
estate concern Olympia & York Developments Ltd.
   Olympia & York, which is controlled by Canada's Reichmann
family, has a 10.5 percent stake in Santa Fe. The company last week
launched a $17.50 a share million tender offer worth $245 million
to boost its holdings to 19.9 percent.
   Olympia & York had agreed to support Santa Fe's restructuring in
return for two seats on the Santa Fe board.
   Meanwhile, Henley is waging a proxy fight in hopes of gaining
control of Santa Fe's board of directors at the company's May 24
annual meeting, and is suing Santa Fe in Delaware, where both
companies are incorporated, to block the $4.7 billion special
dividend.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
