<1ST_LINE>u f PM-EconomyRdp-1stLd-Writethru     02-25 0622</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Economy Rdp-1st Ld-Writethru,0639</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Auto Sales Rise, Deficit Declines</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 6 grafs to UPDATE with revised estimate of
fourth-quarter GNP.; uppicks 3rd graf pvs: Exports rose...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. economy surged ahead at its fastest pace in two years _
a robust 4.5 percent annual rate _ in the last quarter of 1987, the
government said today.
   The Commerce Department's measure of growth in the gross
national product, the total output of goods and services, amounted
to an upward revision from a month ago, when the GNP was put at a
slightly slower 4.2 percent growth rate.
   Such a strong performance is usually considered good news, but
some economists fear this time may be an exception.
   They note that three-fourths of the $42 billion in growth in the
October-December quarter came from a $32.1 billion rise in business
inventories, which came as consumer spending was falling at its
fastest rate in more than seven years.
   That means production will have to be cut back sharply in coming
months to work down the excess inventories _ meaning the overall
economy will also probably slow as well in the first half of 1988.
   A separate report Wednesday offered encouraging news on another
front, however, when the Commerce Department said record exports
helped shrink the nation's trade deficit at the end of 1987.
   Exports rose 6 percent as the trade deficit narrowed to $40.2
billion on a balance-of-payments basis in the last three months of
the year, the department said. It was the first quarterly
improvement since the spring of 1986.
   ``We have a genuine export boom going on and I think a lot of
people are pleasantly surprised,'' Robert Ortner, undersecretary of
commerce for economic affairs, said in announcing the turnaround.
   In other economic news Wednesday, sales of U.S.-made cars and
light trucks jumped 14.5 percent in mid-February in a development
that analysts attributed to plentiful, aggressive buyer incentives.
   ``The consumer has more confidence in the economy than the
analysts do,'' said Chris Cedergren, industry analyst with J.D.
Power and Associates in Agoura Hills, Calif.
   The news had little impact on Wall Street, where the Dow Jones
average of 30 industrials edged up 0.83 point to 2,039.95. The Dow
fell 1.17 on Tuesday.
   Gold prices tumbled on expectations of continued low inflation.
Republic National Bank of New York quoted a bid price for gold of
$432.80 a troy ounce as of 4 p.m. EST, down $8.70 from Tuesday's
late level.
   The dollar, meanwhile, turned in a narrowly mixed performance on
the world's foreign-exchange markets. Bond prices edged marginally
lower as a major new issue of Treasury bonds waited in the wings.
   Ortner said further improvements in trade were likely in the
months ahead because of the beneficial effects of the cheaper
dollar, which has declined sharply in value since late 1985 as part
of a Reagan administration effort to thwart protectionist sentiment
in Congress.
   Still, the year finished with a record $159.3 billion
balance-of-payments trade deficit for all of 1987, the report said.
   In volume alone, the trade deficit actually showed a 5 percent
improvement from 1986 to 1987. The fact that import prices rose
more rapidly than export prices helped mask this improvement,
Commerce Department analysts said.
   The new figures confirmed an end-of-year narrowing of the trade
shortfall that already had shown up in the department's monthly
merchandise trade reports. The earlier figures showed a $43 billion
deficit for the fourth quarter and a $171.2 billion shortfall for
all of 1987.
   Wednesday's figures were smaller because they subtracted factors
such as the cost of shipping, insurance and military sales from the
monthly numbers. The balance-of-payments deficit is also adjusted
for seasonal variations; the monthly figures are not.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
