<1ST_LINE>r f BC-BrokenHill     02-25 0436</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Broken Hill,0450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Broken Hill Shareholders Approve Restructuring, Stock Buyback</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MELBOURNE, Australia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Shareholders of Broken Hill
Proprietary Co. on Thursday approved a major restructuring of
Australia's largest company, which included the repurchase of most
BHP shares owned by its two biggest stockholders.
   Under the plan outlined late last month, Broken Hill will pay
2.1 billion Australian dollars, about $1.5 billion at current
exchange rates, to buy back 300 million BHP shares controlled by
financier Robert Holmes a Court, a persistent suitor for the
company.
   The buyback will reduce Holmes a Court's stake, held by his Bell
Resources conglomerate, to 10 percent from 29 percent.
   Broken Hill also plans to pay 575 million Australian dollars to
Elders IXL Ltd., a diversified company run by entrepreneur John
Elliott, for a 50 percent interest in an Elders unit that owns 19
percent of BHP, reducing Elliott's Broken Hill stake by half.
   Elliott and Holmes a Court also will resign from Broken Hill's
board of directors.
   The steel, oil and mining company, which has major holdings in
the United States, South America and elsewhere has been eager to
reduce the influence of both entrepreneurs, especially because of
Holmes a Court's repeated attempts in recent years to buy control
of the giant company.
   Elders had acquired its stake in Broken Hill in 1986 to thwart a
takeover attempt by Holmes a Court.
   Broken Hill also had been concerned that Holmes a Court and
Elliott might dump their shares following October's stock market
crash, depressing the company's stock price.
   Companies controlled by Holmes a Court lost about 500 million
Australian dollars in the stock market crash, the biggest corporate
loss in Australian history, due to investment writedowns. The
financier has been selling a number of assets to help ease cash
problems raised by the sharp decline in its market value during the
crash.
   Broken Hill is selling at least 1 billion Australian dollars
worth of non-strategic investments and assets to help finance its
restructuring, which was expected to cost 2.68 billion Australian
dollars, about $1.9 billion.
   Sir James Balderstone, chairman of Broken Hill, said the
restructuring would not be completed for several months.
   Balderstone said the plan would be completed once the
transactions with Holmes a Court and Elliott were settled, Broken
Hill shareholders approved the plan to cancel the 300 million
shares acquired from Holmes a Court and Australia's Supreme Court
approved the reduction in Broken Hill's capital.
   Broken Hill's plans received clearance Tuesday by Australian
securities regulators, who said they would not take any action
because shareholders of all companies involved were to vote on the
proposals.
</TEXT>
