<1ST_LINE>u f PM-AutoSales 1stLd-Writethru f0010 02-25 0587</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Auto Sales, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0010,0602</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS new 3rd graf with comment from Phillippi about
incentives; SUBS 14th graf to remove first reference to Phillippi;
picks up 15th graf pvs bg'ng, Sales of ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JANET BRAUNSTEIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Auto Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sales of domestic cars and light trucks in
mid-February slowed from early in the month but jumped 14.5 percent
over the same period a year earlier, reflecting aggressive buyer
incentives offered by automakers.
   General Motors Corp., Ford Motor Co. and Chrysler Corp.
Wednesday reported healthy sales increases over a year earlier,
which were not shared by most foreign makers who build cars in this
country.
   ``They had a lot of help from incentives. I think that's pretty
evident looking at Chrysler's numbers. Chrysler has had huge
incentives,'' said Joseph Phillippi, an analyst with Shearson
Lehman Hutton Inc. in New York.
   Total domestic car sales rose 11.9 percent in the nine selling
days from Feb. 11-20, while domestic truck sales, which increased
for all makers, jumped 19.6 percent as the surge in light-truck
popularity showed no sign of slowing.
   The eight companies building domestic vehicles sold 325,422 cars
and light trucks in mid-February, up from 284,278 a year earlier _
210,316 cars and 115,106 trucks, compared with 188,001 cars and
96,277 trucks a year earlier.
   But mid-February domestic car sales moved at a seasonally
adjusted rate of less than 7.8 million a year, down from an 8.4
million rate in early February.
   ``The consumer has more confidence in the economy than the
analysts do,'' said Chris Cedergren, industry analyst with J.D.
Power and Associates in Agoura Hills, Calif.
   ``All economic indicators point to lower sales for 1988 than
1987,'' Cedergren said. ``We do expect the downward trend to
continue.''
   Nevertheless, the Big Three have shown renewed optimism toward
the U.S. economy and vehicle market, increasing planned production
for 1988 in reverses of cuts planned after the stock market crash
in October.
   GM announced Wednesday it is restoring second shifts at three
plants, reopening a Framingham, Mass., assembly plant on one shift
and boosting overtime at other car and truck plants.
   The increases will put 8,600 laid-off workers back on the job
and will add 175,000 cars and trucks to GM's 1988 production
schedule.
   In mid-February, Chrysler led the Big Three in domestic car
sales increases with a 21.7 percent boost. Chrysler's domestic
truck sales rose even further, jumping 47.3 percent over
mid-February 1986.
   GM reported a 16.3 percent increase in domestic car sales and a
21.8 percent boost in domestic truck sales over mid-February a year
earlier. Ford's car sales rose 2.2 percent and truck sales
increased 5.4 percent.
   Ford's share of the domestic car market fell to 28.8 percent
from 31.5 percent a year earlier, while GM's share jumped to 50.7
percent from 48.8 percent a year earlier and Chrysler's share grew
to 15.5 percent from 14.3 percent a year earlier.
   Gains by GM and Chrysler were somewhat deceptive because both
had weaker sales in mid-February 1986 than Ford, and both have
needed to use incentives more aggressively than Ford this year,
Phillippi said.
   Sales of U.S.-built cars fell 4.5 percent for Honda Motor Co.,
23.9 percent for Volkswagen and 10.7 percent for Nissan Motor Corp.
   Toyota Motor Corp. sales of domestic cars rose 72.2 percent,
continuing a buildup from 1987. Toyota, like Mazda Motor Corp., has
only been building cars in the United States for a short time.
   Mazda began U.S. production in the fall at its Flat Rock
assembly plant.
</TEXT>
