<HEAD>Prices Tumble Amid Oversupply Fears</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: new throughout with morning activity. No pickup</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oil prices tumbled substantially today,
reflecting growing market nervousness that world supplies are
increasing too fast.
   At midday, contracts for April delivery of West Texas
Intermediate, the benchmark U.S. crude, stood at $16.03 per
42-gallon barrel, down 43 cents from Wednesday's close on the New
York Mercantile Exchange.
   Among March contracts for refined products, wholesale heating
oil was selling at 45.45 cents a gallon, down 0.95 cent from
Wednesday, while unleaded gasoline stood at 45.45 cents per gallon,
0.90 cent lower.
   Peter Beutel, assistant director of the energy group at Elders
Futures Inc., said fundamental and technical factors were pushing
the prices lower, with crude touching as little as $15.98 a barrel
at one point before struggling back.
   ``OPEC is producing about 1 million barrels a day more than it
was a month ago, and this perception is getting into the market _
which isn't thrilled by it,'' he said.
   Recent estimates have put production by members of the
Organization of petroleum Exporting Countries close to 18 million
barrels a day.
   Beutel said the slide also picked up after crude broke below
$16.37 a barrel, ``which had been seen as a very important support
level.''
</TEXT>
