<HEAD>Grain, Soybean Futures Open Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices opened lower
across the board today on the Chicago Board of Trade.
   New rains in the major soybean-growing region of Brazil prompted
selling of U.S. soybean futures, analysts said. Traders are
watching the South American soybean crop closely as harvest time
rapidly approaches.
   ``The thinking is that inevitably (U.S. soybean) prices will go
down as these crops come in, unless we get some major improvement
in demand, which is not likely,'' said Walter Spilka, an analyst
for Smith Barney, Harris Upham & Co. in New York.
   Corn futures failed to follow through on Wednesday's gains,
which were spurred by rumors of Soviet purchases of U.S. corn.
   The Agriculture Department announced after the close of trading
Wednesday that the Soviets had purchased 350,000 metric tons of
U.S. corn, an amount that Spilka said was ``not enough to carry the
markets very far.''
   Wheat futures slipped lower on a lack of fresh supportive news,
he said.
   In early trading, wheat was \ cent to 1\ cents lower with the
contract for delivery in March at $3.16} a bushel; corn was { cent
to 1{ cents lower with March at $1.98 a bushel; oats were } cent to
1\ cents lower with March at $1.89{ a bushel; soybeans were 2{
cents to 4 cents ower with March at $6.22\ a bushel.
   Livestock and meat futures were mixed to lower in early trading
on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .25 cent lower to .10 cent higher with April at
71.95 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .03 cent to .27 cent lower
with March at 80.80 a pound; live hogs were unchanged to .12 cent
lower with April at 44 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were
unchanged to .47 cent higher with March at(52.45 cents a pound.
   Cattle futures closed mostly higher on Wednesday while pork
futures ended mixed.
