<1ST_LINE>a f BC-PersonalFile-Evans Adv26   02-25 0884</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Personal File-Evans, Adv 26,0908</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 26</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Friday Feb 26 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Harry Evans: From Fleet Street to Madison Avenue</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former top editor of one of the world's most
powerful newspapers has taken up a new challenge: to send people
packing.
   Harold Evans, who resigned as editor of The Times of London in
1982 in a dispute with owner Rupert Murdoch over editorial
independence, has changed his itinerary to become editor in chief
of a new travel magazine, Conde Nast's Traveler.
   Traveler, launched last fall by Conde Nast Publications Inc., a
division of privately-owned Newhouse Newspapers, already prides
itself in being different from the scores of other magazines aimed
at the booming travel industry.
   It is hard-hitting _ in the tradition of Fleet Street, not
Madison Avenue _ with pointed writing, vivid photographs, fold-out
maps and offbeat humor.
   Evans planned the magazine for Conde Nast starting in September
1986 _ following stints as editorial director of U.S. News & World
Report and editor in chief of Atlantic Monthly Press, a publishing
company.
   The 59-year-old ``Harry'' Evans has put his personal stamp on
Traveler, which has a full-time staff of around 40 and claims a
monthly circulation of some 900,000 copies. For starters, unlike
traditional travel magazines, Traveler doesn't allow its writers to
accept free trips or accommodations.
   ``We pay our own way; the plan is to be truthful,'' Evans said
in an interview in his office on Madison Avenue. ``We print things
without fear.''
   That policy has generated, for example, an investigative article
on airline safety and a report that 22 of 56 cruise liners failed
recent inspections by the U.S. Public Health Service.
   Such ``truth in travel'' has already had repercussions. Last
November, after Traveler printed a summary of a report by the World
Health Organization on air pollution in more than 50 cities around
the world, ads for VARIG Brazilian Airlines were pulled from the
magazine.
   The advertising agency for VARIG, Jonas Berger Associates, told
Traveler it cancelled the ads for Brazil's national airline because
it couldn't ``understand the logic in your telling your readers
about the pollution problem in Rio de Janeiro.''
   Evans, in turn, fired off an unrepentant editorial. ``Readers
are tired of fluff and puff,'' he wrote. ``They know it's a big
world where sometimes it's sunny and sometimes it rains. They want
to be stimulated, but they want to explore and enjoy with all the
facts and insights they can acquire.''
   The editor's pull-no-punches approach has led Traveler to take
other strong editorial stands _ advocating, for instance, efforts
to preserve wildlife in Africa and natural beauty spots in the
United States.
   The magazine's brash approach may have been emboldened by the
built-in circulation it inherited from its predecessor, Signature
magazine. Conde Nast, a titan of magazine publishing, bought
Signature in January 1987 from Citicorp Diner's Club for around $40
million _ then relaunched it as Traveler last September.
   Although Traveler is a completely new product, it picked up a
circulation of around 700,000 copies a month from the defunct
Signature.
   In its first four issues (from September through December of
last year), Traveler carried 198.5 advertising pages, bringing in
around $4.2 million in ad revenues, according to figures compiled
by the Publishers Information Bureau.
   Ronald Galotti, Traveler's publisher, said the magazine is
aiming for more than 500 ad pages this year, which would translate
into $12 million to $13 million in revenues. ``We're running very,
very much on target,'' he said.
   Travel & Leisure, a magazine owned by American Express Co. that
is the dominant force in the travel field, carried around 1,227
pages last year fetching $38.5 million.
   Evans seems to relish bridging the gap between his hard-knocks
newspaper upbringing and the upscale world of magazines. At work,
he is a whirling dervish of energy _ talking rapid-fire,
punctuating his remarks by jumping up to pull out documents and
magazines to illustrate his points, fretting over a technical
production problem. He seems to have brought the high-tension level
of a big-city newspaper to the normally more subdued environs of
magazine publishing.
   A native of Manchester in England's industrial north, he started
in 1954 as a reporter for the Manchester Evening News and later
became editor of The Northern Echo, a regional daily.
   Evans is no stranger to this country. Besides his more recent
jobs with U.S. News and Atlantic Monthly, he spent 15 months here
in 1984 on a journalism fellowship, advising and working on several
small-town newspapers. He also was an adviser to Gannett Co. Inc.,
which publishes USA Today.
   He has encouraged offbeat humor in Traveler _ like a guide to
shoe-shopping in Paris titled ``Confessions of a Shoe Fetishist''
and a regular feature called ``Room with a View'' profiling
specific hotel rooms. October's was Room 472 in the Hotel Splendido
in Portofino, Italy, where Elizabeth Taylor and Richard Burton
stayed in 1976.
   The magazine's style, with a breezy sophistication bordering on
snobbishness, has prompted some critics in publishing circles to
deride Traveler as ``Vanity Fair goes to the beach.'' The editor in
chief of Vanity Fair, another Conde Nast magazine that touts good
writing, is Tina Brown _ who is married to Evans.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Friday Feb 26</NOTE>
</DOC>
