<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market ran up a broad gain today,
reviving its recent rally after sluggish showings in the past two
sessions.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials rose 17.58 to 2,057.53
by 2 p.m. on Wall Street, making a run at new highs since the crash
last fall.
   Advancing issues outnumbered declines by more than 2 to 1 in the
overall tally of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 1,026
up, 458 down and 432 unchanged.
   Before the opening the Commerce Department said the nation's
gross nation product grew at a 4.5 percent annual rate, after
adjustment for inflation, in the fourth quarter of last year.
   The department had previously estimated the pace of growth for
the October-December period at 4.2 percent.
   The upward revision was somewhat smaller than some analysts had
been expecting. But traders still apparently saw it as a plus for
the business outlook.
   Many Wall Streeters were still watching to see whether the Dow
Jones industrials could close above the 2,051.89 mark reached on
Jan. 7, which stood as the average's closing high since the crash
last October.
   Eastman Kodak led the active list, up 1] at 42}. The company
said it expects its 1988 earnings to be a good deal higher than
recently published estimates by Wall Street analysts.
   Airline stocks were broadly higher with a lift from falling oil
prices. Delta Air Lines climbed 1[ to 48\; AMR 1| to 40\; NWA 1[ to
42\, and Allegis 1| to 76[.
   Compaq Computer rose 1{ to 48| in active trading. The stock was
added to Standard & Poor's 500-stock composite index, prompting
buying by so-called index funds set up to duplicate the performance
of the 500.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks
gained 1.10 to 149.64. At the American Stock Exchange, the market
value index was up 2.41 at 285.61.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 147.06 million shares with two
hours to go.
