<HEAD>Conrail Engineer Calls for Random Drug Testing of Rail Workers</HEAD>
<HEAD>Ed: Inserts graf 9, Conrail spokesman, with Conrail no-comment.
Also removes ``prepared'' in grafs 2, I believe, and 5, While the
act; Also moved on general newswires</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Conrail engineer convicted of manslaughter
after a train crash that killed 16 people said today drug and
alcohol abuse are a major problem in the railroad industry and
random testing of rail workers is needed.
   ``I believe that random drug and alcohol testing is the
appropriate response to an industry-wide problem,'' the engineer,
Ricky L. Gates, said in testimony to the Senate Commerce Committee.
   Gates has pleaded guilty to manslaughter in the Jan. 4, 1987,
crash in which the Conrail locomotive he was driving slammed into a
crowded Amtrak train near Chase, Md. Sixteen people were killed and
175 were hurt in the crash.
   Gates has admitted he smoked marijuana shortly before the
accident. The National Transportation Safety Board has said that
marijuana use by Gates and his brakeman, Edward W. Cromwell, was
the primary cause of the accident.
   ``While the act of using the marijuana contributed to his
inattentiveness, there is no proof that Mr. Gates was impaired,''
one of Gates' lawyers, Donna Shearer, said in testimony for the
Senate committee.
   ``I cannot begin to imagine the pain and grief I have caused
those touched by the accident,'' said the statement by Gates, who
faces sentencing March 29. ``I am sorry.''
   Gates said railroad management ``often looks the other way''
when a worker has a drug or alcohol problem. ``I know this because
once when I was called to work ... I told the dispatcher that I was
intoxicated and could not work,'' he said. ``I was told if I did
not report I would be cited for refusing duty.''
   ``I believe that drug and alcohol use is widespread in the
industry,'' Gates said.
   Conrail spokesman Pat Linsky said the railroad was studying
Gates' remarks, and would have no immediate comment.
   The Senate last year approved legislation that would require
various types of drug and alcohol testing of rail, airline,
trucking and bus company employees. But the House has yet to act on
similar legislation.
   The most controversial type of testing proposed is random
testing of transportation workers. Supporters say random testing is
the only true deterrent to drug and alcohol abuse, while opponents
say such testing is an invasion of privacy and is often inaccurate.
   Earlier this month, a federal court in San Francisco ruled that
testing rail workers involved in accidents based on a suspicion
that they had recently used drugs or alcohol is illegal.
   Sen. Ernest Hollings, D-S.C., chairman of the Senate panel,
expressed frustration that the House has so far not approved a bill
requiring drug and alcohol testing of transportation workers.
   ``No one has a constitutional right to drive under the
influence, or fly under the influence,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
