<FILEID>AP-NR-02-25-88 0737EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Turner-Dividend     02-25 0330</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Turner-Dividend,0341</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Turner: Cable Operators To Get TBS Stock Instead Of Cash Dividend</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cable operators that own part of Turner
Broadcasting System Inc. have tentatively agreed to accept $35
million in stock instead of a cash dividend payment, TBS Chairman
Ted Turner said.
   ``This will give us some breathing room,'' Turner told reporters
Tuesday after addressing a business group. ``We are drawing up the
documents now, but we think we've got it nailed down.''
   A group of about 30 cable operators invested $560 million in
Turner Broadcasting last year and is due to receive the dividend in
April. The operators also were given seven seats on the 15-member
TBS board of directors.
   Under the original agreement, TBS had to pay the dividend within
six months of April 15 or give the cable operators two more seats
on the board. One cable operator said the original investment was
drawn up under the impression that Turner Broadcasting's $1.4
billion in debt would be refinanced by this time.
   Much of the debt stems from Turner's purchase of the
Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer film library, which has become a staple of
programming on the TBS cable channel. The debt carries a 16.5
percent interest rate.
   Turner has said his company was close to a refinancing agreement
early last fall, but the stock market plunge in October made it
impossible to work out a favorable deal.
   Under what Turner called an ``agreement in principle,'' Turner
Broadcasting would pay the dividend with shares of its Class B
stock, which closed Tuesday at $8 per share on the American Stock
Exchange. At that price, Turner's equity ownership in TBS would
fall to about 49.7 percent from the current 51 percent.
   The Class B stock was created so that TBS could use it for
business transactions such as paying the dividend without causing
Turner to lose voting control of the company.
   The deal would cause virtually no dilution of Turner's 68
percent voting stake in the company.
</TEXT>
