<1ST_LINE>u f AM-MoneyFunds     02-25 0385</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Money Funds,0397</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Money Funds Rose $2.56 Billion in Latest Week</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Interest rate figures reported by Donoghue's Money Fund
Report are for week ended Tuesday. All other figures are for the
week ended Wednesday.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Assets of the nation's 418 money market mutual
funds climbed $2.56 billion in the latest week to a record high
level of nearly $280 billion, the Investment Company Institute said
Thursday.
   The rise, to $279.99 billion in the seven-day period ended
Wednesday, followed a revised $608 million decline in the funds'
assets the previous week, according to the Washington-based mutual
fund trade group.
   The previous week's decline had originally been reported as
$1.19 billion.
   The latest gain leaves the fund's assets at their highest level
ever, surpassing the previous high mark of $278.04 billion in the
week ended Feb. 10.
   The Investment Company Institute said that in the latest week,
assets of 208 general purpose funds fell $522.8 million to $81.44
billion, assets of 97 broker-dealer funds rose $1.07 billion to
$115.52 billion and assets of 113 institutional funds jumped $2.01
billion to $83.02 billion.
   The seven-day average yield on money market mutual funds rose in
the week ended Tuesday to 6.16 percent from 6.14 percent the
previous week, according to Donoghue's Money Fund Report, a trade
journal based in Holliston, Mass.
   The 30-day average yield fell, to 6.23 percent from 6.28
percent, Donoghue's said.
   The average maturity of the portfolios held by money funds was
43 days, up from 42 days, Donoghue's said.
   Separately, the newsletter Bank Rate Monitor said its survey of
100 leading commercial banks, savings and loan assocations and
savings banks in the nation's 10 largest markets showed the
effective annual yield available on money market accounts slipped
to 5.75 percent as of Wednesday from 5.76 percent a week earlier.
   The North Palm Beach, Fla.-based newsletter said the effective
annual yield available on special savings accounts, called Super
NOW accounts, was unchanged from the previous week at 5.17 percent.
   Bank Rate Monitor said the effective annual yield was 6.88
percent on six-month certificates of deposit, down from 6.92 the
previous week. Yields were 7.20 percent on 1-year CDs, down from
7.23 percent; 7.62 percent on 2{-year CDs, down from 7.64 percent;
and 8.08 percent on 5-year CDs, down from 8.10 percent.
</TEXT>
