<1ST_LINE>u f AM-USGBid Bjt   02-25 0453</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-USG Bid, Bjt,0468</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Texas Oilmen Bid For USG, But Market Reaction Skeptical</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   USG Corp. kept quiet Thursday about two Texas
oilmen's $1.96 billion takeover attempt of the nation's largest
producer of gypsum, an important building material.
   ``At this time, we have nothing to say on any aspect of this,''
said Paul Colitti, a spokesman for Chicago-based USG.
   Desert Partners L.P., controlled by oilmen Cyril Wagner Jr. and
Jack E. Brown, said Wednesday it would pay $42 a share in cash for
at least 21.5 million common shares, or less than half the total
shares outstanding.
   The rest of the shares would be exchanged for subordinated debt
securities and warrants valued by Desert Partners at $42 a share.
   Analysts didn't give the proposal much chance of success because
of USG's previously stated desire to avoid dealing with Wagner and
Brown, takeover strategists who have made forays against several
companies.
   Some suggested the partners might be seeking a way to increase
the value of their 9.9 percent stake in the company, purchased last
fall at between $44 and $45 a share, so they could sell it with
minimal loss.
   Investor reaction to the bid was skeptical. USG's stock, which
rose $4.62{ Wednesday to $37 in composite New York Stock Exchange
trading, fell back to $35.87{ Thursday.
   In a letter to Robert J. Day, USG chairman and chief executive
officer, Desert Partners said it is genuinely interested in
acquiring the company and will refuse to accept ``greenmail'' _ the
purchase of its USG stock at a premium over the market price _ from
USG.
   The company produces gypsum and gypsum-related products in about
100 plants nationwide. Gypsum is a mineral component of plaster and
other building materials.
   ``We're hopeful, now that we've made a specific proposal, that
USG's board, recognizing its fiduciary responsibilities, will give
it serious consideration,'' said Joel Reed, president of a Desert
Partners subsidiary formed to try to acquire USG.
   In November, USG senior management said it had no interest in
participating in a buyout of the company with Desert Partners.
   The latest proposal came after a federal judge in Chicago on
Monday blocked USG's request to permanently bar Desert Partners
from buying additional USG shares.
   Last week, Mesa Limited Partners, headed by corporate raider T.
Boone Pickens, disclosed its 1.5 percent stake in USG.
   Several years ago, Wagner and Brown teamed with Pickens in a
number of takeover attempts, but Desert Partners has denied that
the parties have joined to gain control of USG this time.
   In its letter, Desert Partners said it has invested about $225
million, or about $44.30 a share, to accumulate its stake in USG.
The partnership owns about 5.08 million common shares.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
