<1ST_LINE>u f AM-MoneySupply     02-25 0505</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Money Supply,0523</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Narrow Measure of Money Supply Falls; Broader Measures Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's basic money supply fell $1.1
billion in mid February, while two broader measures, M2 and M3,
rose by $6.3 billion and $11.7 billion respectively, the Federal
Reserve Board reported Thursday.
   The Fed said M1 fell to a seasonally adjusted $759.9 billion in
the week ended Feb. 17 from $761 billion the previous week. M1
includes cash in circulation, deposits in checking accounts and
non-bank travelers checks.
   For the latest 13 weeks, M1 averaged $755.4 billion, a 2.1
percent seasonally adjusted annual rate of gain from the previous
13 weeks.
   Since early 1987, the Fed has not set a specific target range
for M1 growth because of ``uncertainties about its underlying
relationship to the behavior of the economy and its sensitivity to
a variety of economic and financial circumstances and assumptions.''
   M2, made up of M1 and such accounts as savings deposits and
money-market mutual funds, rose to a seasonally adjusted average of
$2,945.7 billion in the week ended Feb. 17. This compared with a
revised $2,939.4 billion the previous week, which was originally
reported as $2,939.9, the Fed said.
   For the latest 13 weeks, it averaged $2,915.8 billion, growing
at a 4.1 percent rate of gain.
   M3, the sum of M2 plus less-liquid accounts, such as
certificates of deposit in minimum denominations of $100,000, rose
to a seasonally adjusted average of $3,722.7 billion in the same
period.
   This compared with a revised $3,711 billion in the previous
week, which originally reported as $3,712 billion, the Fed said.
   For the latest 13 weeks, M3 has averaged $3,680 billion, growing
at a 5.1 percent rate of gain from the week earlier, the Fed said.
   The Fed said in early 1988 that it would like annual growth for
Ms and M3 to be between 4 percent and 8 percent, which is slightly
lower than the 1987 target of 5.5 percent to 8.5 percent.
   Analysts warned that it is difficult to draw short-term
conclusions about the meaning of the three figures, because they
are inclined to be volatile on a week-to-week basis.
   Beth Reiners, an analyst at the Dean Witter Reynolds securities
firm, said the data were mainly in line with the company's
expectations, and had no impact on the bond market.
   In other reports:
   _The Federal Reserve Bank of New York reported commercial and
industrial loans at major New York City banks rose $433 million in
the week ended Feb. 17, compared with a decline of $368 million a
week earlier.
   _The Federal Reserve said bank borrowings from the Federal
Reserve System averaged $132 million a day in the week ended
Wednesday, down from $254 million in the previous week.
   _The Federal Reserve Bank of St. Louis reported that the
monetary base, the seasonally adjusted total of member bank
reserves held at Federal Reserve banks and cash in bank vaults and
in circulation, was $272.3 billion in the two-week period ended
Wednesday, up from $272.1 billion two weeks earlier.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880225-0317 </DOCNO>
