<FILEID>AP-NR-02-25-88 2240EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-FCC-PhoneTrade     02-25 0414</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-FCC-Phone Trade,0427</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>FCC Expresses Displeasure About Closed Foreign Markets</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Communications Commission on
Thursday signaled to foreign governments that the United States
remains concerned about markets that have been closed or severely
limited to U.S. telecommunications manufacturers.
   The FCC stopped short of taking action that would reciprocally
exclude or limit foreign-owned companies from participating in the
U.S. market, though Chairman Dennis R. Patrick said such measures
``are still very much open, very much alive'' at the commission.
   The FCC said it needs more information on the trade imbalance
and ordered large long-distance and local phone companies to report
annually to the agency on big equipment purchases, including
switches and transmission equipment.
   ``By seeking this information we in no way imply an opposition
to foreign participation in U.S. markets,'' said FCC Chairman
Dennis R. Patrick. ``We believe in the economic utility of free
trade and in the proposition that, through that free trade,
consumers in the United States benefit by access to goods and
services that are provided by concerns around the world.
   ``However, we also believe in the principle of reciprocity and
there ought to be equally open markets in other parts of the
world,'' he said.
   The U.S. telecommunications equipment trade deficit is about $2
billion annually, the FCC said.
   Japan, Germany and France are among the countries whose
telecommunications trade policies have contributed heavily to the
deficit.
   The FCC will require annual reports from the country's seven
largest long-distance companies as well as the local Bell and large
independent companies. It also will require interstate carriers
that are 15 percent or more owned by foreign interests to file
annual revenue and traffic reports.
   The reporting requirements were proposed in December 1986 by
then-Chairman Mark S. Fowler. At the time, the commission also
sought comments on steps the FCC could take in pressuring foreign
countries to open their markets.
   Fowler, now in private law practice in Washington, said there is
no need at this time to change U.S. trade policy in reaction to
closed foreign markets, but ``by leaving the question open, there's
the spectre of further government action.''
   His intention in initiating the proposal was to put foreign
governments on notice of the U.S. concerns, he said.
   ``The only way we could get some countries' attention was to hit
them over the head with a threat,'' he said, adding, ``There's more
utility in making the threat than in implenting it.''
</TEXT>
