<FILEID>AP-NR-02-25-88 1806EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-NorthwestStrike     02-25 0420</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Northwest Strike,0434</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Union: Flight Attendants Strike Imminent</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TONY KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BLOOMINGTON, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Northwest Airlines and flight
attendants bargained intensively Thursday to avert a weekend
strike, but a union representing the workers said a walkout
appeared likely.
   ``There's a 100 percent chance of a strike,'' said William
Genoese, director of the International Brotherhood of Teamsters
Airline Division. ``As far as I'm concerned we're on a collision
course with Northwest Airlines to strike.''
   Flight attendants were preparing to strike at midnight Friday if
an agreement wasn't reached.
   Airline spokesman Redmond Tyler said progress is being made on
some major contract issues. The two sides have been meeting since
Tuesday at Northwest's world headquarters with the assistance of a
federal mediator, Tyler said.
   Senority wage scales, pensions and work rules are among the
major issues in the dispute. Former Republic Airlines flight
attendants have been working under their old contract since
Northwest acquired Republic in 1986. The company is trying to bring
the workers under one contract.
   ``We believe we're making substantial progress at the bargaining
table,'' Tyler said. ``We're not Jimmy the Greek, but we continue
to believe that we will get this resolved without a strike.''
   The national president of the International Association of
Machinists has vowed his union's support of the flight attendants,
but stopped short of saying machinists would honor picket lines.
Officials at national and local IAM offices did not return
telephone calls for clarification.
   Tyler said machinists are under a contract that forbids them to
strike in sympathy with another union. ``We expect our machinists
to honor their contract,'' he said.
   Pilots are forbidden from sympathy strikes under provisions of
the Railway Labor Act, Tyler said.
   Asked if those workers would be lockd out if they walk off their
jobs in sympathy with the flight attendants, Tyler said, ``We won't
address that because we don't want to play that `what if?' game.''
   Genoese said flight attendants would have the full backing of
the international Teamsters, which could result in delays of supply
shipments from truckers.
   Industry analysts were skeptical of the Teamsters power to
disrupt Northwest. Anthony Hatch, an airline industry analyst for
Argus Research of New York, said Genoese is ``overblowing the role
the teamsters play in an airline.''
   ``It's pilots and machinists that shut down an airline and
nothing else,'' Hatch said.
   Tyler said the airline is armed with about 2,000 management
workers who are certified as flight attendants to step if the 6,700
union flight attendants strike.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
