<1ST_LINE>u f AM-CommodityRdp     02-25 0785</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Commodity Rdp,0814</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Coffee Futures Tumble On Speculation Supplies Will Ease</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Coffee futures prices fell sharply Thursday, reversing a
five-month trend on speculation that a tight supply situation may
soon ease, analysts said.
   On other markets, energy futures prices dropped; grains and
soybeans moved lower; precious metals gained slightly; livestock
and meat futures were mostly higher; and stock-index futures
retreated.
   Coffee contracts on New York's Coffee, Sugar & Cocoa Exchange
lost as much as 2.87 cents a pound as the executive committee of
the International Coffee Organzation opened a two-day meeting in
London.
   At that meeting, delegates from consumer nations complained of
slow shipments of high-quality beans from producer nations and
claimed some producer nations had sold coffee at discounted prices
to non-member nations, said Sandra Kaul, an analyst in New York for
Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc.
   The apparent willingess of some producers to sell coffee at a
discount, along with news that Colombia had begun registering
coffee for export in April, suggests an easing of supplies, Ms.
Kaul said.
   ``This indicates that the short-term supply situation that
pushed the market up so sharply is about to come to an end at the
same time that seasonal demand eases,'' she said.
   In addition, analyst Kim Badenhop of Prudential-Bache Securities
noted that coffee prices were nearing levels that could trigger a
relaxation of ICO export quotas and increase shipments.
   Coffee settled 2 cents to 2.87 cents lower with the contract for
delivery in March at $1.3829 a pound.
   Crude oil futures slipped below $16 a barrel while gasoline and
heating oil prices fell sharply on the New York Mercantile Exchange.
   A Department of Energy report issued Wednesday showing an
8.5-million-barrel increase in U.S. oil stocks triggered the
sell-off, said Bob Baker, an analyst for Prudential-Bache
Securities Inc.
   But Peter Beutel of Elders Futures Inc. linked the price decline
to perceptions of rising oil production by OPEC members.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 40 cents to 50 cents
lower with February at $15.36 a barrel; heating oil was 1.18 cents
to 1.25 cents lower with March at 45.22 cents a gallon; unleaded
gasoline was .98 cent to 1.10 cents lower with March at 45.37 cents
a gallon.
   Indications that the Brazilian soybean crop may be larger than
expected sent U.S. soybean futures prices down sharply on the
Chicago Board of Trade. Most grain futures declined slightly.
   Soybean futures opened lower on news that rain had eased dry
conditions in the soybean-growing region of Brazil. Later in the
morning, the Brazilian Institute of Geography and Statistics
estimated the impending harvest would yield 19.4 million metric
tons, significantly higher than the U.S. Agriculture Department's
latest estimate of 18.5 million metric tons.
   ``This estimate was obviously negative for the U.S. market, and
it took off any rallying attempt the beans might have had,'' said
Walter Spilka, an analyst in New York for Smith Barney, Harris
Upham & Co.
   Wheat settled 1} cents lower to } cent higher with March at
$3.17} a bushel; corn was \ cent to } cent lower with March at
$1.98{ a bushel; oats were { cent lower to } cent higher with March
at $1.91 a bushel; soybeans were 3} cents to 8 cents lower with
March at $6.21 a bushel.
   Gold and silver futures posted modest gains on New York's
Commodity Exchange after two days of steep losses.
   The precious metals are caught in tug-of-war between bulls who
believe inflation is set to rise and bears who feel a recession is
near, said Jack Barbanel, an analyst for Gruntal & Co.
   ``It's a very volatile marketplace,'' he said.
   Gold settled 60 cents to $1.30 higher with April at $434.70 a
troy ounce; silver was 4.9 cents to 5.2 cents higher with March at
$6.245 a troy ounce.
   Most livestock and meat futures advanced on the Chicago
Mercantile Exchange.
   The cattle market was choppy but ended higher on improved demand
from packers, while pork prices rose on expectations for stronger
cash markets next week, said Philip Stanley, an analyst in Chicago
for Thomson McKinnon Securities Inc.
   Live cattle settled .20 cent to .40 cent higher with April at
72.40 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .40 cent lower to .25 cent
higher with March at 80.67 cents a pound; hogs were unchanged to
.25 cent higher with April at 44.12 cents a pound; frozen pork
bellies were .12 cent to .60 cent higher with March at 52.57 cents
a pound.
   Stock-index futures retreated on the Chicago Mercantile
Exchange, where the contract for March delivery of the Standard &
Poor's 500 index settled 2.35 points lower at 262.85. The
underlying spot index was down 2.86 points at 261.58.
</TEXT>
