<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Chrysler-Acustar     02-25 0469</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Chrysler-Acustar,0485</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Angry Workers Demonstrate, Vow End to Cooperation with Chrysler</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JANET BRAUNSTEIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Auto Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HIGHLAND PARK, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of angry, sign-waving
workers protesting the possible sale of Chrysler Corp.'s
parts-making division gathered outside company headquarters
Thursday shouting ``Strike! Strike!.'' ``You do whatever you need
to do _ and you know what to do,'' United Auto Workers union Vice
President Marc Stepp told more than 1,000 workers who marched in
windy, 20-degree weather for more than two hours.
   Chrysler Chairman Lee Iacocca has said Chrysler is considering
selling its 28,000-worker, $1 billion Acustar Inc. parts-making
subsidiary and may announce a decision next month.
   The union is trying to pressure Chrysler into retreating from
the sale, which Stepp said threatens the job security of all
Chrysler workers and is further damaging Chrysler's already injured
labor relations.
   Besides potential strikes over local issues at key plants that
could shut Chrysler down, local leaders said they will stop
cooperating in programs aimed at improving quality and efficiency.
   Chrysler spokesman Doug Nicoll said Chrysler had no immediate
comment.
   Acustar, which has plants in Mexico and Canada as well as the
United States, represents nearly a fifth of Chrysler's worldwide
operations, already the leanest among the Big Three U.S. automakers.
   Chrysler has said it may sell Acustar because it doesn't want to
invest in the research needed to upgrade some operations. Chrysler
already buys 70 percent of its parts elsewhere.
   Before the demonstration, Stepp met in Detroit with the
140-member Chrysler national bargaining council, which represents
all of Chrysler's 49 UAW locals, and about 100 others who came to
listen.
   The union cannot legally call a national strike over the sale of
Acustar. But Stepp said he told the council he will authorize
locals to strike on a plant-by-plant basis over unresolved issues
such as health and safety grievances.
   At least seven Chrysler locals already have voted to ask for
authorization and one, at Chrysler's key 4,000-worker stamping
plant in Sterling Heights, will receive permission as early as next
week, Stepp said.
   Other locals are gathering grievances and preparing to take
strike votes and seek national authorization. If disputes aren't
resolved, local unions may strike seven days after they receive
authorization.
   The council unanimously passed a resolution calling for
suspension of all joint labor-management programs, including
special team-concept agreements at six plants, that require trust
and cooperation.
   Workers say they are angry at the possible sale because they
made concessions and helped Iacocca win loan guarantees from the
federal government to rescue the company from the verge of
bankruptcy eight years ago.
   ``Let this be a lesson to all America, to trade unionists
everywhere, if you think you can work out some cooperative programs
to generate trust with this corporation, forget it, because you
can't,'' Stepp told the protesters.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
