<2ND_LINE>AM-Gillette, 1st Ld-Writethru,0606</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gillette Urges Stockholders To Rebuff Coniston Board Challenge</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Grafs 1-7 new to CLARIFY what Coniston wants Gillette to do,
CORRECT that Coniston is a partnership, UPDATE with final stock
price. Picks up 8th graf pvs: Analysts believe ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By STEFAN FATSIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gillette Co. urged its stockholders Thursday to
resist an attempt by Coniston Partners to seize four seats on
Gillette's board of directors.
   Coniston wants Gillette to boost the value of its stock, by
selling itself to another company, or selling off its assets
piecemeal or restructuring its finances. Gillette Chairman Colman
M. Mockler Jr. asked stockholders not to sign proxy cards being
distributed by Coniston, which controls a roughly 6 percent stake
in the consumer products maker.
   ``The board of directors believes the stated intentions and
suggestions of this group are not in the best interests of your
company and intends to oppose the group's actions vigorously,'' a
letter from Mockler to stockholders said.
   Coniston, a New York investment partnership, announced earlier
this month that it was approaching potential buyers of the
Boston-based company and might take other moves to boost Gillette's
share price.
   The firm last week nominated four candidates for the seats on
the 12-member board of directors up for election at Gillette's
annual meeting April 21. Stockholders as of March 7 will be
eligible to take part in the board vote.
   ``This letter is essentially a stop, look and listen letter,''
Gillette spokesman Dick Gauthier said.
   Gillette stock fell $1.37{ a share to $39.87{ Thursday in
consolidated New York Stock Exchange trading.
   Analysts believe Gillette's recent stock price is well below the
high-$40 to low-$50 range estimated as its acquisition value. The
company late last year rejected a $47-a-share, $5.4 billion buyout
offer from Revlon Group Inc., which has bid for Gillette since 1986.
   The company reported a 12 percent rise in sales and doubling in
operating profits last year.
   Gus Oliver, a general partner in Coniston, said Thursday the
company stood by its position that the proxy fight was necessary
because Gillette's takeover defenses meant the board had power to
accept or reject any merger offers.
   He criticized Mockler's letter but said: ``I think it's to be
expected from this particular management and board of directors.''
   The letter said Gillette would ``act vigorously'' to resist
attempts by Coniston to gain a greater stake in the independent
company, known for its personal products such as razor blades and
pens.
   ``The board regrets that a costly proxy contest for the control
of the direction of your company may develop, particularly at the
time when the company is starting to realize many of the ongoing
benefits of its restructuring activity,'' the letter said.
   Coniston sucessfully waged a similar strategy of ``strategic
block investing'' last year that led to the break-up of Allegis
Corp.
   ``Your board of directors believes that this is but a catch
phrase for trying to force the sale or dismemberment of companies
in which Coniston takes positions,'' Mockler said.
   ``From what little is publicly known about Coniston Partners,
neither it nor its partners have any direct experience in managing
or running an international consumer products firm.''
   Gillette reported net income of $229.9 million on sales of $3.17
billion for 1987 compared with net income of $15.8 million on sales
of $2.82 billion in 1986. The 1986 figures included a special
charge of $165.3 million.
   Excluding the charge, Gillette reported earnings per share of $2
last year compared with $1.42 in 1986.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
