<1ST_LINE>r f BC-BusinessHighlights 2Takes   02-25 0510</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Business Highlights, 2 Takes,0534</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan has
warned the Reagan administration that further attempts to pressure
the central bank to lower interest rates could boomerang.
   Greenspan's warning came Wednesday as the administration sought
to dampen its dispute with the Fed. Beryl Sprinkel, the president's
chief economic adviser, said the administration is ``delighted with
monetary policy.''
   At issue is a critical letter sent by Assistant Treasury
Secretary Michael Darby to top Fed policy-makers 10 days before
they were to meet to set 1988 monetary growth targets.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's record trade deficit shrank in
the final quarter of 1987 as U.S. exports climbed 6 percent to
record levels, the Commerce Department says.
   While narrowing just $200 million from the summer, the deficit's
decline to $40.2 billion on a balance-of-payments basis marked the
first quarterly improvement since the spring of 1986, the
department said Wednesday.
   Robert Ortner, undersecretary of commerce for economic affairs,
said further improvements were likely.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sales of domestically made cars and light trucks
jumped 14.5 percent in mid-February from a year earlier despite
cold weather that could have kept some buyers out of showrooms,
automakers said.
   Total domestic car sales rose 11.9 percent in the nine selling
days from Feb. 11-20, while domestic truck sales jumped 19.6
percent, the automakers reported Wednesday.
   General Motors Corp., Ford Motor Co. and Chrysler Corp. reported
healthy increases in sales, which were not shared by most
foreign-based automakers.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   General Motors Corp. has boosted 1988 production
plans by 175,000 cars and trucks and will recall 8,600 laid-off
workers and reopen a temporarily closed assembly plant.
   ``The strengthening demand for GM vehicles reflects the ongoing
product quality improvements resulting from plant modernization and
employee involvement programs,'' GM President Robert Stempel stated
Wednesday.
   GM will increase production by running some plants, particularly
for trucks, on overtime; restoring second shifts at two U.S. plants
and one in Canada; and reopening its closed Framingham, Mass.,
assembly plant.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Santa Fe Southern Pacific Corp. has rejected
Henley Group Inc.'s latest offer to buy a controlling interest in
the company.
   Santa Fe said Wednesday that the proposal would give Henley an
effective controlling stake in the company without having to pay a
premium to other shareholders.
   Henley, which holds a 15.7 percent stake in Santa Fe, offered
Monday to buy 44.6 million new shares for $780 million if the
Chicago company would abandon its ``poison pill'' takeover defense
and restructure a $4.7 billion special dividend to stockholders.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dart Group Corp. says it will continue a $1.03
billion hostile takeover bid for Stop & Shop Cos. Inc., which is
negotiating with several other potential buyers.
   Stop & Shop confirmed Wednesday it had begun talks with several
parties considering a buyout of the supermarket and discount store
chain, raising the possibility it might find a ``white knight''
friendly suitor to thwart Dart.
   Sandy Bouzoukis, a Stop & Shop spokeswoman, declined to name the
parties interested.
</TEXT>
