<1ST_LINE>r f AM-PhoneRates     02-25 0319</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Phone Rates,0328</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>FCC Extends Rate of Return on AT&T's Interstate Operations</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Communications Commission on
Thursday voted to extend through 1989 American Telephone &
Telegraph Co.'s 12.2 percent authorized rate of return on its
regulated interstate operations.
   The FCC also decided to extend the 12 percent rate of return
that local telephone companies can earn on the payments they
receive from long-distance companies for providing access to the
local networks.
   The FCC had set those rates in August 1986 to cover the calendar
years 1987 and 1988. The commission voted 3-0 to extend the rates
for a third year because economic conditions are about the same
today as they were when the rates were set two years ago.
   FCC Chairman Dennis R. Patrick said the extension would also add
stability to phone rates and give the commission more time to
refine the formula for determining appropriate rates of return.
   Gerald Brock, the FCC's top telephone staff official, said the
action has ``no direct effect'' on the commission's proposal to
replace rate-of-return regulation of AT&T and the local Bell phone
companies with a cap on the rates they can charge.
   The agency proposed a broad rate-cap plan last August and, under
pressure from Congress, said recently it will propose a more
specific plan, probably this spring.
   Under the current form of regulation, the FCC sets the profit
level it will allow for phone companies under its jurisdiction and
allows that target to be met over a period of time.
   A federal appeals court earlier this year struck down the FCC's
rules for ordering refunds by companies that exceed their
authorized rate of return because the rules didn't permit companies
that earn less than the allowed rate to recoup any shortfalls.
   The court invited the agency to fashion a new refund policy, but
the FCC has not yet responded.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
